1088_129236_000002_000000 LOVE.
1088_129236_000003_000000 "I was as a gem concealed; Me my burning ray revealed." Koran.
1088_129236_000005_000000 Every promise of the soul has innumerable fulfilments; each of its joys ripens into a new want.
1088_129236_000005_000001 Nature, uncontainable, flowing, forelooking, in the first sentiment of kindness anticipates already a benevolence which shall lose all particular regards in its general light.
1088_129236_000006_000001 The delicious fancies of youth reject the least savor of a mature philosophy, as chilling with age and pedantry their purple bloom.
1088_129236_000006_000002 And therefore I know I incur the imputation of unnecessary hardness and stoicism from those who compose the Court and Parliament of Love.
1088_129236_000006_000003 But from these formidable censors I shall appeal to my seniors.
1088_129236_000006_000004 For it is to be considered that this passion of which we speak, though it begin with the young, yet forsakes not the old, or rather suffers no one who is truly its servant to grow old, but makes the aged participators of it not less than the tender maiden, though in a different and nobler sort.
1088_129236_000006_000005 For it is a fire that kindling its first embers in the narrow nook of a private bosom, caught from a wandering spark out of another private heart, glows and enlarges until it warms and beams upon multitudes of men and women, upon the universal heart of all, and so lights up the whole world and all nature with its generous flames.
1088_129236_000006_000006 It matters not therefore whether we attempt to describe the passion at twenty, at thirty, or at eighty years.
1088_129236_000006_000007 He who paints it at the first period will lose some of its later, he who paints it at the last, some of its earlier traits.
1088_129236_000007_000001 For each man sees his own life defaced and disfigured, as the life of man is not, to his imagination.
1088_129236_000007_000002 Each man sees over his own experience a certain stain of error, whilst that of other men looks fair and ideal.
1088_129236_000007_000003 Let any man go back to those delicious relations which make the beauty of his life, which have given him sincerest instruction and nourishment, he will shrink and moan.
1088_129236_000007_000005 I know not why, but infinite compunctions embitter in mature life the remembrances of budding joy and cover every beloved name.
1088_129236_000007_000006 Every thing is beautiful seen from the point of the intellect, or as truth.
1088_129236_000007_000007 But all is sour, if seen as experience.
1088_129236_000007_000008 Details are melancholy; the plan is seemly and noble.
1088_129236_000007_000010 With thought, with the ideal, is immortal hilarity, the rose of joy.
1088_129236_000007_000011 Round it all the Muses sing.
1088_129236_000007_000012 But grief cleaves to names, and persons, and the partial interests of to day and yesterday.
1088_129236_000008_000000 The strong bent of nature is seen in the proportion which this topic of personal relations usurps in the conversation of society.
1088_129236_000008_000002 What books in the circulating libraries circulate?
1088_129236_000008_000003 How we glow over these novels of passion, when the story is told with any spark of truth and nature!
1088_129236_000008_000004 And what fastens attention, in the intercourse of life, like any passage betraying affection between two parties?
1088_129236_000008_000005 Perhaps we never saw them before, and never shall meet them again.
1088_129236_000008_000006 But we see them exchange a glance, or betray a deep emotion, and we are no longer strangers.
1088_129236_000008_000007 We understand them, and take the warmest interest in the development of the romance.
1088_129236_000008_000008 All mankind love a lover. The earliest demonstrations of complacency and kindness are nature's most winning pictures.
1088_129236_000008_000009 It is the dawn of civility and grace in the coarse and rustic.
1088_129236_000008_000010 The rude village boy teases the girls about the school house door;--but to day he comes running into the entry, and meets one fair child disposing her satchel; he holds her books to help her, and instantly it seems to him as if she removed herself from him infinitely, and was a sacred precinct.
1088_129236_000008_000011 Among the throng of girls he runs rudely enough, but one alone distances him; and these two little neighbors, that were so close just now, have learned to respect each other's personality.
1088_129236_000008_000014 The girls may have little beauty, yet plainly do they establish between them and the good boy the most agreeable, confiding relations, what with their fun and their earnest, about Edgar and Jonas and Almira, and who was invited to the party, and who danced at the dancing school, and when the singing school would begin, and other nothings concerning which the parties cooed.
1088_129236_000008_000015 By and by that boy wants a wife, and very truly and heartily will he know where to find a sincere and sweet mate, without any risk such as Milton deplores as incident to scholars and great men.
1088_129236_000009_000001 But now I almost shrink at the remembrance of such disparaging words.
1088_129236_000009_000002 For persons are love's world, and the coldest philosopher cannot recount the debt of the young soul wandering here in nature to the power of love, without being tempted to unsay, as treasonable to nature, aught derogatory to the social instincts.
1088_129236_000009_000004 But here is a strange fact; it may seem to many men, in revising their experience, that they have no fairer page in their life's book than the delicious memory of some passages wherein affection contrived to give a witchcraft, surpassing the deep attraction of its own truth, to a parcel of accidental and trivial circumstances.
1088_129236_000009_000005 In looking backward they may find that several things which were not the charm have more reality to this groping memory than the charm itself which embalmed them.
1088_129236_000011_000000 In the noon and the afternoon of life we still throb at the recollection of days when happiness was not happy enough, but must be drugged with the relish of pain and fear; for he touched the secret of the matter who said of love,--
1088_129236_000012_000000 "All other pleasures are not worth its pains:"
1088_129236_000014_000000 The passion rebuilds the world for the youth.
1088_129236_000014_000001 It makes all things alive and significant.
1088_129236_000014_000002 Nature grows conscious.
1088_129236_000014_000003 Every bird on the boughs of the tree sings now to his heart and soul.
1088_129236_000014_000004 The notes are almost articulate. The clouds have faces as he looks on them.
1088_129236_000014_000005 The trees of the forest, the waving grass and the peeping flowers have grown intelligent; and he almost fears to trust them with the secret which they seem to invite. Yet nature soothes and sympathizes.
1088_129236_000014_000006 In the green solitude he finds a dearer home than with men:--
1088_129236_000015_000000 "Fountain heads and pathless groves, Places which pale passion loves, Moonlight walks, when all the fowls Are safely housed, save bats and owls, A midnight bell, a passing groan,-- These are the sounds we feed upon."
1088_129236_000016_000000 Behold there in the wood the fine madman!
1088_129236_000016_000001 He is a palace of sweet sounds and sights; he dilates; he is twice a man; he walks with arms akimbo; he soliloquizes; he accosts the grass and the trees; he feels the blood of the violet, the clover and the lily in his veins; and he talks with the brook that wets his foot.
1088_129236_000017_000000 The heats that have opened his perceptions of natural beauty have made him love music and verse.
1088_129236_000017_000001 It is a fact often observed, that men have written good verses under the inspiration of passion, who cannot write well under any other circumstances.
1088_129236_000018_000000 The like force has the passion over all his nature.
1088_129236_000018_000001 It expands the sentiment; it makes the clown gentle and gives the coward heart.
1088_129236_000018_000002 Into the most pitiful and abject it will infuse a heart and courage to defy the world, so only it have the countenance of the beloved object.
1088_129236_000018_000003 In giving him to another it still more gives him to himself.
1088_129236_000018_000004 He is a new man, with new perceptions, new and keener purposes, and a religious solemnity of character and aims.
1088_129236_000018_000005 He does not longer appertain to his family and society; he is somewhat; he is a person; he is a soul.
1088_129236_000019_000000 And here let us examine a little nearer the nature of that influence which is thus potent over the human youth.
1088_129236_000019_000001 Beauty, whose revelation to man we now celebrate, welcome as the sun wherever it pleases to shine, which pleases everybody with it and with themselves, seems sufficient to itself.
1088_129236_000019_000002 The lover cannot paint his maiden to his fancy poor and solitary.
1088_129236_000019_000003 Like a tree in flower, so much soft, budding, informing loveliness is society for itself; and she teaches his eye why Beauty was pictured with Loves and Graces attending her steps.
1088_129236_000019_000004 Her existence makes the world rich.
1088_129236_000019_000005 Though she extrudes all other persons from his attention as cheap and unworthy, she indemnifies him by carrying out her own being into somewhat impersonal, large, mundane, so that the maiden stands to him for a representative of all select things and virtues.
1088_129236_000019_000007 His friends find in her a likeness to her mother, or her sisters, or to persons not of her blood.
1088_129236_000019_000008 The lover sees no resemblance except to summer evenings and diamond mornings, to rainbows and the song of birds.
1088_129236_000020_000000 The ancients called beauty the flowering of virtue.
1088_129236_000020_000002 We are touched with emotions of tenderness and complacency, but we cannot find whereat this dainty emotion, this wandering gleam, points.
1088_129236_000020_000003 It is destroyed for the imagination by any attempt to refer it to organization.
1088_129236_000020_000004 Nor does it point to any relations of friendship or love known and described in society, but, as it seems to me, to a quite other and unattainable sphere, to relations of transcendent delicacy and sweetness, to what roses and violets hint and foreshow.
1088_129236_000020_000005 We cannot approach beauty.
1088_129236_000020_000006 Its nature is like opaline doves'-neck lustres, hovering and evanescent.
1088_129236_000020_000007 Herein it resembles the most excellent things, which all have this rainbow character, defying all attempts at appropriation and use.
1088_129236_000020_000010 The god or hero of the sculptor is always represented in a transition from that which is representable to the senses, to that which is not.
1088_129236_000020_000011 Then first it ceases to be a stone.
1088_129236_000020_000012 The same remark holds of painting.
1088_129236_000020_000013 And of poetry the success is not attained when it lulls and satisfies, but when it astonishes and fires us with new endeavors after the unattainable.
1088_129236_000022_000000 Hence arose the saying, "If I love you, what is that to you?" We say so because we feel that what we love is not in your will, but above it.
1088_129236_000022_000001 It is not you, but your radiance.
1088_129236_000022_000002 It is that which you know not in yourself and can never know.
1088_129236_000024_000001 By conversation with that which is in itself excellent, magnanimous, lowly, and just, the lover comes to a warmer love of these nobilities, and a quicker apprehension of them.
1088_129236_000024_000002 Then he passes from loving them in one to loving them in all, and so is the one beautiful soul only the door through which he enters to the society of all true and pure souls.
1088_129236_000025_000001 If Plato, Plutarch and Apuleius taught it, so have Petrarch, Angelo and Milton.
1088_129236_000025_000002 It awaits a truer unfolding in opposition and rebuke to that subterranean prudence which presides at marriages with words that take hold of the upper world, whilst one eye is prowling in the cellar; so that its gravest discourse has a savor of hams and powdering tubs.
1088_129236_000026_000000 But this dream of love, though beautiful, is only one scene in our play.
1088_129236_000026_000001 In the procession of the soul from within outward, it enlarges its circles ever, like the pebble thrown into the pond, or the light proceeding from an orb.
1088_129236_000026_000002 The rays of the soul alight first on things nearest, on every utensil and toy, on nurses and domestics, on the house and yard and passengers, on the circle of household acquaintance, on politics and geography and history.
1088_129236_000026_000003 But things are ever grouping themselves according to higher or more interior laws.
1088_129236_000026_000004 Neighborhood, size, numbers, habits, persons, lose by degrees their power over us. Cause and effect, real affinities, the longing for harmony between the soul and the circumstance, the progressive, idealizing instinct, predominate later, and the step backward from the higher to the lower relations is impossible.
1088_129236_000026_000005 Thus even love, which is the deification of persons, must become more impersonal every day.
1088_129236_000026_000006 Of this at first it gives no hint.
1088_129236_000026_000007 Little think the youth and maiden who are glancing at each other across crowded rooms with eyes so full of mutual intelligence, of the precious fruit long hereafter to proceed from this new, quite external stimulus.
1088_129236_000026_000008 The work of vegetation begins first in the irritability of the bark and leaf buds.
1088_129236_000026_000009 From exchanging glances, they advance to acts of courtesy, of gallantry, then to fiery passion, to plighting troth and marriage.
1088_129236_000026_000010 Passion beholds its object as a perfect unit.
1088_129236_000027_000000 "Her pure and eloquent blood Spoke in her cheeks, and so distinctly wrought, That one might almost say her body thought."
1088_129236_000028_000000 Romeo, if dead, should be cut up into little stars to make the heavens fine.
1088_129236_000028_000001 Life, with this pair, has no other aim, asks no more, than Juliet,--than Romeo.
1088_129236_000028_000003 The lovers delight in endearments, in avowals of love, in comparisons of their regards.
1088_129236_000028_000005 Does that other see the same star, the same melting cloud, read the same book, feel the same emotion, that now delight me?
1088_129236_000028_000006 They try and weigh their affection, and adding up costly advantages, friends, opportunities, properties, exult in discovering that willingly, joyfully, they would give all as a ransom for the beautiful, the beloved head, not one hair of which shall be harmed. But the lot of humanity is on these children.
1088_129236_000028_000007 Danger, sorrow, and pain arrive to them, as to all.
1088_129236_000028_000008 Love prays.
1088_129236_000028_000009 It makes covenants with Eternal Power in behalf of this dear mate.
1088_129236_000028_000010 The union which is thus effected and which adds a new value to every atom in nature-for it transmutes every thread throughout the whole web of relation into a golden ray, and bathes the soul in a new and sweeter element-is yet a temporary state. Not always can flowers, pearls, poetry, protestations, nor even home in another heart, content the awful soul that dwells in clay.
1088_129236_000028_000011 It arouses itself at last from these endearments, as toys, and puts on the harness and aspires to vast and universal aims.
1088_129236_000028_000012 The soul which is in the soul of each, craving a perfect beatitude, detects incongruities, defects and disproportion in the behavior of the other.
1088_129236_000028_000013 Hence arise surprise, expostulation and pain.
1088_129236_000028_000014 Yet that which drew them to each other was signs of loveliness, signs of virtue; and these virtues are there, however eclipsed.
1088_129236_000028_000015 They appear and reappear and continue to attract; but the regard changes, quits the sign and attaches to the substance.
1088_129236_000028_000016 This repairs the wounded affection.
1088_129236_000028_000018 For it is the nature and end of this relation, that they should represent the human race to each other. All that is in the world, which is or ought to be known, is cunningly wrought into the texture of man, of woman:--
1088_129236_000029_000000 "The person love does to us fit, Like manna, has the taste of all in it."
1088_129236_000030_000000 The world rolls; the circumstances vary every hour.
1088_129236_000030_000001 The angels that inhabit this temple of the body appear at the windows, and the gnomes and vices also.
1088_129236_000030_000002 By all the virtues they are united.
1088_129236_000030_000003 If there be virtue, all the vices are known as such; they confess and flee.
1088_129236_000030_000004 Their once flaming regard is sobered by time in either breast, and losing in violence what it gains in extent, it becomes a thorough good understanding.
1088_129236_000030_000005 They resign each other without complaint to the good offices which man and woman are severally appointed to discharge in time, and exchange the passion which once could not lose sight of its object, for a cheerful, disengaged furtherance, whether present or absent, of each other's designs.
1088_129236_000031_000000 Thus are we put in training for a love which knows not sex, nor person, nor partiality, but which seeks virtue and wisdom everywhere, to the end of increasing virtue and wisdom.
1088_129236_000031_000001 We are by nature observers, and thereby learners.
1088_129236_000031_000002 That is our permanent state.
1088_129236_000031_000003 But we are often made to feel that our affections are but tents of a night.
1088_129236_000031_000005 There are moments when the affections rule and absorb the man and make his happiness dependent on a person or persons.
1088_129236_000031_000007 But we need not fear that we can lose any thing by the progress of the soul.
1088_129236_000031_000008 The soul may be trusted to the end.
1088_129236_000031_000009 That which is so beautiful and attractive as these relations, must be succeeded and supplanted only by what is more beautiful, and so on for ever.
