1743_142914_000006_000000 "I didn't mean to scare him," apologized peter.
1743_142914_000006_000001 "I really didn't mean to.
1743_142914_000006_000002 Do you think he was really very much scared?"
1743_142914_000007_000000 "Not too scared to come back, anyway," said Longbill himself, dropping down just in front of peter.
1743_142914_000007_000003 I am glad it is no one but you, peter, for I was having a splendid meal here, and I should have hated to leave it.
1743_142914_000007_000004 You'll excuse me while I go on eating, I hope.
1743_142914_000007_000005 We can talk between bites."
1743_142914_000008_000001 But peter couldn't see a thing that looked good to eat.
1743_142914_000008_000002 There wasn't even a bug or a worm crawling on the ground.
1743_142914_000008_000003 Longbill took two or three steps in rather a stately fashion.
1743_142914_000008_000006 But his bill was long enough to make up.
1743_142914_000008_000007 His back was a mixture of gray, brown, black and buff, while his breast and under parts were a beautiful reddish buff.
1743_142914_000008_000008 It was his head that made him look queer.
1743_142914_000008_000009 His eyes were very big and they were set so far back that peter wondered if it wasn't easier for him to look behind him than in front of him.
1743_142914_000009_000000 Suddenly Longbill plunged his bill into the ground.
1743_142914_000009_000001 He plunged it in for the whole length.
1743_142914_000009_000002 Then he pulled it out and peter caught a glimpse of the tail end of a worm disappearing down Longbill's throat.
1743_142914_000010_000001 "mrs Woodcock made some of them."
1743_142914_000011_000000 "And was there a worm in every one?" asked peter, his eyes very wide with interest.
1743_142914_000012_000000 Longbill nodded.
1743_142914_000013_000001 But the worms Welcome Robin got were always close to the surface, while these worms were so deep in the earth that peter couldn't understand how it was possible for any one to know that they were there.
1743_142914_000014_000003 See here!" Longbill suddenly thrust his bill straight out in front of him and to Peter's astonishment he lifted the end of the upper half without opening the rest of his bill at all.
1743_142914_000014_000004 "That's the way I get them," said he.
1743_142914_000014_000005 "I can feel them when I reach them, and then I just open the top of my bill and grab them.
1743_142914_000014_000006 I think there is one right under my feet now; watch me get him." Longbill bored into the ground until his head was almost against it.
1743_142914_000014_000007 When he pulled his bill out, sure enough, there was a worm.
1743_142914_000014_000008 "Of course," explained Longbill, "it is only in soft ground that I can do this.
1743_142914_000014_000009 That is why I have to fly away south as soon as the ground freezes at all."
1743_142914_000015_000000 "It's wonderful," sighed peter.
1743_142914_000015_000001 "I don't suppose any one else can find hidden worms that way."
1743_142914_000016_000000 "My cousin, Jack Snipe, can," replied Longbill promptly.
1743_142914_000017_000000 peter nodded.
1743_142914_000017_000001 "I do," said he.
1743_142914_000017_000002 "Now you speak of it, there is a strong family resemblance, although I hadn't thought of him as a relative of yours before.
1743_142914_000017_000004 I'm ever so glad to have seen you, and I'm coming over to call again the first chance I get."
1743_142914_000018_000000 So peter said good by and kept on down the Laughing Brook to the Smiling Pool.
1743_142914_000018_000001 Right where the Laughing Brook entered the Smiling Pool there was a little pebbly beach.
1743_142914_000018_000002 Running along the very edge of the water was a slim, trim little bird with fairly long legs, a long slender bill, brownish gray back with black spots and markings, and a white waistcoat neatly spotted with black.
1743_142914_000018_000003 Every few steps he would stop to pick up something, then stand for a second bobbing up and down in the funniest way, as if his body was so nicely balanced on his legs that it teetered back and forth like a seesaw.
1743_142914_000018_000004 It was Teeter the Spotted Sandpiper, an old friend of Peter's.
1743_142914_000018_000005 peter greeted him joyously.
1743_142914_000019_000000 "Peet weet!
1743_142914_000019_000001 Peet weet!" cried Teeter, turning towards peter and bobbing and bowing as only Teeter can.
1743_142914_000019_000002 Before peter could say another word Teeter came running towards him, and it was plain to see that Teeter was very anxious about something.
1743_142914_000019_000003 "Don't move, peter Rabbit!
1743_142914_000019_000004 Don't move!" he cried.
1743_142914_000020_000000 "Why not?" demanded peter, for he could see no danger and could think of no reason why he shouldn't move.
1743_142914_000020_000001 Just then mrs Teeter came hurrying up and squatted down in the sand right in front of peter.
1743_142914_000021_000000 "Thank goodness!" exclaimed Teeter, still bobbing and bowing.
1743_142914_000021_000001 "If you had taken another step, peter Rabbit, you would have stepped right on our eggs.
1743_142914_000021_000002 You gave me a dreadful start."
1743_142914_000022_000000 peter was puzzled.
1743_142914_000022_000001 He showed it as he stared down at mrs Teeter just in front of him.
1743_142914_000022_000002 "I don't see any nest or eggs or anything," said he rather testily.
1743_142914_000023_000000 mrs Teeter stood up and stepped aside.
1743_142914_000023_000001 Then peter saw right in a little hollow in the sand, with just a few bits of grass for a lining, four white eggs with big dark blotches on them.
1743_142914_000023_000003 peter hastily backed away a few steps.
1743_142914_000023_000004 mrs Teeter slipped back on the eggs and settled herself comfortably.
1743_142914_000023_000005 It suddenly struck peter that if he hadn't seen her do it, he wouldn't have known she was there.
1743_142914_000025_000000 mrs Teeter chuckled softly.
1743_142914_000025_000003 The only time they are in danger is when somebody comes along, as you did, and is likely to step on them without seeing them.
1743_142914_000025_000004 But that doesn't happen often."
1841_150351_000000_000000 THE NATIVE INHABITANTS OF THE PACIFIC SLOPE
1841_150351_000001_000000 The explorers and early settlers found a native race occupying nearly every portion of our continent.
1841_150351_000001_000001 These people had many characteristics in common and were all called Indians.
1841_150351_000001_000002 It is believed that they came originally from Asia, but their migration and scattering occurred so long ago that they have become divided into many groups, each having its own language and customs.
1841_150351_000002_000000 In the western portion of the country, where the surface is broken by numerous barriers, such as mountains and deserts, almost every valley was found to be occupied by a distinct group of Indians called a "tribe." The language of each tribe differed so much from the languages of adjoining tribes that they could with difficulty understand one another.
1841_150351_000002_000001 These tribes were almost continually at war.
1841_150351_000003_000000 The Indians upon the Pacific slope were generally found to be inferior in most respects to those living in the central and eastern portions of the continent.
1841_150351_000003_000001 One might suppose that the tribes possessing the fair and fertile valleys of California would be the most advanced in civilization, but such was not the case.
1841_150351_000003_000002 Many of them were among the most degraded upon the continent.
1841_150351_000003_000003 They seemed unable to adapt themselves to the white man and his ways, and in the older settled districts they have now nearly disappeared.
1841_150351_000003_000004 In the newer portions of the Northwest and along the coast toward Alaska the Indians have not yet come into so direct contact with the white men, and remain more nearly in their primitive condition.
1841_150351_000004_000000 When the Indians of central California were first seen, they wore but little clothing, and knew how to construct only the simplest dwellings for protection from the weather.
1841_150351_000004_000001 They did not cultivate the soil, nor did they hunt a great deal, although the country abounded with game.
1841_150351_000004_000003 The acorns were ground in stone mortars and made into soup or into a kind of bread.
1841_150351_000005_000000 It would seem natural that about San Francisco Bay the natives should have used canoes, but, according to early travellers, they had none.
1841_150351_000005_000001 When they wished to go out upon the water they built rafts of bundles of rushes or tules tied together.
1841_150351_000006_000000 At favorable points along the shore the Indians collected for their feasts, and these spots are now indicated by heaps of shells, in some places forming mounds of considerable size.
1841_150351_000006_000001 Many interesting implements have been dug from these mounds, or kitchen middens as they are sometimes called.
1841_150351_000006_000002 In the mountains the sites of the villages are marked by chips of obsidian (a volcanic glass used in making arrow tips) and by holes in the flat surfaces of granitic rocks near some spring or stream.
1841_150351_000006_000003 These holes were made for the purpose of grinding acorns or nuts.
1841_150351_000007_000000 Many of the Indian tribes developed great skill in the weaving of baskets, which they used for many different purposes.
1841_150351_000007_000001 The baskets are still made in some places, and are much sought after because of their beauty.
1841_150351_000008_000000 The Indians of northern California in building their homes dug round, shallow holes, over which poles were bent in the form of a half circle, and then tied together at the top.
1841_150351_000008_000001 Bark was laid upon the outside, and earth was thrown over the whole structure.
1841_150351_000010_000000 "Sweat houses" were built in much the same manner, and were used chiefly during the winter.
1841_150351_000010_000001 When an Indian wished to take a sweat, hot stones were placed in one of these houses, and after he had entered and all openings were closed, he poured water upon the stones until the room was filled with steam.
1841_150351_000010_000002 After enduring this process as long as he desired, the Indian came out and plunged into the cold water of a near by stream.
1841_150351_000010_000003 As may be imagined, such a bath often resulted disastrously to the weak or sick.
1841_150351_000011_000000 The fact that the California Indians could support themselves without any great exertion undoubtedly had the effect of making them indolent, while in the desert regions of the Great Basin the struggle for something to eat was so severe that it kept the natives in a degraded condition.
1841_150351_000013_000001 Where wood was abundant their homes were similar in some respects to those of the coast Indians north of the mouth of the Columbia.
1841_150351_000013_000002 Fish was their main article of diet.
1841_150351_000013_000005 After being partly dried they were packed in bales for winter use.
1841_150351_000013_000006 The fish thus prepared were considered very valuable and formed an article of trade with the tribes living farther from the river.
1841_150351_000014_000000 The Indians inhabiting the coast northward from the mouth of the Columbia were different in many respects from those farther south or inland.
1841_150351_000014_000001 They built better homes, took more pains with their clothing, were skilled in the making of canoes, and showed marked ability in navigating the stormy waters of the channels and sounds.
1841_150351_000017_000000 The Vancouver Island Indians are called Nootkas, from the name of an important tribe upon the west coast.
1841_150351_000017_000002 These two groups are very similar.
1841_150351_000017_000003 They live upon the shores of densely wooded, mountainous lands and travel little except by water.
1841_150351_000017_000004 Some of the canoes which these tribes construct are over fifty feet long and will easily carry from fifty to one hundred persons.
1841_150351_000017_000005 Such a canoe is hewn out of a single cedar log, and presents a very graceful appearance with its upward curving bow.
1841_150351_000017_000006 In these boats the Indians take trips of hundreds of miles.
1841_150351_000019_000000 A ride in one of the large canoes is an interesting experience. When a party starts out to visit the neighboring villages, carrying invitations to a festival, the men are gayly dressed, and shout and sing in unison as they ply their paddles.
1841_150351_000019_000001 The great canoe jumps up and onward like a living thing at every stroke of the paddles, which are dipped into the water all at once as the rowers keep time to their songs.
1841_150351_000020_000000 These Indians, as might be supposed, live largely upon fish.
1841_150351_000020_000001 Berries are abundant during the summer and are also much used for food. The clothing of the Indians was originally a sort of blanket made of the woven fibres of cedar bark, or more rarely, of the skins of animals, although among the northern tribes skins were used almost exclusively.
1841_150351_000022_000001 sixty four).
1841_150351_000022_000002 This deformity is produced by binding a piece of board upon the forehead in babyhood and leaving it there while the head is growing.
1841_150351_000023_000000 The villages are located in some protected spot where the canoes can lie in safety.
1841_150351_000023_000001 The buildings are strung along the shore close under the edge of the thick forest and just above the reach of the waves at high tide.
1841_150351_000023_000002 They are very solidly constructed, for these Indians do not move about as much as those farther south where the forests are less dense.
1841_150351_000023_000004 This is sometimes two feet in diameter and from sixty to eighty feet long.
1841_150351_000023_000005 It must require the united strength of many men to roll such a log into position.
1841_150351_000023_000006 Upon the framework thus constructed split cedar boards are fastened, and the building is practically finished.
1841_150351_000023_000007 Such a house is usually occupied by a number of families.
1841_150351_000023_000008 Upon Queen Charlotte Islands there is a dwelling of this kind large enough to hold seven hundred Indians.
1841_150351_000024_000000 The fronts of the houses are ornamented with figures hewn out of wood.
1841_150351_000024_000001 These represent men, birds and animals and have a religious significance.
1841_150351_000024_000002 Sometimes these figures are mounted upon the tops of tall poles.
1841_150351_000025_000000 The "totem pole" is a most interesting affair.
1841_150351_000025_000002 It is one of the finest upon the north coast.
1841_150351_000025_000003 The figures of animals and birds carved upon it represent the mythological ancestors of the family or clan in front of whose abode the pole stands.
1841_150351_000025_000004 The Indians often hunt similar animals to day, but believe that their ancestors had supernatural power which raised them above the ordinary creatures.
1841_150351_000026_000000 The Chinook Indians live upon the lower Columbia.
1841_150351_000026_000001 The name "chinook" has been given to a warm, dry wind which blows down the eastern slope of the Rocky Mountains and out upon the Great Plains.
1841_150351_000026_000002 This wind is so named because it blows from the direction of the Chinook Indians' country.
1841_150351_000026_000003 The "Chinook" jargon is a strange sort of mixed language with which nearly all the tribes of the Northwest are familiar.
1841_150351_000026_000004 It is formed of words from the Chinook language, together with others from different Indian languages, French Canadian, and English.
1841_150351_000026_000005 Through the influence of the trappers and traders the "Chinook" has come into wide use, so that by means of it conversation can be carried on with tribes speaking different languages.
1841_150351_000029_000000 Although there are so many different tribes, with great diversities of language, throughout the West, they were probably all derived from the same source.
1841_150351_000029_000001 As we go north the similarity between the coast Indians and the inhabitants of eastern Asia becomes more noticeable.
1841_150351_000029_000002 It seems almost certain that these American Indians originally came across the narrow strip of water separating Asia from America.
1841_150351_000030_000000 We do not know how long the Indians have occupied our country, but it has probably been several thousand years.
1841_150351_000030_000001 Some of the main groups have undoubtedly been here longer than others.
