1841_159771_000004_000000 Owl Friends
1841_159771_000005_000000 "THERE'S no sense in wasting our time here," said Solomon Owl to his small cousin, Simon Screecher.
1841_159771_000005_000001 "It's a fine night.
1841_159771_000005_000002 The Mice will all be out sooner or later.
1841_159771_000005_000003 Let's go over and sit in that old oak on the edge of the meadow!"
1841_159771_000006_000000 Simon Screecher was more than willing.
1841_159771_000007_000000 Solomon Owl stopped him quickly.
1841_159771_000008_000000 "Don't do that!" he said sharply.
1841_159771_000008_000001 "Do you want to scare the Mice?" Simon Screecher cut his whistle off right in the middle of it.
1841_159771_000009_000000 "I forgot," he murmured.
1841_159771_000009_000002 I don't think there are many Mice left on Farmer Green's place. It's my opinion that they've moved away-most of them.
1841_159771_000009_000003 Or maybe old Rough leg, the Hawk, has caught more than his share.
1841_159771_000010_000001 He was a person of few words.
1841_159771_000010_000002 If anybody asked his opinion he was ready to give it.
1841_159771_000010_000003 But he seldom gave any unsought advice.
1841_159771_000011_000000 "I've about made up my mind," said Simon Screecher, "that I'd move to some other neighborhood.
1841_159771_000011_000001 If I knew where there was good mousing I'd move to morrow."
1841_159771_000012_000000 While he was speaking, Solomon Owl started ever so slightly.
1841_159771_000013_000000 At that moment his cousin began to whistle again.
1841_159771_000014_000000 "Be quiet!" Solomon Owl thundered.
1841_159771_000014_000001 "If I'm not mistaken I heard a squeak.
1841_159771_000014_000002 But no Meadow Mouse will ever venture out of doors if you're going to whistle."
1841_159771_000015_000000 "I forgot," said Simon Screecher once more.
1841_159771_000017_000000 "That's the reason why you can't catch more Mice," Solomon Owl snapped; for he was angry.
1841_159771_000017_000002 But of course you can't surprise them if you tell them you're coming.
1841_159771_000018_000000 Simon Screecher was silenced for the time being.
1841_159771_000019_000000 And it wasn't long before Solomon Owl gave another start.
1841_159771_000020_000000 "There's that squeak again!" he whispered.
1841_159771_000020_000001 "I believe it is getting nearer, too."
1841_159771_000021_000000 Now, Master Meadow Mouse had a tunnel that led right beneath the tree where the two cousins were sitting.
1841_159771_000021_000001 And he had strolled that way after scurrying under the snow when he heard Solomon Owl laughing in the woods earlier in the evening.
1841_159771_000022_000000 It was he that Solomon heard.
1841_159771_000022_000001 It was he that stuck his head out of a hole in the snow and peeped up at the star sprinkled sky.
1841_159771_000023_000001 And he dived out of the old oak straight at Master Meadow Mouse.
1841_159771_000025_000000 "I didn't suppose that chap would be here as soon as this," he gasped. "He must have hurried over here from the woods.
1841_159771_000025_000001 He must be very hungry."
1841_159771_000027_000000 "Missed him-didn't you?" he inquired.
1841_159771_000028_000000 "Yes!"
1841_159771_000029_000000 "Why didn't you grab him out of the snow?" Simon asked.
1841_159771_000029_000001 "What are your claws for?
1841_159771_000029_000002 What's your beak for?"
1841_159771_000030_000000 "I couldn't dig him out," Solomon Owl replied.
1841_159771_000030_000001 "The snow is three feet deep.
1841_159771_000030_000002 And it has seven different crusts, one under another."
1841_159771_000031_000000 "This is a hard winter," said Simon Screecher.
1841_159771_000031_000001 "I wish I'd gone South last fall.
