1841_159771_000035_000000 Eating a Tree
1841_159771_000036_000000 AS SIMON SCREECHER remarked to his cousin, Solomon Owl, it was a hard winter.
1841_159771_000036_000001 The snow was deep.
1841_159771_000036_000002 The days were cold.
1841_159771_000036_000003 And the nights were colder.
1841_159771_000036_000004 And, worst of all, food became scarce.
1841_159771_000036_000005 It seemed as if there wasn't anything to eat anywhere except at the farm buildings, which Farmer Green had stuffed full of hay and grain during the summer and autumn.
1841_159771_000036_000006 Many of the forest folk stole down from Blue Mountain after nightfall and visited the farmyard in the hope of getting a bite of something or other.
1841_159771_000037_000001 He had stored away a stock of food.
1841_159771_000037_000002 But it hadn't been big enough.
1841_159771_000037_000003 And that was a great mistake.
1841_159771_000037_000004 Master Meadow Mouse promised himself that he would not repeat it another time.
1841_159771_000037_000005 Unfortunately, all the promises in the world wouldn't give him a square meal when he needed one.
1841_159771_000039_000000 "This is my first winter," Master Meadow Mouse explained.
1841_159771_000040_000000 "That's easy," his cousin answered.
1841_159771_000040_000001 "Get more!" And then he hurried away, for he had important business to attend to.
1841_159771_000041_000001 It was hard to follow his cousin through the winding galleries beneath the snow.
1841_159771_000041_000002 Several times Master Meadow Mouse took the wrong turn and had to retrace his steps. But at last he found his busy cousin again.
1841_159771_000042_000000 "You advised me to get more food," said Master Meadow Mouse.
1841_159771_000042_000001 "But you didn't tell me where to get it."
1841_159771_000043_000000 "In the orchard!" his cousin cried.
1841_159771_000043_000001 And then he hurried away again.
1841_159771_000044_000000 "I wish he'd wait a minute," Master Meadow Mouse grumbled as he tore after his cousin once more.
1841_159771_000044_000001 "I don't feel like running.
1841_159771_000045_000000 The cousin seemed surprised when Master Meadow Mouse overtook him.
1841_159771_000047_000001 "I've been chasing you.
1841_159771_000047_000002 I want you to tell me what I'll find to eat when I go to the orchard."
1841_159771_000048_000000 "That's easy," his cousin replied.
1841_159771_000048_000001 "Trees!" Having said those three words he dashed off again even faster than before.
1841_159771_000049_000000 "Trees!" Master Meadow Mouse echoed.
1841_159771_000049_000001 "I can't eat trees.
1841_159771_000049_000003 There must be something that my cousin forgot to explain.
1841_159771_000049_000004 So I suppose I'll have to run after him again and ask him what he meant."
1841_159771_000050_000000 The fourth time that Master Meadow Mouse found his cousin he took no chances.
1841_159771_000050_000001 He caught his cousin by his tail and held on firmly.
1841_159771_000051_000000 "You're not going to get away from me till I've found out what I want to know," he declared.
1841_159771_000051_000001 "How can I eat a tree?" Master Meadow Mouse demanded.
1841_159771_000052_000000 "You can't!" his cousin replied, struggling desperately to free himself, for he was too busy to stop long.
1841_159771_000053_000000 "Then explain what you mean!" Master Meadow Mouse cried.
1841_159771_000054_000000 "Eat the bark!" his cousin answered.
1841_159771_000055_000000 Then-and not till then-did Master Meadow Mouse let him go.
1841_159771_000056_000000 Master Meadow Mouse chased his cousin no more, but hurried away to Farmer Green's orchard, where he gnawed a ring all the way around one of the young fruit trees, at the top of the snow.
1841_159771_000056_000001 It was the first big meal he had enjoyed for weeks.
1841_159771_000056_000002 And he went home feeling that the winter was not so hard as he had thought, after all.
1841_159771_000057_000000 But Farmer Green didn't agree with him.
1841_159771_000057_000001 When he happened to go into the orchard one day, later, and saw tree after tree ruined, he was very, very much displeased.
1841_159771_000058_000000 "I ought to have put wire netting around those young trees," he told the hired man.
1841_159771_000058_000001 "This is what comes of a hard winter."
1841_159771_000061_000000 twenty one
1841_159771_000062_000000 A Cold Dip
1841_159771_000063_000000 IN one way peter Mink was like Master Meadow Mouse.
1841_159771_000063_000001 He enjoyed swimming. And he spent a great deal of his time along the streams that threaded their way through Pleasant Valley.
1841_159771_000063_000002 Sometimes peter dawdled on the banks of Swift River.
1841_159771_000063_000003 Sometimes he lingered for days in the neighborhood of Black Creek.
1841_159771_000063_000004 Nor did he disdain so small a stream as the brook that crossed the meadow.
1841_159771_000063_000005 It was deep enough for a swim.
1841_159771_000063_000006 And he knew that muskrats lived under its banks.
1841_159771_000063_000008 If it hadn't been for the meadow mice perhaps he wouldn't have visited the brook so often.
1841_159771_000064_000001 So he ran one of his many snow tunnels to the brook, making a little opening that led under the ice, where the water had fallen away and left a cavern.
1841_159771_000064_000002 Just because there was skating for Johnnie Green on top of the brook it mustn't be supposed that Master Meadow Mouse wasn't going to have a swim when he wanted one.
1841_159771_000065_000000 When peter Mink wandered along a stream in winter he preferred to travel under the ice, rather than walk upon the upper side of it.
1841_159771_000065_000001 It made little difference to him whether there was a dry strip along the edge of the stream, where he could steal silently along without wetting his feet.
1841_159771_000065_000002 When he found no place to walk, he swam.
1841_159771_000067_000000 To be sure, Master Meadow Mouse tried to be careful.
1841_159771_000067_000001 Before he crept from the end of his tunnel, he stuck his head out and looked up and down and all around.
1841_159771_000067_000002 He peeped under the bank of the brook.
1841_159771_000067_000003 He even stared into the water.
1841_159771_000067_000004 And then-if he saw nobody that was fiercer than Paddy Muskrat-only then would he venture to skip to the water's edge and plunge in.
1841_159771_000068_000000 To tell the truth, Master Meadow Mouse always felt safer when one of the Muskrat family happened to be taking a swim at the same time.
1841_159771_000068_000001 For the Muskrats all had a warning signal that told everybody when there was danger.
1841_159771_000068_000002 When one of them caught sight of peter Mink he never failed-if he was in the water-to give a loud slap upon the surface with his tail.
1841_159771_000069_000000 Master Meadow Mouse always had one ear that was listening for that slap. And when it sounded he never waited an instant, but darted into his tunnel without even stopping to shake the water off his coat.
1841_159771_000069_000001 He said that he could dry his coat after he reached home; while if he stopped to dry it at the edge of the brook perhaps he'd never get home at all.
1841_159771_000070_000000 You might think that now and then he would have said to himself, "Oh, I won't bother to look for peter Mink to day.
1841_159771_000070_000001 He must be miles away.
1841_159771_000070_000002 I'll step right out of my tunnel and have my swim without taking a look see first." But Master Meadow Mouse was never so lazy as that.
1841_159771_000070_000003 And the day came at last when it was well worth his while to take the little extra trouble of peeping out before he had his swim.
1841_159771_000071_000000 For Master Meadow Mouse caught a glimpse of a snakelike head that darted out from under the bank of the brook and darted back again, out of sight.
1841_179183_000008_000000 THE SEEING HAND
1841_179183_000009_000000 I
1841_179183_000011_000001 He was rolling on the grass, with pleasure in every muscle and limb.
1841_179183_000011_000002 I wanted to catch a picture of him in my fingers, and I touched him as lightly as I would cobwebs; but lo, his fat body revolved, stiffened and solidified into an upright position, and his tongue gave my hand a lick!
1841_179183_000011_000004 He loved it with his tail, with his paw, with his tongue.
1841_179183_000011_000005 If he could speak, I believe he would say with me that paradise is attained by touch; for in touch is all love and intelligence.
1841_179183_000012_000000 This small incident started me on a chat about hands, and if my chat is fortunate I have to thank my dog star.
1841_179183_000012_000001 In any case, it is pleasant to have something to talk about that no one else has monopolized; it is like making a new path in the trackless woods, blazing the trail where no foot has pressed before.
1841_179183_000012_000003 But at the very outset we encounter a difficulty.
1841_179183_000012_000004 You are so accustomed to light, I fear you will stumble when I try to guide you through the land of darkness and silence.
1841_179183_000012_000005 The blind are not supposed to be the best of guides.
1841_179183_000012_000006 Still, though I cannot warrant not to lose you, I promise that you shall not be led into fire or water, or fall into a deep pit.
1841_179183_000012_000007 If you will follow me patiently, you will find that "there's a sound so fine, nothing lives 'twixt it and silence," and that there is more meant in things than meets the eye.
1841_179183_000013_000001 In large measure we travel the same highways, read the same books, speak the same language, yet our experiences are different.
1841_179183_000013_000002 All my comings and goings turn on the hand as on a pivot.
1841_179183_000013_000003 It is the hand that binds me to the world of men and women.
1841_179183_000013_000004 The hand is my feeler with which I reach through isolation and darkness and seize every pleasure, every activity that my fingers encounter.
1841_179183_000013_000005 With the dropping of a little word from another's hand into mine, a slight flutter of the fingers, began the intelligence, the joy, the fullness of my life.
1841_179183_000013_000006 Like Job, I feel as if a hand had made me, fashioned me together round about and moulded my very soul.
1841_179183_000014_000000 In all my experiences and thoughts I am conscious of a hand.
1841_179183_000014_000002 You might as well say that a sight which makes you glad, or a blow which brings the stinging tears to your eyes, is unreal as to say that those impressions are unreal which I have accumulated by means of touch.
1841_179183_000015_000000 Ideas make the world we live in, and impressions furnish ideas.
1841_179183_000015_000003 Remember that you, dependent on your sight, do not realize how many things are tangible.
1841_179183_000015_000004 All palpable things are mobile or rigid, solid or liquid, big or small, warm or cold, and these qualities are variously modified.
1841_179183_000015_000005 The coolness of a water lily rounding into bloom is different from the coolness of an evening wind in summer, and different again from the coolness of the rain that soaks into the hearts of growing things and gives them life and body.
1841_179183_000015_000007 The hardness of the rock is to the hardness of wood what a man's deep bass is to a woman's voice when it is low.
1841_179183_000015_000008 What I call beauty I find in certain combinations of all these qualities, and is largely derived from the flow of curved and straight lines which is over all things.
1841_179183_000017_000001 It symbolizes duty.
1841_179183_000017_000003 When I have something to do that must not be set aside, I feel as if I were going forward in a straight line, bound to arrive somewhere, or go on forever without swerving to the right or to the left.
1841_179183_000018_000000 That is what it means.
1841_179183_000018_000001 To escape this moralizing you should ask, "How does the straight line feel?"
1841_179183_000018_000002 It feels, as I suppose it looks, straight-a dull thought drawn out endlessly.
1841_179183_000018_000003 Eloquence to the touch resides not in straight lines, but in unstraight lines, or in many curved and straight lines together.
1841_179183_000018_000004 They appear and disappear, are now deep, now shallow, now broken off or lengthened or swelling.
1841_179183_000018_000005 They rise and sink beneath my fingers, they are full of sudden starts and pauses, and their variety is inexhaustible and wonderful.
1841_179183_000018_000006 So you see I am not shut out from the region of the beautiful, though my hand cannot perceive the brilliant colours in the sunset or on the mountain, or reach into the blue depths of the sky.
1841_179183_000019_000001 A tangible object passes complete into my brain with the warmth of life upon it, and occupies the same place that it does in space; for, without egotism, the mind is as large as the universe.
1841_179183_000019_000002 When I think of hills, I think of the upward strength I tread upon.
1841_179183_000019_000003 When water is the object of my thought, I feel the cool shock of the plunge and the quick yielding of the waves that crisp and curl and ripple about my body.
1841_179183_000019_000004 The pleasing changes of rough and smooth, pliant and rigid, curved and straight in the bark and branches of a tree give the truth to my hand.
1841_179183_000019_000007 My fingers are tickled to delight by the soft ripple of a baby's laugh, and find amusement in the lusty crow of the barnyard autocrat.
1841_179183_000019_000008 Once I had a pet rooster that used to perch on my knee and stretch his neck and crow.
1841_179183_000019_000009 A bird in my hand was then worth two in the-barnyard.
1841_179183_000020_000000 My fingers cannot, of course, get the impression of a large whole at a glance; but I feel the parts, and my mind puts them together.
1841_179183_000020_000001 I move around my house, touching object after object in order, before I can form an idea of the entire house.
1841_179183_000020_000002 In other people's houses I can touch only what is shown to me-the chief objects of interest, carvings on the wall, or a curious architectural feature, exhibited like the family album.
1841_179183_000020_000003 Therefore a house with which I am not familiar has for me, at first, no general effect or harmony of detail.
1841_179183_000020_000004 It is not a complete conception, but a collection of object impressions which, as they come to me, are disconnected and isolated.
1841_179183_000020_000005 But my mind is full of associations, sensations, theories, and with them it constructs the house.
1841_179183_000020_000007 The silent worker is imagination which decrees reality out of chaos.
1841_179183_000021_000000 Without imagination what a poor thing my world would be!
1841_179183_000021_000001 My garden would be a silent patch of earth strewn with sticks of a variety of shapes and smells.
1841_179183_000021_000002 But when the eye of my mind is opened to its beauty, the bare ground brightens beneath my feet, and the hedge row bursts into leaf, and the rose tree shakes its fragrance everywhere.
1841_179183_000021_000003 I know how budding trees look, and I enter into the amorous joy of the mating birds, and this is the miracle of imagination.
1841_179183_000022_000001 Although, compared with the life warm, mobile face of a friend, the marble is cold and pulseless and unresponsive, yet it is beautiful to my hand.
1841_179183_000022_000002 Its flowing curves and bendings are a real pleasure; only breath is wanting; but under the spell of the imagination the marble thrills and becomes the divine reality of the ideal. Imagination puts a sentiment into every line and curve, and the statue in my touch is indeed the goddess herself who breathes and moves and enchants.
1841_179183_000023_000000 It is true, however, that some sculptures, even recognized masterpieces, do not please my hand.
1841_179183_000023_000001 When I touch what there is of the Winged Victory, it reminds me at first of a headless, limbless dream that flies towards me in an unrestful sleep.
1841_179183_000023_000002 The garments of the Victory thrust stiffly out behind, and do not resemble garments that I have felt flying, fluttering, folding, spreading in the wind.
1841_179183_000024_000000 I find in a beautiful statue perfection of bodily form, the qualities of balance and completeness.
1841_179183_000025_000000 So imagination crowns the experience of my hands.
