2836_5355_000094_000001 Sir Francis left the room, but not immediately the house.
2836_5355_000094_000003 Then he paid a visit to the landlord, and handed him, likewise a year's rent in advance, making the same remark.
2836_5355_000094_000004 After that, he ordered dinner at a hotel, and the same night he and Pierre departed on their journey home again, Sir Francis thanking his lucky star that he had so easily got rid of a vexatious annoyance.
2836_5355_000095_000000 And Lady Isabel?
2836_5355_000095_000001 She passed her evening alone, sitting in the same place, close to the fire and the sparks.
2836_5355_000096_000000 When Lady Isabel lay down to rest, she sank into a somewhat calmer sleep than she had known of late; also into a dream.
2836_5355_000096_000001 She thought she was back at East Lynne-not back, in one sense, but that she seemed never to have gone away from it-walking in the flower garden with mr Carlyle, while the three children played on the lawn.
2836_5355_000096_000002 Her arm was within her husband's, and he was relating something to her.
2836_5355_000096_000003 What the news was, she could not remember afterward, excepting that it was connected with the office and old mr Dill, and that mr Carlyle laughed when he told it.
2836_5355_000096_000004 They appeared to be interrupted by the crying of Archibald; and, in turning to the lawn to ask what was the matter, she awoke.
2836_5355_000096_000005 Alas!
2836_5355_000096_000006 It was the actual crying of her own child which awoke her-this last child-the ill fated little being in the cradle beside her.
2836_5355_000096_000007 But, for a single instant, she forgot recent events and doings, she believed she was indeed in her happy home at East Lynne, a proud woman, an honored wife.
2843_152918_000000_000003 They had undergone a remarkable change since our arrival at the Butcher's Shop; they now wandered about, fat, sleek, and contented, and their former voracity had completely disappeared.
2843_152918_000000_000004 As regards ourselves, a day or two longer made no difference; our most important article of diet, the pemmican, was practically left untouched, as for the time being dog had completely taken its place.
2843_152918_000000_000005 There was thus no great sign of depression to be noticed when we came back into the tent after finishing our work, and had to while away the time.
2843_152918_000000_000006 As I went in, I could descry Wisting a little way off kneeling on the ground, and engaged in the manufacture of cutlets.
2843_152918_000000_000008 The north-east wind whistled and howled, the air was thick with driving snow, and Wisting was not to be envied.
2843_152918_000000_000010 During the evening the wind moderated a little, and went more to the east; we went to sleep with the best hopes for the following day.
2843_152918_000001_000000 saturday november twenty fifth, came; it was a grand day in many respects.
2843_152918_000001_000001 I had already seen proofs on several occasions of the kind of men my comrades were, but their conduct that day was such that I shall never forget it, to whatever age I may live.
2843_152918_000001_000002 In the course of the night the wind had gone back to the north, and increased to a gale.
2843_152918_000001_000003 It was blowing and snowing so that when we came out in the morning we could not see the sledges; they were half snowed under.
2843_152918_000001_000007 We had all taken a turn outside to look at the weather, and were sitting on our sleeping bags discussing the poor prospect.
2843_152918_000001_000009 This is the fifth day, and it's blowing worse than ever." We all agreed.
2843_152918_000001_000012 "Shall we try it?" No sooner was the proposal submitted than it was accepted unanimously and with acclamation.
2843_152918_000001_000014 All the qualities that I most admire in a man were clearly shown at that juncture: courage and dauntlessness, without boasting or big words.
2843_152918_000001_000015 Amid joking and chaff, everything was packed, and then -- out into the blizzard.
2843_152918_000002_000000 It was practically impossible to keep one's eyes open; the fine drift snow penetrated everywhere, and at times one had a feeling of being blind.
2843_152918_000002_000001 The tent was not only drifted up, but covered with ice, and in taking it down we had to handle it with care. so as not to break it in pieces.
2843_152918_000002_000002 The dogs were not much inclined to start, and it took time to get them into their harness, but at last we were ready.
2843_152918_000002_000003 One more glance over the camping ground to see that nothing we ought to have with us had been forgotten.
2843_152918_000002_000004 The fourteen dogs' carcasses that were left were piled up in a heap, and Hassel's sledge was set up against it as a mark.
2843_152918_000002_000005 The spare sets of dog harness, some Alpine ropes, and all our crampons for ice work, which we now thought would not be required, were left behind.
2843_152918_000002_000006 The last thing to be done was planting a broken ski upright by the side of the depot.
2843_152918_000002_000007 It was Wisting who did this, thinking, presumably, that an extra mark would do no harm.
2843_152918_000002_000008 That it was a happy thought the future will show.
2843_152918_000003_000000 And then we were off: It was a hard pull to begin with, both for men and beasts, as the high sastrugi continued towards the south, and made it extremely difficult to advance.
2843_152918_000003_000002 We went on like this, slowly enough, but the main thing was that we made progress.
2843_152918_000003_000005 Meanwhile the sastrugi grew smaller and smaller, and finally they disappeared altogether, and the surface became quite flat.
2843_152918_000003_000008 The surface, which had become perfectly level, had the appearance at times of sinking; in any case, one would have thought so from the pace of the sledges.
2843_152918_000003_000010 The wind aft, no doubt, helped the pace somewhat, but it alone could not account for the change.
2843_152918_000004_000002 So far the incline had not been so great as to cause uneasiness, but if it seriously began to go downhill, we should have to stop and camp.
2843_152918_000004_000004 We might risk falling into some chasm before we had time to pull up.
2843_152918_000005_000001 Strictly speaking, I should now have been going in advance, but the uneven surface at the start and the rapid pace afterwards had made it impossible to walk as fast the dogs could pull.
2843_152918_000005_000003 Suddenly I saw Hanssen's dogs shoot ahead, and downhill they went at the wildest pace, Wisting after them.
2843_152918_000005_000004 I shouted to Hanssen to stop, and he succeeded in doing so by twisting his sledge.
2843_152918_000005_000005 The others, who were following, stopped when they came up to him.
2843_152918_000005_000006 We were in the middle of a fairly steep descent; what there might be below was not easy to decide, nor would we try to find out in that weather.
2843_152918_000005_000009 We trampled down a place for the tent in the loose snow, and soon got it up.
2843_152918_000005_000010 It was not a long day's march that we had done -- eleven and three quarter miles -- but we had put an end to our stay at the Butcher's Shop, and that was a great thing.
2843_152918_000005_000011 The boiling point test that evening showed that we were ten thousand three hundred feet above the sea, and that we had thus gone down six hundred twenty feet from the Butcher's.
2843_152918_000005_000012 We turned in and went to sleep.
2843_152918_000005_000015 We therefore all slept with one eye open, and we knew well that nothing could happen without our noticing it.
2843_152918_000006_000002 The sun showed as yet like a pat of butter, and had not succeeded in dispersing the thick mists; the wind had dropped somewhat, but was still fairly strong.
2843_152918_000006_000003 This is, after all, the worst part of one's job -- turning out of one's good, warm sleeping bag, and standing outside for some time in thin clothes, watching the weather.
2843_152918_000006_000004 We knew by experience that a gleam like this, a clearing in the weather, might come suddenly, and then one had to be on the spot.
2843_152918_000006_000005 The gleam came; it did not last long, but long enough.
2843_152918_000006_000007 The descent on the south was too abrupt, but on the south-east it was better and more gradual, and ended in a wide, level tract.
2843_152918_000006_000011 Well content with our morning's work, we turned in again and slept till six a m, when we began our morning preparations.
2843_152918_000006_000012 The weather, which had somewhat improved during the night, had now broken loose again, and the north easter was doing all it could.
2843_152918_000007_000000 After putting ample brakes on the sledge runners, we started off downhill in a south easterly direction.
2843_152918_000007_000002 The descent was easy and smooth, and we reached the plain without any adventure.
2843_152918_000007_000007 If our progress was nevertheless slow and difficult, this was due to the wretched going, which was real torture to all of us.
2843_152918_000007_000008 A sledge journey through the Sahara could not have offered a worse surface to move over.
2843_152918_000008_000000 The weather improved in the course of the day, and when we camped in the afternoon it looked quite smiling.
2843_152918_000008_000003 The distance according to our three sledge meters was eighteen and a half miles; taking the bad going into consideration, we had reason to be well satisfied with it.
2843_152918_000008_000004 Our altitude came out at nine thousand four hundred seventy five feet above the sea, or a drop of eight hundred twenty five feet in the course of the day.
2843_152918_000008_000005 This surprised me greatly.
2843_152918_000008_000006 What did it mean?
2843_152918_000008_000008 Something extraordinary must await us farther on, but, what?
2843_152918_000009_000000 november twenty seventh did not bring us the desired weather; the night was filled with sharp gusts from the north; the morning came with a slack wind, but accompanied by mist and snowfall.
2843_152918_000009_000002 The surface remained about the same -- possibly rather more undulating.
2843_152918_000009_000004 Luckily for us, the snowfall of the last few days had filled these up, so as to present a level surface.
2843_152918_000009_000005 It was heavy going, though better than on the previous day.
2843_152918_000010_000000 As we were advancing, still blindly, and fretting at the persistently thick weather, one of us suddenly called out: "Hullo, look there!" A wild, dark summit rose high out of the mass of fog to the east south-east.
2843_152918_000010_000001 It was not far away -- on the contrary, it seemed threateningly near and right over us.
2843_152918_000010_000002 We stopped and looked at the imposing sight, but Nature did not expose her objects of interest for long.
2843_152918_000010_000008 We continued our course in the constant expectation of finding some surprise or other in our line of route.
2843_152918_000010_000009 The air ahead of us was as black as pitch, as though it concealed something.
2843_152918_000010_000010 It could not be a storm, or it would have been already upon us.
2843_152918_000010_000012 Our day's march was eighteen and a half miles.
2843_152918_000011_000000 I see that my diary for november twenty eighth does not begin very promisingly: "Fog, fog -- and again fog.
2843_152918_000011_000001 Also fine falling snow, which makes the going impossible.
2843_152918_000011_000002 Poor beasts, they have toiled hard to get the sledges forward to day." But the day did not turn out so badly after all, as we worked our way out of this uncertainty and found out what was behind the pitch dark clouds.
2843_152918_000011_000004 From this mass, right across our course, ran a great, ancient glacier; the sun shone down upon it and showed us a surface full of huge irregularities.
2843_152918_000011_000005 On the side nearest to the mountain these disturbances were such that a hasty glance was enough to show us the impossibility of advancing that way.
2843_152918_000011_000006 But right in our line of route -- straight on to the glacier -- it looked, as far as we could see, as though we could get along.
2843_152918_000011_000007 The fog came and went, and we had to take advantage of the clear intervals to get our bearings.
2843_152918_000011_000008 It would, no doubt, have been better if we could have halted, set up our tent, and waited for decently clear weather, so that we might survey the ground at our ease and choose the best way.
2843_152918_000011_000011 That question was unanswerable; possibly a week, or even a fortnight, and we had no time for that.
2843_152918_000012_000000 What we could see of the glacier appeared to be pretty steep; but it was only between the south and south-east, under the new land, that the fog now and again lifted sufficiently to enable us to see anything.
2843_152918_000012_000001 From the south round to the west the fog lay as thick as gruel.
2843_152918_000012_000003 It was to the south we had to go, and there it was possible to go forward a little way.
2843_152918_000012_000005 It was our intention to lighten our sledges before tackling the glacier; from the little we could see of it, it was plain enough that we should have stiff work.
2843_152918_000012_000006 It was therefore important to have as little as possible on the sledges.
2843_152918_000013_000000 We set to work at once to build the depot; the snow here was excellent for this purpose -- as hard as glass.
2843_152918_000013_000001 In a short time an immense erection of adamantine blocks of snow rose into the air, containing provisions for five men for six days and for eighteen dogs for five days.
2843_152918_000013_000002 A number of small articles were also left behind.
2843_152918_000014_000001 It appeared to be quite isolated, and to consist of four mountains; one of these -- Mount Helmer Hanssen -- lay separated from the rest.
2843_152918_000014_000003 Behind this group the air had been heavy and black the whole time, showing that more land must be concealed there.
2843_152918_000014_000008 For that matter, the site of the depot was so well marked by its position under the foot of the glacier that we agreed it would be impossible to miss it.
2843_152918_000015_000007 We examined the compass from time to time, and went forward cautiously.
2843_152918_000016_000004 We kept it going, however, by using the utmost caution.
2843_152918_000016_000005 Wisting came near to sounding the depth of one of these dangerous crevasses with sledge, dogs and all, as the bridge he was about to cross gave way.
2843_152918_000016_000006 Thanks to his presence of mind and a lightning like movement -- some would call it luck -- he managed to save himself.
2843_152918_000016_000007 In this way we worked up about two hundred feet, but then we came upon such a labyrinth of yawning chasms and open abysses that we could not move.
2843_152918_000016_000008 There was nothing to be done but to find the least disturbed spot, and set the tent there.
2843_152918_000017_000000 As soon as this was done Hanssen and I set out to explore.
2843_152918_000017_000001 We were roped, and therefore safe enough.
2843_152918_000017_000002 It required some study to find a way out of the trap we had run ourselves into.
2843_152918_000017_000008 Thank God we were not here while this was going on, I thought to myself, as I stood looking out over this battlefield; it must have been a spectacle like doomsday, and not on a small scale either.
2843_152918_000017_000009 To advance in that direction, then, was hopeless, but that was no great matter, since our way was to the south.
2843_152918_000018_000002 We saw well enough that this would be a difficult place to pass with sledges and dogs, but in default of anything better it would have to be done.
2843_152918_000018_000004 The fog prevented our seeing far, but the immediate surroundings were enough to convince us that with caution we could beat up farther.
2843_152918_000019_000001 The language we used about the glacier as we went was not altogether complimentary; we had endless tacking and turning to get on.
2843_152918_000019_000003 Can anyone be surprised that we called it the Devil's Glacier?
2843_152918_000019_000004 At any rate, our companions acknowledged the justness of the name with ringing acclamations when we told them of it.
2843_152918_000020_000002 This formation -- like every -- thing else on the glacier was obviously very old, and for the most part filled with snow.
2843_152918_000021_000000 Our companions were no less pleased with the news we brought of our prospects.
2843_152918_000021_000001 Our altitude that evening was eight thousand six hundred fifty feet above the sea -- that is to say, at the foot of the glacier we had reached an altitude of eight thousand four hundred fifty feet, or a drop from the Butcher's of two thousand five hundred seventy feet.
2843_152918_000022_000007 The beacons we had put up came to our aid, and for our final success we owe a deep debt of gratitude to our prudence and thoughtfulness in adopting this expedient.
2843_152918_000024_000001 They had to drive with great circumspection and patience to grapple with the kind of ground we had before us; a slight mistake might be enough to send both sledge and dogs with lightning rapidity into the next world.
2843_152918_000024_000002 It took, nevertheless, a remarkably short time to cover the distance we had explored on the previous evening; before we knew it, we were at Hell's Gate.
2843_152918_000025_000002 This was the photographer, who, in passing over this snow bridge, struck his ski into it to try the strength of the support.
2843_152918_000025_000003 Close to the tracks can be seen an open piece of the crevasse; it is a pale blue at the top, but ends in the deepest black -- in a bottomless abyss.
2843_152918_000025_000005 The two small black figures in the distance, on the right, are Hassel and I, who are reconnoitring ahead.
2843_152918_000026_000001 But, taking into account all the turns and circuits we had been compelled to make, it was not so short after all.
2843_152918_000026_000005 It was a fairy landscape in blue and white, red and black, a play of colours that defies description.
2843_152918_000027_000002 Some were sharp, but most were long and rounded.
2893_139310_000001_000000 CHAPTER nine
2893_139310_000002_000000 THE PEOPLE MARCH
2893_139310_000003_000000 He became aware of someone urging a glass of clear fluid upon his attention, looked up and discovered this was a dark young man in a yellow garment.
2893_139310_000003_000001 He took the dose forthwith, and in a moment he was glowing.
2893_139310_000003_000003 This man was shouting close to his ear and yet what was said was indistinct because of the tremendous uproar from the great theatre.
2893_139310_000003_000004 Behind the man was a girl in a silvery grey robe, whom Graham, even in this confusion, perceived to be beautiful.
2893_139310_000003_000005 Her dark eyes, full of wonder and curiosity, were fixed on him, her lips trembled apart. A partially opened door gave a glimpse of the crowded hall, and admitted a vast uneven tumult, a hammering, clapping and shouting that died away and began again, and rose to a thunderous pitch, and so continued intermittently all the time that Graham remained in the little room.
2893_139310_000003_000006 He watched the lips of the man in black and gathered that he was making some explanation.
2893_139310_000004_000000 He stared stupidly for some moments at these things and then stood up abruptly; he grasped the arm of this shouting person.
2893_139310_000005_000000 "Tell me!" he cried.
2893_139310_000006_000000 The others came nearer to hear his words.
2893_139310_000007_000000 "They have told him nothing!" cried the girl.
2893_139310_000008_000000 "Tell me, tell me!" cried Graham.
2893_139310_000009_000001 You are owner of the world."
2893_139310_000010_000000 He did not believe he heard aright.
2893_139310_000010_000001 He resisted the persuasion.
2893_139310_000010_000003 He lifted his voice again.
2893_139310_000010_000004 "I have been awake three days-a prisoner three days.
2893_139310_000011_000000 "Yes," said the younger man.
2893_139310_000012_000000 "And those who meet in the great hall with the white Atlas?
2893_139310_000012_000001 How does it concern me?
2893_139310_000012_000005 I have gone mad....
2893_139310_000012_000007 Why should they try to drug me?"
2893_139310_000013_000000 "To keep you insensible," said the man in yellow.
2893_139310_000013_000001 "To prevent your interference."
2893_139310_000015_000001 "The world is on your shoulders.
2893_139310_000015_000002 They rule it in your name."
2893_139310_000017_000000 Graham stood, his intelligence clinging helplessly to the thing he had just heard.
2893_139310_000017_000001 "The Council," he repeated blankly, and then snatched at a name that had struck him.
2893_139310_000019_000000 "In my name?--And you?
2893_139310_000019_000001 Why is he not here?"
2893_139310_000020_000000 "He-has deputed us.
2893_139310_000020_000001 I am his brother-his half brother, Lincoln.
2893_139310_000020_000004 He is at the wind vane offices directing.
2893_139310_000021_000001 "They have ruled, crushed, tyrannised.
2893_139310_000021_000002 At last even-"
2893_139310_000022_000001 My name!
2893_139310_000022_000002 Master?"
2893_139310_000023_000001 "No one expected you to wake.
2893_139310_000023_000002 No one expected you to wake.
2893_139310_000023_000003 They were cunning.
2893_139310_000023_000004 Damned tyrants!
2893_139310_000025_000000 "Ostrog is at the wind vane offices ready-.
2893_139310_000026_000000 The man who had called himself Lincoln came close to him.
2893_139310_000026_000002 Trust him.
2893_139310_000026_000006 Then-"
2893_139310_000028_000000 "We have arms," cried Lincoln.
2893_139310_000028_000001 "We have plans.
2893_139310_000028_000002 A leader.
2893_139310_000028_000003 Their police have gone from the streets and are massed in the-" (inaudible).
2893_139310_000029_000000 "Hear the people calling to you!"
2893_139310_000030_000000 Graham's mind was like a night of moon and swift clouds, now dark and hopeless, now clear and ghastly.
2893_139310_000030_000001 He was Master of the Earth, he was a man sodden with thawing snow.
2893_139310_000030_000003 The other side had imprisoned him, debated his death.
2893_139310_000030_000004 These shouting thousands beyond the little doorway had rescued him.
2893_139310_000030_000005 But why these things should be so he could not understand.
2893_139310_000031_000000 The door opened, Lincoln's voice was swept away and drowned, and a rash of people followed on the heels of the tumult.
2893_139310_000031_000001 These intruders came towards him and Lincoln gesticulating.
2893_139310_000031_000002 The voices without explained their soundless lips.
2893_139310_000031_000003 "Show us the Sleeper, show us the Sleeper!" was the burden of the uproar.
2893_139310_000031_000004 Men were bawling for "Order!
2893_139310_000031_000005 Silence!"
2893_139310_000032_000001 He met the wonder and expectation of the girl's eyes.
2893_139310_000032_000002 What did these people expect from him.
2893_139310_000032_000003 He was dimly aware that the tumult outside had changed its character, was in some way beating, marching.
2893_139310_000032_000004 His own mind, too, changed.
2893_139310_000032_000006 But a moment that was near to panic passed.
2893_139310_000032_000007 He tried to make audible inquiries of what was required of him.
2893_139310_000033_000000 Lincoln was shouting in his ear, but Graham was deafened to that.
2893_139310_000033_000002 He perceived what had happened to the uproar.
2893_139310_000033_000003 The whole mass of people was chanting together.
2893_139310_000033_000004 It was not simply a song, the voices were gathered together and upborne by a torrent of instrumental music, music like the music of an organ, a woven texture of sounds, full of trumpets, full of flaunting banners, full of the march and pageantry of opening war.
2893_139310_000033_000005 And the feet of the people were beating time-tramp, tramp.
2893_139310_000034_000001 He obeyed mechanically.
2893_139310_000034_000002 The strength of that chant took hold of him, stirred him, emboldened him.
2893_139310_000035_000000 "Wave your arm to them," said Lincoln.
2893_139310_000035_000001 "Wave your arm to them."
2893_139310_000036_000000 "This," said a voice on the other side, "he must have this." Arms were about his neck detaining him in the doorway, and a black subtly folding mantle hung from his shoulders.
2893_139310_000036_000001 He threw his arm free of this and followed Lincoln.
2893_139310_000036_000002 He perceived the girl in grey close to him, her face lit, her gesture onward.
2893_139310_000036_000004 He emerged in the alcove again.
2893_139310_000036_000005 Incontinently the mounting waves of the song broke upon his appearing, and flashed up into a foam of shouting. Guided by Lincoln's hand he marched obliquely across the centre of the stage facing the people.
2893_139310_000037_000000 The hall was a vast and intricate space-galleries, balconies, broad spaces of amphitheatral steps, and great archways.
2893_139310_000037_000001 Far away, high up, seemed the mouth of a huge passage full of struggling humanity.
2893_139310_000037_000003 Individual figures sprang out of the tumult, impressed him momentarily, and lost definition again. Close to the platform swayed a beautiful fair woman, carried by three men, her hair across her face and brandishing a green staff.
2893_139310_000037_000006 The multitude were beating time with their feet-marking time, tramp, tramp, tramp, tramp.
2893_139310_000037_000008 He raised his arm, and the roaring was redoubled.
2893_139310_000037_000010 He waved his arm again and pointed to the archway, shouting "Onward!"
2893_139310_000037_000011 They were no longer marking time, they were marching; tramp, tramp, tramp, tramp.
2893_139310_000037_000012 In that host were bearded men, old men, youths, fluttering robed bare armed women, girls.
2893_139310_000037_000015 A monstrous black banner jerked its way to the right.
2893_139310_000037_000016 He perceived a blue clad negro, a shrivelled woman in yellow, then a group of tall fair haired, white faced, blue clad men pushed theatrically past him.
2893_139310_000037_000017 He noted two Chinamen.
2893_139310_000037_000018 A tall, sallow, dark haired, shining eyed youth, white clad from top to toe, clambered up towards the platform shouting loyally, and sprang down again and receded, looking backward.
2893_139310_000037_000019 Heads, shoulders, hands clutching weapons, all were swinging with those marching cadences.
2893_139310_000038_000000 Faces came out of the confusion to him as he stood there, eyes met his and passed and vanished.
2893_139310_000038_000001 Men gesticulated to him, shouted inaudible personal things.
2893_139310_000038_000002 Most of the faces were flushed, but many were ghastly white.
2893_139310_000038_000005 Strange and incredible meeting! As the broad stream passed before him to the right, tributary gangways from the remote uplands of the hall thrust downward in an incessant replacement of people; tramp, tramp, tramp, tramp.
2893_139310_000038_000007 Men and women mingled in the ranks; tramp, tramp, tramp, tramp. The whole world seemed marching.
2893_139310_000038_000008 Tramp, tramp, tramp, tramp; his brain was tramping.
2893_139310_000039_000000 Tramp, tramp, tramp, tramp; at Lincoln's pressure he turned towards the archway, walking unconsciously in that rhythm, scarcely noticing his movement for the melody and stir of it.
2893_139310_000039_000001 The multitude, the gesture and song, all moved in that direction, the flow of people smote downward until the upturned faces were below the level of his feet.
2893_139310_000039_000002 He was aware of a path before him, of a suite about him, of guards and dignities, and Lincoln on his right hand.
2893_139310_000039_000003 Attendants intervened, and ever and again blotted out the sight of the multitude to the left.
2893_139310_000039_000006 He did not know whither he went; he did not want to know.
2893_139310_000039_000007 He glanced back across a flaming spaciousness of hall.
2893_139322_000001_000000 CHAPTER twenty one
2893_139322_000003_000000 From the Business Quarter they presently passed by the running ways into a remote quarter of the city, where the bulk of the manufactures was done.
2893_139322_000003_000001 On their way the platforms crossed the Thames twice, and passed in a broad viaduct across one of the great roads that entered the city from the North.
2893_139322_000003_000002 In both cases his impression was swift and in both very vivid. The river was a broad wrinkled glitter of black sea water, overarched by buildings, and vanishing either way into a blackness starred with receding lights.
2893_139322_000003_000003 A string of black barges passed seaward, manned by blue clad men.
2893_139322_000003_000005 Here, too, the distinctive blue of the Labour Department was in abundance.
2893_139322_000003_000007 One lank and very high carriage with longitudinal metallic rods hung with the dripping carcasses of many hundred sheep arrested his attention unduly.
2893_139322_000003_000008 Abruptly the edge of the archway cut and blotted out the picture.
2893_139322_000004_000000 Presently they left the way and descended by a lift and traversed a passage that sloped downward, and so came to a descending lift again.
2893_139322_000004_000002 Even the pretence of architectural ornament disappeared, the lights diminished in number and size, the architecture became more and more massive in proportion to the spaces as the factory quarters were reached.
2893_139322_000004_000003 And in the dusty biscuit making place of the potters, among the felspar mills, in the furnace rooms of the metal workers, among the incandescent lakes of crude Eadhamite, the blue canvas clothing was on man, woman and child.
2893_139322_000005_000001 The only people not in blue canvas were the overlookers of the work places and the orange clad Labour Police.
2893_139322_000005_000004 The burly labourers of the old Victorian times had followed that dray horse and all such living force producers, to extinction; the place of his costly muscles was taken by some dexterous machine.
2893_139322_000005_000005 The latter day labourer, male as well as female, was essentially a machine minder and feeder, a servant and attendant, or an artist under direction.
2893_139322_000006_000000 The women, in comparison with those Graham remembered, were as a class distinctly plain and flat chested.
2893_139322_000006_000002 To be brilliant physically or mentally, to be in any way attractive or exceptional, had been and was still a certain way of emancipation to the drudge, a line of escape to the Pleasure City and its splendours and delights, and at last to the Euthanasy and peace.
2893_139322_000006_000003 To be steadfast against such inducements was scarcely to be expected of meanly nourished souls.
2893_139322_000006_000004 In the young cities of Graham's former life, the newly aggregated labouring mass had been a diverse multitude, still stirred by the tradition of personal honour and a high morality; now it was differentiating into an instinct class, with a moral and physical difference of its own-even with a dialect of its own.
2893_139322_000007_000000 They penetrated downward, ever downward, towards the working places. Presently they passed underneath one of the streets of the moving ways, and saw its platforms running on their rails far overhead, and chinks of white lights between the transverse slits.
2893_139322_000007_000001 The factories that were not working were sparsely lighted; to Graham they and their shrouded aisles of giant machines seemed plunged in gloom, and even where work was going on the illumination was far less brilliant than upon the public ways.
2893_139322_000008_000001 They were high and dark, and rather cold. In the first a few men were making ornaments of gold filigree, each man at a little bench by himself, and with a little shaded light.
2893_139322_000008_000002 The long vista of light patches, with the nimble fingers brightly lit and moving among the gleaming yellow coils, and the intent face like the face of a ghost, in each shadow, had the oddest effect.
2893_139322_000009_000002 They assumed this on coming to work, but at night they were stripped and examined before they left the premises of the Department.
2893_139322_000009_000003 In spite of every precaution, the Labour policeman told them in a depressed tone, the Department was not infrequently robbed.
2893_139322_000010_000002 "This is what I wanted to see," said Graham; "this is what I wanted to see," trying to avoid a start at a particularly striking disfigurement.
2893_139322_000011_000000 "She might have done better with herself than that," said Asano.
2893_139322_000012_000000 Graham made some indignant comments.
2893_139322_000013_000000 "But, Sire, we simply could not stand that stuff without the purple," said Asano.
2893_139322_000013_000001 "In your days people could stand such crudities, they were nearer the barbaric by two hundred years."
2893_139322_000014_000001 Looking over the parapet, Graham saw that beneath was a wharf under yet more tremendous archings than any he had seen.
2893_139322_000014_000002 Three barges, smothered in floury dust, were being unloaded of their cargoes of powdered felspar by a multitude of coughing men, each guiding a little truck; the dust filled the place with a choking mist, and turned the electric glare yellow.
2893_139322_000014_000003 The vague shadows of these workers gesticulated about their feet, and rushed to and fro against a long stretch of white washed wall.
2893_139322_000014_000004 Every now and then one would stop to cough.
2893_139322_000016_000000 "Stop that!" shouted one of the policemen, but the order was disobeyed, and first one and then all the white stained men who were working there had taken up the beating refrain, singing it defiantly-the Song of the Revolt.
2893_139322_000016_000001 The feet upon the planks thundered now to the rhythm of the song, tramp, tramp, tramp.
2893_139322_000016_000003 He made no further effort to stop the singing.
2893_139322_000017_000001 That walk left on Graham's mind a maze of memories, fluctuating pictures of swathed halls, and crowded vaults seen through clouds of dust, of intricate machines, the racing threads of looms, the heavy beat of stamping machinery, the roar and rattle of belt and armature, of ill lit subterranean aisles of sleeping places, illimitable vistas of pin point lights.
