374_180298_000029_000001 Duvernoy being needful on account of the old duke, Prudence was one of those women who seem made on purpose for days in the country.
374_180298_000029_000002 With her unchanging good humour and her eternal appetite, she never left a dull moment to those whom she was with, and was perfectly happy in ordering eggs, cherries, milk, stewed rabbit, and all the rest of the traditional lunch in the country.
374_180298_000030_000000 We had now only to decide where we should go.
374_180298_000031_000000 "Do you want to go to the real country?" she asked.
374_180298_000032_000000 "Yes."
374_180298_000035_000004 Beyond that, Paris in the mist!
374_180298_000035_000005 As Prudence had told us, it was the real country, and, I must add, it was a real lunch.
374_180298_000036_000000 It is not only out of gratitude for the happiness I owe it, but Bougival, in spite of its horrible name, is one of the prettiest places that it is possible to imagine.
374_180298_000038_000000 People have always associated the country with love, and they have done well; nothing affords so fine a frame for the woman whom one loves as the blue sky, the odours, the flowers, the breeze, the shining solitude of fields, or woods.
374_180298_000038_000001 However much one loves a woman, whatever confidence one may have in her, whatever certainty her past may offer us as to her future, one is always more or less jealous.
374_180298_000038_000004 As for me, I experienced that more than most.
374_180298_000039_000000 The courtesan disappeared little by little.
374_180298_000039_000001 I had by me a young and beautiful woman, whom I loved, and who loved me, and who was called Marguerite; the past had no more reality and the future no more clouds. The sun shone upon my mistress as it might have shone upon the purest bride.
374_180298_000039_000002 We walked together in those charming spots which seemed to have been made on purpose to recall the verses of Lamartine or to sing the melodies of Scudo.
374_180298_000039_000003 Marguerite was dressed in white, she leaned on my arm, saying over to me again under the starry sky the words she had said to me the day before, and far off the world went on its way, without darkening with its shadow the radiant picture of our youth and love.
374_180298_000040_000000 That was the dream that the hot sun brought to me that day through the leaves of the trees, as, lying on the grass of the island on which we had landed, I let my thought wander, free from the human links that had bound it, gathering to itself every hope that came in its way.
374_180298_000041_000001 Climbing flowers clung about the doorway of this uninhabited house, mounting as high as the first story.
374_180298_000042_000000 I looked at the house so long that I began by thinking of it as mine, so perfectly did it embody the dream that I was dreaming; I saw Marguerite and myself there, by day in the little wood that covered the hillside, in the evening seated on the grass, and I asked myself if earthly creatures had ever been so happy as we should be.
374_180298_000044_000000 "Where?" asked Prudence.
374_180298_000045_000000 "Yonder," and Marguerite pointed to the house in question.
374_180298_000046_000000 "Ah, delicious!" replied Prudence.
374_180298_000046_000001 "Do you like it?"
374_180298_000047_000000 "Very much."
374_180298_000048_000000 "Well, tell the duke to take it for you; he would do so, I am sure.
374_180298_000048_000001 I'll see about it if you like."
374_180298_000049_000001 My dream vanished at the last words of Prudence, and brought me back to reality so brutally that I was still stunned with the fall.
374_180298_000050_000000 "Yes, yes, an excellent idea," I stammered, not knowing what I was saying.
374_180298_000051_000000 "Well, I will arrange that," said Marguerite, freeing my hand, and interpreting my words according to her own desire.
374_180298_000051_000001 "Let us go and see if it is to let."
374_180298_000052_000000 The house was empty, and to let for two thousand francs.
374_180298_000053_000000 "Would you be happy here?" she said to me.
374_180298_000054_000000 "Am I sure of coming here?"
374_180298_000055_000000 "And for whom else should I bury myself here, if not for you?"
374_180298_000056_000000 "Well, then, Marguerite, let me take it myself."
374_180298_000057_000001 You know perfectly well that I have no right to accept it save from one man. Let me alone, big baby, and say nothing."
374_180298_000058_000000 "That means," said Prudence, "that when I have two days free I will come and spend them with you."
374_180298_000059_000000 We left the house, and started on our return to Paris, talking over the new plan.
374_180299_000001_000000 Chapter seventeen
374_180299_000002_000000 Next day Marguerite sent me away very early, saying that the duke was coming at an early hour, and promising to write to me the moment he went, and to make an appointment for the evening.
374_180299_000002_000001 In the course of the day I received this note:
374_180299_000003_000000 "I am going to Bougival with the duke; be at Prudence's to night at eight."
374_180299_000004_000002 "Well, it is all settled," she said, as she entered.
374_180299_000004_000003 "The house is taken?" asked Prudence.
374_180299_000004_000004 "Yes; he agreed at once."
374_180299_000005_000000 I did not know the duke, but I felt ashamed of deceiving him.
374_180299_000006_000000 "But that is not all," continued Marguerite.
374_180299_000007_000000 "What else is there?"
374_180299_000008_000000 "I have been seeing about a place for Armand to stay."
374_180299_000009_000000 "In the same house?" asked Prudence, laughing.
374_180299_000010_000003 I took it.
374_180299_000010_000004 Was I right?" I flung my arms around her neck and kissed her.
374_180299_000011_000000 "It will be charming," she continued.
374_180299_000011_000002 I think, between ourselves, that he is enchanted with a caprice which will keep me out of Paris for a time, and so silence the objections of his family.
374_180299_000011_000003 However, he has asked me how I, loving Paris as I do, could make up my mind to bury myself in the country.
374_180299_000011_000004 I told him that I was ill, and that I wanted rest.
374_180299_000011_000005 He seemed to have some difficulty in believing me. The poor old man is always on the watch.
374_180299_000011_000007 Does all that suit you?"
374_180299_000012_000000 "Yes," I answered, trying to quiet the scruples which this way of living awoke in me from time to time.
374_180299_000013_000000 "We went all over the house, and we shall have everything perfect.
374_180299_000013_000001 The duke is going to look after every single thing.
374_180299_000015_000000 "As soon as possible."
374_180299_000016_000000 "Will you take your horses and carriage?"
374_180299_000017_000000 "I shall take the whole house, and you can look after my place while I am away."
374_180299_000018_000000 A week later Marguerite was settled in her country house, and I was installed at Point du Jour.
374_180299_000019_000000 Then began an existence which I shall have some difficulty in describing to you.
374_180299_000019_000002 For a whole month there was not a day when Marguerite had not eight or ten people to meals.
374_180299_000019_000003 Prudence, on her side, brought down all the people she knew, and did the honours of the house as if the house belonged to her.
374_180299_000020_000000 The duke's money paid for all that, as you may imagine; but from time to time Prudence came to me, asking for a note for a thousand francs, professedly on behalf of Marguerite.
374_180299_000020_000001 You know I had won some money at gambling; I therefore immediately handed over to Prudence what she asked for Marguerite, and fearing lest she should require more than I possessed, I borrowed at Paris a sum equal to that which I had already borrowed and paid back.
374_180299_000020_000002 I was then once more in possession of some ten thousand francs, without reckoning my allowance.
374_180299_000020_000004 The duke, who had taken the house in order that Marguerite might rest there, no longer visited it, fearing to find himself in the midst of a large and merry company, by whom he did not wish to be seen.
374_180299_000021_000000 Marguerite rose from table, and joined the duke in the next room, where she tried, as far as possible, to induce him to forget the incident, but the old man, wounded in his dignity, bore her a grudge for it, and could not forgive her.
374_180299_000021_000001 He said to her, somewhat cruelly, that he was tired of paying for the follies of a woman who could not even have him treated with respect under his own roof, and he went away in great indignation.
374_180299_000022_000000 Since that day he had never been heard of.
374_180299_000023_000000 In vain Marguerite dismissed her guests, changed her way of life; the duke was not to be heard of.
374_180299_000023_000002 Marguerite could not be without me.
374_180299_000023_000003 Not caring what the result might be, she publicly proclaimed our liaison, and I had come to live entirely at her house.
374_180299_000023_000004 The servants addressed me officially as their master.
374_180299_000024_000000 Prudence had strictly sermonized Marguerite in regard to her new manner of life; but she had replied that she loved me, that she could not live without me, and that, happen what might, she would not sacrifice the pleasure of having me constantly with her, adding that those who were not satisfied with this arrangement were free to stay away.
374_180299_000024_000001 So much I had heard one day when Prudence had said to Marguerite that she had something very important to tell her, and I had listened at the door of the room into which they had shut themselves.
374_180299_000025_000000 Not long after, Prudence returned again.
374_180299_000025_000002 I had no doubt, from the way in which Marguerite came to meet her, that another similar conversation was going to take place, and I was anxious to hear what it was about.
374_180299_000026_000000 "Well?" said Marguerite.
374_180299_000027_000000 "Well, I have seen the duke."
374_180299_000028_000000 "What did he say?"
374_180299_000029_000001 'Let Marguerite leave the young man,' he said to me, 'and, as in the past, I will give her all that she requires; if not, let her ask nothing more from me.'"
374_180299_000030_000000 "And you replied?"
374_180299_000031_000000 "That I would report his decision to you, and I promised him that I would bring you into a more reasonable frame of mind.
374_180299_000031_000001 Only think, my dear child, of the position that you are losing, and that Armand can never give you.
374_180299_000031_000002 He loves you with all his soul, but he has no fortune capable of supplying your needs, and he will be bound to leave you one day, when it will be too late and when the duke will refuse to do any more for you.
374_180299_000031_000003 Would you like me to speak to Armand?"
374_180299_000032_000000 Marguerite seemed to be thinking, for she answered nothing.
374_180299_000032_000001 My heart beat violently while I waited for her reply.
374_180299_000033_000000 "No," she answered, "I will not leave Armand, and I will not conceal the fact that I am living with him.
374_180299_000033_000001 It is folly no doubt, but I love him. What would you have me do?
374_180299_000033_000002 And then, now that he has got accustomed to be always with me, he would suffer too cruelly if he had to leave me so much as an hour a day.
374_180299_000033_000003 Besides, I have not such a long time to live that I need make myself miserable in order to please an old man whose very sight makes me feel old.
374_180299_000033_000004 Let him keep his money; I will do without it."
374_180299_000034_000000 "But what will you do?"
374_180299_000035_000000 "I don't in the least know."
374_180299_000036_000000 Prudence was no doubt going to make some reply, but I entered suddenly and flung myself at Marguerite's feet, covering her hands with tears in my joy at being thus loved.
374_180299_000037_000000 "My life is yours, Marguerite; you need this man no longer.
374_180299_000037_000001 Am I not here?
374_180299_000037_000002 Shall I ever leave you, and can I ever repay you for the happiness that you give me?
374_180299_000037_000003 No more barriers, my Marguerite; we love; what matters all the rest?"
374_180299_000038_000002 We will be happy; we will live quietly, and I will say good bye forever to the life for which I now blush.
374_180299_000038_000003 You won't ever reproach me for the past? Tell me!"
374_180299_000039_000000 Tears choked my voice.
374_180299_000040_000000 "Well," said she, turning to Prudence, and speaking in a broken voice, "you can report this scene to the duke, and you can add that we have no longer need of him."
374_180299_000041_000000 From that day forth the duke was never referred to.
374_180299_000041_000001 Marguerite was no longer the same woman that I had known.
374_180299_000041_000002 She avoided everything that might recall to me the life which she had been leading when I first met her.
374_180299_000041_000003 Never did wife or sister surround husband or brother with such loving care as she had for me.
374_180299_000041_000004 Her nature was morbidly open to all impressions and accessible to all sentiments.
374_180299_000041_000005 She had broken equally with her friends and with her ways, with her words and with her extravagances.
374_180299_000042_000000 Alas, we made haste to be happy, as if we knew that we were not to be happy long.
374_180299_000043_000000 For two months we had not even been to Paris.
374_180299_000044_000000 I passed whole days at the feet of my mistress.
374_180299_000045_000000 Her delight in the smallest things was like that of a child.
374_180299_000045_000001 There were days when she ran in the garden, like a child of ten, after a butterfly or a dragon fly.
374_180299_000045_000002 This courtesan who had cost more money in bouquets than would have kept a whole family in comfort, would sometimes sit on the grass for an hour, examining the simple flower whose name she bore.
374_180299_000047_000000 The duke wrote to her two or three times.
374_180299_000047_000001 She recognised the writing and gave me the letters without reading them.
374_180299_000047_000002 Sometimes the terms of these letters brought tears to my eyes.
3807_4923_000011_000003 It's liberty we require."
3807_4923_000014_000001 "What, here?"
3807_4923_000021_000002 He began to think that he was the victim of a nightmare.
3807_4923_000028_000002 What do they mean to do next?"
3807_4923_000029_000000 The answer came pat to the question.
3807_4923_000029_000001 From the dark hull of the brig broke a flash and a report, and a musket ball cut the water beside them with a chirping noise.
3830_12529_000002_000000 CHAPTER ELEVEN
3830_12529_000004_000000 OUR enjoyment of this first home did not last long.
3830_12529_000005_000000 In April of eighteen fifty three, the word had begun to pass around that we were to have a new Territory to embrace the country north of the Columbia River.
3830_12529_000005_000001 Its capital was to be on Puget Sound.
3830_12529_000005_000002 Here on the Columbia we should be away off to one side, out of touch with the people who would shortly become a great separate commonwealth.
3830_12529_000009_000000 Our expectations had been raised high by the glowing accounts of Puget Sound.
3830_12529_000009_000001 But a feeling of deep disappointment fell upon us when we could see in the foreground only bare, dismal mud flats, and beyond these a channel scarcely twice as wide as that of the great river we had left, bounded on either side by high, heavily timbered land.
3830_12529_000009_000002 We wished ourselves back at our cabin on the Columbia.
3830_12529_000010_000000 Should we turn around and go back?
3830_12529_000010_000002 But what was the use of stopping here?
3830_12529_000010_000003 We wanted a place to make a farm, and we could not do it on such forbidding land as this.
3830_12529_000010_000005 My first camp on Puget Sound was not cheerful.
3830_12529_000011_000000 Olympia at the time contained about one hundred inhabitants.
3830_12529_000011_000001 It had three stores, a hotel, a livery stable, a saloon, and one weekly newspaper.
3830_12529_000012_000000 We could not stay at Olympia.
3830_12529_000012_000001 We had pushed on past some good locations on the Chehalis, and farther south, without locating.
3830_12529_000012_000003 Oliver said no, and my better judgment also said no, though I was sorely pressed with a feeling of homesickness.
3830_12529_000013_000004 When I came to know the Indians better and saw their performances in these frail craft, my admiration for the canoes was even greater than my distrust had been.
3830_12529_000014_000000 Neither Oliver nor I had much experience in boating, and we had none in boat building.
3830_12529_000014_000001 However, when we had discarded the idea of taking a canoe, we set to work with a hearty good will to build us a skiff.
3830_12529_000014_000002 We made it out of light lumber, then easily obtained at Tumwater.
3830_12529_000015_000000 As in the trip across the Plains, we must provide our own transportation.
3830_12529_000015_000001 Here and there might be a vessel loading piles and square timber for the San Francisco market, but not a steamer was then plying on the Sound; there was not even a sailing craft that essayed to carry passengers.
3830_12529_000018_000000 We floated lazily with the tide, sometimes taking a few strokes with the oars, and at other times whistling for the wind.
3830_12529_000018_000001 The little town of Olympia to the south became dimmed by distance.
3830_12529_000018_000002 But we were no sooner fairly out of sight of the little village than the question came up which way to go.
3830_12529_000018_000003 What channel should we take?
3830_12529_000019_000000 "Let the tide decide; that will carry us out toward the ocean."
3830_12529_000020_000000 "No, we are drifting into another bay; that cannot be where we want to go."
3830_12529_000021_000000 "Why, we are drifting right back almost in the same direction from which we came, but into another bay!
3830_12529_000023_000000 "Yes, but I do not see any way out there."
3830_12529_000025_000000 "The best thing we can do is to camp," said Oliver.
3830_12529_000026_000001 So our first night's camp was scarcely twelve miles from where we had started in the morning.
3830_12529_000026_000003 A beautiful pebbly beach extended almost to the water's edge even at low tide.
3830_12529_000026_000006 We felt so happy that we were almost glad the journey had been interrupted.
3830_12529_000028_000000 An encampment of Indians being near, a party of them soon visited our camp and began making signs for trade.
3830_12529_000030_000000 "What does she say, Oliver?"
3830_12529_000031_000000 "I'm blessed if I know, but it looks as if she wanted to sell some clams."
3830_12529_000032_000000 After considerable dickering, with signs and gestures and words many times repeated, we were able to impart the information that we wanted a lesson in cookery.
3830_12529_000032_000001 If she would show us how to cook the clams, we would buy some.
3830_12529_000032_000002 This brought some merriment in the camp.
3830_12529_000032_000003 The idea that there lived a person who did not know how to cook clams!
3830_12529_000032_000004 Without saying by your leave or anything else, the motherly looking native woman began tearing down our camp fire.
3830_12529_000035_000000 "Let her alone, and see what she's up to," said Oliver, noticing that I was disturbed at such interference with my well laid plans for bread baking.
3830_12529_000036_000001 Upon these the clams were deposited.
3830_12529_000036_000002 They were covered with fine twigs, and upon the twigs earth was placed.
3830_12529_000041_000000 Thus began and ended our first lesson in the Chinook jargon, and our first experience with a clam bake.
3830_12529_000042_000000 This first clam bake gave us great encouragement.
3830_12529_000042_000001 We soon learned that the bivalves were to be found in almost unlimited quantity and were widely distributed.
3830_12529_000042_000002 The harvest was ready twice a day, when the tide was out, and we need have no fear of a famine even if cast away in some unfrequented place.
3830_12529_000044_000000 Without understanding her words, but knowing well what she meant, we fell to disposing of this, our first clam dinner.
3830_12529_000044_000002 The natives soon withdrew to their own camp.
3830_12529_000045_000000 Before retiring for the night, we repaid the visit.
3830_12529_000045_000002 We had been in Indian country for nearly a year, but with guns by our side, if not in our hands, during nearly half the time.
3830_12529_000045_000003 We had not stopped to study the Indian character.
3830_12529_000046_000000 We took a lesson in Chinook, and by signs and words held conversation until a late hour.
3830_12529_000047_000000 We had made the Indians a present first, it is true; but we did not expect any return, except perhaps goodwill.
3830_12530_000007_000000 CHAPTER TWELVE
3830_12530_000008_000000 CRUISING ABOUT ON PUGET SOUND
3830_12530_000010_000000 As the tide and wind favored us, we did not stop.
3830_12530_000010_000001 Soon we came in sight of a fleet of seven vessels lying at anchor in a large bay, several miles in extent.
3830_12530_000010_000002 The sight of those seven vessels lying in the offing made a profound impression upon our minds.
3830_12530_000011_000000 Upon the eastern slope of the shores of this bay lay the two towns, Port Steilacoom, and Steilacoom City, both established in eighteen fifty one.
3830_12530_000011_000001 A far larger trade centered here than at any other point on Puget Sound, and we decided on a halt to make ourselves acquainted with the surroundings.
3830_12530_000011_000002 A mile and a half from the shore we found also Fort Steilacoom.
3830_12530_000011_000003 It was simply the camp of a company of United States soldiers, quartered in wooden shells of houses and log cabins.
3830_12530_000012_000000 Intense rivalry ran between the two towns, upper and lower Steilacoom, at this time.
3830_12530_000012_000001 As a result things were booming.
3830_12530_000012_000002 We were sorely tempted to accept the flattering offer of four dollars a day for common labor in a timber camp, but concluded not to be swerved from the search for a new homesite.
3830_12530_000013_000001 They seemed to be a listless lot, with no thought for the future, or even for the immediate present.
3830_12530_000013_000003 Here and there we saw a family industriously pursuing some object; but as a class they seemed to me the laziest set of people on earth.
3830_12530_000014_000000 That opinion was materially modified later, as I became better acquainted with their habits.
3830_12530_000014_000001 I have found just as industrious people, both men and women, among the Indians as among the whites.
3830_12530_000014_000002 The workers, it may be said, are less numerous among the men; the women are all industrious.
3830_12530_000015_000001 After a sober second thought, we realized that we had nothing to trade but labor; and we had not come as far as this to be laborers for hire.
3830_12530_000015_000002 We had come to find a place to make a farm, and a farm we were going to have.
3830_12530_000015_000003 Again we set about searching for claims, and the more we searched the less we liked the look of things.
3830_12530_000016_000002 As the sun shone warm and the tide was taking us rapidly in the direction we wanted to go, why shouldn't I doze a little too, even if we did miss some of the sightseeing?
3830_12530_000018_000000 "It surely can't be," I responded, three quarters asleep.
3830_12530_000020_000000 We were wide awake now and gave chase.
3830_12530_000020_000001 Very soon we caught up with the animal and succeeded in throwing a rope over its horns.
3830_12530_000020_000002 By this time we had drifted into the Narrows, and we soon found we had something more important to do than to tow a deer.
3830_12530_000021_000001 Turning the deer loose, we pulled our best for the shore, and found shelter in an eddy.
3830_12530_000021_000002 A perpendicular bluff rose from the highwater mark, leaving no place for camp fire or bed.
3830_12530_000022_000001 It was our first introduction to a genuine tide rip.
3830_12530_000022_000003 A flat bottomed boat like our little skiff, we thought, could not stay afloat there very long.
3830_12530_000023_000000 Just then some Indian canoes came along, moving with the tide.
3830_12530_000023_000002 I have said well manned, but half the paddles, in fact, were wielded by women, and the post of honor, or that where most dexterity was required, was occupied by a woman.
3830_12530_000027_000001 We responded, partly in English and partly in Chinook, that we were, and besides that it was impossible for us to proceed against the strong current.
3830_12530_000031_000001 We hardly knew whether to camp in our boat or to start out on unknown waters in the dark.
3830_12530_000031_000002 Our Indian visitors made preparations to proceed on their journey, and assured us it was all right ahead.
3830_12530_000032_000000 Sure enough, a short pull with a favorable current brought us to the Narrows and into Commencement Bay, in sight of numerous camp fires in the distance.
3830_12530_000032_000001 I remember that camp quite vividly; though I cannot locate it exactly, I know that it was on the water front within the present limits of the large and thriving city of Tacoma.
3830_12530_000035_000002 The Indians told us that there were two other like obstructions a few miles farther up the river, and that the current was very strong.
3830_12530_000036_000001 It took a tugging of two days to go six miles.
3830_12530_000037_000003 Over these pack animals could pass, but wagon roads there were none; and whether a feasible route for one could be found, only time and labor could determine.
3830_12530_000038_000002 Oliver did not sing as usual while preparing for camp.
3830_12530_000038_000003 Neither did I have much to say; but I fell to work, mechanically preparing the much needed meal. We ate in silence and then went to sleep.
3830_12530_000039_000000 We had crossed the two great states of Illinois and Iowa, over hundreds of miles of unoccupied prairie land as rich as anything that ever "lay out of doors," on our way from Indiana to Oregon in search of land on which to make a home.
3830_12530_000039_000001 Here, at what we might call the end of our rope, we had found the land, but with conditions that seemed almost too adverse to overcome.
3830_12530_000040_000000 It was a discouraging outlook, even if there had been roads.
3830_12530_000040_000001 Such timber!
3830_12530_000040_000002 It seemed an appalling undertaking to clear this land, the greater part of it being covered with a heavy growth of balm and alder trees and a thick tangle of underbrush besides.
3830_12530_000040_000003 When we fell asleep that night, it was without visions of new found wealth.
3830_12530_000042_000000 We lingered at the mouth of the river in doubt as to what best to do.
3830_12530_000042_000001 My thoughts went back to wife and baby in the lonely cabin on the Columbia River, and again to that bargain we had made before marriage, that we were going to be farmers.
3830_12530_000042_000002 How could we be farmers if we did not have land?
3830_12530_000043_000000 With misgivings and doubts, on the fourth day Oliver and I loaded our outfit into our skiff and floated out on the receding tide, whither, we did not know.
3830_12530_000044_000000 As we drew off from the mouth of the Puyallup River, numerous parties of Indians were in sight.
3830_12530_000044_000001 Some were trolling for salmon, with a lone Indian in the bow of each canoe; others with poles were fishing for smelt; still others with nets seemed waiting for fisherman's luck.
3830_12530_000045_000000 Other parties were passing, those in each canoe singing a plaintive chant in minor key, accompanied by heavy strokes of the paddle handles against the sides of the canoe, as if to keep time.
3830_12530_000045_000001 There were some fine voices to be heard, and though there were but slight variations in the sounds or words, the Indians seemed never to tire in repeating, and I must confess we never tired of listening.
3830_12530_000048_000000 As we were not looking for a mill site or town site, we pushed on next day.
3830_12530_000048_000005 Fortune favored us, for we found a good sandy beach upon which to land, though we got a thorough drenching while so doing.
3830_12530_000051_000000 Here we were compelled to remain two or three days in a dismal camp, until the weather became more favorable.
3830_12530_000051_000001 Then launching our boat, we pulled for the head of Whidbey's Island, a few miles to the northwest.
3830_12530_000052_000000 Now I have a fish story to tell.
3830_12530_000052_000001 I have always been shy about telling it, lest some smart fellow should up and say I was drawing on my imagination: I am not.
3830_12530_000053_000000 When we had broken camp and were sailing along, we heard a dull sound like that often heard from the tide rips.
3830_12530_000054_000000 We could feel the fish striking against the boat in such vast numbers that they fairly moved it.
3830_12530_000056_000000 This camp did not prove so dreary as the last one, although it was more exposed to the swell of the big waters and the sweep of the wind.
3830_12530_000056_000002 As we afterwards ascertained, we could see the famous San Juan Island, later the bone of contention between our government and Great Britain, when the northern boundary of the United States was settled.
3830_12530_000057_000001 We did not know the exact location of the town.
3830_12530_000057_000002 Like the lost hunters, "we knew where we were, but we didn't know where any place else was." Not lost ourselves, the world was lost from us.
3830_12530_000058_000001 The other two were gracefully beating their way out against the stiff breeze to the open waters beyond.
3830_12530_000058_000002 What prettier sight is there than a full rigged vessel with all sails spread!
3830_12530_000060_000002 The shining, pebbly beach in front, the clear, level spot adjoining, with the beautiful open and comparatively level plateau in the background, and two or three vessels at anchor in the foreground, made a picture of a perfect city site.
3830_12530_000061_000001 Many shacks and camps, at first mistaken for the white men's houses, were found to be occupied by natives.
3830_12530_000061_000002 They were a drunken, rascally rabble, spending their gains from the sale of fish and oil in a debauch that would last as long as their money held out.
3830_12530_000062_000001 They would often go out even to the open sea on their fishing excursions in canoes manned by thirty men or more.
3830_12530_000063_000001 We remembered the timber camps, the bustle and stir of the little new village, and the activity that we saw there, greater than anywhere else on the waters of the Sound.
3830_12530_000063_000002 Most of all, my thoughts would go on to the little cabin on the Columbia River.
3830_12530_000064_000000 Three days sufficed to land us back in the bay we sought, but the ships were gone.
3830_12530_000064_000001 Not a sailing craft of any kind was in sight of the little town, though the building activity was going on as before.
3830_12530_000065_000000 The memory of those ships, however, remained with us and determined our minds on the important question where the trade center was to be.
3830_12531_000004_000000 CHAPTER THIRTEEN
3830_12531_000006_000000 "CAN I get home tonight?" I asked myself.
3830_12531_000007_000001 I was well up the left bank of the Cowlitz River; how far I could not tell, for there were no milestones on the crooked, half obstructed trail leading downstream.
3830_12531_000007_000002 At best it would be a race with the sun, but the days were long, and the twilight was long, and I would camp that much nearer home if I made haste.
3830_12531_000008_000001 I had neither coat nor blanket. I wore a heavy woolen shirt, a slouch hat, and worn shoes; both hat and shoes gave ample ventilation.
3830_12531_000008_000002 Socks I had none; neither had I suspenders, an improvised belt taking their place.
3830_12531_000008_000003 I was dressed for the race and was eager for the trial.
3830_12531_000009_000002 We never thought of catching cold from lying on the ground or on cedar boughs, or from getting a good drenching.
3830_12531_000010_000000 After all, the cabin could not be reached, as the trail could not be followed at night.
3830_12531_000010_000001 Slackening pace at nightfall to cool my system gradually, I finally made my camp and slept as soundly as if on a bed of down.
3830_12531_000010_000002 My consolation was that the night was short and I could see to travel by three o'clock.
3830_12531_000011_000000 I do not look upon those years of camp and cabin life as years of hardship.
3830_12531_000011_000001 To be sure, our food was plain as well as our dress; our hours of labor were long and the labor itself was frequently severe; the pioneers appeared rough and uncouth.
3830_12531_000011_000002 Yet underlying all this there ran a vein of good cheer, of hopefulness.
3830_12531_000011_000004 The days were always too short, and interest in our work was always unabated.
3830_12531_000012_000000 The cabin could not be seen until the trail came quite near it.
3830_12531_000012_000003 She never finished milking that cow, nor did she ever milk any cow when her husband was at home.
3830_12531_000013_000001 Much of the conversation naturally centered on the question of our moving to a new home.
3830_12531_000014_000001 I saw them selling at that.
3830_12531_000014_000002 The butter you have there would bring you a dollar a pound as fast as you could weigh it out.
3830_12531_000016_000000 "Oh, almost everybody has to buy.
3830_12531_000017_000000 "Where do they get the money?"
3830_12531_000018_000000 "Everybody seems to have money.
3830_12531_000018_000001 Some take it there with them.
3830_12531_000018_000002 Men working in the timber camps get four dollars a day and their board.
3830_12531_000018_000004 I was offered five cents a foot for piles.
3830_12531_000018_000005 If we had Buck and Dandy over there we could make twenty dollars a day putting in piles."
3830_12531_000020_000000 "Off the government land, of course.
3830_12531_000020_000001 All help themselves to what they want.
3830_12531_000021_000000 "But what about the land for the claim?"
3830_12531_000022_000000 That question was a stumper.
3830_12531_000022_000001 The little wife never lost sight of that bargain made before we were married.
3830_12531_000022_000002 Now I found myself praising a country for the agricultural qualities of which I could not say much. But if we could sell produce higher, might we not well lower our standard of an ideal farm?
3830_12531_000022_000004 However, we decided to move, and began to prepare for the journey.
3830_12531_000023_000000 The wife, baby, bedding, ox yoke, and log chain were sent up the Cowlitz in a canoe.
3830_12531_000023_000001 Buck and Dandy and I took the trail.
3830_12531_000023_000002 On this occasion I was ill prepared for a cool night camp, having neither blanket nor coat.
3830_12531_000023_000003 I had expected to reach Hard Bread's Hotel, where the people in the canoe would stop overnight.
3830_12531_000023_000004 But I could not make it, so again I lay out on the trail.
3830_12531_000024_000000 I found that my wife had not fared any better than I had on the trail, and in fact not so well.
3830_12531_000024_000001 The floor of the cabin-that is, the hotel-was a great deal harder than the sand spit where I had passed the night.
3830_12531_000024_000002 I had plenty of pure, fresh air, while she, in a closed cabin and in the same room with many others, had neither fresh air nor freedom from creeping things that make life miserable.
3830_12531_000024_000003 With her shoes for a pillow, a shawl for covering, small wonder that she reported, "I did not sleep a wink last night."
3830_12531_000026_000001 And such a road!
3830_12531_000026_000002 However, we had one consolation,--it would be worse in winter than at that time.
3830_12531_000027_000001 Our cows were gone-given for provender to save the lives of the oxen during the deep December snow.
3830_12531_000027_000002 So when we took account of stock, we had the baby, Buck and Dandy, a tent, an ox yoke and chain, enough clothing and bedding to keep us comfortable, a very little food, and no money.
3830_12531_000027_000003 The money had all been expended on the canoe passage.
3830_12531_000029_000000 That great hearted pioneer, john r Jackson, did not hesitate a moment, stranger though I was, to say, "Yes, you can have two if you need them."
3830_12531_000030_000000 Jackson had settled there eight years before, ten miles out from the landing, and now had an abundance around him.
3830_12531_000030_000001 Like all the earlier pioneers, he took a pride in helping others who came later.
3830_12531_000030_000002 He would not listen to our proceeding any farther before the next day.
3830_12531_000030_000003 He insisted on entertaining us in his comfortable cabin, and sent us on our way in the morning, rejoicing in plenty.
3830_12531_000031_000001 Here a camp must be established again.
3830_12531_000033_000001 I knew that smallpox was raging among the Indians, and that a camp where it was prevalent was less than a quarter of a mile away.
3830_12531_000033_000003 Could it be possible my folks had been taken sick and had been removed?
3830_12531_000035_000003 God bless those earlier pioneers!
3830_12531_000035_000004 They were all good to us, sometimes to the point of embarrassment, in their generous hospitality.
3830_12531_000036_000000 Oliver was to have had the cabin ready by the time I returned.
3830_12531_000036_000002 Not knowing what else to do, I paddled over to the town of Steilacoom.
3830_12531_000036_000003 There I found out where the boat and the provisions had been left, and after an earnest parley succeeded in getting possession.
3830_12531_000036_000004 With my canoe in tow I soon made my way back to where my little flock was, and speedily transferred all to the spot that was to be our island dwelling.
3830_12531_000036_000005 We set up our tent, and felt at home once more.
3830_12531_000038_000001 mount Rainier looked bigger and taller than ever.
3830_12531_000038_000003 Everything looked cheerful; everything interested us, especially the crows, with their trick of breaking clams by rising in the air and dropping them on the boulders. There were so many new things to observe that for a time we almost forgot that we were nearly out of provisions and money and did not know what had happened to Oliver.
3830_12531_000039_000001 Finding that the boat and provisions had been taken and seeing smoke in the bight, he surmised what had happened and came paddling across to the tent.
3830_12531_000039_000003 As a result of this work, he was able to exhibit a slug of California gold and other money that looked precious indeed in our eyes.
3830_12531_000041_000000 It was in this same year, eighteen fifty three, that Congress cut off from Oregon the region that now comprises the state of Washington and all of Idaho north of the Snake River.
3830_12535_000001_000000 CHAPTER SEVENTEEN
3830_12535_000002_000000 FINDING MY PEOPLE
3830_12535_000003_000000 ON leaving my newly found friends I faced a discouraging prospect.
3830_12535_000003_000001 The start for the high, arid table lands bordering the Yakima valley cut me loose from all communication.
3830_12535_000003_000002 No more immigrants were met until I reached the main traveled route beyond the Columbia River.
3830_12535_000004_000001 As the sun rose, the heat became intolerable.
3830_12535_000004_000002 The dust, in places, brought vivid memories of the trip across the Plains.
3830_12535_000005_000000 Strive against it as I might, my eyes would strain at the horizon to catch a glimpse of the expected train.
3830_12535_000005_000001 Then an intolerable thirst seized upon me and compelled me to leave the road and descend into the valley for water.
3830_12535_000006_000002 Tethering my pony for his much needed dinner, I opened my sack of hard bread to count the contents; my store was half gone.
3830_12535_000006_000003 I lay down in the shade of a small tree near the spring to take an afternoon nap.
3830_12535_000006_000004 Rousing before sundown, refreshed, Bobby and I took the trail with new courage.
3830_12535_000007_000000 When night came, I could not find it in my heart to camp.
3830_12535_000007_000001 The cool of the evening invigorated the pony, and we pushed on.
3830_12535_000007_000002 Finding that the road could be followed, though but dimly seen, I kept on the trail until a late hour, when I unsaddled and hobbled the pony.
3830_12535_000008_000001 To make matters worse, his hobbles had become loosened, giving him free use of all his feet, and he was in no mood to take the trail again. Coaxing was of no avail, driving would do no good.
3830_12535_000008_000002 Taking an opportunity to seize his tail, I followed him around about over the plain and through the sage brush at a rapid gait; finally he slackened pace and I again became master.
3830_12535_000010_000001 When the trail was found, there was the saddle to look for, and this was located with some difficulty.
3830_12535_000011_000001 A few hundred yards of travel brought uneasiness, as it was evident that we were not on the regular trail.
3830_12535_000011_000002 Not knowing but this was some cut-off, I went on until the Columbia River bluff was reached and the great river was in sight, half a mile distant and several hundred feet lower.
3830_12535_000012_000000 The next incident that I remember vividly was my attempt to cross the Columbia, just below the mouth of the Snake River.
3830_12535_000012_000002 Their behavior was so in contrast to that of the Indians on the Sound that I could not help wondering what it meant.
3830_12535_000013_000001 I tethered my pony this time, and rolled myself up in the blanket, only to find myself fairly buried in the drifting sand in the morning.
3830_12535_000013_000002 It required a great effort to creep out of the blanket, and an even greater effort to free the blanket from the accumulated sand.
3830_12535_000013_000003 By this time the wind had gone down and comparative calm prevailed.
3830_12535_000015_000000 Then came the attempt to make myself heard across the wide river by the people of the fort.
3830_12535_000015_000001 I traveled up and down the river bank for half a mile or so, in the hope of catching a favorable breeze to carry my voice to the fort, yet all to no avail.
3830_12535_000015_000002 I sat upon the bank hopelessly discouraged, not knowing what to do.
3830_12535_000015_000003 I must have been two hours hallooing at the top of my voice, until I was hoarse from the violent effort.
3830_12535_000016_000000 Finally, while sitting there wondering what to do, I spied a blue smoke arising from a cabin on the other side.
3830_12535_000016_000001 Soon after I saw a man; he immediately responded to my renewed efforts to attract attention.
3830_12535_000016_000002 The trouble had been that the people were all asleep, while I was there in the early morning expending my breath for nothing.
3830_12535_000017_000000 The man was Shirley Ensign, of Olympia, who had established a ferry across the Columbia River and had lingered to set over belated immigrants, if any should come along.
3830_12535_000017_000001 He came across the river and gave me glad tidings.
3830_12535_000018_000000 But I could not wait there for them.
3830_12535_000018_000001 Procuring a fresh horse, I started out in a cheerful mood, determined to reach camp that night if I could possibly do so.
3830_12535_000018_000003 Dusk came on, and still no signs.
3830_12535_000019_000000 Rejoicing and outbursts of grief followed.
3830_12535_000019_000001 I inquired for my mother the first thing.
3830_12535_000019_000004 My younger brother also lay buried on the Plains, near Independence Rock.
3830_12535_000020_000000 When we came to consider how the party should proceed, I advised the over mountain trip.
3830_12535_000020_000001 But I cautioned them to expect some snow and much hard work.
3830_12535_000021_000000 "How long will it take?" they asked.
3830_12535_000022_000000 "About three weeks."
3830_12535_000023_000000 This brought disappointment; they had thought they were about through with the journey.
3830_12535_000024_000000 "You came to stay with us, didn't you?"
3830_12535_000025_000000 "I want to; but what about my wife and the two babies, at the island?"
3830_12535_000026_000000 Father said some one must go and look after them.
3830_12535_000026_000001 So Oliver was sent ahead, while I was to take his place and help the immigrants through the Natchess Pass.
3830_12535_000027_000001 We made the trip across the divide in twenty two days without serious mishap or loss.
3830_12535_000027_000003 Every man literally "put his shoulder to the wheel." We were compelled often to take hold of the wheels to boost the wagons over the logs or to ease them down steep places.
3830_12535_000027_000006 I have often thought that some one ought to write a just tribute to their valor and patience, a book of their heroic deeds.
3830_12535_000028_000000 One day we encountered a newly fallen tree, cocked up on its own upturned roots, four feet from the ground.
3830_12535_000028_000001 Go around it we could not; to cut it out with our dulled, flimsy saw seemed an endless task.
3830_12535_000030_000002 As to this return trip, I can truly say for myself that it was not one of hardship.
3830_12535_000030_000003 I enjoyed overcoming the difficulties, and so did the greater number of the company.
3830_12535_000030_000004 Many of them, it is true, were weakened by the long trip across the Plains; but better food was obtainable, and the goal was near at hand.
3830_12535_000031_000001 Hundreds of cattle, sheep, and horses were quietly grazing, scattered over the landscape as far as one could see.
3830_12535_000031_000002 The spirits of the tired party rose as they looked upon this scene, indicating a contentment and prosperity in which they might participate if they so desired.
3830_12535_000032_000001 Great was the feasting, with clam bakes, huckleberry pies and puddings, venison for meat, and fresh vegetables from our garden, at which the newcomers could not cease from marveling.
3830_12535_000032_000002 The row of sweet peas that my wife had planted near the cabin helped to put heart into those travel weary pioneers; where flowers could be planted, a home could be made.
3830_12535_000033_000000 For a short time the little party halted to take breath and to look over the new country.
3830_12535_000033_000001 This rest, however, could not last long.
3830_12535_000033_000002 Preparations must be made without delay for shelter from the coming storms of winter; the stock must be cared for, and other beginnings made for a new life of independence.
3857_180923_000002_000001 Enough has been told of what it did to furnish grounds for deducing what it was; but to deal with the regiment on the personal side is hardly possible within the limits of such a sketch as this, though it is a matter that cannot be entirely passed by.
3857_180923_000003_000000 Any body of men-a college class, a legislature, a regiment-is in character what its component members make it; in this case there was the material, which, furnished with worthy leadership-and it unquestionably had that-made up the organization whose not uneventful existence has been described.
3857_180923_000003_000002 In fact, to have passed the tests of so fierce a course of education gives them a title to a place thus apart.
3857_180923_000003_000003 The university man of to day, as the burden of the baccalaureate sermons so frequently testifies, is consigned to a special place of responsibility in life because of his training; these men surely earned one of special honor by reason of theirs, which was, too, not like the other, preparation alone, but also fulfilment.
3857_180923_000004_000001 A number of the officers and men were college graduates when they enlisted, and others gained degrees after the war ended; the list which follows is, however, necessarily incomplete; in fact, an absolutely correct list is no doubt hopelessly impossible.
3857_180923_000005_000000 Major james q Rice, who was killed at Winchester, was a member of the class of eighteen fifty at Wesleyan, and received from that institution the degree of Master of Arts in eighteen fifty five.
3857_180923_000005_000001 At the time of the regiment's formation he was conducting an academy in Goshen, and was enlisted as captain of a company which he had been active in recruiting.
3857_180923_000006_000000 Lieutenant Colonel Nathaniel Smith of Woodbury entered the Yale Law School in the class of eighteen fifty three, but did not graduate.
3857_180923_000007_000000 Judge Augustus h Fenn, Major and Brevet Colonel, came back from the war, having lost an arm at Cedar Creek, to take a course in the Law School at Harvard, and Yale made him a Master of Arts in eighteen eighty nine.
3857_180923_000007_000002 At the time of his death in eighteen ninety seven, he was a lecturer in the Yale Law School, and member of the Supreme Court of Errors.
3857_180923_000008_000000 reverend James Deane, Captain and Brevet Major, was a graduate of Williams in the class of eighteen fifty seven.
3857_180923_000008_000001 He was pastor of the Congregational church at East Canaan when the regiment was organized, and was one of its recruiting officers.
3857_180923_000009_000000 Adjutant Theodore f Vaill, the historian of the regiment, was a student before the war at Union College, but did not graduate.
3857_180923_000010_000000 Captain George s Williams, of New Milford, was a member of the class of eighteen fifty two at Yale for a time, and received a degree from Trinity in eighteen fifty five.
3857_180923_000011_000000 Surgeon Henry Plumb, and Assistant Surgeons Robert g Hazzard and john w Lawton were all graduates of the Yale Medical School, in the classes of eighteen sixty one, eighteen sixty two, and eighteen fifty nine.
3857_180923_000011_000002 He was captain in a New York regiment in the early part of the war, and became afterward superintendent of the Buffalo State Hospital, and a recognized authority on insanity before his death in eighteen ninety four.
3857_180923_000012_000001 He was later connected with a church college in Missouri, where he died in eighteen ninety eight.
3857_180923_000013_000000 Captain William h Lewis junior, studied after the war at the Berkeley Divinity School, and has been for many years rector of saint John's Church in Bridgeport.
3857_180923_000015_000000 Corporal Francis j Young entered the Yale Medical School before the war, and returned after its close to take his degree in eighteen sixty six.
3857_180923_000017_000000 Sergeant Theodore c Glazier was a graduate of Trinity in the class of eighteen sixty, and was a tutor there when he enlisted.
3857_180923_000017_000001 He was later made colonel of a colored regiment, and served with credit in that capacity.
3857_180923_000018_000000 Corporal Edward c Hopson, a graduate of Trinity in eighteen sixty four, was killed at Cedar Creek.
3857_180923_000019_000000 Sergeant Garwood r Merwin, who had been a member of the class of eighteen sixty four at Yale, died at Alexandria in eighteen sixty three.
3857_180923_000020_000000 Sergeant Romulus c Loveridge, who had been entered in the class of eighteen sixty five at Yale, received a commission in a colored regiment.
3857_180923_000021_000000 Colonel Mackenzie graduated at West Point in eighteen sixty two, but he was never a resident of the county, or of Connecticut, and his only connection with either was through his commission from Governor Buckingham.
3857_180923_000023_000000 As a whole, the regiment was a body thoroughly representative not only of the army of which it was a fraction, an army as has been often said unlike any other the world has known, but also of the population from which it was drawn.
3857_180923_000023_000001 It was made up of men of almost all conditions of life and of widely different ages, though naturally with young men in a large majority; of mechanics from the Housatonic and Naugatuck valleys, and farmers' boys from the hills; of men of education and men of none.
3857_180923_000023_000002 Though the large addition to its numbers which the increase in size necessitated made it perhaps somewhat less homogeneous than at first, it did not greatly alter its essential characteristics.
3857_180923_000024_000001 The names of men of every sort and kind are found upon the rolls.
3857_180923_000025_000000 A large part of these men came back after their service ended to resume the peaceful life of citizenship, and every town among us has known some of them ever since among its leading figures, while some in quarters far distant have also attained to honors and responsibilities, as the records show.
3857_182315_000000_000001 All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain.
3857_182315_000000_000002 For more information, or to volunteer, please visit librivox dot org.
3857_182315_000005_000001 As for me, I am proud of my close kinship with other animals.
3857_182315_000005_000002 I take a jealous pride in my Simian ancestry.
3857_182315_000006_000000 w n p Barbellion.
3857_182315_000008_000001 It was a mild afternoon and great crowds of people were out. Sunday afternoon crowds.
3857_182315_000008_000002 They were not going anywhere,--they were just strolling up and down, staring at each other, and talking. There were thousands and thousands of them.
3857_182315_000014_000000 "Yes," I said, "those for example are distinctively simian.
3857_182315_000014_000001 Why should you feel disappointment at something inevitable?" And I went on to argue that it wasn't as though we were descended from eagles for instance, instead of (broadly speaking) from ape like or monkeyish beings.
3857_182315_000014_000002 Being of simian stock, we had simian traits. Our development naturally bore the marks of our origin.
3857_182315_000014_000005 What could you expect?
3857_182315_000017_000000 But considering our simian descent, it has done very well.
3857_182315_000017_000002 Or who-unconsciously-still let it color their thinking.
3857_182315_000018_000000 There certainly seems to be a power at work in the world, by virtue of which every living thing grows and develops.
3857_182315_000018_000001 And it tends toward splendor.
3857_182315_000018_000002 Seeds become trees, and weak little nations grow great. But the push or the force that is doing this, the yeast as it were, has to work in and on certain definite kinds of material.
3857_182315_000018_000003 Because this yeast is in us there may be great and undreamed of possibilities awaiting mankind; but because of our line of descent there are also queer limitations.
3857_182315_000020_000000 In those distant invisible epochs before men existed, before even the proud missing link strutted around through the woods (little realizing how we his greatgrandsons would smile wryly at him much as our own descendants may shudder at us, ages hence) the various animals were desperately competing for power.
3857_182315_000020_000001 They couldn't or didn't live as equals.
3857_182315_000020_000002 Certain groups sought the headship.
3857_182315_000021_000000 Many strange forgotten dynasties rose, met defiance, and fell. In the end it was our ancestors who won, and became simian kings, and bequeathed a whole planet to us-and have never been thanked for it.
3857_182315_000022_000001 Familiar with the ways of evolution elsewhere in the universe, we naturally should have wondered what course it would take on this earth.
3857_182315_000022_000002 "Even in this out of the way corner of the Cosmos," we might have reflected, "and on this tiny star, it may be of interest to consider the trend of events." We should have tried to appraise the different species as they wandered around, each with its own set of good and bad characteristics.
3857_182315_000022_000003 Which group, we'd have wondered, would ever contrive to rule all the rest?
3857_182315_000026_000000 Still-those frowsy, unlovely hordes of apes and monkeys were so completely lacking in signs of kingship; they were so flighty, too, in their ways, and had so little purpose, and so much love for absurd and idle chatter, that they would have struck us, we thought, as unlikely material.
3857_182315_000026_000001 Such traits, we should have reminded ourselves, persist.
3857_182315_000026_000002 They are not easily left behind, even after long stages; and they form a terrible obstacle to all high advancement.
3857_182315_000028_000001 Their smallness of size was not necessarily too much of a handicap.
3857_182315_000028_000002 They could have made poison their weapon for the subjugation of rivals. And in these orderly insects there are obviously a capacity for labor, and co-operative labor at that, which could carry them far. We all know that they have a marked genius: great gifts of their own.
3857_182315_000028_000003 In a civilization of super ants or bees, there would have been no problem of the hungry unemployed, no poverty, no unstable government, no riots, no strikes for short hours, no derision of eugenics, no thieves, perhaps no crime at all.
3857_182315_000029_000000 Ants are good citizens: they place group interests first.
3857_182315_000030_000000 But they carry it so far, they have few or no political rights. An ant doesn't have the vote, apparently: he just has his duties.
3857_182315_000031_000000 This quality may have something to do with their having groups wars. The egotism of their individual spirits is allowed scant expression, so the egotism of the groups is extremely ferocious and active.
3857_182315_000031_000003 And the ants commit atrocities in and after their battles that are-I wish I could truly say-inhuman.
3857_182315_000032_000000 But conversely, ants are absolutely unselfish within the community. They are skilful.
3857_182315_000032_000001 Ingenious.
3857_182315_000032_000003 The scientists speak of their paved streets, vaulted halls, their hundreds of different domesticated animals, their pluck and intelligence, their individual initiative, their chaste and industrious lives.
3857_182315_000032_000004 Darwin said the ant's brain was "one of the most marvelous atoms in the world, perhaps more so than the brain of man"--yes, of present day man, who for thousands and thousands of years has had so much more chance to develop his brain....
3857_182315_000033_000000 When we think of these creatures as little men (which is all wrong of course) we see they have their faults.
3857_182315_000033_000001 To our eyes they seem too orderly, for instance.
3857_182315_000033_000002 Repressively so.
3857_182315_000033_000003 Their ways are more fixed than those of the old Egyptians, and their industry is painful to think of, it's hyper Chinese.
3857_182315_000033_000004 But we must remember this is a simian comment.
3857_182315_000033_000005 The instincts of the species that you and I belong to are of an opposite kind; and that makes it hard for us to judge ants fairly.
3857_182315_000034_000001 And instead of merely struggling with Nature for it, they also fight other ants.
3857_182315_000034_000002 The custom of plunder seems to be a part of most of their wars.
3857_182315_000034_000003 This has gone on for ages among them, and continues today.
3857_182315_000034_000004 Raids, ferocious combats, and loot are part of an ant's regular life.
3857_182315_000034_000005 Ant reformers, if there were any, might lay this to their property sense, and talk of abolishing property as a cure for the evil.
3857_182315_000036_000001 But this would have run against their strongest instincts.
3857_182315_000036_000002 The ant is knowing and wise; but he doesn't know enough to take a vacation. The worshipper of energy is too physically energetic to see that he cannot explore certain higher fields until he is still.
3857_182315_000037_000000 Even if such a race had somehow achieved self consciousness and reason, would they have been able therewith to rule their instincts, or to stop work long enough to examine themselves, or the universe, or to dream of any noble development?
3857_182315_000037_000001 Probably not.
3857_182315_000037_000002 Reason is seldom or never the ruler: it is the servant of instinct.
3857_182315_000038_000000 "Toil has brought you up from the ruck of things." Reason would have plausibly said, "it's by virtue of feverish toil that you have become what you are.
3857_182317_000000_000000 seven
3857_182317_000001_000000 There are many other beasts that one might once have thought had a chance.
3857_182317_000002_000000 Some, like horses and deer, were not bold enough; or were stupid, like buffaloes.
3857_182317_000003_000000 Some had over trustful characters, like the seals; or exploitable characters, like cows, and chickens, and sheep.
3857_182317_000003_000001 Such creatures sentence themselves to be captives, by their lack of ambition.
3857_182317_000004_000001 They have more spirit.
3857_182317_000004_000005 And we have betrayed them by making under simians of them.
3857_182317_000004_000007 Loving us, they let us stop their developing in tune with their natures; and they've patiently tried ever since to adopt ways of ours.
3857_182317_000004_000008 They have done it, too; but of course they can't get far: it's not their own road.
3857_182317_000004_000010 They've been true to us, yes, but they haven't been true to themselves.
3857_182317_000005_000001 The pig is remarkably intelligent and brave,--but he's gross; and grossness delays one's achievement, it takes so much time.
3857_182317_000005_000003 If super snake men had had banquets they would have been too vast to describe.
3857_182317_000005_000004 Each little snake family could have eaten a herd of cattle at Christmas.
3857_182317_000006_000000 Goats, then?
3857_182317_000006_000002 Wolves, whales, crows?
3857_182317_000007_000003 He had the best chance of all.
3857_182317_000007_000004 Wiser even than the lion, or the wisest of apes, his wisdom furthermore was benign where theirs was sinister. Consider his dignity, his poise and skill.
3857_182317_000007_000005 He was plastic, too.
3857_182317_000007_000011 What was it then, that put them out of the race?
3857_182317_000009_000000 And when they saw that they hadn't, and that the monkey men were getting ahead, were they too great minded and decent to exterminate their puny rivals?
3857_182317_000010_000000 It may have been their tolerance and patience that betrayed them. They wait too long before they resent an imposition or insult. Just as ants are too energetic and cats too shrewd for their own highest good, so the elephants suffer from too much patience.
3857_182317_000010_000001 Their exhibitions of it may seem superb,--such power and such restraint, combined, are noble,--but a quality carried to excess defeats itself.
3857_182317_000010_000002 Kings who won't lift their scepters must yield in the end; and, the worst of it is, to upstarts who snatch at their crowns.
3857_182317_000011_000002 All species must surrender unconditionally-those are our terms-and come and live in barns alongside us; or on us, as parasites.
3857_182317_000011_000003 The creatures that want to live a life of their own, we call wild.
3857_182317_000011_000005 Some might be our friends.
3857_182317_000011_000006 We don't wish it.
3857_182317_000011_000007 We keep them all terrorized.
3857_182317_000011_000009 It is not that we have planned this deliberately: but they know what we're like.
3857_182317_000011_000010 Race by race they have been slaughtered.
3857_182317_000012_000000 If we had been as strong as the elephants, we might have been kinder. When great power comes naturally to people, it is used more urbanely. We use it as parvenus do, because that's what we are.
3857_182317_000012_000001 The elephant, being born to it, is easy going, confident, tolerant.
3857_182317_000015_000001 Isn't it strange?
3857_182317_000015_000002 A tool, in the most primitive sense, is any object, lying around, that can obviously be used as an instrument for this or that purpose.
3857_182317_000015_000005 When an elephant plucks off a branch and swishes his flanks, and thus keeps away insects, he is using a tool.
3857_182317_000015_000007 If he once became a conscious user of tools he would of course go much further.
3857_182317_000016_000001 Think of the long epochs that passed before it entered our heads.
3857_182317_000017_000001 The lesson to be learned was simple: the reward was the rule of a planet. Yet only one species, our own, has ever had that much brains.
3857_182317_000019_000000 It is not necessarily stupid however, to fail to use tools.
3857_182317_000019_000001 To use tools involves using reason, instead of sticking to instinct. Now, sticking to instinct has its disadvantages, but so has using reason.
3857_182317_000019_000002 Whichever faculty you use, the other atrophies, and partly deserts you.
3857_182317_000019_000003 We are trying to use both.
3857_182317_000019_000004 But we still don't know which has the more value.
3857_182317_000022_000000 eight
3857_182317_000023_000000 We have been considering which species was on the whole most finely equipped to be rulers, and thereafter achieve a high civilization; but that wasn't the problem.
3857_182317_000025_000000 The rhinoceros cares little for adaptability.
3857_182317_000025_000001 He slogs through the world.
3857_182317_000025_000002 But we! we are experts.
3857_182317_000025_000003 Adaptability is what we depend on. We talk of our mastery of nature, which sounds very grand; but the fact is we respectfully adapt ourselves first, to her ways.
3857_182317_000025_000004 "We attain no power over nature till we learn natural laws, and our lordship depends on the adroitness with which we learn and conform."
3857_182317_000026_000000 Adroitness however is merely an ability to win; back of it there must be some spur to make us use our adroitness.
3857_182317_000026_000001 Why don't we all die or give up when we're sick of the world?
3857_182317_000026_000002 Because the love of life is reenforced, in most energized beings, by some longing that pushes them forward, in defeat and in darkness.
3857_182317_000026_000003 All creatures wish to live, and to perpetuate their species, of course; but those two wishes alone evidently do not carry any race far.
3857_182317_000026_000004 In addition to these, a race, to be great, needs some hunger, some itch, to spur it up the hard path we lately have learned to call evolution.
3857_182317_000027_000000 With us is it curiosity?
3857_182317_000027_000001 endless interest in one's environment?
3857_182317_000028_000001 By a master passion, I mean a passion that is really your master: some appetite which habitually, day in, day out, makes its subjects forget fatigue or danger, and sacrifice their ease to its gratification.
3857_182317_000028_000002 That is the kind of hold that curiosity has on the monkeys.
3879_173592_000005_000000 FAMINE.
3879_173592_000005_000001 WAR. SUCCOR.
3879_173592_000006_000000 While the mutiny was brewing, one La Roche Ferriere had been sent out as an agent or emissary among the more distant tribes.
3879_173592_000006_000001 Sagacious, bold, and restless, he pushed his way from town to town, and pretended to have reached the mysterious mountains of Appalache.
3879_173592_000006_000002 He sent to the fort mantles woven with feathers, quivers covered with choice furs, arrows tipped with gold, wedges of a green stone like beryl or emerald, and other trophies of his wanderings.
3879_173592_000006_000003 A gentleman named Grotaut took up the quest, and penetrated to the dominions of Hostaqua, who, it was pretended, could muster three or four thousand warriors, and who promised, with the aid of a hundred arquebusiers, to conquer all the kings of the adjacent mountains, and subject them and their gold mines to the rule of the French.
3879_173592_000006_000006 But, as his sway verged towards despotism, his subjects took offence, and split his head with a hatchet.
3879_173592_000007_000000 During the winter, Indians from the neighborhood of Cape Canaveral brought to the fort two Spaniards, wrecked fifteen years before on the southwestern extremity of the peninsula.
3879_173592_000007_000001 They were clothed like the Indians,--in other words, were not clothed at all,--and their uncut hair streamed loose down their backs.
3879_173592_000007_000003 They told of the King of Cabs, on whose domains they had been wrecked, a chief mighty in stature and in power. In one of his villages was a pit, six feet deep and as wide as a hogshead, filled with treasure gathered from Spanish wrecks on adjacent reefs and keys.
3879_173592_000007_000004 The monarch was a priest too, and a magician, with power over the elements.
3879_173592_000007_000005 Each year he withdrew from the public gaze to hold converse in secret with supernal or infernal powers; and each year he sacrificed to his gods one of the Spaniards whom the fortune of the sea had cast upon his shores.
3879_173592_000007_000006 The name of the tribe is preserved in that of the river Caboosa.
3879_173592_000007_000007 In close league with him was the mighty Oathcaqua, dwelling near Cape Canaveral, who gave his daughter, a maiden of wondrous beauty, in marriage to his great ally.
3879_173592_000008_000001 Ottigny set forth on this fool's errand with thrice the force demanded.
3879_173592_000008_000002 Three hundred Thirnagoas and thirty Frenchmen took up their march through the pine barrens.
3879_173592_000008_000003 Outina's conjurer was of the number, and had wellnigh ruined the enterprise.
3879_173592_000008_000006 Again they moved forward, and soon encountered Potanou with all his host.
3879_173592_000008_000008 But no persuasion could induce Outina to follow up his victory.
3879_173592_000008_000009 He went home to dance round his trophies, and the French returned disgusted to Fort Caroline.
3879_173592_000009_000000 And now, in ample measure, the French began to reap the harvest of their folly.
3879_173592_000009_000001 Conquest, gold, and military occupation had alone been their aims.
3879_173592_000009_000002 Not a rod of ground had been stirred with the spade.
3879_173592_000009_000003 Their stores were consumed, and the expected supplies had not come.
3879_173592_000009_000004 The Indians, too, were hostile.
3879_173592_000009_000006 Yet in these, their dark and subtle neighbors, was their only hope.
3879_173592_000010_000000 May day came, the third anniversary of the day when Ribaut and his companions, full of delighted anticipation, had first explored the flowery borders of the saint John's.
3879_173592_000010_000002 If they had had any skill in hunting and fishing, the river and the woods would have supplied their needs; but in this point, as in others, they were lamentably unfit for the work they had taken in hand.
3879_173592_000011_000000 Had Coligny left them to perish?
3879_173592_000011_000001 Or had some new tempest of calamity, let loose upon France, drowned the memory of their exile?
3879_173592_000011_000002 In vain the watchman on the hill surveyed the solitude of waters.
3879_173592_000011_000003 A deep dejection fell upon them,--a dejection that would have sunk to despair could their eyes have pierced the future.
3879_173592_000012_000000 The Indians had left the neighborhood, but from time to time brought in meagre supplies of fish, which they sold to the famished soldiers at exorbitant prices.
3879_173592_000012_000002 If at any time they shewed unto the savages the excessive price which they tooke, these villaines would answere them roughly and churlishly: If thou make so great account of thy marchandise, eat it, and we will eat our fish: then fell they out a laughing, and mocked us with open throat."
3879_173592_000013_000000 The spring wore away, and no relief appeared.
3879_173592_000013_000001 One thought now engrossed the colonists, that of return to France.
3879_173592_000013_000003 But these vessels were insufficient, and they prepared to build a new one.
3879_173592_000013_000004 The energy of reviving hope lent new life to their exhausted frames.
3879_173592_000014_000000 The colonists applied to Outina, who owed them two victories.
3879_173592_000014_000001 The result was a churlish message and a niggardly supply of corn, coupled with an invitation to aid him against an insurgent chief, one Astina, the plunder of whose villages would yield an ample supply.
3879_173592_000014_000002 The offer was accepted.
3879_173592_000015_000001 The commandant was forced to comply.
3879_173592_000015_000003 Having reached Outina's landing, they marched inland, entered his village, surrounded his mud plastered palace, seized him amid the yells and howlings of his subjects, and led him prisoner to their boats.
3879_173592_000015_000004 Here, anchored in mid stream, they demanded a supply of corn and beans as the price of his ransom.
3879_173592_000016_000000 The alarm spread.
3879_173592_000016_000001 Excited warriors, bedaubed with red, came thronging from all his villages.
3879_173592_000016_000003 Yet no ransom was offered, since, reasoning from their own instincts, they never doubted that, after the price was paid, the captive would be put to death.
3879_173592_000017_000001 In a rude chamber of Fort Caroline the sentinel stood his guard, pike in hand, while before him crouched the captive chief, mute, impassive, and brooding on his woes.
3879_173592_000017_000002 His old enemy, Satouriona, keen as a hound on the scent of prey, tried, by great offers, to bribe Laudonniere to give Outina into his hands; but the French captain refused, treated his prisoner kindly, and assured him of immediate freedom on payment of the ransom.
3879_173592_000018_000000 Meanwhile his captivity was bringing grievous affliction on his tribesmen; for, despairing of his return, they mustered for the election of a new chief.
3879_173592_000018_000001 Party strife ran high.
3879_173592_000018_000002 Some were for a boy, his son, and some for an ambitious kinsman.
3879_173592_000018_000003 Outina chafed in his prison on learning these dissentions; and, eager to convince his over hasty subjects that their chief still lived, he was so profuse of promises that he was again embarked and carried up the river.
3879_173592_000019_000000 At no great distance from Lake George, a small affluent of the saint John's gave access by water to a point within six French leagues of Outina's principal town.
3879_173592_000019_000001 The two barges, crowded with soldiers, and bearing also the captive Outina, rowed up this little stream.
3879_173592_000019_000003 As they were deaf to all other terms, Laudonniere yielded, released his prisoner, and received in his place two hostages, who were fast bound in the boats.
3879_173592_000019_000004 Ottigny and Arlac, with a strong detachment of arquebusiers, went to receive the promised supplies, for which, from the first, full payment in merchandise had been offered.
3879_173592_000019_000005 On their arrival at the village, they filed into the great central lodge, within whose dusky precincts were gathered the magnates of the tribe. Council chamber, forum, banquet hall, and dancing hall all in one, the spacious structure could hold half the population.
3879_173592_000019_000006 Here the French made their abode.
3879_173592_000019_000008 Corn came in slowly, but warriors mustered fast.
3879_173592_000019_000009 The village without was full of them.
3879_173592_000019_000010 The French officers grew anxious, and urged the chiefs to greater alacrity in collecting the promised ransom. The answer boded no good: "Our women are afraid when they see the matches of your guns burning.
3879_173592_000019_000011 Put them out, and they will bring the corn faster."
3879_173592_000020_000000 Outina was nowhere to be seen.
3879_173592_000020_000001 At length they learned that he was in one of the small huts adjacent.
3879_173592_000020_000002 Several of the officers went to him, complaining of the slow payment of his ransom.
3879_173592_000020_000003 The kindness of his captors at Fort Caroline seemed to have won his heart.
3879_173592_000020_000005 The peril was thickening hourly, and Ottigny resolved to regain the boats while there was yet time.
3879_173592_000021_000000 On the twenty seventh of July, at nine in the morning, he set his men in order.
3879_173592_000021_000001 Each shouldering a sack of corn, they marched through the rows of huts that surrounded the great lodge, and out betwixt the overlapping extremities of the palisade that encircled the town.
3879_173592_000021_000002 Before them stretched a wide avenue, three or four hundred paces long, flanked by a natural growth of trees,--one of those curious monuments of native industry to which allusion has already been made.
3879_173592_000021_000003 Here Ottigny halted and formed his line of march.
3879_173592_000021_000004 Arlac, with eight matchlock men, was sent in advance, and flanking parties were thrown into the woods on either side.
3879_173592_000021_000006 He was right.
3879_173592_000021_000007 As Arlac's party reached the spot, the whole pack gave tongue at once.
3879_173592_000021_000009 They stood firm, and sent back their shot so steadily that several of the assailants were laid dead, and the rest, two or three hundred in number, gave way as Ottigny came up with his men.
3879_173592_000022_000000 They moved on for a quarter of a mile through a country, as it seems, comparatively open, when again the war cry pealed in front, and three hundred savages bounded to the assault.
3879_173592_000022_000001 Their whoops were echoed from the rear.
3879_173592_000022_000002 It was the party whom Arlac had just repulsed, and who, leaping and showering their arrows, were rushing on again with a ferocity restrained only by their lack of courage.
3879_173592_000022_000003 There was no panic among the French.
3879_173592_000022_000007 With cries that imitated the yell of owls, the scream of cougars, and the howl of wolves, they ran up in successive bands, let fly their arrows, and instantly fell back, giving place to others.
3879_173592_000022_000010 As they fell, the soldiers picked them up and broke them.
3879_173592_000022_000011 Thus, beset with swarming savages, the handful of Frenchmen pushed slowly onward, fighting as they went.
3879_173592_000023_000000 The Indians gradually drew off, and the forest was silent again.
3879_173592_000023_000002 Of the corn, two bags only had been brought off.
3879_173592_000024_000000 Famine and desperation now reigned at Fort Caroline.
3879_173592_000024_000001 The Indians had killed two of the carpenters; hence long delay in the finishing of the new ship.
3879_173592_000025_000001 A great ship was standing towards the river's mouth.
3879_173592_000025_000002 Then another came in sight, and another, and another. He despatched a messenger with the tidings to the fort below.
3879_173592_000026_000000 A doubt soon mingled with their joy.
3879_173592_000026_000001 Who were the strangers?
3879_173592_000026_000002 Were they the friends so long hoped for in vain? or were they Spaniards, their dreaded enemies?
3879_173592_000026_000003 They were neither.
3879_173592_000026_000004 The foremost ship was a stately one, of seven hundred tons, a great burden at that day.
3879_173592_000027_000001 They were the pioneers of that detested traffic destined to inoculate with its infection nations yet unborn, the parent of discord and death, filling half a continent with the tramp of armies and the clash of fratricidal swords.
3879_173592_000027_000002 Their chief was Sir john Hawkins, father of the English slave trade.
3879_173592_000028_000000 He had been to the coast of Guinea, where he bought and kidnapped a cargo of slaves.
3879_173592_000028_000001 These he had sold to the jealous Spaniards of Hispaniola, forcing them, with sword, matchlock, and culverin, to grant him free trade, and then to sign testimonials that he had borne himself as became a peaceful merchant.
3879_173592_000029_000000 Among the rugged heroes of the British marine, Sir john stood in the front rank, and along with Drake, his relative, is extolled as "a man borne for the honour of the English name....
3879_173592_000030_000000 Hawkins came up the river in a pinnace, and landed at Fort Caroline, accompanied, says Laudonniere, "with gentlemen honorably apparelled, yet unarmed." Between the Huguenots and the English Puritans there was a double tie of sympathy.
3879_173592_000030_000001 Both hated priests, and both hated Spaniards. Wakening from their apathetic misery, the starveling garrison hailed him as a deliverer.
3879_173592_000030_000002 Yet Hawkins secretly rejoiced when he learned their purpose to abandon Florida; for although, not to tempt his cupidity, they hid from him the secret of their Appalachian gold mine, he coveted for his royal mistress the possession of this rich domain.
3879_173592_000030_000003 He shook his head, however, when he saw the vessels in which they proposed to embark, and offered them all a free passage to France in his own ships.
3879_173592_000031_000000 Laudonniere hesitated, and hereupon arose a great clamor.
3879_173592_000031_000001 A mob of soldiers and artisans beset his chamber, threatening loudly to desert him, and take passage with Hawkins, unless the offer were accepted.
3879_173592_000031_000002 The commandant accordingly resolved to buy the vessel.
3879_173592_000031_000003 The generous slaver, whose reputed avarice nowhere appears in the transaction, desired him to set his own price; and, in place of money, took the cannon of the fort, with other articles now useless to their late owners.
3879_173592_000032_000000 Before the English top sails had sunk beneath the horizon, the colonists bestirred themselves to depart.
3879_173592_000032_000001 In a few days their preparations were made.
3879_173592_000032_000002 They waited only for a fair wind.
3879_173592_000032_000003 It was long in coming, and meanwhile their troubled fortunes assumed a new phase.
3879_173592_000033_000001 Again the fort was wild with excitement.
3879_173592_000033_000002 Friends or foes, French or Spaniards, succor or death,--betwixt these were their hopes and fears divided.
3879_173592_000033_000003 On the following morning, they saw seven barges rowing up the river, bristling with weapons, and crowded with men in armor.
3879_173592_000033_000004 The sentries on the bluff challenged, and received no answer.
3879_173592_000033_000005 One of them fired at the advancing boats, and still there was no response.
3879_173592_000033_000006 Laudonniere was almost defenceless.
3879_173592_000033_000007 He had given his heavier cannon to Hawkins, and only two field pieces were left.
3879_173592_000033_000008 They were levelled at the foremost boats, and the word to fire was about to be given, when a voice from among the strangers called out that they were French, commanded by Jean Ribaut.
3879_173592_000034_000001 Ribaut had been commissioned to sail with seven ships for Florida.
3879_173592_000035_000000 No longer in dread of the Spaniards, the colonists saluted the new comers with the cannon by which a moment before they had hoped to blow them out of the water.
3879_173592_000035_000002 Ribaut was present, conspicuous by his long beard, an astonishment to the Indians; and here, too, were officers, old friends of Laudonniere.
3879_173592_000035_000003 Why, then, had they approached in the attitude of enemies?
3879_173592_000035_000004 The mystery was soon explained; for they expressed to the commandant their pleasure at finding that the charges made against him had proved false.
3879_173592_000035_000005 He begged to know more; on which Ribaut, taking him aside, told him that the returning ships had brought home letters filled with accusations of arrogance, tyranny, cruelty, and a purpose of establishing an independent command,--accusations which he now saw to be unfounded, but which had been the occasion of his unusual and startling precaution. He gave him, too, a letter from Admiral Coligny.
3879_173592_000035_000006 In brief but courteous terms, it required him to resign his command, and requested his return to France to clear his name from the imputations cast upon it.
3879_173592_000036_000000 Worn in body and mind, mortified and wounded, he soon fell ill again.
3879_173592_000037_000000 Stores were landed, tents were pitched, women and children were sent on shore, feathered Indians mingled in the throng, and the borders of the River of May swarmed with busy life.
3879_173592_000037_000001 "But, lo, how oftentimes misfortune doth search and pursue us, even then when we thinke to be at rest!" exclaims the unhappy Laudonniere.
3879_174923_000002_000000 Phineas Finn returned from Tankerville to London in much better spirits than those which had accompanied him on his journey thither. He was not elected; but then, before the election, he had come to believe that it was quite out of the question that he should be elected.
3879_174923_000002_000001 And now he did think it probable that he should get the seat on a petition.
3879_174923_000002_000002 A scrutiny used to be a very expensive business, but under the existing law, made as the scrutiny would be in the borough itself, it would cost but little; and that little, should he be successful, would fall on the shoulders of mr Browborough.
3879_174923_000002_000003 Should he knock off eight votes and lose none himself, he would be member for Tankerville.
3879_174923_000002_000004 He knew that many votes had been given for Browborough which, if the truth were known of them, would be knocked off; and he did not know that the same could be said of any one of those by which he had been supported.
3879_174923_000002_000005 But, unfortunately, the judge by whom all this would be decided might not reach Tankerville in his travels till after Christmas, perhaps not till after Easter; and in the meantime, what should he do with himself?
3879_174923_000003_000000 As for going back to Dublin, that was now out of the question.
3879_174923_000003_000001 He had entered upon a feverish state of existence in which it was impossible that he should live in Ireland.
3879_174923_000003_000002 Should he ultimately fail in regard to his seat he must-vanish out of the world.
3879_174923_000003_000005 Of one club he had always remained a member, and he had already been re-elected a member of the Reform.
3879_174923_000003_000006 So he took up his residence once more at the house of a certain mr and mrs Bunce, in Great Marlborough Street, with whom he had lodged when he first became a member of Parliament.
