3879_174923_000019_000002 Now Lord Chiltern was again his very intimate friend.
3879_174923_000019_000004 Alas! alas! how soon might he now require that money lender's services!
3879_174923_000019_000005 And then he recollected how he had left these rooms to go into others, grander and more appropriate to his life when he had filled high office under the State.
3879_174923_000019_000006 Would there ever again come to him such cause for migration?
3879_174923_000019_000007 And would he again be able to load the frame of the looking glass over the fire with countless cards from Countesses and Ministers' wives?
3879_174923_000019_000008 He had opened the oyster for himself once, though it had closed again with so sharp a snap when the point of his knife had been withdrawn.
3879_174923_000019_000009 Would he be able to insert the point again between those two difficult shells?
3879_174923_000019_000010 Would the Countesses once more be kind to him?
3879_174923_000019_000011 Would drawing rooms be opened to him, and sometimes opened to him and to no other?
3879_174923_000019_000012 Then he thought of certain special drawing rooms in which wonderful things had been said to him.
3879_174923_000019_000013 Since that he had been a married man, and those special drawing rooms and those wonderful words had in no degree actuated him in his choice of a wife.
3879_174923_000019_000014 He had left all those things of his own free will, as though telling himself that there was a better life than they offered to him.
3879_174923_000019_000016 He had certainly sighed for the gauds which he had left.
3879_174923_000019_000017 While his young wife was living he had kept his sighs down, so that she should not hear them; but he had been forced to acknowledge that his new life had been vapid and flavourless.
3879_174923_000019_000018 Now he had been tempted back again to the old haunts. Would the Countesses' cards be showered upon him again?
3879_174923_000020_000000 One card, or rather note, had reached him while he was yet at Tankerville, reminding him of old days.
3879_174923_000020_000001 It was from mrs Low, the wife of the barrister with whom he had worked when he had been a law student in London.
3879_174923_000020_000002 She had asked him to come and dine with them after the old fashion in Baker Street, naming a day as to which she presumed that he would by that time have finished his affairs at Tankerville, intimating also that mr Low would then have finished his at North Broughton.
3879_174923_000020_000003 Now mr Low had sat for North Broughton before Phineas left London, and his wife spoke of the seat as a certainty.
3879_174923_000020_000004 Phineas could not keep himself from feeling that mrs Low intended to triumph over him; but, nevertheless, he accepted the invitation.
3879_174923_000020_000005 They were very glad to see him, explaining that, as nobody was supposed to be in town, nobody had been asked to meet him.
3879_174923_000020_000006 In former days he had been very intimate in that house, having received from both of them much kindness, mingled, perhaps, with some touch of severity on the part of the lady.
3879_174923_000020_000007 But the ground for that was gone, and mrs Low was no longer painfully severe.
3879_174923_000020_000008 A few words were said as to his great loss.
