405_130894_000004_000000 CHAPTER sixteen
405_130894_000005_000000 Shortage of Air
405_130894_000006_000001 We were the Ice Bank's prisoners! The Canadian banged a table with his fearsome fist.
405_130894_000006_000004 He pondered.
405_130894_000006_000005 The Nautilus did not stir.
405_130894_000007_000000 The captain then broke into speech:
405_130894_000008_000000 "Gentlemen," he said in a calm voice, "there are two ways of dying under the conditions in which we're placed."
405_130894_000009_000000 This inexplicable individual acted like a mathematics professor working out a problem for his pupils.
405_130894_000010_000000 "The first way," he went on, "is death by crushing.
405_130894_000010_000001 The second is death by asphyxiation.
405_130894_000010_000003 Therefore, let's concentrate on our chances of being crushed or asphyxiated."
405_130894_000011_000000 "As for asphyxiation, captain," I replied, "that isn't a cause for alarm, because the air tanks are full."
405_130894_000015_000000 "Which one?" I asked.
405_130894_000016_000000 "Borings will tell us that.
405_130894_000017_000000 "Can the panels in the lounge be left open?"
405_130894_000018_000000 "Without ill effect.
405_130894_000019_000000 Captain Nemo went out.
405_130894_000019_000002 The Nautilus slowly settled and rested on the icy bottom at a depth of three hundred fifty meters, the depth at which the lower shelf of ice lay submerged.
405_130894_000020_000000 "My friends," I said, "we're in a serious predicament, but I'm counting on your courage and energy."
405_130894_000021_000000 "Sir," the Canadian replied, "this is no time to bore you with my complaints.
405_130894_000021_000001 I'm ready to do anything I can for the common good."
405_130894_000022_000000 "Excellent, Ned," I said, extending my hand to the Canadian.
405_130894_000023_000000 "I might add," he went on, "that I'm as handy with a pick as a harpoon. If I can be helpful to the captain, he can use me any way he wants."
405_130894_000024_000000 "He won't turn down your assistance.
405_130894_000025_000001 I informed the captain of Ned's proposition, which was promptly accepted.
405_130894_000027_000000 Some moments later, we saw a dozen crewmen set foot on the shelf of ice, among them Ned Land, easily recognized by his tall figure. Captain Nemo was with them.
405_130894_000028_000000 Before digging into the ice, the captain had to obtain borings, to insure working in the best direction.
405_130894_000028_000001 Long bores were driven into the side walls; but after fifteen meters, the instruments were still impeded by the thickness of those walls.
405_130894_000028_000002 It was futile to attack the ceiling since that surface was the Ice Bank itself, more than four hundred meters high.
405_130894_000028_000003 Captain Nemo then bored into the lower surface. There we were separated from the sea by a ten meter barrier. That's how thick the iceberg was.
405_130894_000029_000000 Work began immediately and was carried on with tireless tenacity. Instead of digging all around the Nautilus, which would have entailed even greater difficulties, Captain Nemo had an immense trench outlined on the ice, eight meters from our port quarter. Then his men simultaneously staked it off at several points around its circumference.
405_130894_000029_000002 But this hardly mattered so long as the lower surface kept growing thinner.
405_130894_000030_000001 The Nautilus's chief officer supervised us.
405_130894_000031_000000 The water struck me as unusually cold, but I warmed up promptly while wielding my pick.
405_130894_000031_000001 My movements were quite free, although they were executed under a pressure of thirty atmospheres.
405_130894_000032_000002 Meanwhile, after twelve hours had gone by, we had removed from the outlined surface area a slice of ice only one meter thick, hence about six hundred cubic meters. Assuming the same work would be accomplished every twelve hours, it would still take five nights and four days to see the undertaking through to completion.
405_130894_000033_000000 "Five nights and four days!" I told my companions.
405_130894_000033_000001 "And we have oxygen in the air tanks for only two days."
405_130894_000034_000000 "Without taking into account," Ned answered, "that once we're out of this damned prison, we'll still be cooped up beneath the Ice Bank, without any possible contact with the open air!"
405_130894_000035_000000 An apt remark.
405_130894_000035_000001 For who could predict the minimum time we would need to free ourselves?
405_130894_000035_000002 Before the Nautilus could return to the surface of the waves, couldn't we all die of asphyxiation?
405_130894_000035_000003 Were this ship and everyone on board doomed to perish in this tomb of ice? It was a dreadful state of affairs.
405_130894_000035_000004 But we faced it head on, each one of us determined to do his duty to the end.
405_130894_000036_000000 During the night, in line with my forecasts, a new one meter slice was removed from this immense socket.
405_130894_000037_000000 I didn't tell my two companions about this new danger. There was no point in dampening the energy they were putting into our arduous rescue work.
405_130894_000037_000001 But when I returned on board, I mentioned this serious complication to Captain Nemo.
405_130894_000038_000000 "I know," he told me in that calm tone the most dreadful outlook couldn't change.
405_130894_000038_000003 We've got to get there first, that's all."
405_130894_000039_000000 Get there first!
405_130894_000039_000001 By then I should have been used to this type of talk!
405_130894_000040_000000 For several hours that day, I wielded my pick doggedly. The work kept me going.
405_130894_000040_000001 Besides, working meant leaving the Nautilus, which meant breathing the clean oxygen drawn from the air tanks and supplied by our equipment, which meant leaving the thin, foul air behind.
405_130894_000041_000001 Oh, if only we had the chemical methods that would enable us to drive out this noxious gas! There was no lack of oxygen.
405_130894_000041_000002 All this water contained a considerable amount, and after it was decomposed by our powerful batteries, this life giving elastic fluid could have been restored to us. I had thought it all out, but to no avail because the carbon dioxide produced by our breathing permeated every part of the ship. To absorb it, we would need to fill containers with potassium hydroxide and shake them continually.
405_130894_000041_000003 But this substance was missing on board and nothing else could replace it.
405_130894_000042_000000 That evening Captain Nemo was forced to open the spigots of his air tanks and shoot a few spouts of fresh oxygen through the Nautilus's interior. Without this precaution we wouldn't have awakened the following morning.
405_130894_000043_000000 The next day, march twenty sixth, I returned to my miner's trade, working to remove the fifth meter.
405_130894_000043_000001 The Ice Bank's side walls and underbelly had visibly thickened.
405_130894_000043_000002 Obviously they would come together before the Nautilus could break free.
405_130894_000043_000003 For an instant I was gripped by despair. My pick nearly slipped from my hands.
405_130894_000043_000004 What was the point of this digging if I was to die smothered and crushed by this water turning to stone, a torture undreamed of by even the wildest savages! I felt like I was lying in the jaws of a fearsome monster, jaws irresistibly closing.
405_130894_000044_000000 Supervising our work, working himself, Captain Nemo passed near me just then.
405_130894_000045_000000 The captain understood and gave me a signal to follow him. We returned on board.
405_130894_000046_000000 "Professor Aronnax," he told me, "this calls for heroic measures, or we'll be sealed up in this solidified water as if it were cement."
405_130894_000047_000000 "Yes!" I said.
405_130894_000047_000001 "But what can we do?"
405_130894_000048_000000 "Oh," he exclaimed, "if only my Nautilus were strong enough to stand that much pressure without being crushed!"
405_130894_000049_000000 "Well?" I asked, not catching the captain's meaning.
405_130894_000050_000000 "Don't you understand," he went on, "that the congealing of this water could come to our rescue?
405_130894_000050_000002 Aren't you aware that this force could be the instrument of our salvation rather than our destruction?"
405_130894_000051_000000 "Yes, captain, maybe so.
405_130894_000051_000001 But whatever resistance to crushing the Nautilus may have, it still couldn't stand such dreadful pressures, and it would be squashed as flat as a piece of sheet iron."
405_130894_000052_000001 So we can't rely on nature to rescue us, only our own efforts.
405_130894_000052_000002 We must counteract this solidification. We must hold it in check.
405_130894_000052_000003 Not only are the side walls closing in, but there aren't ten feet of water ahead or astern of the Nautilus. All around us, this freeze is gaining fast."
405_130894_000053_000000 "How long," I asked, "will the oxygen in the air tanks enable us to breathe on board?"
405_130894_000055_000000 "After tomorrow," he said, "the air tanks will be empty!"
405_130894_000056_000000 I broke out in a cold sweat.
405_130894_000056_000003 It was now the twenty sixth. We had lived off the ship's stores for five days! And all remaining breathable air had to be saved for the workmen. Even today as I write these lines, my sensations are so intense that an involuntary terror sweeps over me, and my lungs still seem short of air!
405_130894_000057_000000 Meanwhile, motionless and silent, Captain Nemo stood lost in thought. An idea visibly crossed his mind.
405_130894_000057_000001 But he seemed to brush it aside. He told himself no
405_130894_000057_000002 At last these words escaped his lips:
405_130894_000058_000000 "Boiling water!" he muttered.
405_130894_000059_000000 "Boiling water?" I exclaimed.
405_130894_000060_000001 We're shut up in a relatively confined area. If the Nautilus's pumps continually injected streams of boiling water into this space, wouldn't that raise its temperature and delay its freezing?"
405_130894_000061_000000 "It's worth trying!" I said resolutely.
405_130894_000062_000000 "So let's try it, professor."
405_130894_000064_000001 That was one degree gained. Two hours later the thermometer gave only minus four degrees.
405_130894_000065_000000 After I monitored the operation's progress, double checking it with many inspections, I told the captain, "It's working."
405_130894_000066_000000 "I think so," he answered me.
405_130894_000066_000001 "We've escaped being crushed. Now we have only asphyxiation to fear."
405_130894_000068_000000 By the next day, march twenty seventh, six meters of ice had been torn from the socket.
405_130894_000068_000003 Accordingly, that day it kept getting worse.
405_130894_000069_000001 Near three o'clock in the afternoon, this agonizing sensation affected me to an intense degree. Yawns dislocated my jaws.
405_130894_000069_000002 My lungs were gasping in their quest for that enkindling elastic fluid required for breathing, now growing scarcer and scarcer.
405_130894_000069_000004 He held my hand, he kept encouraging me, and I even heard him mutter:
405_130894_000070_000000 "Oh, if only I didn't have to breathe, to leave more air for master!"
405_130894_000071_000000 It brought tears to my eyes to hear him say these words.
405_130894_000072_000001 Arms grew weary, hands were rubbed raw, but who cared about exhaustion, what difference were wounds? Life sustaining air reached our lungs!
405_130894_000072_000002 We could breathe! We could breathe!
405_130894_000073_000000 And yet nobody prolonged his underwater work beyond the time allotted him.
405_130894_000073_000001 His shift over, each man surrendered to a gasping companion the air tank that would revive him.
405_130894_000073_000002 Captain Nemo set the example and was foremost in submitting to this strict discipline. When his time was up, he yielded his equipment to another and reentered the foul air on board, always calm, unflinching, and uncomplaining.
405_130894_000074_000001 But the ship's air tanks were nearly empty.
405_130894_000074_000002 The little air that remained had to be saved for the workmen.
405_130894_000075_000000 When I returned on board, I felt half suffocated.
405_130894_000075_000001 What a night! I'm unable to depict it.
405_130894_000075_000002 Such sufferings are indescribable. The next day I was short winded.
405_130894_000075_000003 Headaches and staggering fits of dizziness made me reel like a drunk.
405_130894_000075_000005 Some crewmen were at their last gasp.
405_130894_000076_000000 That day, the sixth of our imprisonment, Captain Nemo concluded that picks and mattocks were too slow to deal with the ice layer still separating us from open water-and he decided to crush this layer. The man had kept his energy and composure.
405_130894_000076_000001 He had subdued physical pain with moral strength.
405_130894_000076_000002 He could still think, plan, and act.
405_130894_000077_000000 At his orders the craft was eased off, in other words, it was raised from its icy bed by a change in its specific gravity. When it was afloat, the crew towed it, leading it right above the immense trench outlined to match the ship's waterline. Next the ballast tanks filled with water, the boat sank, and was fitted into its socket.
405_130894_000078_000000 Just then the whole crew returned on board, and the double outside door was closed.
405_130894_000080_000000 We waited, we listened, we forgot our sufferings, we hoped once more. We had staked our salvation on this one last gamble.
405_130894_000081_000001 We tilted.
405_130894_000081_000002 The ice cracked with an odd ripping sound, like paper tearing, and the Nautilus began settling downward.
405_130894_000083_000000 I couldn't answer him.
405_130894_000083_000001 I clutched his hand.
405_130894_000083_000002 I squeezed it in an involuntary convulsion.
405_130894_000084_000000 All at once, carried away by its frightful excess load, the Nautilus sank into the waters like a cannonball, in other words, dropping as if in a vacuum!
405_130894_000085_000000 Our full electric power was then put on the pumps, which instantly began to expel water from the ballast tanks. After a few minutes we had checked our fall.
405_130894_000085_000001 The pressure gauge soon indicated an ascending movement.
405_130894_000085_000002 Brought to full speed, the propeller made the sheet iron hull tremble down to its rivets, and we sped northward.
405_130894_000086_000001 Another day?
405_130894_000086_000002 I would be dead first!
405_130894_000087_000000 Half lying on a couch in the library, I was suffocating. My face was purple, my lips blue, my faculties in abeyance. I could no longer see or hear.
405_130894_000087_000001 I had lost all sense of time. My muscles had no power to contract.
405_130894_000088_000000 I'm unable to estimate the hours that passed in this way. But I was aware that my death throes had begun.
405_130894_000088_000001 I realized that I was about to die . . .
405_130894_000089_000000 Suddenly I regained consciousness.
405_130894_000089_000002 Had we risen to the surface of the waves? Had we cleared the Ice Bank?
405_130894_000090_000002 Instead of breathing it themselves, they had saved it for me, and while they were suffocating, they poured life into me drop by drop!
405_130894_000090_000003 I tried to push the device away. They held my hands, and for a few moments I could breathe luxuriously.
405_130894_000091_000000 My eyes flew toward the clock.
405_130894_000091_000002 The Nautilus was traveling at the frightful speed of forty miles per hour.
405_130894_000091_000003 It was writhing in the waters.
405_130894_000092_000000 Where was Captain Nemo?
405_130894_000092_000001 Had he perished?
405_130894_000092_000002 Had his companions died with him?
405_130894_000093_000001 Separating us from the open air was a mere tract of ice.
405_130894_000093_000002 Could we break through it?
405_130894_000094_000000 Perhaps!
405_130894_000094_000001 In any event the Nautilus was going to try.
405_130894_000094_000002 In fact, I could feel it assuming an oblique position, lowering its stern and raising its spur.
405_130894_000094_000003 The admission of additional water was enough to shift its balance.
405_130895_000001_000000 CHAPTER seventeen
405_130895_000002_000000 From Cape Horn to the Amazon
405_130895_000003_000001 But I could breathe, I could inhale the life giving sea air.
405_130895_000003_000002 Next to me my two companions were getting tipsy on the fresh oxygen particles. Poor souls who have suffered from long starvation mustn't pounce heedlessly on the first food given them.
405_130895_000003_000003 We, on the other hand, didn't have to practice such moderation: we could suck the atoms from the air by the lungful, and it was the breeze, the breeze itself, that poured into us this luxurious intoxication!
405_130895_000004_000002 Let master have no fears about breathing.
405_130895_000004_000003 There's enough for everyone."
405_130895_000005_000000 As for Ned Land, he didn't say a word, but his wide open jaws would have scared off a shark.
405_130895_000005_000001 And what powerful inhalations! The Canadian "drew" like a furnace going full blast.
405_130895_000006_000000 Our strength returned promptly, and when I looked around, I saw that we were alone on the platform.
405_130895_000006_000001 No crewmen. Not even Captain Nemo.
405_130895_000006_000003 Not one of them had come up to enjoy the open air.
405_130895_000007_000000 The first words I pronounced were words of appreciation and gratitude to my two companions.
405_130895_000008_000001 Not a thing.
405_130895_000008_000002 It was a question of simple arithmetic.
405_130895_000008_000003 Your life is worth more than ours. So we had to save it."
405_130895_000009_000001 Nobody could be better than a kind and generous man like yourself!"
405_130895_000010_000000 "All right, all right!" the Canadian repeated in embarrassment.
405_130895_000012_000000 "Not too much, to be candid with master.
405_130895_000012_000002 Besides, when I saw master fainting, it left me without the slightest desire to breathe. It took my breath away, in a manner of . . ."
405_130895_000014_000000 "My friends," I replied, very moved, "we're bound to each other forever, and I'm deeply indebted to you-"
405_130895_000015_000000 "Which I'll take advantage of," the Canadian shot back.
405_130895_000017_000000 "Yes," Ned Land went on.
405_130895_000017_000001 "You can repay your debt by coming with me when I leave this infernal Nautilus."
405_130895_000019_000000 "Yes," I replied, "because we're going in the direction of the sun, and here the sun is due north."
405_130895_000020_000000 "Sure," Ned Land went on, "but it remains to be seen whether we'll make for the Atlantic or the Pacific, in other words, whether we'll end up in well traveled or deserted seas."
405_130895_000021_000000 I had no reply to this, and I feared that Captain Nemo wouldn't take us homeward but rather into that huge ocean washing the shores of both Asia and America.
405_130895_000021_000001 In this way he would complete his underwater tour of the world, going back to those seas where the Nautilus enjoyed the greatest freedom.
405_130895_000021_000002 But if we returned to the Pacific, far from every populated shore, what would happen to Ned Land's plans?
405_130895_000022_000000 We would soon settle this important point.
405_130895_000022_000001 The Nautilus traveled swiftly.
405_130895_000022_000002 Soon we had cleared the Antarctic Circle plus the promontory of Cape Horn.
405_130895_000023_000000 By then all our past sufferings were forgotten.
405_130895_000023_000001 The memory of that imprisonment under the ice faded from our minds. We had thoughts only of the future.
405_130895_000023_000003 The positions reported each day on the world map were put there by the chief officer, and they enabled me to determine the Nautilus's exact heading. Now then, that evening it became obvious, much to my satisfaction, that we were returning north by the Atlantic route.
405_130895_000025_000000 "That's good news," the Canadian replied, "but where's the Nautilus going?"
405_130895_000026_000000 "I'm unable to say, Ned."
405_130895_000027_000000 "After the South Pole, does our captain want to tackle the North Pole, then go back to the Pacific by the notorious Northwest Passage?"
405_130895_000029_000000 "Oh well," the Canadian said, "we'll give him the slip long before then."
405_130895_000031_000000 "Especially once we've left him," Ned Land shot back.
405_130895_000033_000000 "A first-class barometer, my friend."
405_130895_000035_000000 Just then its peak appeared before us, standing out distinctly against the background of the skies.
405_130895_000035_000001 This forecast fair weather. And so it proved.
405_130895_000036_000002 Here seals and otters could indulge in a sumptuous meal, mixing meat from fish with vegetables from the sea, like the English with their Irish stews.
405_130895_000037_000000 The Nautilus passed over these lush, luxuriant depths with tremendous speed.
405_130895_000037_000001 Near evening it approached the Falkland Islands, whose rugged summits I recognized the next day.
405_130895_000037_000002 The sea was of moderate depth.
405_130895_000037_000005 Later Sir Richard Hawkins called them the Maidenland, after the Blessed Virgin.
405_130895_000038_000000 In these waterways our nets brought up fine samples of algae, in particular certain fucus plants whose roots were laden with the world's best mussels.
405_130895_000038_000001 Geese and duck alighted by the dozens on the platform and soon took their places in the ship's pantry. As for fish, I specifically observed some bony fish belonging to the goby genus, especially some gudgeon two decimeters long, sprinkled with whitish and yellow spots.
405_130895_000039_000000 I likewise marveled at the numerous medusas, including the most beautiful of their breed, the compass jellyfish, unique to the Falkland seas. Some of these jellyfish were shaped like very smooth, semispheric parasols with russet stripes and fringes of twelve neat festoons.
405_130895_000039_000001 Others looked like upside-down baskets from which wide leaves and long red twigs were gracefully trailing. They swam with quiverings of their four leaflike arms, letting the opulent tresses of their tentacles dangle in the drift. I wanted to preserve a few specimens of these delicate zoophytes, but they were merely clouds, shadows, illusions, melting and evaporating outside their native element.
405_130895_000041_000001 Keeping to its northerly heading, it followed the long windings of South America.
405_130895_000041_000002 By then we had fared sixteen thousand leagues since coming on board in the seas of Japan.
405_130895_000042_000000 Near eleven o'clock in the morning, we cut the Tropic of Capricorn on the thirty seventh meridian, passing well out from Cape Frio.
405_130895_000042_000001 Much to Ned Land's displeasure, Captain Nemo had no liking for the neighborhood of Brazil's populous shores, because he shot by with dizzying speed. Not even the swiftest fish or birds could keep up with us, and the natural curiosities in these seas completely eluded our observation.
405_130895_000043_000003 The floor of this immense valley is made picturesque by mountains that furnish these underwater depths with scenic views. This description is based mostly on certain hand drawn charts kept in the Nautilus's library, charts obviously rendered by Captain Nemo himself from his own personal observations.
405_130895_000044_000001 The Nautilus would do long, diagonal dives that took us to every level.
405_130895_000045_000000 We cut the Equator.
405_130895_000047_000000 Some zoophytes were dredged up by the chain of our trawl.
405_130895_000051_000000 One of our nets had hauled up a type of very flat ray that weighed some twenty kilograms; with its tail cut off, it would have formed a perfect disk.
405_130895_000051_000001 It was white underneath and reddish on top, with big round spots of deep blue encircled in black, its hide quite smooth and ending in a double lobed fin.
405_130895_000052_000000 Instantly there he was, thrown on his back, legs in the air, his body half paralyzed, and yelling:
405_130895_000053_000001 Will you help me!"
405_130895_000054_000000 For once in his life, the poor lad didn't address me "in the third person."
405_130895_000055_000000 The Canadian and I sat him up; we massaged his contracted arms, and when he regained his five senses, that eternal classifier mumbled in a broken voice:
405_130895_000057_000000 "Yes, my friend," I answered, "it was an electric ray that put you in this deplorable state."
405_130895_000059_000000 "How?"
405_130895_000060_000000 "I'll eat it."
405_130895_000061_000000 Which he did that same evening, but strictly as retaliation. Because, frankly, it tasted like leather.
405_130895_000062_000001 Living in a conducting medium such as water, this bizarre animal can electrocute other fish from several meters away, so great is the power of its electric organ, an organ whose two chief surfaces measure at least twenty seven square feet.
405_130895_000064_000000 "And do you know," I added, "what happened since man has almost completely wiped out these beneficial races? Rotting weeds have poisoned the air, and this poisoned air causes the yellow fever that devastates these wonderful countries. This toxic vegetation has increased beneath the seas of the Torrid Zone, so the disease spreads unchecked from the mouth of the Rio de la Plata to Florida!"
405_130895_000065_000001 By then, crowded with jellyfish, squid, and other devilfish, the oceans will have become huge centers of infection, because their waves will no longer possess "these huge stomachs that God has entrusted with scouring the surface of the sea."
405_130895_000066_000001 In essence, it was an issue of stocking the larder with excellent red meat, even better than beef or veal. Their hunting was not a fascinating sport.
405_130895_000067_000000 The same day an odd fishing practice further increased the Nautilus's stores, so full of game were these seas. Our trawl brought up in its meshes a number of fish whose heads were topped by little oval slabs with fleshy edges.
405_130895_000067_000001 These were suckerfish from the third family of the subbrachian Malacopterygia.
405_130895_000067_000002 These flat disks on their heads consist of crosswise plates of movable cartilage, between which the animals can create a vacuum, enabling them to stick to objects like suction cups.
405_130895_000068_000002 Right after catching them, our seamen dropped them in buckets of water.
405_130895_000069_000000 Its fishing finished, the Nautilus drew nearer to the coast. In this locality a number of sea turtles were sleeping on the surface of the waves.
405_130895_000069_000001 It would have been difficult to capture these valuable reptiles, because they wake up at the slightest sound, and their solid carapaces are harpoon proof.
405_130895_000069_000002 But our suckerfish would effect their capture with extraordinary certainty and precision. In truth, this animal is a living fishhook, promising wealth and happiness to the greenest fisherman in the business.
4088_158077_000055_000000 Still uncertain as to the purposes of the Republicans, the Democrats were moved to further action.
4088_158077_000056_000003 And so the Democratic Executive Committee began to spread abroad the news that its act was not really official, but merely reflected the "personal conviction" of the members present.
4088_158077_000057_000000 And so it went like a great game of chess.
4088_158077_000057_000002 The fact was that the pickets had moved the Democrats a step.
4088_158077_000057_000003 The Republicans had then attempted to
4088_158077_000059_000001 Behind this matching of political wits by the two parties stood the faithful pickets compelling them both to act.
4088_158077_000060_000000 Simultaneously with these moves and counter moves in political circles, the people in all sections of this vast country began to speak their minds.
4088_158077_000060_000002 Even the South, the Administration's stronghold, sent fiery telegrams demanding action.
4088_158077_000060_000003 Alabama, South Carolina, Texas, Maryland, Mississippi, as well as the West, Middle West, New England and the East the stream was endless.
4088_158077_000061_000000 Every time a new piece of legislation was passed; the war tax bill, food conservation or what not,-women from unex pected quarters sent to the Government their protest against the passage of measures so vital to women without women's consent, coupled with an appeal for the liberation of women. Club women, college women, federations of labor; various kinds of organizations sent protests to the Administration leaders.
4088_158077_000065_000000 The manifestations of popular approval of suffrage, the constant stream of protests to the Administration against its delay nationally, and the shame of having women begging at its gates, could result in only one of two things.
4088_158077_000065_000001 The Administration had little choice.
4088_158077_000065_000002 It must yield to this pressure from the people or it must suppress the agitation which was causing such interest. It must pass the amendment or remove the troublesome pickets.
4088_158077_000066_000000 It decided to remove the pickets.
4088_158077_000068_000000 Chapter three
4088_158077_000069_000000 The First Arrests
4088_158077_000070_000000 The Administration chose suppression.
4088_158077_000070_000001 They resorted to force in an attempt to end picketing.
4088_158077_000070_000005 This fact supplied us with a fresh angle of attack.
4088_158077_000072_000001 This occasion offered us the opportunity again to expose the Administration's weakness in claiming complete political democracy while women were still denied their political freedom.
4088_158077_000075_000000 with the visit of the Russian diplomats to the President.
4088_158077_000075_000001 As the car carrying the envoys passed swiftly through the gates of the White House there stood on the picket line two silent sentinels, Miss Lucy Burns of New York and mrs Lawrence Lewis of Philadelphia, both members of the National Executive Committee, with a great lettered banner which read:
4088_158077_000076_000000 TO THE RUSSIAN ENVOYS
4088_158077_000082_000001 In answering the criticism, Miss Paul publicly stated our position thus: "The intolerable conditions
4088_158077_000084_000000 against which we protest can be changed in the twinkling of an eye.
4088_158077_000084_000001 The responsibility for our protest is, therefore, with the Administration and not with the women of America, if the lack of democracy at home weakens the Administration in its fight for democracy three thousand miles away."
4088_158077_000085_000000 This was too dreadful.
4088_158077_000085_000001 A flurry at the gates of the Chief of the nation at such a time would never do.
4088_158077_000085_000002 Our allies in the crusade for democracy must not know that we had a day by day unrest at home.
4088_158077_000085_000003 Something must be done to stop this expose at once.
4088_158077_000085_000005 Had they no shame?
4088_158077_000085_000006 Was the fundamental weakness in our boast of pure and perfect democracy to be so wantonly displayed with impunity?
4088_158077_000086_000000 Of course it was embarrassing.
4088_158077_000086_000001 We meant it to be.
4088_158077_000086_000002 The truth must be told at all costs.
4088_158077_000086_000003 This was no time for manners.
4088_158077_000087_000000 Hurried conferences behind closed doors!
4088_158077_000087_000002 Women could not advance on drawn bayonets.
4088_158077_000087_000003 And if they did . . .
4088_158077_000087_000004 What a picture!
4088_158077_000087_000006 I daresay political wisdom crept into the reasoning of others.
4088_158077_000088_000000 Closing the Woman's Party headquarters was discussed.
4088_158077_000088_000001 Perhaps a raid!
4088_158077_000088_000002 And all for what?
4088_158077_000088_000003 Because women were holding banners asking for the precious principle at home that men were supposed to be dying for abroad.
4088_158077_000094_000000 "I warn you, you will be arrested if you attempt to picket again."
4088_158077_000096_000000 News had spread through the city that the pickets were to be arrested.
4088_158077_000096_000002 To know that we were no longer wanted at the gates of the White House and that the police were no longer our "friends" was enough for the mob mind.
4088_158077_000097_000000 Some members of the crowd made sport of the women.
4088_158077_000097_000001 Others hurled cheap and childish epithets at them.
4088_158077_000098_000000 Thinking they had been mistaken in believing the pickets were to be arrested, and having grown weary of their strenuous sport, the crowd moved on its way.
4088_158077_000099_000000 Miss Burns and Miss Morey upon arriving at the police station, insisted, to the great surprise of all the officials, upon knowing the charge against them.
4088_158077_000099_000004 People could not be arrested for picketing.
4088_158077_000101_000001 Disorderly conduct?
4088_158077_000101_000003 Inciting to riot?
4088_158077_000101_000004 Impossible!
4088_158077_000101_000005 The women had stood as silent sentinels holding the President's own eloquent words.
4088_158077_000102_000000 Doors opened and closed mysteriously.
4088_158077_000102_000002 Whispered conversations were heard. The book on rules and regulations was hopefully thumbed.
4088_158077_000103_000001 All carried banners with the same words of the President.
4088_158077_000103_000003 They were promptly arrested for "obstructing the traffic." They, too, were dismissed and their cases never tried.
4088_158077_000103_000005 When. however. women continued to picket in the face of arrest, the Administration quickened its advance into the venture of suppression.
4088_158077_000103_000006 It decided to bring the offenders to trial.
4088_158077_000105_000000 "Not a dollar of your fine will we pay," was the answer of the women.
4088_158077_000105_000001 "To pay a fine would be an admission of guilt.
4088_158077_000105_000002 We are innocent."
4088_158077_000106_000000 The six women who were privileged to serve the first terms of imprisonment for suffrage in this country, were Miss Katherine Morey of Massachusetts, mrs Annie Arneil and Miss Mabel Vernon of Delaware, Miss Lavinia Dock of Pennsylvania, Miss Maud Jamison of Virginia, and Miss Virginia Arnold of
4088_158077_000108_000000 North Carolina.
4088_158077_000109_000001 Champ Clark, late Democratic speaker of the House, is declaiming to a cheering crowd behind the White House, "Governments derive their just powers from the consent of the governed." In front of the White House thirteen silent sentinels with banners bearing the same words, are arrested.
