40_222_000008_000000 "Dear Catherine,
40_222_000009_000000 "Though, God knows, with little inclination for writing, I think it my duty to tell you that everything is at an end between Miss Thorpe and me.
40_222_000009_000001 I left her and Bath yesterday, never to see either again.
40_222_000009_000002 I shall not enter into particulars-they would only pain you more.
40_222_000009_000004 Thank God!
40_222_000009_000005 I am undeceived in time! But it is a heavy blow!
40_222_000009_000006 After my father's consent had been so kindly given-but no more of this.
40_222_000009_000007 She has made me miserable forever!
40_222_000009_000008 Let me soon hear from you, dear Catherine; you are my only friend; your love I do build upon.
40_222_000009_000009 I wish your visit at Northanger may be over before Captain Tilney makes his engagement known, or you will be uncomfortably circumstanced.
40_222_000009_000010 Poor Thorpe is in town: I dread the sight of him; his honest heart would feel so much.
40_222_000009_000013 I cannot understand even now what she would be at, for there could be no need of my being played off to make her secure of Tilney.
40_222_000009_000014 We parted at last by mutual consent-happy for me had we never met!
40_222_000011_000000 Catherine had not read three lines before her sudden change of countenance, and short exclamations of sorrowing wonder, declared her to be receiving unpleasant news; and Henry, earnestly watching her through the whole letter, saw plainly that it ended no better than it began.
40_222_000011_000001 He was prevented, however, from even looking his surprise by his father's entrance.
40_222_000011_000002 They went to breakfast directly; but Catherine could hardly eat anything.
40_222_000011_000003 Tears filled her eyes, and even ran down her cheeks as she sat
