40_222_000043_000000 "You feel, as you always do, what is most to the credit of human nature. Such feelings ought to be investigated, that they may know themselves."
412_126975_000002_000000 The Flying Stars
412_126975_000003_000001 As an artist I had always attempted to provide crimes suitable to the special season or landscapes in which I found myself, choosing this or that terrace or garden for a catastrophe, as if for a statuary group.
412_126975_000003_000002 Thus squires should be swindled in long rooms panelled with oak; while Jews, on the other hand, should rather find themselves unexpectedly penniless among the lights and screens of the Cafe Riche.
412_126975_000003_000003 Thus, in England, if I wished to relieve a dean of his riches (which is not so easy as you might suppose), I wished to frame him, if I make myself clear, in the green lawns and grey towers of some cathedral town.
412_126975_000004_000000 "Well, my last crime was a Christmas crime, a cheery, cosy, English middle class crime; a crime of Charles Dickens.
412_126975_000004_000001 I did it in a good old middle class house near Putney, a house with a crescent of carriage drive, a house with a stable by the side of it, a house with the name on the two outer gates, a house with a monkey tree.
412_126975_000004_000002 Enough, you know the species.
412_126975_000004_000003 I really think my imitation of Dickens's style was dexterous and literary.
412_126975_000004_000004 It seems almost a pity I repented the same evening."
412_126975_000005_000000 Flambeau would then proceed to tell the story from the inside; and even from the inside it was odd.
412_126975_000005_000001 Seen from the outside it was perfectly incomprehensible, and it is from the outside that the stranger must study it.
412_126975_000005_000002 From this standpoint the drama may be said to have begun when the front doors of the house with the stable opened on the garden with the monkey tree, and a young girl came out with bread to feed the birds on the afternoon of Boxing Day.
412_126975_000005_000003 She had a pretty face, with brave brown eyes; but her figure was beyond conjecture, for she was so wrapped up in brown furs that it was hard to say which was hair and which was fur.
412_126975_000005_000004 But for the attractive face she might have been a small toddling bear.
412_126975_000006_000000 The winter afternoon was reddening towards evening, and already a ruby light was rolled over the bloomless beds, filling them, as it were, with the ghosts of the dead roses.
412_126975_000006_000001 On one side of the house stood the stable, on the other an alley or cloister of laurels led to the larger garden behind.
412_126975_000006_000003 Here she gave an exclamation of wonder, real or ritual, and looking up at the high garden wall above her, beheld it fantastically bestridden by a somewhat fantastic figure.
412_126975_000007_000000 "Oh, don't jump, mr Crook," she called out in some alarm; "it's much too high."
412_126975_000008_000000 The individual riding the party wall like an aerial horse was a tall, angular young man, with dark hair sticking up like a hair brush, intelligent and even distinguished lineaments, but a sallow and almost alien complexion.
412_126975_000008_000002 Perhaps it was a symbol.
412_126975_000009_000000 "I think I was meant to be a burglar," he said placidly, "and I have no doubt I should have been if I hadn't happened to be born in that nice house next door.
412_126975_000009_000001 I can't see any harm in it, anyhow."
412_126975_000010_000000 "How can you say such things!" she remonstrated.
412_126975_000011_000000 "Well," said the young man, "if you're born on the wrong side of the wall, I can't see that it's wrong to climb over it."
412_126975_000012_000000 "I never know what you will say or do next," she said.
412_126975_000013_000000 "I don't often know myself," replied mr Crook; "but then I am on the right side of the wall now."
412_126975_000014_000000 "And which is the right side of the wall?" asked the young lady, smiling.
412_126975_000015_000000 "Whichever side you are on," said the young man named Crook.
412_126975_000016_000000 As they went together through the laurels towards the front garden a motor horn sounded thrice, coming nearer and nearer, and a car of splendid speed, great elegance, and a pale green colour swept up to the front doors like a bird and stood throbbing.
412_126975_000017_000001 I didn't know, Miss Adams, that your Santa Claus was so modern as this."
412_126975_000018_000000 "Oh, that's my godfather, Sir Leopold Fischer.
412_126975_000018_000001 He always comes on Boxing Day."
412_126975_000019_000000 Then, after an innocent pause, which unconsciously betrayed some lack of enthusiasm, Ruby Adams added:
412_126975_000020_000000 "He is very kind."
412_126975_000021_000000 john Crook, journalist, had heard of that eminent City magnate; and it was not his fault if the City magnate had not heard of him; for in certain articles in The Clarion or The New Age Sir Leopold had been dealt with austerely.
412_126975_000021_000001 But he said nothing and grimly watched the unloading of the motor car, which was rather a long process.
412_126975_000021_000002 A large, neat chauffeur in green got out from the front, and a small, neat manservant in grey got out from the back, and between them they deposited Sir Leopold on the doorstep and began to unpack him, like some very carefully protected parcel.
412_126975_000022_000000 Long before this revelation was complete the two big doors of the porch had opened in the middle, and Colonel Adams (father of the furry young lady) had come out himself to invite his eminent guest inside.
412_126975_000022_000001 He was a tall, sunburnt, and very silent man, who wore a red smoking cap like a fez, making him look like one of the English Sirdars or Pashas in Egypt. With him was his brother in law, lately come from Canada, a big and rather boisterous young gentleman farmer, with a yellow beard, by name james Blount.
412_126975_000022_000002 With him also was the more insignificant figure of the priest from the neighbouring Roman Church; for the colonel's late wife had been a Catholic, and the children, as is common in such cases, had been trained to follow her.
412_126975_000022_000003 Everything seemed undistinguished about the priest, even down to his name, which was Brown; yet the colonel had always found something companionable about him, and frequently asked him to such family gatherings.
412_126975_000023_000000 In the large entrance hall of the house there was ample room even for Sir Leopold and the removal of his wraps.
412_126975_000023_000001 Porch and vestibule, indeed, were unduly large in proportion to the house, and formed, as it were, a big room with the front door at one end, and the bottom of the staircase at the other.
412_126975_000023_000002 In front of the large hall fire, over which hung the colonel's sword, the process was completed and the company, including the saturnine Crook, presented to Sir Leopold Fischer.
412_126975_000023_000003 That venerable financier, however, still seemed struggling with portions of his well lined attire, and at length produced from a very interior tail coat pocket, a black oval case which he radiantly explained to be his Christmas present for his god daughter.
412_126975_000023_000004 With an unaffected vain glory that had something disarming about it he held out the case before them all; it flew open at a touch and half blinded them.
412_126975_000023_000005 It was just as if a crystal fountain had spurted in their eyes.
412_126975_000023_000006 In a nest of orange velvet lay like three eggs, three white and vivid diamonds that seemed to set the very air on fire all round them.
412_126975_000023_000007 Fischer stood beaming benevolently and drinking deep of the astonishment and ecstasy of the girl, the grim admiration and gruff thanks of the colonel, the wonder of the whole group.
412_126975_000024_000000 "I'll put 'em back now, my dear," said Fischer, returning the case to the tails of his coat.
412_126975_000024_000002 They're the three great African diamonds called 'The Flying Stars,' because they've been stolen so often.
412_126975_000024_000003 All the big criminals are on the track; but even the rough men about in the streets and hotels could hardly have kept their hands off them.
412_126975_000024_000005 It was quite possible."
412_126975_000025_000000 "Quite natural, I should say," growled the man in the red tie.
412_126975_000025_000001 "I shouldn't blame 'em if they had taken 'em.
412_126975_000025_000002 When they ask for bread, and you don't even give them a stone, I think they might take the stone for themselves."
412_126975_000026_000000 "I won't have you talking like that," cried the girl, who was in a curious glow.
412_126975_000026_000001 "You've only talked like that since you became a horrid what's his name.
412_126975_000026_000002 You know what I mean.
412_126975_000026_000003 What do you call a man who wants to embrace the chimney sweep?"
412_126975_000027_000000 "A saint," said Father Brown.
412_126975_000028_000000 "I think," said Sir Leopold, with a supercilious smile, "that Ruby means a Socialist."
412_126975_000029_000000 "A radical does not mean a man who lives on radishes," remarked Crook, with some impatience; "and a Conservative does not mean a man who preserves jam.
412_126975_000029_000001 Neither, I assure you, does a Socialist mean a man who desires a social evening with the chimney sweep.
412_126975_000029_000002 A Socialist means a man who wants all the chimneys swept and all the chimney sweeps paid for it."
412_126975_000030_000000 "But who won't allow you," put in the priest in a low voice, "to own your own soot."
412_126975_000031_000000 Crook looked at him with an eye of interest and even respect.
412_126975_000031_000001 "Does one want to own soot?" he asked.
412_126975_000032_000001 "I've heard that gardeners use it.
412_126975_000032_000002 And I once made six children happy at Christmas when the conjuror didn't come, entirely with soot-applied externally."
412_126975_000033_000000 "Oh, splendid," cried Ruby.
412_126975_000033_000001 "Oh, I wish you'd do it to this company."
412_126975_000034_000000 The boisterous Canadian, mr Blount, was lifting his loud voice in applause, and the astonished financier his (in some considerable deprecation), when a knock sounded at the double front doors.
412_126975_000034_000001 The priest opened them, and they showed again the front garden of evergreens, monkey tree and all, now gathering gloom against a gorgeous violet sunset.
412_126975_000034_000002 The scene thus framed was so coloured and quaint, like a back scene in a play, that they forgot a moment the insignificant figure standing in the door.
412_126975_000034_000003 He was dusty looking and in a frayed coat, evidently a common messenger.
412_126975_000034_000004 "Any of you gentlemen mr Blount?" he asked, and held forward a letter doubtfully.
412_126975_000034_000005 mr Blount started, and stopped in his shout of assent.
412_126975_000034_000006 Ripping up the envelope with evident astonishment he read it; his face clouded a little, and then cleared, and he turned to his brother in law and host.
412_126975_000035_000000 "I'm sick at being such a nuisance, colonel," he said, with the cheery colonial conventions; "but would it upset you if an old acquaintance called on me here tonight on business?
412_126975_000035_000001 In point of fact it's Florian, that famous French acrobat and comic actor; I knew him years ago out West (he was a French Canadian by birth), and he seems to have business for me, though I hardly guess what."
412_126975_000036_000000 "Of course, of course," replied the colonel carelessly-"My dear chap, any friend of yours.
412_126975_000036_000001 No doubt he will prove an acquisition."
412_126975_000037_000000 "He'll black his face, if that's what you mean," cried Blount, laughing. "I don't doubt he'd black everyone else's eyes.
412_126975_000037_000001 I don't care; I'm not refined.
412_126975_000037_000002 I like the jolly old pantomime where a man sits on his top hat."
412_126975_000038_000000 "Not on mine, please," said Sir Leopold Fischer, with dignity.
412_126975_000039_000000 "Well, well," observed Crook, airily, "don't let's quarrel.
412_126975_000039_000001 There are lower jokes than sitting on a top hat."
412_126975_000040_000000 Dislike of the red tied youth, born of his predatory opinions and evident intimacy with the pretty godchild, led Fischer to say, in his most sarcastic, magisterial manner: "No doubt you have found something much lower than sitting on a top hat.
412_126975_000040_000001 What is it, pray?"
412_126975_000041_000000 "Letting a top hat sit on you, for instance," said the Socialist.
412_126975_000042_000000 "Now, now, now," cried the Canadian farmer with his barbarian benevolence, "don't let's spoil a jolly evening.
412_126975_000042_000001 What I say is, let's do something for the company tonight.
412_126975_000042_000002 Not blacking faces or sitting on hats, if you don't like those-but something of the sort.
412_126975_000042_000003 Why couldn't we have a proper old English pantomime-clown, columbine, and so on.
412_126975_000042_000004 I saw one when I left England at twelve years old, and it's blazed in my brain like a bonfire ever since.
412_126975_000042_000005 I came back to the old country only last year, and I find the thing's extinct.
412_126975_000042_000006 Nothing but a lot of snivelling fairy plays.
412_126975_000042_000007 I want a hot poker and a policeman made into sausages, and they give me princesses moralising by moonlight, Blue Birds, or something.
412_126975_000042_000008 Blue Beard's more in my line, and him I like best when he turned into the pantaloon."
412_126975_000043_000000 "I'm all for making a policeman into sausages," said john Crook.
412_126975_000043_000001 "It's a better definition of Socialism than some recently given.
412_126975_000043_000002 But surely the get up would be too big a business."
412_126975_000044_000000 "Not a scrap," cried Blount, quite carried away.
412_126975_000044_000001 "A harlequinade's the quickest thing we can do, for two reasons.
412_126975_000044_000002 First, one can gag to any degree; and, second, all the objects are household things-tables and towel horses and washing baskets, and things like that."
412_126975_000045_000000 "That's true," admitted Crook, nodding eagerly and walking about. "But I'm afraid I can't have my policeman's uniform?
412_126975_000045_000001 Haven't killed a policeman lately."
412_126975_000046_000001 "Yes, we can!" he cried.
412_126975_000046_000002 "I've got Florian's address here, and he knows every costumier in London.
412_126975_000046_000003 I'll phone him to bring a police dress when he comes." And he went bounding away to the telephone.
412_126975_000047_000000 "Oh, it's glorious, godfather," cried Ruby, almost dancing.
412_126975_000047_000001 "I'll be columbine and you shall be pantaloon."
412_126975_000048_000000 The millionaire held himself stiff with a sort of heathen solemnity.
412_126975_000048_000001 "I think, my dear," he said, "you must get someone else for pantaloon."
412_126975_000049_000000 "I will be pantaloon, if you like," said Colonel Adams, taking his cigar out of his mouth, and speaking for the first and last time.
412_126975_000050_000000 "You ought to have a statue," cried the Canadian, as he came back, radiant, from the telephone.
412_126975_000050_000001 "There, we are all fitted.
412_126975_000050_000002 mr Crook shall be clown; he's a journalist and knows all the oldest jokes.
412_126975_000050_000003 I can be harlequin, that only wants long legs and jumping about.
412_126975_000050_000004 My friend Florian 'phones he's bringing the police costume; he's changing on the way.
412_126975_000050_000005 We can act it in this very hall, the audience sitting on those broad stairs opposite, one row above another.
412_126975_000051_000000 How even such a banquet of bosh was got ready in the time remained a riddle.
412_126975_000051_000001 But they went at it with that mixture of recklessness and industry that lives when youth is in a house; and youth was in that house that night, though not all may have isolated the two faces and hearts from which it flamed.
412_126975_000051_000002 As always happens, the invention grew wilder and wilder through the very tameness of the bourgeois conventions from which it had to create.
412_126975_000051_000003 The columbine looked charming in an outstanding skirt that strangely resembled the large lamp shade in the drawing room.
412_126975_000051_000004 The clown and pantaloon made themselves white with flour from the cook, and red with rouge from some other domestic, who remained (like all true Christian benefactors) anonymous.
412_126975_000051_000005 The harlequin, already clad in silver paper out of cigar boxes, was, with difficulty, prevented from smashing the old Victorian lustre chandeliers, that he might cover himself with resplendent crystals.
412_126975_000051_000006 In fact he would certainly have done so, had not Ruby unearthed some old pantomime paste jewels she had worn at a fancy dress party as the Queen of Diamonds.
412_126975_000051_000007 Indeed, her uncle, james Blount, was getting almost out of hand in his excitement; he was like a schoolboy.
412_126975_000051_000008 He put a paper donkey's head unexpectedly on Father Brown, who bore it patiently, and even found some private manner of moving his ears.
412_126975_000051_000009 He even essayed to put the paper donkey's tail to the coat tails of Sir Leopold Fischer.
412_126975_000051_000010 This, however, was frowned down. "Uncle is too absurd," cried Ruby to Crook, round whose shoulders she had seriously placed a string of sausages.
412_126975_000051_000011 "Why is he so wild?"
412_126975_000052_000000 "He is harlequin to your columbine," said Crook.
412_126975_000052_000001 "I am only the clown who makes the old jokes."
412_126975_000054_000000 Father Brown, though he knew every detail done behind the scenes, and had even evoked applause by his transformation of a pillow into a pantomime baby, went round to the front and sat among the audience with all the solemn expectation of a child at his first matinee.
412_126975_000054_000002 The pantomime was utterly chaotic, yet not contemptible; there ran through it a rage of improvisation which came chiefly from Crook the clown.
412_126975_000054_000003 Commonly he was a clever man, and he was inspired tonight with a wild omniscience, a folly wiser than the world, that which comes to a young man who has seen for an instant a particular expression on a particular face.
412_126975_000054_000005 At abrupt intervals in the outrageous performance he would hurl himself in full costume at the piano and bang out some popular music equally absurd and appropriate.
412_126975_000055_000000 The climax of this, as of all else, was the moment when the two front doors at the back of the scene flew open, showing the lovely moonlit garden, but showing more prominently the famous professional guest; the great Florian, dressed up as a policeman.
412_126975_000055_000001 The clown at the piano played the constabulary chorus in the "Pirates of Penzance," but it was drowned in the deafening applause, for every gesture of the great comic actor was an admirable though restrained version of the carriage and manner of the police.
412_126975_000055_000003 Then it was that the strange actor gave that celebrated imitation of a dead man, of which the fame still lingers round Putney.
412_126975_000055_000004 It was almost impossible to believe that a living person could appear so limp.
412_126975_000056_000000 The athletic harlequin swung him about like a sack or twisted or tossed him like an Indian club; all the time to the most maddeningly ludicrous tunes from the piano.
412_126975_000057_000000 At about this limit of mental anarchy Father Brown's view was obscured altogether; for the City magnate in front of him rose to his full height and thrust his hands savagely into all his pockets.
412_126975_000057_000001 Then he sat down nervously, still fumbling, and then stood up again.
412_126975_000057_000002 For an instant it seemed seriously likely that he would stride across the footlights; then he turned a glare at the clown playing the piano; and then he burst in silence out of the room.
412_126975_000058_000000 The priest had only watched for a few more minutes the absurd but not inelegant dance of the amateur harlequin over his splendidly unconscious foe.
412_126975_000058_000001 With real though rude art, the harlequin danced slowly backwards out of the door into the garden, which was full of moonlight and stillness.
412_126975_000058_000002 The vamped dress of silver paper and paste, which had been too glaring in the footlights, looked more and more magical and silvery as it danced away under a brilliant moon.
412_126975_000059_000000 He followed his summoner with increasing doubt, which was not dispelled by a solemn comicality in the scene of the study.
412_126975_000059_000001 There sat Colonel Adams, still unaffectedly dressed as a pantaloon, with the knobbed whalebone nodding above his brow, but with his poor old eyes sad enough to have sobered a Saturnalia.
412_126975_000059_000002 Sir Leopold Fischer was leaning against the mantelpiece and heaving with all the importance of panic.
412_126975_000060_000000 "This is a very painful matter, Father Brown," said Adams.
412_126975_000060_000001 "The truth is, those diamonds we all saw this afternoon seem to have vanished from my friend's tail coat pocket.
412_126975_000060_000002 And as you-"
412_126975_000061_000000 "As I," supplemented Father Brown, with a broad grin, "was sitting just behind him-"
412_126975_000062_000000 "Nothing of the sort shall be suggested," said Colonel Adams, with a firm look at Fischer, which rather implied that some such thing had been suggested.
412_126975_000062_000001 "I only ask you to give me the assistance that any gentleman might give."
412_126975_000063_000000 "Which is turning out his pockets," said Father Brown, and proceeded to do so, displaying seven and sixpence, a return ticket, a small silver crucifix, a small breviary, and a stick of chocolate.
412_126975_000064_000000 The colonel looked at him long, and then said, "Do you know, I should like to see the inside of your head more than the inside of your pockets.
412_126975_000065_000000 "She has lately," cried out old Fischer, "opened her father's house to a cut throat Socialist, who says openly he would steal anything from a richer man.
412_126975_000065_000001 This is the end of it.
412_126975_000065_000002 Here is the richer man-and none the richer."
412_126975_000066_000000 "If you want the inside of my head you can have it," said Brown rather wearily.
412_126975_000066_000001 "What it's worth you can say afterwards.
412_126975_000066_000002 But the first thing I find in that disused pocket is this: that men who mean to steal diamonds don't talk Socialism.
412_126975_000066_000003 They are more likely," he added demurely, "to denounce it."
412_126975_000067_000000 Both the others shifted sharply and the priest went on:
412_126975_000068_000000 "You see, we know these people, more or less.
412_126975_000068_000001 That Socialist would no more steal a diamond than a Pyramid.
412_126975_000068_000002 We ought to look at once to the one man we don't know.
412_126975_000068_000003 The fellow acting the policeman-Florian.
412_126975_000068_000004 Where is he exactly at this minute, I wonder."
412_126975_000069_000000 The pantaloon sprang erect and strode out of the room.
412_126975_000069_000001 An interlude ensued, during which the millionaire stared at the priest, and the priest at his breviary; then the pantaloon returned and said, with staccato gravity, "The policeman is still lying on the stage.
412_126975_000069_000002 The curtain has gone up and down six times; he is still lying there."
412_126975_000070_000000 Father Brown dropped his book and stood staring with a look of blank mental ruin.
412_126975_000070_000001 Very slowly a light began to creep in his grey eyes, and then he made the scarcely obvious answer.
412_126975_000071_000000 "Please forgive me, colonel, but when did your wife die?"
412_126975_000072_000000 "Wife!" replied the staring soldier, "she died this year two months.
412_126975_000072_000001 Her brother james arrived just a week too late to see her."
412_126975_000073_000000 The little priest bounded like a rabbit shot.
412_126975_000073_000001 "Come on!" he cried in quite unusual excitement.
412_126975_000073_000002 "Come on!
412_126975_000073_000003 We've got to go and look at that policeman!"
412_126975_000074_000000 They rushed on to the now curtained stage, breaking rudely past the columbine and clown (who seemed whispering quite contentedly), and Father Brown bent over the prostrate comic policeman.
412_126975_000075_000000 "Chloroform," he said as he rose; "I only guessed it just now."
412_126975_000076_000000 There was a startled stillness, and then the colonel said slowly, "Please say seriously what all this means."
412_126975_000077_000000 Father Brown suddenly shouted with laughter, then stopped, and only struggled with it for instants during the rest of his speech. "Gentlemen," he gasped, "there's not much time to talk.
412_126975_000077_000001 I must run after the criminal.
412_126975_000077_000002 But this great French actor who played the policeman-this clever corpse the harlequin waltzed with and dandled and threw about-he was-" His voice again failed him, and he turned his back to run.
412_126975_000078_000000 "He was?" called Fischer inquiringly.
412_126975_000079_000000 "A real policeman," said Father Brown, and ran away into the dark.
412_126975_000080_000000 There were hollows and bowers at the extreme end of that leafy garden, in which the laurels and other immortal shrubs showed against sapphire sky and silver moon, even in that midwinter, warm colours as of the south.
412_126975_000080_000001 The green gaiety of the waving laurels, the rich purple indigo of the night, the moon like a monstrous crystal, make an almost irresponsible romantic picture; and among the top branches of the garden trees a strange figure is climbing, who looks not so much romantic as impossible.
412_126975_000080_000002 He sparkles from head to heel, as if clad in ten million moons; the real moon catches him at every movement and sets a new inch of him on fire.
412_126975_000080_000003 But he swings, flashing and successful, from the short tree in this garden to the tall, rambling tree in the other, and only stops there because a shade has slid under the smaller tree and has unmistakably called up to him.
412_126975_000081_000000 "Well, Flambeau," says the voice, "you really look like a Flying Star; but that always means a Falling Star at last."
412_126975_000082_000000 The silver, sparkling figure above seems to lean forward in the laurels and, confident of escape, listens to the little figure below.
412_126975_000083_000000 "You never did anything better, Flambeau.
412_126975_000083_000001 It was clever to come from Canada (with a Paris ticket, I suppose) just a week after mrs Adams died, when no one was in a mood to ask questions.
412_126975_000083_000003 Stealing the stones, I suppose, was nothing to you.
412_126975_000083_000004 You could have done it by sleight of hand in a hundred other ways besides that pretence of putting a paper donkey's tail to Fischer's coat.
412_126975_000083_000005 But in the rest you eclipsed yourself."
412_126975_000084_000000 The silvery figure among the green leaves seems to linger as if hypnotised, though his escape is easy behind him; he is staring at the man below.
412_126975_000085_000000 "Oh, yes," says the man below, "I know all about it.
412_126975_000085_000001 I know you not only forced the pantomime, but put it to a double use.
412_126975_000085_000002 You were going to steal the stones quietly; news came by an accomplice that you were already suspected, and a capable police officer was coming to rout you up that very night.
412_126975_000085_000003 A common thief would have been thankful for the warning and fled; but you are a poet.
412_126975_000085_000004 You already had the clever notion of hiding the jewels in a blaze of false stage jewellery.
412_126975_000085_000005 Now, you saw that if the dress were a harlequin's the appearance of a policeman would be quite in keeping.
412_126975_000085_000006 The worthy officer started from Putney police station to find you, and walked into the queerest trap ever set in this world.
412_126975_000085_000008 Oh, you will never do anything better.
412_126975_000085_000009 And now, by the way, you might give me back those diamonds."
412_126975_000086_000000 The green branch on which the glittering figure swung, rustled as if in astonishment; but the voice went on:
412_126975_000087_000000 "I want you to give them back, Flambeau, and I want you to give up this life.
412_126975_000087_000001 There is still youth and honour and humour in you; don't fancy they will last in that trade.
412_126975_000087_000002 Men may keep a sort of level of good, but no man has ever been able to keep on one level of evil.
412_126975_000087_000003 That road goes down and down.
412_126975_000087_000004 The kind man drinks and turns cruel; the frank man kills and lies about it.
412_126975_000087_000005 Many a man I've known started like you to be an honest outlaw, a merry robber of the rich, and ended stamped into slime. Maurice Blum started out as an anarchist of principle, a father of the poor; he ended a greasy spy and tale bearer that both sides used and despised.
412_126975_000087_000006 Harry Burke started his free money movement sincerely enough; now he's sponging on a half starved sister for endless brandies and sodas.
412_126975_000087_000007 Lord Amber went into wild society in a sort of chivalry; now he's paying blackmail to the lowest vultures in London.
412_126975_000087_000008 Captain Barillon was the great gentleman apache before your time; he died in a madhouse, screaming with fear of the "narks" and receivers that had betrayed him and hunted him down.
412_126975_000087_000009 I know the woods look very free behind you, Flambeau; I know that in a flash you could melt into them like a monkey. But some day you will be an old grey monkey, Flambeau.
412_126975_000087_000010 You will sit up in your free forest cold at heart and close to death, and the tree tops will be very bare."
412_126975_000089_000000 "Your downward steps have begun.
412_126975_000089_000001 You used to boast of doing nothing mean, but you are doing something mean tonight.
412_126975_000089_000002 You are leaving suspicion on an honest boy with a good deal against him already; you are separating him from the woman he loves and who loves him.
412_126975_000089_000003 But you will do meaner things than that before you die."
412_126975_000090_000000 Three flashing diamonds fell from the tree to the turf.
412_126975_000090_000001 The small man stooped to pick them up, and when he looked up again the green cage of the tree was emptied of its silver bird.
