4160_11550_000011_000004 It was hard to resist Broome street, knowing that there must be news to be heard there, and so she gradually fell into the habit of paying visits, more to Miss Elizabeth Gower than to her niece.
4160_11550_000011_000005 The elder Miss Gower was always communicative, and always ready to talk about her favorites, and to Theo, in her half puzzled, half sad frame of mind, this was a curious consolation.
4160_11550_000011_000006 The two spent hours together, sometimes, in the tiny parlor, stumbling over Berlin wool difficulties, and now and then wandering to and fro, conversationally, from Priscilla to the octagon stitch, and from the octagon stitch to Denis.
4160_11550_000012_000001 But she was even more silent than she had seemed at first, Theo thought, and she was sure her pale, handsome face was paler, though, of course, that was easily to be accounted for by her lover's absence.
4160_11550_000013_000001 The first time Theo ever saw her display an interest in anybody, or in anything, was when she first heard Pamela's love story mentioned.
4160_11550_000014_000000 She was sitting at work near them, when Theo chanced to mention Arthur Brunwalde, and, to her surprise, Priscilla looked up from her desk immediately.
4160_11550_000015_000000 "He was your sister's lover, was he not?" she said, with an abrupt interest in the subject.
4160_11550_000016_000000 "Yes," answered Theo; "but he died, you know."
4160_11550_000018_000001 "mr Oglethorpe told me so."
4160_11550_000019_000000 Theo answered in the affirmative again.
4160_11550_000020_000000 "And poor Pam could not forget him," she added, her usual tender reverence for poor Pam showing itself in her sorrowing voice.
4160_11550_000021_000000 Priscilla got up from her chair, and, coming to the hearth, leaned against the low mantel, pen in hand.
