5322_7678_000002_000000 Chapter twenty
5322_7678_000003_000000 The next day Olenin went alone to the spot where he and the old man startled the stag.
5322_7678_000003_000002 He had hardly stepped among the briers when the pheasants began to rise at every step (the old man had not shown him that place the day before as he meant to keep it for shooting from behind the screen).
5322_7678_000003_000004 He called off his dog, uncocked his gun, put in a bullet above the small shot, and brushing away the mosquitoes with the wide sleeve of his Circassian coat he went slowly to the spot where they had been the day before.
5322_7678_000004_000000 The day was perfectly clear, calm, and hot.
5322_7678_000004_000001 The morning moisture had dried up even in the forest, and myriads of mosquitoes literally covered his face, his back, and his arms.
5322_7678_000004_000002 His dog had turned from black to grey, its back being covered with mosquitoes, and so had Olenin's coat through which the insects thrust their stings.
5322_7678_000004_000003 Olenin was ready to run away from them and it seemed to him that it was impossible to live in this country in the summer.
5322_7678_000004_000004 He was about to go home, but remembering that other people managed to endure such pain he resolved to bear it and gave himself up to be devoured.
5322_7678_000004_000005 And strange to say, by noontime the feeling became actually pleasant.
5322_7678_000004_000006 He even felt that without this mosquito filled atmosphere around him, and that mosquito paste mingled with perspiration which his hand smeared over his face, and that unceasing irritation all over his body, the forest would lose for him some of its character and charm.
5322_7678_000004_000007 These myriads of insects were so well suited to that monstrously lavish wild vegetation, these multitudes of birds and beasts which filled the forest, this dark foliage, this hot scented air, these runlets filled with turbid water which everywhere soaked through from the Terek and gurgled here and there under the overhanging leaves, that the very thing which had at first seemed to him dreadful and intolerable now seemed pleasant.
5322_7678_000004_000008 After going round the place where yesterday they had found the animal and not finding anything, he felt inclined to rest.
5322_7678_000004_000009 The sun stood right above the forest and poured its perpendicular rays down on his back and head whenever he came out into a glade or onto the road.
5322_7678_000004_000011 Having found the traces of yesterday's stag he crept under a bush into the thicket just where the stag had lain, and lay down in its lair.
5322_7678_000004_000012 He examined the dark foliage around him, the place marked by the stag's perspiration and yesterday's dung, the imprint of the stag's knees, the bit of black earth it had kicked up, and his own footprints of the day before.
5322_7678_000004_000013 He felt cool and comfortable and did not think of or wish for anything.
5322_7678_000004_000016 Here I sit, and around me stand old and young trees, one of them festooned with wild grape vines, and pheasants are fluttering, driving one another about and perhaps scenting their murdered brothers.' He felt his pheasants, examined them, and wiped the warm blood off his hand onto his coat.
5322_7678_000004_000018 Here's some one we can eat!' They buzzed and stuck to him.
5322_7678_000004_000020 'Just as they, just as Daddy Eroshka, I shall live awhile and die, and as he says truly:
5322_7678_000006_000000 'But what though the grass does grow?' he continued thinking.
5322_7678_000006_000001 'Still I must live and be happy, because happiness is all I desire.
5322_7678_000006_000002 Never mind what I am-an animal like all the rest, above whom the grass will grow and nothing more; or a frame in which a bit of the one God has been set,--still I must live in the very best way.
5322_7678_000006_000003 How then must I live to be happy, and why was I not happy before?' And he began to recall his former life and he felt disgusted with himself.
5322_7678_000006_000004 He appeared to himself to have been terribly exacting and selfish, though he now saw that all the while he really needed nothing for himself.
5322_7678_000006_000005 And he looked round at the foliage with the light shining through it, at the setting sun and the clear sky, and he felt just as happy as before.
5322_7678_000006_000006 'Why am I happy, and what used I to live for?' thought he.
5322_7678_000006_000007 'How much I exacted for myself; how I schemed and did not manage to gain anything but shame and sorrow!
5322_7678_000006_000008 and, there now, I require nothing to be happy;' and suddenly a new light seemed to reveal itself to him.
5322_7678_000006_000009 'Happiness is this!' he said to himself.
5322_7678_000006_000011 That is evident.
5322_7678_000006_000012 The desire for happiness is innate in every man; therefore it is legitimate.
5322_7678_000006_000013 When trying to satisfy it selfishly-that is, by seeking for oneself riches, fame, comforts, or love-it may happen that circumstances arise which make it impossible to satisfy these desires. It follows that it is these desires that are illegitimate, but not the need for happiness.
5322_7678_000006_000014 But what desires can always be satisfied despite external circumstances?
5322_7678_000006_000015 What are they?
5322_7678_000006_000016 Love, self sacrifice.' He was so glad and excited when he had discovered this, as it seemed to him, new truth, that he jumped up and began impatiently seeking some one to sacrifice himself for, to do good to and to love.
5322_7678_000006_000017 'Since one wants nothing for oneself,' he kept thinking, 'why not live for others?' He took up his gun with the intention of returning home quickly to think this out and to find an opportunity of doing good.
5322_7678_000006_000018 He made his way out of the thicket.
5322_7678_000006_000019 When he had come out into the glade he looked around him; the sun was no longer visible above the tree tops.
5322_7678_000006_000020 It had grown cooler and the place seemed to him quite strange and not like the country round the village.
5322_7678_000006_000021 Everything seemed changed-the weather and the character of the forest; the sky was wrapped in clouds, the wind was rustling in the tree tops, and all around nothing was visible but reeds and dying broken down trees.
5322_7678_000006_000022 He called to his dog who had run away to follow some animal, and his voice came back as in a desert.
5322_7678_000006_000024 He grew frightened.
5322_7678_000006_000025 He remembered the abreks and the murders he had been told about, and he expected every moment that an abrek would spring from behind every bush and he would have to defend his life and die, or be a coward.
5322_7678_000006_000026 He thought of God and of the future life as for long he had not thought about them.
5322_7678_000006_000028 'And is it worth while living for oneself,' thought he, 'when at any moment you may die, and die without having done any good, and so that no one will know of it?' He went in the direction where he fancied the village lay.
5322_7678_000006_000029 Of his shooting he had no further thought; but he felt tired to death and peered round at every bush and tree with particular attention and almost with terror, expecting every moment to be called to account for his life.
5322_7678_000006_000030 After having wandered about for a considerable time he came upon a ditch down which was flowing cold sandy water from the Terek, and, not to go astray any longer, he decided to follow it. He went on without knowing where the ditch would lead him.
5322_7678_000006_000031 Suddenly the reeds behind him crackled.
5322_7678_000006_000032 He shuddered and seized his gun, and then felt ashamed of himself: the over excited dog, panting hard, had thrown itself into the cold water of the ditch and was lapping it!
5322_7678_000007_000000 He too had a drink, and then followed the dog in the direction it wished to go, thinking it would lead him to the village.
5322_7678_000007_000001 But despite the dog's company everything around him seemed still more dreary.
5322_7678_000007_000002 The forest grew darker and the wind grew stronger and stronger in the tops of the broken old trees.
5322_7678_000007_000003 Some large birds circled screeching round their nests in those trees.
5322_7678_000007_000004 The vegetation grew poorer and he came oftener and oftener upon rustling reeds and bare sandy spaces covered with animal footprints.
5322_7678_000007_000006 Altogether his spirits became gloomy.
5322_7678_000007_000007 Putting his hand behind him he felt his pheasants, and found one missing.
5322_7678_000007_000008 It had broken off and was lost, and only the bleeding head and beak remained sticking in his belt.
5322_7678_000007_000009 He felt more frightened than he had ever done before.
5322_7679_000001_000001 He heard Russian being spoken, and also heard the rapid smooth flow of the Terek, and a few steps farther in front of him saw the brown moving surface of the river, with the dim coloured wet sand of its banks and shallows, the distant steppe, the cordon watch tower outlined above the water, a saddled and hobbled horse among the brambles, and then the mountains opening out before him.
5322_7679_000001_000002 The red sun appeared for an instant from under a cloud and its last rays glittered brightly along the river over the reeds, on the watch tower, and on a group of Cossacks, among whom Lukashka's vigorous figure attracted Olenin's involuntary attention.
5322_7679_000002_000000 Olenin felt that he was again, without any apparent cause, perfectly happy.
5322_7679_000002_000002 He accosted the Cossacks, but not finding as yet any excuse for doing anyone a kindness, he entered the hut; nor in the hut did he find any such opportunity.
5322_7679_000002_000003 The Cossacks received him coldly.
5322_7679_000002_000004 On entering the mud hut he lit a cigarette.
5322_7679_000002_000005 The Cossacks paid little attention to him, first because he was smoking a cigarette, and secondly because they had something else to divert them that evening.
5322_7679_000002_000006 Some hostile Chechens, relatives of the abrek who had been killed, had come from the hills with a scout to ransom the body; and the Cossacks were waiting for their Commanding Officer's arrival from the village.
5322_7679_000002_000007 The dead man's brother, tall and well shaped with a short cropped beard which was dyed red, despite his very tattered coat and cap was calm and majestic as a king.
5322_7679_000002_000008 His face was very like that of the dead abrek.
5322_7679_000002_000010 He was evidently a brave who had met Russians more than once before in quite other circumstances, and nothing about them could astonish or even interest him.
5322_7679_000002_000011 Olenin was about to approach the dead body and had begun to look at it when the brother, looking up at him from under his brows with calm contempt, said something sharply and angrily.
5322_7679_000002_000012 The scout hastened to cover the dead man's face with his coat.
5322_7679_000002_000014 He began to speak to him, asking from what village he came, but the Chechen, scarcely giving him a glance, spat contemptuously and turned away.
5322_7679_000002_000015 Olenin was so surprised at the Chechen not being interested in him that he could only put it down to the man's stupidity or ignorance of Russian; so he turned to the scout, who also acted as interpreter.
5322_7679_000002_000016 The scout was as ragged as the other, but instead of being red haired he was black haired, restless, with extremely white gleaming teeth and sparkling black eyes.
5322_7679_000002_000017 The scout willingly entered into conversation and asked for a cigarette.
5322_7679_000003_000000 'There were five brothers,' began the scout in his broken Russian. 'This is the third brother the Russians have killed, only two are left. He is a brave, a great brave!' he said, pointing to the Chechen. 'When they killed Ahmet Khan (the dead brave) this one was sitting on the opposite bank among the reeds.
5322_7679_000003_000001 He saw it all.
5322_7679_000003_000002 Saw him laid in the skiff and brought to the bank.
5322_7679_000003_000003 He sat there till the night and wished to kill the old man, but the others would not let him.'
5322_7679_000004_000000 Lukashka went up to the speaker, and sat down.
5322_7679_000005_000000 'From there in the hills,' replied the scout, pointing to the misty bluish gorge beyond the Terek. 'Do you know Suuk su?
5322_7679_000005_000001 It is about eight miles beyond that.'
5322_7679_000006_000001 'He is my kunak.'
5322_7679_000007_000000 'He is my neighbour,' answered the scout.
5322_7679_000008_000000 'He's a trump!' and Lukashka, evidently much interested, began talking to the scout in Tartar.
5322_7679_000009_000000 Presently a Cossack captain, with the head of the village, arrived on horseback with a suite of two Cossacks.
5322_7679_000009_000001 The captain-one of the new type of Cossack officers-wished the Cossacks 'Good health,' but no one shouted in reply, 'Hail!
5322_7679_000009_000002 Good health to your honour,' as is customary in the Russian Army, and only a few replied with a bow.
5322_7679_000009_000003 Some, and among them Lukashka, rose and stood erect.
5322_7679_000009_000004 The corporal replied that all was well at the outposts.
5322_7679_000009_000005 All this seemed ridiculous: it was as if these Cossacks were playing at being soldiers.
5322_7679_000009_000006 But these formalities soon gave place to ordinary ways of behaviour, and the captain, who was a smart Cossack just like the others, began speaking fluently in Tartar to the interpreter.
5322_7679_000009_000008 Then they approached the body.
5322_7679_000010_000000 'Which of you is luke Gavrilov?' asked the captain.
5322_7679_000012_000000 'I have reported your exploit to the Commander.
5322_7679_000012_000001 I don't know what will come of it.
5322_7679_000012_000003 Can you read?'
5322_7679_000013_000000 'I can't.'
5322_7679_000014_000000 'But what a fine fellow to look at!' said the captain, again playing the commander.
5322_7679_000014_000001 'Put on your cap.
5322_7679_000014_000002 Which of the Gavrilovs does he come of? ... the Broad, eh?'
5322_7679_000015_000000 'His nephew,' replied the corporal.
5322_7679_000016_000001 Well, lend a hand, help them,' he said, turning to the Cossacks.
5322_7679_000017_000001 He moved away from the corporal, and having put on his cap sat down beside Olenin.
5322_7679_000018_000000 When the body had been carried to the skiff the brother Chechen descended to the bank.
5322_7679_000018_000001 The Cossacks involuntarily stepped aside to let him pass.
5322_7679_000018_000002 He jumped into the boat and pushed off from the bank with his powerful leg, and now, as Olenin noticed, for the first time threw a rapid glance at all the Cossacks and then abruptly asked his companion a question.
5322_7679_000018_000003 The latter answered something and pointed to Lukashka.
5322_7679_000018_000004 The Chechen looked at him and, turning slowly away, gazed at the opposite bank.
5322_7679_000018_000005 That look expressed not hatred but cold contempt.
5322_7679_000018_000006 He again made some remark.
5322_7679_000020_000001 It's always the same,' replied the scout, evidently inventing, and he smiled, showing his white teeth, as he jumped into the skiff.
5322_7679_000021_000000 The dead man's brother sat motionless, gazing at the opposite bank.
5322_7679_000021_000001 He was so full of hatred and contempt that there was nothing on this side of the river that moved his curiosity.
5322_7679_000021_000002 The scout, standing up at one end of the skiff and dipping his paddle now on one side now on the other, steered skilfully while talking incessantly.
5322_7679_000021_000003 The skiff became smaller and smaller as it moved obliquely across the stream, the voices became scarcely audible, and at last, still within sight, they landed on the opposite bank where their horses stood waiting.
5322_7679_000021_000004 There they lifted out the corpse and (though the horse shied) laid it across one of the saddles, mounted, and rode at a foot pace along the road past a Tartar village from which a crowd came out to look at them.
5322_7679_000021_000005 The Cossacks on the Russian side of the river were highly satisfied and jovial.
5322_7679_000021_000006 Laughter and jokes were heard on all sides.
5322_7679_000021_000007 The captain and the head of the village entered the mud hut to regale themselves.
5322_7679_000021_000008 Lukashka, vainly striving to impart a sedate expression to his merry face, sat down with his elbows on his knees beside Olenin and whittled away at a stick.
5322_7679_000022_000000 'Why do you smoke?' he said with assumed curiosity.
5322_7679_000022_000001 'Is it good?'
5322_7679_000023_000000 He evidently spoke because he noticed Olenin felt ill at ease and isolated among the Cossacks.
5322_7679_000024_000000 'It's just a habit,' answered Olenin. 'Why?'
5322_7679_000025_000001 Look there now, the mountains are not far off,' continued Lukashka, 'yet you can't get there!
5322_7679_000025_000002 How will you get back alone?
5322_7679_000025_000003 It's getting dark.
5322_7679_000025_000004 I'll take you, if you like.
5322_7679_000025_000005 You ask the corporal to give me leave.'
5322_7679_000026_000001 He remembered Maryanka and the kiss he had heard by the gate, and he was sorry for Lukashka and his want of culture.
5322_7679_000026_000002 'What confusion it is,' he thought.
5322_7679_000026_000003 'A man kills another and is happy and satisfied with himself as if he had done something excellent.
5322_7679_000026_000004 Can it be that nothing tells him that it is not a reason for any rejoicing, and that happiness lies not in killing, but in sacrificing oneself?'
5322_7679_000027_000000 'Well, you had better not meet him again now, mate!' said one of the Cossacks who had seen the skiff off, addressing Lukashka. 'Did you hear him asking about you?'
5322_7679_000028_000000 Lukashka raised his head.
5322_7679_000029_000000 'My godson?' said Lukashka, meaning by that word the dead Chechen.
5322_7679_000030_000000 'Your godson won't rise, but the red one is the godson's brother!'
5322_7679_000032_000000 'What are you glad about?' asked Olenin. 'Supposing your brother had been killed; would you be glad?'
5322_7679_000033_000000 The Cossack looked at Olenin with laughing eyes.
5322_7679_000033_000001 He seemed to have understood all that Olenin wished to say to him, but to be above such considerations.
5322_7679_000034_000000 'Well, that happens too!
5322_7679_000034_000001 Don't our fellows get killed sometimes?'
5322_7680_000005_000000 Chapter twenty two
5322_7680_000006_000000 The Captain and the head of the village rode away, and Olenin, to please Lukashka as well as to avoid going back alone through the dark forest, asked the corporal to give Lukashka leave, and the corporal did so.
5322_7680_000006_000001 Olenin thought that Lukashka wanted to see Maryanka and he was also glad of the companionship of such a pleasant looking and sociable Cossack.
5322_7680_000006_000002 Lukashka and Maryanka he involuntarily united in his mind, and he found pleasure in thinking about them.
5322_7680_000006_000003 'He loves Maryanka,' thought Olenin, 'and I could love her,' and a new and powerful emotion of tenderness overcame him as they walked homewards together through the dark forest.
5322_7680_000006_000004 Lukashka too felt happy; something akin to love made itself felt between these two very different young men.
5322_7680_000007_000000 'By which gate do you enter?' asked Olenin.
5322_7680_000008_000000 'By the middle one.
5322_7680_000008_000002 After that you have nothing to fear.'
5322_7680_000009_000000 Olenin laughed.
5322_7680_000010_000000 'Do you think I am afraid?
5322_7680_000010_000001 Go back, and thank you.
5322_7680_000011_000000 'It's all right!
5322_7680_000011_000002 And how can you help being afraid? Even we are afraid,' said Lukashka to set Olenin's self esteem at rest, and he laughed too.
5322_7680_000012_000000 'Then come in with me.
5322_7680_000012_000001 We'll have a talk and a drink and in the morning you can go back.'
5322_7680_000013_000000 'Couldn't I find a place to spend the night?' laughed Lukashka. 'But the corporal asked me to go back.'
5322_7680_000014_000000 'I heard you singing last night, and also saw you.'
5322_7680_000015_000000 'Every one...' and luke swayed his head.
5322_7680_000017_000001 But I have not got a horse yet.'
5322_7680_000018_000000 'Aren't you in the regular service?'
5322_7680_000019_000000 'Oh dear no! I've only just joined, and have not got a horse yet, and don't know how to get one.
5322_7680_000019_000001 That's why the marriage does not come off.'
5322_7680_000020_000000 'And what would a horse cost?'
5322_7680_000021_000000 'We were bargaining for one beyond the river the other day and they would not take sixty rubles for it, though it is a Nogay horse.'
5322_7680_000022_000000 'Will you come and be my drabant?' (A drabant was a kind of orderly attached to an officer when campaigning.) 'I'll get it arranged and will give you a horse,' said Olenin suddenly.
5322_7680_000022_000001 'Really now, I have two and I don't want both.'
5322_7680_000023_000000 'How-don't want it?' Lukashka said, laughing.
5322_7680_000023_000001 'Why should you make me a present?
5322_7680_000023_000002 We'll get on by ourselves by God's help.'
5322_7680_000024_000000 'No, really!
5322_7680_000024_000001 Or don't you want to be a drabant?' said Olenin, glad that it had entered his head to give a horse to Lukashka, though, without knowing why, he felt uncomfortable and confused and did not know what to say when he tried to speak.
5322_7680_000025_000000 Lukashka was the first to break the silence.
5322_7680_000027_000000 Olenin could not refrain from replying that he had not only one, but several houses.
5322_7680_000028_000000 'A good house?
5322_7680_000028_000001 Bigger than ours?' asked Lukashka good naturedly.
5322_7680_000029_000000 'Much bigger; ten times as big and three storeys high,' replied Olenin.
5322_7680_000031_000000 'I have a hundred horses, worth three or four hundred rubles each, but they are not like yours.
5322_7680_000031_000001 They are trotters, you know....
5322_7680_000031_000002 But still, I like the horses here best.'
5322_7680_000032_000000 'Well, and did you come here of your own free will, or were you sent?' said Lukashka, laughing at him.
5322_7680_000032_000001 'Look! that's where you lost your way,' he added, 'you should have turned to the right.'
5322_7680_000034_000000 'I would go on an expedition any day,' said Lukashka. 'D'you hear the jackals howling?' he added, listening.
5322_7680_000036_000000 'What's there to be frightened about?
5322_7680_000036_000001 But I should like to join an expedition,' Lukashka repeated.
5322_7680_000036_000002 'How I want to!
5322_7680_000036_000003 How I want to!'
5322_7680_000037_000000 'Perhaps we may be going together.
5322_7680_000037_000001 Our company is going before the holidays, and your "hundred" too.'
5322_7680_000038_000000 'And what did you want to come here for?
5322_7680_000038_000002 In your place I'd do nothing but make merry!
5322_7680_000039_000000 'I am a cadet, but have been recommended for a commission.'
5322_7680_000040_000000 'Well, if you're not bragging about your home, if I were you I'd never have left it!
5322_7680_000040_000001 Yes, I'd never have gone away anywhere.
5322_7680_000040_000002 Do you find it pleasant living among us?'
5322_7680_000041_000000 'Yes, very pleasant,' answered Olenin.
5322_7680_000042_000000 It had grown quite dark before, talking in this way, they approached the village.
5322_7680_000042_000001 They were still surrounded by the deep gloom of the forest.
5322_7680_000042_000002 The wind howled through the tree tops.
5322_7680_000042_000003 The jackals suddenly seemed to be crying close beside them, howling, chuckling, and sobbing; but ahead of them in the village the sounds of women's voices and the barking of dogs could already be heard; the outlines of the huts were clearly to be seen; lights gleamed and the air was filled with the peculiar smell of kisyak smoke.
5322_7680_000042_000004 Olenin felt keenly, that night especially, that here in this village was his home, his family, all his happiness, and that he never had and never would live so happily anywhere as he did in this Cossack village.
5322_7680_000042_000005 He was so fond of everybody and especially of Lukashka that night.
5322_7680_000042_000006 On reaching home, to Lukashka's great surprise, Olenin with his own hands led out of the shed a horse he had bought in Groznoe-it was not the one he usually rode but another-not a bad horse though no longer young, and gave it to Lukashka.
5322_7680_000043_000000 'Why should you give me a present?' said Lukashka, 'I have not yet done anything for you.'
5322_7680_000044_000000 'Really it is nothing,' answered Olenin. 'Take it, and you will give me a present, and we'll go on an expedition against the enemy together.'
5322_7680_000045_000000 Lukashka became confused.
5322_7680_000047_000000 'Take it, take it!
5322_7680_000047_000001 If you don't you will offend me.
5322_7680_000047_000002 Vanyusha!
5322_7680_000047_000003 Take the grey horse to his house.'
5322_7680_000048_000000 Lukashka took hold of the halter.
5322_7680_000049_000001 This is something unexpected, undreamt of.'
5322_7680_000050_000000 Olenin was as happy as a boy of twelve.
5322_7680_000051_000000 'Tie it up here.
5322_7680_000051_000001 It's a good horse.
5322_7680_000051_000002 I bought it in Groznoe; it gallops splendidly!
5322_7680_000051_000003 Vanyusha, bring us some chikhir.
5322_7680_000051_000004 Come into the hut.'
5322_7680_000052_000000 The wine was brought.
5322_7680_000052_000001 Lukashka sat down and took the wine bowl.
5322_7680_000053_000000 'God willing I'll find a way to repay you,' he said, finishing his wine.
5322_7680_000053_000001 'How are you called?'
5322_7680_000055_000001 We will be kunaks.
5322_7680_000055_000002 Now you must come to see us.
5322_7680_000055_000003 Though we are not rich people still we can treat a kunak, and I will tell mother in case you need anything-clotted cream or grapes-and if you come to the cordon I'm your servant to go hunting or to go across the river, anywhere you like!
5322_7680_000055_000004 There now, only the other day, what a boar I killed, and I divided it among the Cossacks, but if I had only known, I'd have given it to you.' 'That's all right, thank you!
5322_7680_000055_000005 But don't harness the horse, it has never been in harness.'
5322_7680_000056_000000 'Why harness the horse?
5322_7680_000056_000001 And there is something else I'll tell you if you like,' said Lukashka, bending his head.
5322_7680_000056_000002 'I have a kunak, Girey Khan.
5322_7680_000056_000003 He asked me to lie in ambush by the road where they come down from the mountains.
5322_7680_000056_000004 Shall we go together?
5322_7680_000057_000000 'Yes, we'll go; we'll go some day.'
5322_7680_000058_000000 Lukashka seemed quite to have quieted down and to have understood Olenin's attitude towards him.
5322_7680_000058_000001 His calmness and the ease of his behaviour surprised Olenin, and he did not even quite like it.
5322_7680_000058_000002 They talked long, and it was late when Lukashka, not tipsy (he never was tipsy) but having drunk a good deal, left Olenin after shaking hands.
5322_7680_000059_000000 Olenin looked out of the window to see what he would do.
5322_7680_000059_000002 Then, having led the horse out of the gate, he suddenly shook his head, threw the reins of the halter over its head, sprang onto its back like a cat, gave a wild shout, and galloped down the street.
5322_7680_000059_000004 He was as delighted as a boy, and could not refrain from telling Vanyusha not only that he had given Lukashka the horse, but also why he had done it, as well as his new theory of happiness.
5322_7680_000060_000000 Lukashka rode home, jumped off the horse, and handed it over to his mother, telling her to let it out with the communal Cossack herd.
5322_7680_000060_000003 The old woman only shook her head at her son's story, and decided in her own mind that he had stolen it.
5322_7680_000060_000004 She therefore told the deaf girl to take it to the herd before daybreak.
5322_7680_000061_000000 Lukashka went back alone to the cordon pondering over Olenin's action. Though he did not consider the horse a good one, yet it was worth at least forty rubles and Lukashka was very glad to have the present.
5322_7680_000061_000001 But why it had been given him he could not at all understand, and therefore he did not experience the least feeling of gratitude.
5322_7680_000061_000002 On the contrary, vague suspicions that the cadet had some evil intentions filled his mind.
5322_7680_000061_000003 What those intentions were he could not decide, but neither could he admit the idea that a stranger would give him a horse worth forty rubles for nothing, just out of kindness; it seemed impossible.
5322_7680_000061_000004 Had he been drunk one might understand it!
5322_7680_000061_000005 He might have wished to show off. But the cadet had been sober, and therefore must have wished to bribe him to do something wrong.
5322_7680_000061_000006 'Eh, humbug!' thought Lukashka.
5322_7680_000061_000007 'Haven't I got the horse and we'll see later on.
5322_7680_000061_000009 He told no one how he had got the horse.
5322_7680_000061_000010 To some he said he had bought it, to others he replied evasively.
5322_7680_000061_000011 However, the truth soon got about in the village, and Lukashka's mother and Maryanka, as well as Elias Vasilich and other Cossacks, when they heard of Olenin's unnecessary gift, were perplexed, and began to be on their guard against the cadet.
5322_7680_000061_000012 But despite their fears his action aroused in them a great respect for his simplicity and wealth.
5322_7680_000062_000000 'Have you heard,' said one, 'that the cadet quartered on Elias Vasilich has thrown a fifty ruble horse at Lukashka?
5322_7680_000062_000001 He's rich! ...'
5322_7680_000063_000000 'Yes, I heard of it,' replied another profoundly, 'he must have done him some great service.
5322_7680_000063_000001 We shall see what will come of this cadet.
5322_7680_000064_000000 'Those cadets are crafty, awfully crafty,' said a third.
5339_14133_000002_000003 Her life was quiet and monotonous, although hard-working; and while her hands mechanically found and did their accustomed labour, the thoughts that rose in her head always centred on Charley Kinraid, his ways, his words, his looks, whether they all meant what she would fain believe they did, and whether, meaning love at the time, such a feeling was likely to endure.
5339_14133_000002_000004 Her mother's story of crazy Nancy had taken hold of her; but not as a 'caution,' rather as a parallel case to her own.
5339_14133_000003_000002 By degrees both Hepburn and Coulson were introduced to distant manufacturers and wholesale dealers.
5339_14133_000004_000000 When Philip saw Sylvia she was always quiet and gentle; perhaps more silent than she had been a year ago, and she did not attend so briskly to what was passing around her.
5339_14133_000004_000001 She was rather thinner and paler; but whatever change there was in her was always an improvement in Philip's eyes, so long as she spoke graciously to him.
5339_14133_000004_000003 She liked him better, too, than she had done a year or two before, because he did not show her any of the eager attention which teased her then, although its meaning was not fully understood.
5339_14133_000005_000000 Things were much in this state when the frost broke, and milder weather succeeded.
5339_14133_000005_000003 The widow woman was to come and stay in the house, to keep Sylvia company, during her mother's absence.
5339_14133_000006_000005 The shops in the town were equally busy; stores had to be purchased by the whaling masters, warm clothing of all sorts to be provided.
5339_14133_000006_000006 These were the larger wholesale orders; but many a man, and woman, too, brought out their small hoards to purchase extra comforts, or precious keepsakes for some beloved one.
5339_14133_000006_000007 It was the time of the great half yearly traffic of the place; another impetus was given to business when the whalers returned in the autumn, and the men were flush of money, and full of delight at once more seeing their homes and their friends.
5339_14133_000007_000002 But it thus happened that they did not give the prompt assistance they were accustomed to render at such times; and Coulson had been away on some of the new expeditions devolving on him and Philip as future partners.
