5514_19193_000030_000000 CHAPTER fifteen-GAVROCHE OUTSIDE
5514_19193_000031_000000 Courfeyrac suddenly caught sight of some one at the base of the barricade, outside in the street, amid the bullets.
5514_19193_000032_000000 Gavroche had taken a bottle basket from the wine shop, had made his way out through the cut, and was quietly engaged in emptying the full cartridge boxes of the National Guardsmen who had been killed on the slope of the redoubt, into his basket.
5514_19193_000033_000000 "What are you doing there?" asked Courfeyrac.
5514_19193_000034_000000 Gavroche raised his face:--
5514_19193_000035_000000 "I'm filling my basket, citizen."
5514_19193_000036_000000 "Don't you see the grape shot?"
5514_19193_000037_000000 Gavroche replied:
5514_19193_000038_000001 What then?"
5514_19193_000039_000000 Courfeyrac shouted:--"Come in!"
5514_19193_000040_000000 "Instanter," said Gavroche.
5514_19193_000041_000000 And with a single bound he plunged into the street.
5514_19193_000042_000000 It will be remembered that Fannicot's company had left behind it a trail of bodies.
5514_19193_000042_000001 Twenty corpses lay scattered here and there on the pavement, through the whole length of the street.
5514_19193_000042_000002 Twenty cartouches for Gavroche meant a provision of cartridges for the barricade.
5514_19193_000043_000000 The smoke in the street was like a fog.
5514_19193_000043_000001 Whoever has beheld a cloud which has fallen into a mountain gorge between two peaked escarpments can imagine this smoke rendered denser and thicker by two gloomy rows of lofty houses.
5514_19193_000043_000002 It rose gradually and was incessantly renewed; hence a twilight which made even the broad daylight turn pale.
5514_19193_000043_000003 The combatants could hardly see each other from one end of the street to the other, short as it was.
5514_19193_000045_000001 He rifled the first seven or eight cartridge boxes without much danger.
5514_19193_000046_000000 He crawled flat on his belly, galloped on all fours, took his basket in his teeth, twisted, glided, undulated, wound from one dead body to another, and emptied the cartridge box or cartouche as a monkey opens a nut.
5514_19193_000047_000000 They did not dare to shout to him to return from the barricade, which was quite near, for fear of attracting attention to him.
5514_19193_000048_000000 On one body, that of a corporal, he found a powder flask.
5514_19193_000049_000000 "For thirst," said he, putting it in his pocket.
5514_19193_000050_000000 By dint of advancing, he reached a point where the fog of the fusillade became transparent.
5514_19193_000051_000000 At the moment when Gavroche was relieving a sergeant, who was lying near a stone door post, of his cartridges, a bullet struck the body.
5514_19193_000052_000000 "Fichtre!" ejaculated Gavroche.
5514_19193_000052_000001 "They are killing my dead men for me."
5514_19193_000053_000000 A second bullet struck a spark from the pavement beside him.--A third overturned his basket.
5514_19193_000055_000000 He sprang to his feet, stood erect, with his hair flying in the wind, his hands on his hips, his eyes fixed on the National Guardsmen who were firing, and sang:
5514_19193_000057_000000 Then he picked up his basket, replaced the cartridges which had fallen from it, without missing a single one, and, advancing towards the fusillade, set about plundering another cartridge box.
5514_19193_000057_000001 There a fourth bullet missed him, again.
5514_19193_000057_000002 Gavroche sang:
5514_19193_000059_000000 A fifth bullet only succeeded in drawing from him a third couplet.
5514_19193_000061_000000 Thus it went on for some time.
5514_19193_000062_000000 It was a charming and terrible sight.
5514_19193_000062_000001 Gavroche, though shot at, was teasing the fusillade.
5514_19193_000062_000002 He had the air of being greatly diverted.
5514_19193_000062_000003 It was the sparrow pecking at the sportsmen.
5514_19193_000062_000004 To each discharge he retorted with a couplet.
5514_19193_000062_000005 They aimed at him constantly, and always missed him.
5514_19193_000062_000006 The National Guardsmen and the soldiers laughed as they took aim at him.
5514_19193_000062_000007 He lay down, sprang to his feet, hid in the corner of a doorway, then made a bound, disappeared, re appeared, scampered away, returned, replied to the grape shot with his thumb at his nose, and, all the while, went on pillaging the cartouches, emptying the cartridge boxes, and filling his basket.
5514_19193_000062_000008 The insurgents, panting with anxiety, followed him with their eyes.
5514_19193_000062_000009 The barricade trembled; he sang.
5514_19193_000062_000010 He was not a child, he was not a man; he was a strange gamin fairy.
5514_19193_000062_000011 He might have been called the invulnerable dwarf of the fray.
5514_19193_000062_000012 The bullets flew after him, he was more nimble than they.
5514_19193_000062_000013 He played a fearful game of hide and seek with death; every time that the flat nosed face of the spectre approached, the urchin administered to it a fillip.
5514_19193_000063_000000 One bullet, however, better aimed or more treacherous than the rest, finally struck the will o'-the wisp of a child.
5514_19193_000063_000001 Gavroche was seen to stagger, then he sank to the earth.
5514_19193_000064_000001 " 'tis the fault of . . .
5514_19193_000065_000000 He did not finish.
5514_19193_000065_000001 A second bullet from the same marksman stopped him short.
5514_19193_000065_000002 This time he fell face downward on the pavement, and moved no more.
5561_39621_000002_000000 Chapter seven.
5561_39621_000004_000000 The stranger did not pay them the least attention; but Cropole approaching him respectfully, whispered, "Monsieur, the diamond has been valued."
5561_39621_000005_000001 "Well?"
5561_39621_000006_000000 "Well, monsieur, the jeweler of s a r gives two hundred and eighty pistoles for it."
5561_39621_000007_000000 "Have you them?"
5561_39621_000008_000000 "I thought it best to take them, monsieur; nevertheless, I made it a condition of the bargain, that if monsieur wished to keep his diamond, it should be held till monsieur was again in funds."
5561_39621_000011_000000 "Pay yourself," added the unknown.
5561_39621_000013_000000 A sad smile passed over the lips of the gentleman.
5561_39621_000014_000000 "Place the money on that trunk," said he, turning round and pointing to the piece of furniture.
5561_39621_000015_000000 Cropole deposited a tolerably large bag as directed, after having taken from it the amount of his reckoning.
5561_39621_000017_000000 The unknown asked for a glass of wine, broke off a morsel of bread, and did not stir from the window whilst he ate and drank.
5561_39621_000018_000000 Shortly after was heard a loud flourish of trumpets; cries arose in the distance, a confused buzzing filled the lower part of the city, and the first distinct sound that struck the ears of the stranger was the tramp of advancing horses.
5561_39621_000019_000000 "The king! the king!" repeated a noisy and eager crowd.
5561_39621_000020_000000 "The king!" cried Cropole, abandoning his guest and his ideas of delicacy, to satisfy his curiosity.
5561_39621_000023_000000 After a company of musketeers, a closely ranked troop of gentlemen, came the litter of monsieur le cardinal, drawn like a carriage by four black horses.
5561_39621_000023_000001 The pages and people of the cardinal marched behind.
5561_39621_000025_000000 The king then appeared, mounted upon a splendid horse of Saxon breed, with a flowing mane.
5561_39621_000025_000001 The young prince exhibited, when bowing to some windows from which issued the most animated acclamations, a noble and handsome countenance, illuminated by the flambeaux of his pages.
5561_39621_000026_000001 The pomp was of a military character.
5561_39621_000027_000000 Some of the courtiers-the elder ones, for instance-wore traveling dresses; but all the rest were clothed in warlike panoply.
5561_39621_000028_000000 When the king passed before him, the unknown, who had leant forward over the balcony to obtain a better view, and who had concealed his face by leaning on his arm, felt his heart swell and overflow with a bitter jealousy.
5561_39621_000029_000000 The noise of the trumpets excited him-the popular acclamations deafened him: for a moment he allowed his reason to be absorbed in this flood of lights, tumult, and brilliant images.
5561_39621_000031_000000 Then, before he had recovered from his sombre reverie, all the noise, all the splendor, had passed away.
5561_39621_000033_000000 "A handsome likeness!" said Pittrino.
5561_39621_000035_000001 But at that moment the voice of the stranger was heard from the window.
5561_39621_000037_000000 Cropole turned around, and, on seeing the old man, cleared a passage for him.
5561_39621_000038_000000 The window was instantly closed.
5561_39621_000040_000000 The stranger waited for him on the landing; he opened his arms to the old man, and led him to a seat.
5561_39621_000041_000001 "Sit down in your presence?--never!"
5561_39621_000042_000000 "Parry," cried the gentleman, "I beg you will; you come from England-you come so far.
5561_39621_000043_000000 "I have my reply to give your lordship, in the first place."
5561_39621_000045_000000 "My lord," said the old man, "do not hasten to alarm yourself; all is not lost, I hope.
5561_39621_000045_000001 You must employ energy, but more particularly resignation."
5561_39621_000046_000000 "Parry," said the young man, "I have reached this place through a thousand snares and after a thousand difficulties; can you doubt my energy?
5561_39621_000046_000001 I have meditated this journey ten years, in spite of all counsels and all obstacles-have you faith in my perseverance?
5561_39621_000048_000001 I do not despair, Parry; have you faith in my resignation?"
5561_39621_000050_000000 "Let me know," said the stranger,--"disguise nothing from me-what has happened?"
5561_39621_000051_000000 "My recital will be short, my lord; but in the name of Heaven do not tremble so."
5561_39621_000052_000001 Come, what did the general say to you?"
5561_39621_000053_000000 "At first the general would not receive me."
5561_39621_000054_000000 "He took you for a spy?"
5561_39621_000055_000000 "Yes, my lord; but I wrote him a letter."
5561_39621_000056_000000 "Well?"
5561_39621_000057_000000 "He read it, and received me, my lord."
5561_39621_000060_000000 "Well-then, Parry."
5561_39621_000061_000000 "Then the general sent me back the letter by an aide de camp, informing me that if I were found the next day within the circumscription of his command, he would have me arrested."
5561_39621_000062_000000 "Arrested!" murmured the young man.
5561_39621_000062_000001 "What! arrest you, my most faithful servant?"
5561_39621_000063_000000 "Yes, my lord."
5561_39621_000064_000000 "And notwithstanding you had signed the name Parry?"
5561_39621_000065_000000 "To all my letters, my lord; and the aide de camp had known me at saint James's and at Whitehall, too," added the old man with a sigh.
5561_39621_000066_000000 The young man leaned forward, thoughtful and sad.
5561_39621_000067_000001 "But, privately-between you and him-what did he do?
5561_39621_000068_000001 These cavaliers conducted me, in great haste, to the little port of Tenby, threw me, rather than embarked me, into a little fishing boat, about to sail for Brittany, and here I am."
5561_39621_000069_000000 "Oh!" sighed the young man, clasping his neck convulsively with his hand, and with a sob.
5561_39621_000069_000001 "Parry, is that all?--is that all?"
5561_39621_000070_000000 "Yes, my lord; that is all."
5561_39621_000071_000000 After this brief reply ensued a long interval of silence, broken only by the convulsive beating of the heel of the young man on the floor.
5561_39621_000072_000000 The old man endeavored to change the conversation; it was leading to thoughts much too sinister.
5561_39621_000073_000001 What are these people crying 'Vive le Roi!' for?
5561_39621_000074_000001 All these trumpets are his, all those gilded housings are his, all those gentlemen wear swords that are his.
5561_39621_000074_000002 His mother precedes him in a carriage magnificently encrusted with silver and gold.
5561_39621_000074_000003 Happy mother!
5561_39621_000074_000004 His minister heaps up millions, and conducts him to a rich bride.
5561_39621_000074_000006 Vive le Roi!'"
5561_39621_000075_000000 "Well, well, my lord," said Parry, more uneasy at the turn the conversation had taken than at the other.
5561_39621_000076_000001 Parry, are there not examples in which a man of my condition should himself-"
5561_39621_000077_000000 "My lord, in the name of Heaven-"
5561_39621_000078_000000 "You are right, Parry; I am a coward, and if I do nothing for myself, what will God do?
5561_39621_000078_000001 No, no; I have two arms, Parry, and I have a sword." And he struck his arm violently with his hand, and took down his sword, which hung against the wall.
5561_39621_000079_000000 "What are you going to do, my lord?"
5561_39621_000080_000000 "What am I going to do, Parry?
5561_39621_000080_000001 What every one in my family does.
5561_39621_000080_000002 My mother lives on public charity, my sister begs for my mother; I have, somewhere or other, brothers who equally beg for themselves; and I, the eldest, will go and do as all the rest do-I will go and ask charity!"
5561_39621_000082_000000 "My good Parry," said he, "order a fire, drink, eat, sleep, and be happy; let us both be happy, my faithful friend, my only friend.
5561_39621_000082_000001 We are rich, as rich as kings!"
5561_41615_000001_000000 A WOULD BE "LARK"
5561_41615_000002_000002 The majority, however, appeared to be highly delighted over what they heard, one group standing near one of the windows, of which Eleanor was the center, laughed so loudly that they were sent to their seats.
5561_41615_000003_000001 Several times they caught sight of a folded paper being stealthily passed from one desk to another, but as to its contents they had no idea, as it was not handed to any one of them.
5561_41615_000004_000000 At recess there was more grouping and whispering, and Grace was puzzled and not a little hurt over the way in which she and her friends were ignored.
5561_41615_000004_000001 Such a thing had not happened since the basketball trouble the previous year.
5561_41615_000006_000000 "Here comes Mabel," said Jessica.
5561_41615_000009_000000 Mabel looked distressed for a moment then she said, "I wish I might tell you all about it, but I gave my word of honor before I read it that I wouldn't mention the contents to any one."
5561_41615_000010_000000 "Then, of course, we won't ask you," said Anne Pierson quickly.
5561_41615_000010_000001 "But tell us this much-is it about any of us?"
5561_41615_000011_000000 "No," replied Mabel.
5561_41615_000011_000001 "It isn't.
5561_41615_000011_000002 It is something I was asked to sign."
5561_41615_000012_000000 "And did you sign it?" asked Jessica.
5561_41615_000013_000000 "I certainly did not," responded Mabel.
5561_41615_000013_000001 "It was----" she stopped, then flushed.
5561_41615_000013_000002 She had been on the point of telling.
5561_41615_000013_000004 "I can't bear to have secrets and not tell you."
5561_41615_000014_000001 "We don't want you to tell.
5561_41615_000014_000002 If it doesn't concern us we don't care, do we, girls?"
5561_41615_000015_000000 "No, indeed," was the reply.
5561_41615_000016_000000 Just then the bell sounded and the girls returned to their seats with the riddle still unsolved.
5561_41615_000017_000000 On Wednesday, aside from a little more whispering and significant glances exchanged among the pupils, not a ripple disturbed the calm of the study hall.
5561_41615_000017_000001 It was therefore a distinct and not altogether pleasant surprise when Miss Thompson walked into the room, dismissed the senior class and requested the three lower classes to remain in their seats.
5561_41615_000018_000000 After the seniors had quietly left the study hall, Miss Thompson stood gravely regarding the rows of girls before her.
5561_41615_000018_000001 Her eyes wandered toward where Eleanor sat, looking bored and indifferent, and then she looked toward Grace, whose steady gray eyes were fixed on the principal's face with respectful attention.
5561_41615_000019_000000 "I don't believe Grace is guilty, at any rate," thought Miss Thompson; then she addressed the assembled girls.
5561_41615_000021_000000 Miss Thompson paused and a number of girls stirred uneasily in their seats, while a few glanced quickly toward Eleanor, who was looking straight ahead, the picture of innocence.
5561_41615_000022_000000 "You all know," continued the principal, "that it is strictly forbidden for any pupil to absent herself from school for the purpose of attending a circus, matinee or any public performance of this nature.
5561_41615_000022_000001 I have so severely disciplined pupils for this offence that for a long time no one has disobeyed me.
5561_41615_000022_000003 Such a decision is worse than disobedience-it is lawlessness.
5561_41615_000022_000005 Therefore, I intend to sift this matter to the bottom and find out what mischievous influence prompted this act of insubordination.
5561_41615_000023_000000 "Report says that this movement originated in the junior class, and that a paper has been circulated and signed by certain pupils, who pledged themselves to play truant and attend the matinee to morrow."
5561_41615_000024_000000 The eyes of Grace and her chums turned questioningly toward Mabel Allison, who nodded slightly in the affirmative.
5561_41615_000025_000002 Even Mabel had refused to sign.
5561_41615_000026_000000 "I have dismissed the senior class, because I have been assured of their entire ignorance of the plot.
5561_41615_000026_000001 What I insist upon knowing now, is who are the real culprits, beginning with the girl who originated the paper to the last one who signed it.
5561_41615_000026_000002 I am going to put every girl on her honor, and I expect absolutely truthful answers.
5561_41615_000026_000003 The girls who signed the paper I have mentioned will rise."
5561_41615_000027_000000 There was a moment of suspense, then Eleanor Savell proudly rose from her seat.
5561_41615_000027_000001 Her example was followed, until two thirds of the girls present were standing.
5561_41615_000027_000002 The principal stood silently regarding them with an expression of severity that was decidedly discomfitting.
5561_41615_000028_000000 "That will do," she said curtly, after they had stood for what seemed to them an age, but was really only a couple of minutes.
5561_41615_000029_000001 The girl who composed and wrote that agreement will now rise and explain herself."
5561_41615_000030_000000 Without hesitating, Eleanor rose and regarded the principal with an insolent smile.
5561_41615_000030_000001 "I wrote it, Miss Thompson," she said clearly.
5561_41615_000030_000003 I am sorry you found out about it, because it has spoiled all our fun."
5561_41615_000031_000000 There was a gasp of horror at Eleanor's assertion.
5561_41615_000031_000001 No one had ever before spoken so disrespectfully to their revered principal.
5561_41615_000032_000000 "Miss Savell," said the principal quietly, although her flashing eyes and set lips showed that she was very angry, "if you have that paper in your possession, bring it to me at once, and never answer me again as you did just now.
5561_41615_000032_000001 You are both disrespectful and impertinent."
5561_41615_000033_000000 But Miss Thompson's anger toward Eleanor was nothing compared with the tempest that the principal had aroused in Eleanor.
5561_41615_000033_000001 The latter flushed, then turned perfectly white with rage.
5561_41615_000033_000002 Still standing, she reached down, picked up a book from her desk and took from it a paper.
5561_41615_000033_000003 "This," she said, in a low tense voice, "is the paper you wish to see.
5561_41615_000033_000004 I do not choose to let you see it, therefore I shall destroy it."
5561_41615_000035_000000 Then she deliberately tore the offending paper into shreds and scattered them broadcast.
5561_41615_000036_000000 "I hope you understand that I am not afraid of you or any other teacher in this school," she continued.
5561_41615_000036_000001 "I have never been punished in my life, therefore I am not liable to give you the first opportunity.
5561_41615_000036_000003 As for the persons who told you about our plan, words cannot express my contempt for them, and right here I accuse Grace Harlowe and her sorority of getting the information from Mabel Allison yesterday and carrying it to you.
5561_41615_000037_000000 With these words, Eleanor angrily flung the book she held on the desk and walked down the aisle toward the door, but Miss Thompson barred her way.
5561_41615_000038_000000 "Stop, Miss Savell," she commanded.
5561_41615_000038_000002 I will not tolerate such behavior."
5561_41615_000042_000000 "Those girls who are not in any way implicated in this matter are dismissed," she said.
5561_41615_000043_000000 About one third of the girls arose and prepared to leave the study hall, the Phi Sigma Tau being among the number.
5561_41615_000043_000001 Grace motioned the girls to hurry.
5561_41615_000043_000004 For the first time since Eleanor had chosen to cut their acquaintance Grace was thoroughly angry with her.
5561_41615_000043_000005 She could not forgive Eleanor for having accused her and her friends of carrying tales before almost the entire school; therefore a forced apology would not appease her wounded pride. She drew a breath of relief when the eight girls were safely outside the study hall door.
5561_41615_000044_000000 "Hurry up," she said.
5561_41615_000044_000001 "We'll talk when we get outside school.
5561_41615_000044_000002 Don't stop for a minute.
5561_41615_000045_000000 The girls silently donned their wraps and fled from the building like fugitives from justice.
5561_41615_000045_000001 Once on the street a lively confab ensued, all talking at once.
5561_41615_000046_000000 "Let's take turns talking," cried Grace, laughing.
5561_41615_000046_000001 "We shall understand each other a little better."
5561_41615_000047_000000 "Now, what do you think of Miss Eleanor?" cried Nora.
5561_41615_000049_000000 "It was abominable," said Eva Allen.
5561_41615_000050_000000 The other girls expressed their disapproval in equally frank terms.
5561_41615_000051_000000 "I suppose it did look as though I told you girls," said Mabel Allison, who had joined them at the gate.
5561_41615_000051_000003 It was passed to me by mistake."
5561_41615_000052_000000 "Very likely," agreed Grace.
5561_41615_000055_000001 "She deserves to be punished.
5561_41615_000055_000002 The things she said to Miss Thompson were disgraceful, and I shall never forgive her for the way she spoke of us."
5561_41615_000056_000000 "I wouldn't say that, Grace," remarked Anne.
5561_41615_000057_000000 "It will have to be something remarkable in this instance," replied Grace grimly, as she bade the girls good bye.
5561_41615_000057_000001 "Remember, girls, basketball practice again to morrow, and the rest of the week.
5561_41615_000057_000002 Miss Thompson has promised me the gymnasium.
5561_41615_000057_000003 Please make it a point to be on hand."
5561_41615_000059_000001 They were spending a most uncomfortable half hour with Miss Thompson.
5561_41615_000059_000005 Miss Thompson had taken their names, but had not stated their punishment and it was certain that they would be made to feel the full weight of her displeasure.
5561_41615_000061_000000 Eleanor looked scornfully at the principal, and was silent.
5561_41615_000062_000000 "Do you intend to obey me, Miss Savell?" asked Miss Thompson.
5561_41615_000063_000000 Still there was no answer.
5561_41615_000064_000000 "Very well," continued Miss Thompson.
5561_41615_000064_000001 "Your silence indicates that you are still insubordinate.
5561_41615_000064_000002 You may, therefore, choose between two things. You may apologize to me now, and to morrow to the girls you have accused of treachery, or you may leave this school, not to return to it unless permitted to do so by the Board of Education."
5561_41615_000065_000000 Without a word Eleanor rose and walked haughtily out of the room.
5561_41616_000001_000000 CHAPTER sixteen
5561_41616_000002_000000 THE JUNIORS FOREVER
5561_41616_000003_000000 When the four classes assembled Thursday morning, every girl, with the exception of Eleanor, was in her seat.
5561_41616_000004_000000 After conducting opening exercises, Miss Thompson pronounced sentence on the culprits.
5561_41616_000004_000001 They were to forfeit their recess, library and all other privileges until the end of the term.
5561_41616_000004_000002 They must turn in two themes every week of not less than six hundred words on certain subjects to be assigned to them.
5561_41616_000004_000003 If, during this time, any one of them should be reported for a misdemeanor, they were to be suspended without delay.
5561_41616_000005_000000 Their penalty was far from light, but they had not been suspended, and so they resolved to endure it as best they might.
5561_41616_000006_000000 Grace Harlowe felt a load lifted from her mind when Miss Thompson publicly announced that she had not received any information from either Mabel Allison or the Phi Sigma Tau.
5561_41616_000007_000000 "Thank goodness, none of us were concerned in that affair," she told the members of her basketball team at recess.
5561_41616_000007_000001 "There are two girls on the sophomore and three on the freshman team whose basketball ardor will have to cool until after the mid year exams."
5561_41616_000011_000000 There was a burst of laughter from the girls at this effusion, in which Nora herself joined.
5561_41616_000012_000000 "What a delicate way of reminding me that I once was a freshman!" she exclaimed.
5561_41616_000013_000001 "She can spout poetry without trying."
5561_41616_000014_000000 "Small credit is due me," said Anne, smiling.
5561_41616_000014_000001 "Anyone can twist 'Annabel Lee' to suit the occasion."
5561_41616_000015_000000 "By the way, Anne," said Grace, "as you are a poet, you must compose a basketball song to day, and I'll see that the juniors all have copies. It's time we had one.
5561_41616_000015_000001 Let me see what would be a good tune?"
5561_41616_000016_000000 "'Rally Round the Flag,'" suggested Miriam Nesbit.
5561_41616_000016_000001 "That has a dandy swing to it."
5561_41616_000017_000000 Grace hummed a few bars.
5561_41616_000018_000000 "The very thing," she exclaimed.
5561_41616_000018_000001 "Now, Anne, get busy at once.
5561_41616_000019_000001 Hippy, David and Reddy have a new one, too.
5561_41616_000019_000002 Reddy says it's 'marvelously extraordinary and appallingly great.'"
5561_41616_000021_000000 "Wasn't it nice of Miss Thompson to exonerate us publicly?" asked Anne.
5561_41616_000022_000000 "She is always just," replied Grace.
5561_41616_000022_000001 "I can't understand how Eleanor could be so rude and disagreeable to her.
5561_41616_000022_000002 She has disliked Miss Thompson from the first."
5561_41616_000023_000000 "I wonder whether she apologized to Miss Thompson last night," mused Grace.
5561_41616_000024_000000 "I feel sure that she didn't, and I am just as sure that she won't get back until she does."
5561_41616_000025_000000 "We shall manage to exist if she doesn't," said Jessica dryly.
