6064_300880_000075_000001 He did so.
6064_300880_000076_000000 "Then I'll just go back and jolly well camp there till somebody jolly well lets me in," decided the caller.
6064_300880_000077_000000 Argument followed while the chauffeur burrowed into the mechanism of his car.
6064_300880_000077_000001 It ended by the Englishman bestowing two dollars upon mr Murphy to get a message to mr Remsen containing a protest and an address.
6064_300880_000077_000002 The two gentlemen then moved away in the extinguished taxi.
6064_300880_000078_000000 Tickets had been provided by the forethoughtful Harmon.
6064_300880_000078_000001 The fugitive was the first man in the parlor car.
6064_300880_000078_000002 Hardly had he settled when a young couple in suspiciously new apparel arrived, and were shown into Drawing Room "A," at the upper end of the car.
6064_300880_000078_000003 Shortly after, another couple, also glistening as to garb, entered and took possession of Drawing Room "B," at the lower end of the car.
6064_300880_000079_000000 "Here we are, all of us," he said to himself, retiring discreetly behind his newspaper.
6064_56165_000002_000000 A SOPHOMORE
6064_56165_000003_000000 When Edith's brother Philip came in from College to spend Saturday and Sunday, Edith's house was apt to be a rendezvous for the other girls. Not that Philip was likely to waste much time with mere girls.
6064_56165_000003_000001 Not he! He was a Harvard sophomore, and realized his own importance quite as much as the girls did.
6064_56165_000003_000002 But still there was always the chance that he would come into the room just for a minute, and tell them some of the latest Cambridge news.
6064_56165_000003_000003 He would have scorned to call it gossip.
6064_56165_000003_000004 If there was any one thing in the world he hated-so he said-it was girls' talk, this jabbering about nothing.
6064_56165_000004_000000 "And upon my word," he concluded, "I wasn't sorry, for the New York set is getting just unbearable.
6064_56165_000004_000002 I guess I'd show him that New York isn't the whole world."
6064_56165_000005_000000 "I should say not," exclaimed Nora; but Belle, who had some New York cousins, was silent.
6064_56165_000005_000001 Brenda, however, noticing Belle's expression, and not feeling disposed to side completely with Nora, said,
6064_56165_000007_000000 "I didn't say so," replied Nora.
6064_56165_000008_000000 "No, but that's what you mean, and I'm surprised, Philip Blair, that a boy should be so awfully one sided."
6064_56165_000009_000000 "Well, you'd better talk, Brenda Barlow," broke in Nora again.
6064_56165_000009_000001 "Just see the way you treat Julia.
6064_56165_000009_000002 If she'd been born in Boston----"
6064_56165_000010_000000 "I don't treat her," interrupted Brenda.
6064_56165_000012_000000 "Oh, I say," said Philip, from his place in front of the mantelpiece, "how queer girls are; do you always fight like this when you're together?"
6064_56165_000013_000000 "We don't fight like you boys," answered Edith, good humoredly.
6064_56165_000013_000001 "We don't knock each other down and run the risk of breaking one another's noses."
6064_56165_000014_000000 Philip looked over his shoulder in the glass.
6064_56165_000014_000001 There was nothing the matter with his own shapely nose, and I doubt that he would have run any such risk as Edith suggested.
6064_56165_000014_000002 Perhaps this was the reason why Philip was not a fighter.
6064_56165_000014_000003 There was one good thing about the little disputes in which Brenda and Belle indulged.
6064_56165_000014_000004 They very seldom lasted long.
6064_56165_000014_000005 In the present instance the girls were ashamed of having shown temper before Philip.
6064_56165_000015_000000 "Oh, say, did you hear about the time Will Hardon had with the Dicky, last week?" he asked.
6064_56165_000016_000000 Nora nodded.
6064_56165_000016_000001 She, too, had a brother in College.
6064_56165_000017_000000 "What was it?" asked Edith.
6064_56165_000018_000000 "How funny you are, Edith," said Belle.
6064_56165_000018_000001 "You never hear anything.
6064_56165_000018_000002 Hasn't anyone told you how the other fellows made him run blindfolded in his shirt sleeves down Beacon Street?"
6064_56165_000019_000000 "No, really?"
6064_56165_000020_000000 "Of course, really!"
6064_56165_000021_000000 "And then they led him up the steps into mrs Oxford's when she was giving an afternoon tea, and when they took the bandage off his eyes there he was in his shirt sleeves, without his hat, and his hair all tumbled, and everybody looking at him."
6064_56165_000022_000000 "Oh," said one girl, and "Ah," said another; and "How silly!" they all cried together.
6064_56165_000023_000000 "If girls amused themselves like that what fun you'd make of us!" said the practical Nora.
6064_56165_000024_000000 "I shouldn't think there'd be much fun in making anybody uncomfortable."
6064_56165_000025_000000 "Oh, it gives a fellow a chance to show what kind of stuff he's made of," explained Philip, "whether he has good manners, and whether he's clever-and all that."
6064_56165_000026_000000 "There must be better ways of showing bravery," said the practical Edith.
6064_56165_000027_000000 "We knew something about his manners."
6064_56165_000028_000000 "What?"
6064_56165_000029_000000 "Why, when he saw where he was, he didn't run away, or flunk out.
6064_56165_000030_000000 "Wasn't he mad at the two fellows for taking him there?"
6064_56165_000031_000000 "Of course not; that's a part of the thing.
6064_56165_000031_000001 Why, there are fellows in Cambridge who would go through fire and water, or stand on their heads in front of a pulpit for the sake of getting into the Dicky.
6064_56165_000031_000002 I tell you we make some of them suffer."
6064_56165_000032_000000 Philip said "we" with a rather important air, although he had belonged to the illustrious organization a very short time.
6064_56165_000034_000000 "If you went to College you'd see more use in them."
6064_56165_000035_000000 "I'm glad girls don't go to College."
6064_56165_000036_000000 "Oh, some do!"
6064_56165_000037_000000 "Not girls we know."
6064_56165_000039_000000 "Well, I declare," exclaimed Nora, "I'd like to know what difference it makes to them."
6064_56165_000040_000000 "Oh, they hate to see these girls going about with books, and trying to get into Harvard."
6064_56165_000041_000000 "Yes, trying to break down the walls," said Nora, sarcastically.
6064_56165_000043_000000 "Are you afraid they'd get ahead of you?" asked Edith, gently.
6064_56165_000044_000000 "Now, look here, Edith, I don't want you to talk that way," responded Philip with brotherly authority.
6064_56165_000044_000001 "There isn't any danger of girls getting ahead of us."
6064_56165_000046_000000 "Oh, yes, I've heard it too," interrupted Philip.
6064_56165_000046_000001 "I've heard that some professors say that their Annex classes do better work than ours,--but anybody can tell that that's all rot."
6064_56165_000047_000000 "I believe it's all perfectly true," said Nora.
6064_56165_000048_000000 "Well, I wish myself that our English instructor hadn't such a fondness for reading themes to us that the girls have written.
6064_56165_000048_000001 He makes out that they are better than ours, but I can't say that I see it myself."
6064_56165_000049_000000 "Who gets the best marks?"
6064_56165_000050_000000 "I'm sure I can't say.
6064_56165_000050_000002 But I wouldn't let a sister of mine go to College," he concluded inconsequently.
6064_56165_000051_000000 "It's a good thing Edith doesn't wish to go," said Nora; adding mischievously, "but Brenda Barlow's cousin Julia is going."
6064_56165_000053_000000 "Does Julia wear glasses, or look green?
6064_56165_000054_000001 "She's about the nicest girl I know."
6064_56165_000055_000000 "Oh, she is lovely," added Edith.
6064_56165_000056_000000 "A matter of opinion," murmured Belle under her breath.
6064_56165_000057_000000 "You don't mean to say you haven't seen her," cried Brenda in surprise.
6064_56165_000058_000000 "No, I haven't happened to," answered Philip.
6064_56165_000059_000000 "She's invited to my cooking party next week," said Nora.
6064_56165_000059_000001 "You know that you've accepted too, so you'll see her."
6064_56165_000060_000000 "Oh, yes, by the way," said Philip, "what evening is it?"
6064_56165_000061_000000 "Friday, of course," replied Nora, "so we can sit up late without thinking about school the next day."
6064_56165_000062_000000 "Well, you'll see me sure," said Philip.
6064_56165_000062_000001 "But see here, it's five o'clock now and I have an engagement down town."
6064_56165_000063_000000 Philip hurried off, bowing in a very grown up way to the group of girls. For whatever criticisms any one might make about Philip's indolence and disinclination to study, no one could deny that he had very good manners.
6064_56165_000063_000001 Though only about four years their senior, he seemed much older than Brenda and her friends.
6064_56165_000063_000002 Years before they had all been playmates together, but his two years in College had taken him away from them, and it was not often that he condescended to spend as long a time in their presence as had been the case this afternoon.
6064_56165_000064_000000 "Do you think that Philip looks very well, Edith," asked Belle when he had left the room.
6064_56165_000066_000000 "It seemed to me he was just a little pale."
6064_56165_000067_000000 "He is always pale," said Edith.
6064_56165_000068_000000 "Do you suppose he sits up too late?" asked Brenda.
6064_56165_000070_000000 "How can you?" cried Nora.
6064_56165_000070_000001 "How can you criticise Edith's brother?
6064_56165_000070_000002 Don't let her do it, Edith."
6064_56165_000071_000000 "It doesn't trouble me," answered the placid Edith.
6064_56165_000071_000001 "I know all about Philip, and he's good enough for me."
6064_56165_000072_000000 "That's right," said Nora.
6064_56165_000072_000001 "Always stand up for your brother.
6064_56165_000072_000002 But I do think he might have better friends.
6064_56165_000072_000003 He really isn't very particular."
6064_56165_000073_000000 "Why, what do you mean?"
6064_56165_000074_000000 "Oh, I don't know exactly, but I heard my brother talking the other day. He says there are two or three fellows just sponging off of Philip all the time, and Philip is too good-natured to say anything."
6064_56165_000075_000000 "I wonder how he'll like Julia," said Edith.
6064_56165_000076_000000 "Oh, he won't like that kind of a girl," hastily interposed Belle.
6064_56165_000076_000001 "Boys never like a girl who studies; especially one who is going to College."
6064_56165_000078_000000 "And Philip is one of the nicest young men I know," said Brenda, politely, turning to Edith.
6064_56165_000078_000001 "But don't tell him I said so," she added with a blush.
