6147_34605_000001_000000 CHAPTER three.
6147_34605_000003_000000 Towards seventeen o five, although Lady Josiana was twenty three and Lord David forty four, the wedding had not yet taken place, and that for the best reasons in the world.
6147_34605_000003_000001 Did they hate each other?
6147_34605_000003_000002 Far from it; but what cannot escape from you inspires you with no haste to obtain it.
6147_34605_000003_000003 Josiana wanted to remain free, David to remain young.
6147_34605_000003_000004 To have no tie until as late as possible appeared to him to be a prolongation of youth. Middle aged young men abounded in those rakish times.
6147_34605_000003_000005 They grew gray as young fops.
6147_34605_000003_000006 The wig was an accomplice: later on, powder became the auxiliary.
6147_34605_000003_000007 At fifty five Lord Charles Gerrard, Baron Gerrard, one of the Gerrards of Bromley, filled London with his successes.
6147_34605_000003_000008 The young and pretty Duchess of Buckingham, Countess of Coventry, made a fool of herself for love of the handsome Thomas Bellasys, Viscount Falconberg, who was sixty seven.
6147_34605_000003_000011 Such were the models of the day.
6147_34605_000004_000000 Josiana and David carried on a flirtation of a particular shade.
6147_34605_000004_000001 They did not love, they pleased, each other.
6147_34605_000004_000003 Why hasten the conclusion?
6147_34605_000004_000004 The novels of those days carried lovers and engaged couples to that kind of stage which was the most becoming.
6147_34605_000004_000005 Besides, Josiana, while she knew herself to be a bastard, felt herself a princess, and carried her authority over him with a high tone in all their arrangements.
6147_34605_000004_000006 She had a fancy for Lord David.
6147_34605_000004_000007 Lord David was handsome, but that was over and above the bargain.
6147_34605_000005_000000 To be fashionable is everything.
6147_34605_000005_000001 Caliban, fashionable and magnificent, would distance Ariel, poor.
6147_34605_000005_000002 Lord David was handsome, so much the better. The danger in being handsome is being insipid; and that he was not.
6147_34605_000005_000003 He betted, boxed, ran into debt.
6147_34605_000005_000004 Josiana thought great things of his horses, his dogs, his losses at play, his mistresses.
6147_34605_000005_000005 Lord David, on his side, bowed down before the fascinations of the Duchess Josiana-a maiden without spot or scruple, haughty, inaccessible, and audacious.
6147_34605_000005_000006 He addressed sonnets to her, which Josiana sometimes read.
6147_34605_000005_000007 In these sonnets he declared that to possess Josiana would be to rise to the stars, which did not prevent his always putting the ascent off to the following year. He waited in the antechamber outside Josiana's heart; and this suited the convenience of both.
6147_34605_000005_000008 At court all admired the good taste of this delay.
6147_34605_000005_000009 Lady Josiana said, "It is a bore that I should be obliged to marry Lord David; I, who would desire nothing better than to be in love with him!"
6147_34605_000006_000000 Josiana was "the flesh." Nothing could be more resplendent.
6147_34605_000006_000001 She was very tall-too tall.
6147_34605_000006_000002 Her hair was of that tinge which might be called red gold.
6147_34605_000006_000003 She was plump, fresh, strong, and rosy, with immense boldness and wit.
6147_34605_000006_000004 She had eyes which were too intelligible.
6147_34605_000006_000005 She had neither lovers nor chastity.
6147_34605_000006_000006 She walled herself round with pride.
6147_34605_000006_000007 Men! oh, fie! a god only would be worthy of her, or a monster.
6147_34605_000006_000009 She disdained intrigues; but she would not have been displeased had she been supposed to have engaged in some, provided that the objects were uncommon, and proportioned to the merits of one so highly placed.
6147_34605_000006_000010 She thought little of her reputation, but much of her glory.
6147_34605_000006_000012 Josiana felt herself majestic and material.
6147_34605_000006_000013 Hers was a cumbrous beauty.
6147_34605_000006_000014 She usurped rather than charmed.
6147_34605_000006_000015 She trod upon hearts. She was earthly.
6147_34605_000006_000017 She discoursed on Locke; she was polite; she was suspected of knowing Arabic.
6147_34605_000007_000000 To be "the flesh" and to be woman are two different things.
6147_34605_000007_000001 Where a woman is vulnerable, on the side of pity, for instance, which so readily turns to love, Josiana was not.
6147_34605_000007_000002 Not that she was unfeeling.
6147_34605_000007_000003 The ancient comparison of flesh to marble is absolutely false.
6147_34605_000007_000004 The beauty of flesh consists in not being marble: its beauty is to palpitate, to tremble, to blush, to bleed, to have firmness without hardness, to be white without being cold, to have its sensations and its infirmities; its beauty is to be life, and marble is death.
6147_34605_000008_000000 Flesh, when it attains a certain degree of beauty, has almost a claim to the right of nudity; it conceals itself in its own dazzling charms as in a veil.
6147_34605_000008_000001 He who might have looked upon Josiana nude would have perceived her outlines only through a surrounding glory.
6147_34605_000008_000003 She had the self possession of a goddess.
6147_34605_000008_000004 To have made her nudity a torment, ever eluding a pursuing Tantalus, would have been an amusement to her.
6147_34605_000009_000001 In admiring her you felt yourself becoming a pagan and a lackey.
6147_34605_000009_000002 Her origin had been bastardy and the ocean.
6147_34605_000009_000003 She appeared to have emerged from the foam.
6147_34605_000009_000004 From the stream had risen the first jet of her destiny; but the spring was royal.
6147_34605_000009_000006 She was well read and accomplished.
6147_34605_000009_000007 Never had a passion approached her, yet she had sounded them all.
6147_34605_000009_000012 She was, in the insolence of high birth, tempting and inaccessible.
6147_34605_000009_000013 Nevertheless, she might find it amusing to plan a fall for herself.
6147_34605_000009_000014 She dwelt in a halo of glory, half wishing to descend from it, and perhaps feeling curious to know what a fall was like.
6147_34605_000009_000015 She was a little too heavy for her cloud.
6147_34605_000009_000016 To err is a diversion.
6147_34605_000009_000017 Princely unconstraint has the privilege of experiment, and what is frailty in a plebeian is only frolic in a duchess.
6147_34605_000009_000018 Josiana was in everything-in birth, in beauty, in irony, in brilliancy-almost a queen.
6147_34605_000009_000020 She regretted that Hercules was dead. She lived in some undefined expectation of a voluptuous and supreme ideal.
6147_34605_000010_000000 Morally, Josiana brought to one's mind the line-
6147_34605_000012_000000 Hers was a noble neck, a splendid bosom, heaving harmoniously over a royal heart, a glance full of life and light, a countenance pure and haughty, and who knows?
6147_34605_000012_000001 below the surface was there not, in a semi transparent and misty depth, an undulating, supernatural prolongation, perchance deformed and dragon like-a proud virtue ending in vice in the depth of dreams.
6147_34605_000014_000000 With all that she was a prude.
6147_34605_000015_000000 It was the fashion.
6147_34605_000017_000001 Elizabeth was more than English-she was Anglican.
6147_34605_000017_000002 Hence the deep respect of the Episcopalian Church for that queen-respect resented by the Church of Rome, which counterbalanced it with a dash of excommunication.
6147_34605_000017_000003 In the mouth of Sixtus the fifth, when anathematizing Elizabeth, malediction turned to madrigal.
6147_34605_000017_000005 Mary Stuart, less concerned with the church and more with the woman part of the question, had little respect for her sister Elizabeth, and wrote to her as queen to queen and coquette to prude: "Your disinclination to marriage arises from your not wishing to lose the liberty of being made love to." Mary Stuart played with the fan, Elizabeth with the axe.
6147_34605_000017_000006 An uneven match.
6147_34605_000017_000007 They were rivals, besides, in literature.
6147_34605_000017_000008 Mary Stuart composed French verses; Elizabeth translated Horace.
6147_34605_000018_000001 That which is biblical may well be Anglican.
6147_34605_000018_000002 Biblical precedent goes so far as to speak of a child who was called Ebnehaquem or Melilechet-that is to say, the Wise Man's son.
6147_34605_000019_000000 Why object to such manners?
6147_34605_000020_000000 Nowadays England, whose Loyola is named Wesley, casts down her eyes a little at the remembrance of that past age.
6147_34605_000020_000001 She is vexed at the memory, yet proud of it.
6147_34605_000021_000000 These fine ladies, moreover, knew Latin.
6147_34605_000021_000002 Lady Jane Grey had carried fashion to the point of knowing Hebrew.
6147_34605_000021_000003 The Duchess Josiana Latinized. Then (another fine thing) she was secretly a Catholic; after the manner of her uncle, Charles the second., rather than her father, james the second.
6147_34605_000021_000005 Thus it was that while a Catholic amongst her intimate friends and the refined of both sexes, she was outwardly a Protestant for the benefit of the riffraff.
6147_34605_000022_000000 This is the pleasant view to take of religion.
6147_34605_000022_000001 You enjoy all the good things belonging to the official Episcopalian church, and later on you die, like Grotius, in the odour of Catholicity, having the glory of a mass being said for you by le Pere Petau.
6147_34605_000023_000000 Although plump and healthy, Josiana was, we repeat, a perfect prude.
6147_34605_000024_000000 At times her sleepy and voluptuous way of dragging out the end of her phrases was like the creeping of a tiger's paws in the jungle.
6147_34605_000025_000000 The advantage of prudes is that they disorganize the human race.
6147_34605_000025_000001 They deprive it of the honour of their adherence.
6147_34605_000025_000002 Beyond all, keep the human species at a distance.
6147_34605_000025_000003 This is a point of the greatest importance.
6147_34605_000026_000001 A pretension to divinity not admitted creates affectation.
6147_34605_000026_000002 In default of thunderclaps there is impertinence.
6147_34605_000026_000003 The temple shrivels into the boudoir.
6147_34605_000026_000004 Not having the power to be a goddess, she is an idol.
6147_34605_000027_000002 Their kinship is visible in the fop.
6147_34605_000027_000003 The subtile is derived from the sensual.
6147_34605_000027_000004 Gluttony affects delicacy, a grimace of disgust conceals cupidity.
6147_34605_000027_000005 And then woman feels her weak point guarded by all that casuistry of gallantry which takes the place of scruples in prudes.
6147_34605_000027_000006 It is a line of circumvallation with a ditch.
6147_34605_000027_000007 Every prude puts on an air of repugnance.
6147_34605_000027_000008 It is a protection.
6147_34605_000027_000009 She will consent, but she disdains-for the present.
6147_34605_000028_000001 She felt such a leaning towards immodesty that she was a prude.
6147_34605_000028_000002 The recoils of pride in the direction opposed to our vices lead us to those of a contrary nature.
6147_34605_000028_000003 It was the excessive effort to be chaste which made her a prude.
6147_34605_000028_000004 To be too much on the defensive points to a secret desire for attack; the shy woman is not strait laced.
6147_34605_000028_000005 She shut herself up in the arrogance of the exceptional circumstances of her rank, meditating, perhaps, all the while, some sudden lapse from it.
6147_34605_000029_000000 It was the dawn of the eighteenth century.
6147_34605_000029_000001 England was a sketch of what France was during the regency.
6147_34605_000029_000002 Walpole and Dubois are not unlike. Marlborough was fighting against his former king, james the second., to whom it was said he had sold his sister, Miss Churchill.
6147_34605_000029_000003 Bolingbroke was in his meridian, and Richelieu in his dawn.
6147_34605_000029_000004 Gallantry found its convenience in a certain medley of ranks.
6147_34605_000029_000005 Men were equalized by the same vices as they were later on, perhaps, by the same ideas.
6147_34605_000029_000006 Degradation of rank, an aristocratic prelude, began what the revolution was to complete.
6147_34605_000029_000007 It was not very far off the time when Jelyotte was seen publicly sitting, in broad daylight, on the bed of the Marquise d'Epinay.
6147_34605_000029_000008 It is true (for manners re echo each other) that in the sixteenth century Smeton's nightcap had been found under Anne Boleyn's pillow.
6147_34605_000030_000001 Never, covering her frailty by her charms, and her weakness by her omnipotence, has she claimed absolution more imperiously.
6147_34605_000030_000002 In making the forbidden the permitted fruit, Eve fell; in making the permitted the forbidden fruit, she triumphs.
6147_34605_000030_000003 That is the climax.
6147_34605_000030_000004 In the eighteenth century the wife bolts out her husband.
6147_34605_000030_000005 She shuts herself up in Eden with Satan.
6147_34605_000030_000006 Adam is left outside.
6147_34605_000031_000000 three.
6147_34605_000032_000000 All Josiana's instincts impelled her to yield herself gallantly rather than to give herself legally.
6147_34605_000032_000001 To surrender on the score of gallantry implies learning, recalls Menalcas and Amaryllis, and is almost a literary act.
6147_34605_000033_000000 The maiden a sovereign, the wife a subject, such was the old English notion.
6147_34605_000033_000001 Josiana was deferring the hour of this subjection as long as she could.
6147_34605_000033_000002 She must eventually marry Lord David, since such was the royal pleasure.
6147_34605_000033_000003 It was a necessity, doubtless; but what a pity!
6147_34605_000033_000004 Josiana appreciated Lord David, and showed him off.
6147_34605_000033_000005 There was between them a tacit agreement neither to conclude nor to break off the engagement. They eluded each other.
6147_34605_000034_000000 It is unbecoming to be married-fades one's ribbons and makes one look old.
6147_34605_000034_000001 An espousal is a dreary absorption of brilliancy.
6147_34605_000034_000002 A woman handed over to you by a notary, how commonplace!
6147_34605_000035_000000 To make Love prosaically decent, how gross! to deprive it of all impropriety, how dull!
6147_34605_000036_000000 Lord David was ripening.
6147_34605_000036_000001 Forty; 'tis a marked period.
6147_34605_000036_000002 He did not perceive this, and in truth he looked no more than thirty.
6147_34605_000036_000004 He possessed others.
6147_34605_000036_000005 He had mistresses.
6147_34605_000036_000006 On the other hand, Josiana had dreams.
6147_34605_000037_000000 The Duchess Josiana had a peculiarity, less rare than it is supposed. One of her eyes was blue and the other black.
6147_34605_000037_000001 Her pupils were made for love and hate, for happiness and misery.
6147_34605_000037_000002 Night and day were mingled in her look.
6147_34605_000038_000000 Her ambition was this-to show herself capable of impossibilities.
6147_34605_000038_000001 One day she said to Swift, "You people fancy that you know what scorn is." "You people" meant the human race.
6147_34605_000039_000000 She was a skin deep Papist.
6147_34605_000039_000002 She would have been a Puseyite in the present day.
6147_34605_000039_000004 She was extravagant in gold lace.
6147_34605_000039_000005 Sometimes she wore an embroidered cloth jacket like a bachelor.
6147_34605_000039_000006 She rode on a man's saddle, notwithstanding the invention of side saddles, introduced into England in the fourteenth century by Anne, wife of Richard the second.
6147_34605_000039_000007 She washed her face, arms, shoulders, and neck, in sugar candy, diluted in white of egg, after the fashion of Castile.
6147_34606_000004_000004 The reaction against the wig was beginning.
6147_34606_000004_000013 He held his ground.
6147_34606_000004_000017 The first, intoxicated by the novelty, may ignore the danger; the second sees the abyss, and rushes into it.
6147_34606_000004_000018 Lord David flung himself into the abyss of no longer wearing a wig.
6147_34606_000006_000000 Lord David, then, did not wear a wig, and did wear cowhide boots.
6147_34606_000006_000001 Such great things made him a mark for public admiration.
6147_34606_000007_000008 All, moreover, had their coats turned the wrong way, for luck.
6147_34606_000007_000009 Lord David was a member of the Beefsteak Club, the Surly Club, and of the Splitfarthing Club, of the Cross Club, the Scratchpenny Club, of the Sealed Knot, a Royalist Club, and of the Martinus Scribblerus, founded by Swift, to take the place of the Rota, founded by Milton.
6147_34606_000008_000000 Though handsome, he belonged to the Ugly Club.
6147_34606_000008_000001 This club was dedicated to deformity.
6147_34606_000008_000002 The members agreed to fight, not about a beautiful woman, but about an ugly man.
6147_34606_000008_000004 This club was still in existence in the beginning of the nineteenth century, and Mirabeau was elected an honorary member.
6147_34606_000009_000000 Since the restoration of Charles the second. revolutionary clubs had been abolished.
6147_34606_000009_000002 To the republican clubs had succeeded monarchical clubs.
6147_34606_000010_000000 There was the Hell fire Club, where they played at being impious.
6147_34606_000010_000001 It was a joust of sacrilege.
6147_34606_000011_000000 There was the Butting Club, so called from its members butting folks with their heads.
6147_34606_000011_000001 They found some street porter with a wide chest and a stupid countenance.
6147_34606_000011_000002 They offered him, and compelled him, if necessary, to accept a pot of porter, in return for which he was to allow them to butt him with their heads four times in the chest, and on this they betted.
6147_34606_000011_000003 One day a man, a great brute of a Welshman named Gogangerdd, expired at the third butt.
6147_34606_000011_000004 This looked serious.
6147_34606_000012_000000 There was the Fun Club.
6147_34606_000012_000002 Fun is to farce what pepper is to salt.
6147_34606_000012_000004 It was fun to cut a square hole in the Holbein at Hampton Court.
6147_34606_000012_000005 Fun would have been proud to have broken the arm of the Venus of Milo.
6147_34606_000012_000006 Under james the second. a young millionaire lord who had during the night set fire to a thatched cottage-a feat which made all London burst with laughter-was proclaimed the King of Fun.
6147_34606_000012_000007 The poor devils in the cottage were saved in their night clothes.
6147_34606_000012_000009 It was the rich who acted thus towards the poor.
6147_34606_000012_000010 For this reason no complaint was possible.
6147_34606_000012_000012 Those manners have not altogether disappeared.
6147_34606_000012_000013 In many places in England and in English possessions-at Guernsey, for instance-your house is now and then somewhat damaged during the night, or a fence is broken, or the knocker twisted off your door.
6147_34606_000012_000014 If it were poor people who did these things, they would be sent to jail; but they are done by pleasant young gentlemen.
6147_34606_000013_000000 The most fashionable of the clubs was presided over by an emperor, who wore a crescent on his forehead, and was called the Grand Mohawk.
6147_34606_000013_000001 The Mohawk surpassed the Fun.
6147_34606_000013_000002 Do evil for evil's sake was the programme.
6147_34606_000013_000003 The Mohawk Club had one great object-to injure.
6147_34606_000013_000004 To fulfil this duty all means were held good.
6147_34606_000013_000005 In becoming a Mohawk the members took an oath to be hurtful.
6147_34606_000013_000007 Every member of the Mohawk Club was bound to possess an accomplishment.
6147_34606_000013_000008 One was "a dancing master;" that is to say he made the rustics frisk about by pricking the calves of their legs with the point of his sword.
6147_34606_000013_000010 The gentleman behind him chastised him for this by a prick of his sword, which made him spring round; another prick in the back warned the fellow that one of noble blood was behind him, and so on, each one wounding him in his turn.
6147_34606_000013_000011 When the man, closed round by the circle of swords and covered with blood, had turned and danced about enough, they ordered their servants to beat him with sticks, to change the course of his ideas.
6147_34606_000014_000000 Such were, towards the beginning of the eighteenth century, the pastimes of the rich idlers of London.
6147_34606_000014_000001 The idlers of Paris had theirs.
6147_34606_000015_000000 Lord David Dirry Moir brought into all these institutions his magnificent and liberal spirit.
6147_34606_000015_000001 Just like any one else, he would gaily set fire to a cot of woodwork and thatch, and just scorch those within; but he would rebuild their houses in stone.
6147_34606_000015_000002 He insulted two ladies.
6147_34606_000015_000003 One was unmarried-he gave her a portion; the other was married-he had her husband appointed chaplain.
6147_34606_000016_000000 Cockfighting owed him some praiseworthy improvements.
6147_34606_000016_000001 It was marvellous to see Lord David dress a cock for the pit.
6147_34606_000016_000002 Cocks lay hold of each other by the feathers, as men by the hair.
6147_34606_000016_000003 Lord David, therefore, made his cock as bald as possible.
6147_34606_000016_000004 With a pair of scissors he cut off all the feathers from the tail and from the head to the shoulders, and all those on the neck.
6147_34606_000016_000005 So much less for the enemy's beak, he used to say.
6147_34606_000016_000007 So much for the enemy's eyes, he would say.
6147_34606_000017_000000 Lord David attended prize fights, and was their living law.
6147_34606_000017_000001 On occasions of great performances it was he who had the stakes driven in and ropes stretched, and who fixed the number of feet for the ring.
6147_34606_000017_000004 All this science, however, did not render him a pedant, nor destroy his ease of manner in society.
6147_34606_000018_000001 Lord David was one of the few referees whom they dared not thrash.
6147_34606_000019_000000 No one could train like him.
6147_34606_000019_000001 The pugilist whose trainer he consented to become was sure to win.
6147_34606_000019_000002 Lord David would choose a Hercules-massive as a rock, tall as a tower-and make him his child.
6147_34606_000019_000004 In this he excelled.
6147_34606_000019_000005 Having once adopted the Cyclops, he never left him.
6147_34606_000019_000007 It was he who invented the athlete's admirable rules, afterwards reproduced by Morley.
6147_34606_000019_000009 In the street he never allowed him to leave his sight, keeping him out of every danger-runaway horses, the wheels of carriages, drunken soldiers, pretty girls.
6147_34606_000019_000010 He watched over his virtue.
6147_34606_000019_000011 This maternal solicitude continually brought some new perfection into the pupil's education.
6147_34606_000019_000012 He taught him the blow with the fist which breaks the teeth, and the twist of the thumb which gouges out the eye.
6147_34606_000019_000013 What could be more touching?
6147_34606_000020_000000 Thus he was preparing himself for public life to which he was to be called later on.
6147_34606_000021_000000 Lord David Dirry Moir was passionately fond of open air exhibitions, of shows, of circuses with wild beasts, of the caravans of mountebanks, of clowns, tumblers, merrymen, open air farces, and the wonders of a fair. The true noble is he who smacks of the people.
6147_34606_000021_000004 They called him Tom Jim Jack.
6147_34606_000021_000005 Under this name he was famous and very popular amongst the dregs of the people.
6147_34606_000021_000006 He played the blackguard in a masterly style: when necessary, he used his fists.
6147_34607_000000_000000 CHAPTER five
6147_34607_000001_000000 QUEEN ANNE.
6147_34607_000003_000000 Above this couple there was Anne, Queen of England.
6147_34607_000003_000001 An ordinary woman was Queen Anne.
6147_34607_000003_000002 She was gay, kindly, august-to a certain extent.
6147_34607_000003_000003 No quality of hers attained to virtue, none to vice.
6147_34607_000003_000004 Her stoutness was bloated, her fun heavy, her good nature stupid.
6147_34607_000003_000005 She was stubborn and weak.
6147_34607_000003_000006 As a wife she was faithless and faithful, having favourites to whom she gave up her heart, and a husband for whom she kept her bed.
6147_34607_000003_000007 As a Christian she was a heretic and a bigot.
6147_34607_000003_000008 She had one beauty-the well-developed neck of a Niobe.
6147_34607_000003_000009 The rest of her person was indifferently formed.
6147_34607_000003_000010 She was a clumsy coquette and a chaste one.
6147_34607_000003_000011 Her skin was white and fine; she displayed a great deal of it.
6147_34607_000003_000013 She had a narrow forehead, sensual lips, fleshy cheeks, large eyes, short sight.
6147_34607_000003_000014 Her short sight extended to her mind.
6147_34607_000003_000015 Beyond a burst of merriment now and then, almost as ponderous as her anger, she lived in a sort of taciturn grumble and a grumbling silence.
6147_34607_000003_000016 Words escaped from her which had to be guessed at.
6147_34607_000003_000018 She liked surprises, which is extremely woman like. Anne was a pattern-just sketched roughly-of the universal Eve.
6147_34607_000003_000019 To that sketch had fallen that chance, the throne.
6147_34607_000003_000020 She drank.
6147_34607_000003_000021 Her husband was a Dane, thoroughbred.
6147_34607_000003_000022 A Tory, she governed by the Whigs-like a woman, like a mad woman.
6147_34607_000003_000023 She had fits of rage.
6147_34607_000003_000024 She was violent, a brawler. Nobody more awkward than Anne in directing affairs of state.
6147_34607_000003_000025 She allowed events to fall about as they might chance.
6147_34607_000003_000026 Her whole policy was cracked.
6147_34607_000003_000027 She excelled in bringing about great catastrophes from little causes.
6147_34607_000003_000028 When a whim of authority took hold of her, she called it giving a stir with the poker.
6147_34607_000003_000030 There was something of the Sphinx in this goose.
6147_34607_000004_000000 She rather liked fun, teasing, and practical jokes.
6147_34607_000004_000001 Could she have made Apollo a hunchback, it would have delighted her.
6147_34607_000004_000002 But she would have left him a god.
6147_34607_000004_000003 good-natured, her ideal was to allow none to despair, and to worry all.
6147_34607_000004_000004 She had often a rough word in her mouth; a little more, and she would have sworn like Elizabeth.
6147_34607_000004_000005 From time to time she would take from a man's pocket, which she wore in her skirt, a little round box, of chased silver, on which was her portrait, in profile, between the two letters q a; she would open this box, and take from it, on her finger, a little pomade, with which she reddened her lips, and, having coloured her mouth, would laugh.
6147_34607_000004_000006 She was greedily fond of the flat Zealand gingerbread cakes.
6147_34607_000004_000007 She was proud of being fat.
6147_34607_000005_000000 More of a Puritan than anything else, she would, nevertheless, have liked to devote herself to stage plays.
6147_34607_000005_000001 She had an absurd academy of music, copied after that of France.
6147_34607_000005_000003 This Forteroche passed into England, and proposed to Queen Anne, who was immediately charmed by the idea, to build in London a theatre with machinery, with a fourth under stage finer than that of the King of France.
6147_34607_000005_000004 Like Louis the fourteenth., she liked to be driven at a gallop.
6147_34607_000007_000000 In Anne's time no meeting was allowed without the permission of two justices of the peace.
6147_34607_000007_000001 The assembly of twelve persons, were it only to eat oysters and drink porter, was a felony.
6147_34607_000007_000002 Under her reign, otherwise relatively mild, pressing for the fleet was carried on with extreme violence-a gloomy evidence that the Englishman is a subject rather than a citizen.
6147_34607_000007_000003 For centuries England suffered under that process of tyranny which gave the lie to all the old charters of freedom, and out of which France especially gathered a cause of triumph and indignation.
6147_34607_000008_000000 The laws against Ireland, emanating from Queen Anne, were atrocious. Anne was born in sixteen sixty four, two years before the great fire of London, on which the astrologers (there were some left, and Louis the fourteenth. was born with the assistance of an astrologer, and swaddled in a horoscope) predicted that, being the elder sister of fire, she would be queen.
6147_34607_000008_000002 She had the humiliation of having only Gilbert, Archbishop of Canterbury, for godfather.
6147_34607_000008_000003 To be godchild of the Pope was no longer possible in England. A mere primate is but a poor sort of godfather.
6147_34607_000008_000006 Why was she a Protestant?
6147_34607_000009_000002 The English under that royalty born of a revolution possessed as much liberty as they could lay hands on between the Tower of London, into which they put orators, and the pillory, into which they put writers. Anne spoke a little Danish in her private chats with her husband, and a little French in her private chats with Bolingbroke.
6147_34607_000009_000003 Wretched gibberish; but the height of English fashion, especially at court, was to talk French.
6147_34607_000009_000006 Six farthings were struck during her reign.
6147_34607_000009_000008 Her father, james the second., was candid and cruel; she was brutal.
6147_34607_000010_000000 At the same time she was mild at bottom.
6147_34607_000010_000001 A contradiction which only appears such.
6147_34607_000010_000003 Heat sugar and it will boil.
6147_34607_000011_000001 England liked feminine rulers.
6147_34607_000011_000002 Why?
6147_34607_000011_000003 France excludes them.
6147_34607_000011_000004 There is a reason at once.
6147_34607_000011_000005 Perhaps there is no other.
6147_34607_000011_000007 As they will. Be it so.
6147_34607_000011_000008 But there is nothing delicate in the reigns of these women. The lines are heavy.
6147_34607_000011_000009 It is gross grandeur and gross good nature.
6147_34607_000011_000010 As to their immaculate virtue, England is tenacious of it, and we are not going to oppose the idea.
6147_34607_000011_000011 Elizabeth was a virgin tempered by Essex; Anne, a wife complicated by Bolingbroke.
6147_34607_000012_000000 three.
6147_34607_000013_000000 One idiotic habit of the people is to attribute to the king what they do themselves.
6147_34607_000013_000001 They fight.
6147_34607_000013_000002 Whose the glory?
6147_34607_000013_000003 The king's.
6147_34607_000013_000004 They pay.
6147_34607_000013_000006 The king's.
6147_34607_000013_000007 Then the people love him for being so rich.
6147_34607_000013_000008 The king receives a crown from the poor, and returns them a farthing.
6147_34607_000013_000011 How great is this myrmidon! he is on my back. A dwarf has an excellent way of being taller than a giant: it is to perch himself on his shoulders.
6147_34607_000013_000012 But that the giant should allow it, there is the wonder; and that he should admire the height of the dwarf, there is the folly.
6147_34607_000013_000013 Simplicity of mankind!
6147_34607_000013_000014 The equestrian statue, reserved for kings alone, is an excellent figure of royalty: the horse is the people.
6147_34607_000013_000015 Only that the horse becomes transfigured by degrees.
6147_34607_000013_000016 It begins in an ass; it ends in a lion.
6147_34607_000013_000017 Then it throws its rider, and you have sixteen forty two in England and seventeen eighty nine in France; and sometimes it devours him, and you have in England sixteen forty nine, and in France seventeen ninety three.
6147_34607_000013_000018 That the lion should relapse into the donkey is astonishing; but it is so.
6147_34607_000013_000020 It had resumed the pack saddle, idolatry of the crown.
6147_34607_000013_000021 Queen Anne, as we have just observed, was popular.
6147_34607_000013_000022 What was she doing to be so?
6147_34607_000013_000023 Nothing.
6147_34607_000013_000024 Nothing!--that is all that is asked of the sovereign of England.
6147_34607_000013_000028 Parliament having voted a patriotic loan of thirty four million francs of annuities, there had been a crush at the Exchequer to subscribe it.
6147_34607_000013_000029 England was sending a squadron to the East Indies, and a squadron to the West of Spain under Admiral Leake, without mentioning the reserve of four hundred sail, under Admiral Sir Cloudesley Shovel.
6147_34607_000013_000031 It was the interval between Hochstadt and Ramillies, and the first of these victories was foretelling the second.
6147_34607_000013_000033 She was bringing into her ports in triumph ten Spanish line of battle ships, and many a galleon laden with gold.
6147_34607_000013_000035 It was felt that he was about to give up his hold over Acadia, saint Christopher, and Newfoundland, and that he would be but too happy if England would only tolerate the King of France fishing for cod at Cape Breton.
6147_34607_000013_000036 England was about to impose upon him the shame of demolishing himself the fortifications of Dunkirk.
6147_34607_000013_000037 Meanwhile, she had taken Gibraltar, and was taking Barcelona.
6147_34607_000013_000038 What great things accomplished!
6147_34607_000013_000039 How was it possible to refuse Anne admiration for taking the trouble of living at the period?
6147_34607_000014_000000 From a certain point of view, the reign of Anne appears a reflection of the reign of Louis the fourteenth.
6147_34607_000014_000002 Like him, she plays at a great reign; she has her monuments, her arts, her victories, her captains, her men of letters, her privy purse to pension celebrities, her gallery of chefs d'oeuvre, side by side with those of his Majesty.
6147_34607_000014_000003 Her court, too, was a cortege, with the features of a triumph, an order and a march.
6147_34607_000014_000004 It was a miniature copy of all the great men of Versailles, not giants themselves.
6147_34607_000014_000005 In it there is enough to deceive the eye; add God save the Queen, which might have been taken from Lulli, and the ensemble becomes an illusion.
6147_34607_000014_000006 Not a personage is missing.
6147_34607_000014_000009 The whole is solemn and pompous, and the Windsor of the time has a faded resemblance to Marly.
6147_34607_000014_000010 Still the whole was effeminate, and Anne's Pere Tellier was called Sarah Jennings.
6147_34607_000014_000012 Although the England of the period quarrels and fights France, she imitates her and draws enlightenment from her; and the light on the facade of England is French light.
6147_34607_000015_000000 A detail to be noted.
6147_34607_000015_000002 "He is the kind of king they want in France," said the English.
6147_34607_000015_000004 That favourable regard of the chains which bind their neighbours sometimes attains to enthusiasm for the despot next door.
6147_34607_000018_000000 Queen Anne bore a little grudge to the Duchess Josiana, for two reasons. Firstly, because she thought the Duchess Josiana handsome.
6147_34607_000018_000001 Secondly, because she thought the Duchess Josiana's betrothed handsome.
6147_34607_000018_000003 One is sufficient for a queen.
6147_34607_000018_000004 Let us add that she bore her a grudge for being her sister.
6147_34607_000018_000005 Anne did not like women to be pretty.
6147_34607_000018_000006 She considered it against good morals. As for herself, she was ugly.
6147_34607_000018_000007 Not from choice, however.
6147_34607_000018_000008 A part of her religion she derived from that ugliness.
6147_34607_000018_000010 To an ugly queen, a pretty duchess is not an agreeable sister.
6147_34607_000019_000000 There was another grievance, Josiana's "improper" birth.
6147_34607_000019_000004 It was an unpleasant resemblance. Josiana had a right to say to Anne, "My mother was at least as good as yours." At court no one said so, but they evidently thought it.
6147_34607_000019_000006 Why this Josiana?
6147_34607_000019_000007 What had put it into her head to be born?
6147_34607_000019_000008 What good was a Josiana?
6147_34607_000019_000009 Certain relationships are detrimental.
6181_216552_000002_000000 Pothier seems to think that property, like royalty, exists by divine right.
6181_216552_000002_000002 He begins in this way:--
6181_216552_000003_000001 For the human race he has created the earth and all its creatures, and has given it a control over them subordinate only to his own.
6181_216552_000004_000000 After this magnificent introduction, who would refuse to believe the human race to be an immense family living in brotherly union, and under the protection of a venerable father?
6181_216552_000004_000002 Are fathers unnatural, and children prodigal?
6181_216552_000005_000001 HE HAS PUT ALL THINGS UNDER MY FEET,--and I have not where to lay my head! MULTIPLY, he tells us through his interpreter, Pothier.
6181_216552_000006_000000 "The human race having multiplied, men divided among themselves the earth and most of the things upon it; that which fell to each, from that time exclusively belonged to him.
6181_216552_000007_000001 Men lived in a state of communism; whether positive or negative it matters little.
6181_216552_000007_000002 Then there was no property, not even private possession.
6181_216552_000007_000003 The genesis and growth of possession gradually forcing people to labor for their support, they agreed either formally or tacitly,--it makes no difference which,--that the laborer should be sole proprietor of the fruit of his labor; that is, they simply declared the fact that thereafter none could live without working.
6181_216552_000007_000004 It necessarily followed that, to obtain equality of products, there must be equality of labor; and that, to obtain equality of labor, there must be equality of facilities for labor.
6181_216552_000007_000005 Whoever without labor got possession, by force or by strategy, of another's means of subsistence, destroyed equality, and placed himself above or outside of the law.
6181_216552_000007_000006 Whoever monopolized the means of production on the ground of greater industry, also destroyed equality.
6181_216552_000008_000001 But in what thing?
6181_216552_000008_000002 Evidently IN THE PRODUCT, not IN THE SOIL. So the Arabs have always understood it; and so, according to Caesar and Tacitus, the Germans formerly held.
6181_216552_000009_000003 The original cultivators of the land, who were also the original makers of the law, were not as learned as our legislators, I admit; and had they been, they could not have done worse: they did not foresee the consequences of the transformation of the right of private possession into the right of absolute property.
6181_216552_000010_000000 Let me call the attention of the writers on jurisprudence to their own maxims.
6181_216552_000011_000002 The field which I have cleared, which I cultivate, on which I have built my house, which supports myself, my family, and my livestock, I can possess: first.
6181_216552_000011_000005 By virtue of the social contract which assigns it to me as my share.
6181_216552_000012_000000 But none of these titles confer upon me the right of property.
6181_216552_000012_000001 For, if I attempt to base it upon occupancy, society can reply, "I am the original occupant." If I appeal to my labor, it will say, "It is only on that condition that you possess." If I speak of agreements, it will respond, "These agreements establish only your right of use." Such, however, are the only titles which proprietors advance.
6181_216552_000012_000004 Why, then, has society recognized a right injurious to itself, where there is no producing cause?
6181_216552_000012_000005 Why, in according possession, has it also conceded property?
6181_216552_000012_000006 Why has the law sanctioned this abuse of power?
6181_216552_000013_000000 The German Ancillon replies thus:--
6181_216552_000014_000000 "Some philosophers pretend that man, in employing his forces upon a natural object,--say a field or a tree,--acquires a right only to the improvements which he makes, to the form which he gives to the object, not to the object itself.
6181_216552_000014_000001 Useless distinction!
6181_216552_000014_000002 If the form could be separated from the object, perhaps there would be room for question; but as this is almost always impossible, the application of man's strength to the different parts of the visible world is the foundation of the right of property, the primary origin of riches."
6181_216552_000015_000000 Vain pretext!
6181_216552_000015_000001 If the form cannot be separated from the object, nor property from possession, possession must be shared; in any case, society reserves the right to fix the conditions of property.
6181_216552_000015_000003 This payment is not rent, it is an indemnity.
6181_216552_000016_000000 What sort of justice is it, then, which makes such laws as this:--
6181_216552_000017_000000 "Whereas, since labor so changes the form of a thing that the form and substance cannot be separated without destroying the thing itself, either society must be disinherited, or the laborer must lose the fruit of his labor; and
6181_216552_000019_000000 "Therefore, the right of appropriation by labor shall never be admitted against individuals, but only against society."
6181_216552_000021_000000 The law is intended to protect men's mutual rights,--that is, the rights of each against each, and each against all; and, as if a proportion could exist with less than four terms, the law makers always disregard the latter.
6181_216552_000021_000001 As long as man is opposed to man, property offsets property, and the two forces balance each other; as soon as man is isolated, that is, opposed to the society which he himself represents, jurisprudence is at fault: Themis has lost one scale of her balance.
6181_216552_000023_000000 "How could this claim, made valid by occupation, become stable and permanent property, which might continue to stand, and which might be reclaimed after the first occupant had relinquished possession?
6181_216552_000024_000000 "Agriculture was a natural consequence of the multiplication of the human race, and agriculture, in its turn, favors population, and necessitates the establishment of permanent property; for who would take the trouble to plough and sow, if he were not certain that he would reap?"
6181_216552_000025_000000 To satisfy the husbandman, it was sufficient to guarantee him possession of his crop; admit even that he should have been protected in his right of occupation of land, as long as he remained its cultivator.
6181_216552_000025_000001 That was all that he had a right to expect; that was all that the advance of civilization demanded.
6181_216552_000025_000003 who pretended to have it?
6181_216552_000026_000000 "Agriculture alone was not sufficient to establish permanent property; positive laws were needed, and magistrates to execute them; in a word, the civil State was needed.
6181_216552_000027_000000 "The multiplication of the human race had rendered agriculture necessary; the need of securing to the cultivator the fruit of his labor made permanent property necessary, and also laws for its protection.
6181_216552_000027_000001 So we are indebted to property for the creation of the civil State."
6181_216552_000028_000000 Yes, of our civil State, as you have made it; a State which, at first, was despotism, then monarchy, then aristocracy, today democracy, and always tyranny.
6181_216552_000029_000000 "Without the ties of property it never would have been possible to subordinate men to the wholesome yoke of the law; and without permanent property the earth would have remained a vast forest.
6181_216552_000030_000001 In this we see what a wonderful change has been effected in property, and to what an extent Nature has been altered by the civil laws."
6181_216552_000031_000001 It has literally CREATED a right outside of its own province.
6181_216552_000032_000000 It has sanctioned selfishness; it has indorsed monstrous pretensions; it has received with favor impious vows, as if it were able to fill up a bottomless pit, and to satiate hell!
6181_216552_000032_000001 Blind law; the law of the ignorant man; a law which is not a law; the voice of discord, deceit, and blood!
6181_216552_000032_000002 This it is which, continually revived, reinstated, rejuvenated, restored, re enforced-as the palladium of society-has troubled the consciences of the people, has obscured the minds of the masters, and has induced all the catastrophes which have befallen nations.
6181_216552_000033_000000 This it is which Christianity has condemned, but which its ignorant ministers deify; who have as little desire to study Nature and man, as ability to read their Scriptures.
6181_216552_000034_000000 But, indeed, what guide did the law follow in creating the domain of property?
6181_216552_000034_000001 What principle directed it?
6181_216552_000034_000002 What was its standard?
6181_216552_000035_000000 Would you believe it?
6181_216552_000035_000001 It was equality.
6181_216552_000036_000000 Agriculture was the foundation of territorial possession, and the original cause of property.
6181_216552_000036_000003 Thus the soil came to be appropriated through need of the equality which is essential to public security and peaceable possession.
6181_216552_000036_000004 Undoubtedly the division was never geographically equal; a multitude of rights, some founded in Nature, but wrongly interpreted and still more wrongly applied, inheritance, gift, and exchange; others, like the privileges of birth and position, the illegitimate creations of ignorance and brute force,--all operated to prevent absolute equality.
6181_216552_000036_000005 But, nevertheless, the principle remained the same: equality had sanctioned possession; equality sanctioned property.
6181_216552_000038_000000 It was not right that the soldier, on returning from an expedition, should find himself dispossessed on account of the services which he had just rendered to his country; his estate ought to be restored to him.
6181_216552_000040_000000 But what is there in common between these rude outlines of instinctive organization and the true social science?
6181_216552_000040_000001 How could these men, who never had the faintest idea of statistics, valuation, or political economy, furnish us with principles of legislation?
6181_216552_000041_000001 'This definition is not exact.
6181_216552_000041_000003 Comte, who has devoted half a volume to its definition, was in the beginning only the EXPRESSION OF A WANT, and the indication of the means of supplying it; and up to this time it has been nothing else.
6181_216552_000047_000000 They did not foresee....
6181_216552_000047_000001 But why need I go farther?
6181_216552_000048_000000 The consequences are plain enough, and this is not the time to criticise the whole Code.
6181_216552_000049_000000 The history of property among the ancient nations is, then, simply a matter of research and curiosity.
6181_216552_000049_000002 Now, property is no exception to this rule: then the universal recognition of the right of property does not legitimate the right of property.
6181_216552_000049_000003 Man is mistaken as to the constitution of society, the nature of right, and the application of justice; just as he was mistaken regarding the cause of meteors and the movement of the heavenly bodies.
6181_216552_000049_000004 His old opinions cannot be taken for articles of faith.
6181_216552_000049_000005 Of what consequence is it to us that the Indian race was divided into four classes; that, on the banks of the Nile and the Ganges, blood and position formerly determined the distribution of the land; that the Greeks and romans placed property under the protection of the gods; that they accompanied with religious ceremonies the work of partitioning the land and appraising their goods?
6181_216552_000052_000000 "The right of property is the most important of human institutions."...
6181_216552_000054_000000 "The original cause of man's prosperity upon earth."
6181_216552_000055_000000 Because justice was supposed to be its principle.
6181_216552_000056_000000 "Property became the legitimate end of his ambition, the hope of his existence, the shelter of his family; in a word, the corner stone of the domestic dwelling, of communities, and of the political State."
6181_216552_000057_000000 Possession alone produced all that.
6181_216552_000058_000000 "Eternal principle,--"
6181_216552_000059_000000 Property is eternal, like every negation,--
6181_216552_000061_000000 For that reason, every institution and every law based on property will perish.
6181_216552_000062_000000 "It is a boon as precious as liberty."
6181_216552_000063_000000 For the rich proprietor.
6181_216552_000064_000000 "In fact, the cause of the cultivation of the habitable earth."
6181_216552_000065_000000 If the cultivator ceased to be a tenant, would the land be worse cared for?
6181_216552_000066_000000 "The guarantee and the morality of labor."
6181_216552_000067_000000 Under the regime of property, labor is not a condition, but a privilege.
6181_216552_000068_000000 "The application of justice."
6181_216552_000069_000000 What is justice without equality of fortunes?
6181_216552_000069_000001 A balance with false weights.
6181_216552_000071_000000 A famished stomach knows no morality,--
6181_216552_000072_000000 "All public order,--"
6181_216552_000073_000000 Certainly, the preservation of property,--
6181_216552_000075_000000 Corner stone of all which is, stumbling block of all which ought to be,--such is property.
6181_216552_000076_000000 To sum up and conclude:--
6181_216552_000077_000000 Not only does occupation lead to equality, it PREVENTS property.
6181_216552_000077_000002 Finally, that, inasmuch as possession, in right, can never remain fixed, it is impossible, in fact, that it can ever become property.
6181_216552_000078_000000 Every occupant is, then, necessarily a possessor or usufructuary,--a function which excludes proprietorship.
6181_216552_000078_000001 Now, this is the right of the usufructuary: he is responsible for the thing entrusted to him; he must use it in conformity with general utility, with a view to its preservation and development; he has no power to transform it, to diminish it, or to change its nature; he cannot so divide the usufruct that another shall perform the labor while he receives the product.
6181_216552_000079_000002 The individual passes away, society is deathless.
6181_216552_000080_000000 What a profound disgust fills my soul while discussing such simple truths!
6181_216552_000081_000000 ALL HAVE AN EQUAL RIGHT OF OCCUPANCY.
6181_216552_000083_000000 This no code has ever expressed; this no constitution can admit!
6181_216552_000084_000000 But I hear the exclamations of the partisans of another system: "Labor, labor! that is the basis of property!"
6181_216552_000085_000001 This new basis of property is worse than the first, and I shall soon have to ask your pardon for having demonstrated things clearer, and refuted pretensions more unjust, than any which we have yet considered.
6209_34599_000002_000000 CHAPTER three.
6209_34599_000003_000000 A BURDEN MAKES A ROUGH ROAD ROUGHER.
6209_34599_000004_000000 It was little more than four hours since the hooker had sailed from the creek of Portland, leaving the boy on the shore.
6209_34599_000005_000001 He was now almost naked.
6209_34599_000005_000002 The few rags which remained to him, hardened by the frost, were sharp as glass, and cut his skin.
6209_34599_000005_000003 He became colder, but the infant was warmer.
6209_34599_000005_000004 That which he lost was not thrown away, but was gained by her. He found out that the poor infant enjoyed the comfort which was to her the renewal of life.
6209_34599_000005_000005 He continued to advance.
6209_34599_000006_000001 At other times, his throat feeling as if it were on fire, he put a little snow in his mouth and sucked it; this for a moment assuaged his thirst, but changed it into fever-a relief which was an aggravation.
6209_34599_000007_000000 The storm had become shapeless from its violence.
6209_34599_000007_000001 Deluges of snow are possible.
6209_34599_000007_000002 This was one.
6209_34599_000007_000003 The paroxysm scourged the shore at the same time that it uptore the depths of ocean.
6209_34599_000007_000004 This was, perhaps, the moment when the distracted hooker was going to pieces in the battle of the breakers.
6209_34599_000008_000000 He travelled under this north wind, still towards the east, over wide surfaces of snow.
6209_34599_000008_000002 For a long time he had ceased to see the smoke.
6209_34599_000008_000003 Such indications are soon effaced in the night; besides, it was past the hour when fires are put out.
6209_34599_000008_000004 Or he had, perhaps, made a mistake, and it was possible that neither town nor village existed in the direction in which he was travelling.
6209_34599_000008_000005 Doubting, he yet persevered.
6209_34599_000009_000000 Two or three times the little infant cried.
6209_34599_000009_000001 Then he adopted in his gait a rocking movement, and the child was soothed and silenced.
6209_34599_000010_000000 The plain was unequal.
6209_34599_000010_000001 In the declivities into which it sloped the snow, driven by the wind into the dips of the ground, was so deep, in comparison with a child so small, that it almost engulfed him, and he had to struggle through it half buried.
6209_34599_000010_000002 He walked on, working away the snow with his knees.
6209_34599_000011_000001 Then he found the surface a sheet of ice.
6209_34599_000011_000002 The little girl's lukewarm breath, playing on his face, warmed it for a moment, then lingered, and froze in his hair, stiffening it into icicles.
6209_34599_000012_000000 He felt the approach of another danger.
6209_34599_000012_000001 He could not afford to fall.
6209_34599_000012_000003 He was overcome by fatigue, and the weight of the darkness would, as with the dead woman, have held him to the ground, and the ice glued him alive to the earth.
6209_34599_000013_000000 He had tripped upon the slopes of precipices, and had recovered himself; he had stumbled into holes, and had got out again.
6209_34599_000013_000001 Thenceforward the slightest fall would be death; a false step opened for him a tomb.
6209_34599_000013_000002 He must not slip.
6209_34599_000013_000003 He had not strength to rise even to his knees.
6209_34599_000013_000005 The little creature whom he carried made his progress fearfully difficult. She was not only a burden, which his weariness and exhaustion made excessive, but was also an embarrassment.
6209_34599_000014_000000 He was obliged to do without this balance.
6209_34599_000016_000000 This little infant was the drop causing the cup of distress to overflow.
6209_34599_000017_000000 He advanced, reeling at every step, as if on a spring board, and accomplishing, without spectators, miracles of equilibrium.
6209_34599_000017_000001 Let us repeat that he was, perhaps, followed on this path of pain by eyes unsleeping in the distances of the shadows-the eyes of the mother and the eyes of God.
6209_34599_000017_000002 He staggered, slipped, recovered himself, took care of the infant, and, gathering the jacket about her, he covered up her head; staggered again, advanced, slipped, then drew himself up.
6209_34599_000017_000003 The cowardly wind drove against him.
6209_34599_000017_000005 He was, to all appearance, on the plains where Bincleaves Farm was afterwards established, between what are now called Spring Gardens and the Parsonage House.
6209_34599_000017_000006 Homesteads and cottages occupy the place of waste lands.
6209_34599_000017_000007 Sometimes less than a century separates a steppe from a city.
6209_34599_000018_000000 Suddenly, a lull having occurred in the icy blast which was blinding him, he perceived, at a short distance in front of him, a cluster of gables and of chimneys shown in relief by the snow.
6209_34599_000018_000001 The reverse of a silhouette-a city painted in white on a black horizon, something like what we call nowadays a negative proof.
6209_34599_000018_000002 Roofs-dwellings-shelter!
6209_34599_000018_000003 He had arrived somewhere at last.
6209_34599_000018_000004 He felt the ineffable encouragement of hope.
6209_34599_000019_000000 He hurried his steps.
6209_34599_000020_000000 At length, then, he was near mankind.
6209_34599_000020_000001 He would soon be amidst living creatures.
6209_34599_000020_000003 There glowed within him that sudden warmth-security; that out of which he was emerging was over; thenceforward there would no longer be night, nor winter, nor tempest.
6209_34599_000020_000004 It seemed to him that he had left all evil chances behind him. The infant was no longer a burden.
6209_34599_000020_000005 He almost ran.
6209_34599_000021_000000 His eyes were fixed on the roofs.
6209_34599_000021_000004 There were the chimneys of which he had seen the smoke.
6209_34599_000022_000000 No smoke arose from them now.
6209_34599_000022_000001 He was not long before he reached the houses.
6209_34599_000022_000002 He came to the outskirts of a town-an open street.
6209_34599_000022_000003 At that period bars to streets were falling into disuse.
6209_34599_000023_000000 The street began by two houses.
6209_34599_000023_000001 In those two houses neither candle nor lamp was to be seen; nor in the whole street; nor in the whole town, so far as eye could reach.
6209_34599_000023_000003 The walls were of mud, the roof was of straw, and there was more thatch than wall.
6209_34599_000023_000005 The hovel had but one door, which was like that of a dog kennel; and a window, which was but a hole.
6209_34599_000023_000007 At the side an inhabited pig sty told that the house was also inhabited.
6209_34599_000024_000001 It was also closed.
6209_34599_000025_000000 The boy did not hesitate.
6209_34599_000025_000001 He approached the great mansion.
6209_34599_000025_000002 The double folding door of massive oak, studded with large nails, was of the kind that leads one to expect that behind it there is a stout armoury of bolts and locks.
6209_34599_000025_000003 An iron knocker was attached to it.
6209_34599_000025_000004 He raised the knocker with some difficulty, for his benumbed hands were stumps rather than hands.
6209_34599_000025_000005 He knocked once.
6209_34599_000026_000000 No answer.
6209_34599_000027_000000 He struck again, and two knocks.
6209_34599_000028_000000 No movement was heard in the house.
6209_34599_000029_000000 He knocked a third time.
6209_34599_000030_000001 He saw that they were all asleep, and did not care to get up.
6209_34599_000031_000000 Then he turned to the hovel.
6209_34599_000031_000001 He picked up a pebble from the snow, and knocked against the low door.
6209_34599_000032_000000 There was no answer.
6209_34599_000033_000000 He raised himself on tiptoe, and knocked with his pebble against the pane too softly to break the glass, but loud enough to be heard.
6209_34599_000034_000000 No voice was heard; no step moved; no candle was lighted.
6209_34600_000001_000000 CHAPTER four.
6209_34600_000002_000000 ANOTHER FORM OF DESERT.
6209_34600_000003_000000 It was Weymouth which he had just entered.
6209_34600_000003_000001 Weymouth then was not the respectable and fine Weymouth of to day.
6209_34600_000004_000000 Ancient Weymouth did not present, like the present one, an irreproachable rectangular quay, with an inn and a statue in honour of George the third.
6209_34600_000004_000001 This resulted from the fact that George the third. had not yet been born.
6209_34600_000004_000002 For the same reason they had not yet designed on the slope of the green hill towards the east, fashioned flat on the soil by cutting away the turf and leaving the bare chalk to the view, the white horse, an acre long, bearing the king upon his back, and always turning, in honour of George the third., his tail to the city.
6209_34600_000004_000003 These honours, however, were deserved.
6209_34600_000004_000004 George the third., having lost in his old age the intellect he had never possessed in his youth, was not responsible for the calamities of his reign.
6209_34600_000004_000006 Why not erect statues to him?
6209_34600_000006_000000 The traveller who entered the tavern, now replaced by the hotel, instead of paying royally his twenty five francs for a fried sole and a bottle of wine, had to suffer the humiliation of eating a pennyworth of soup made of fish-which soup, by the bye, was very good.
6209_34600_000006_000001 Wretched fare!
6209_34600_000007_000000 The deserted child, carrying the foundling, passed through the first street, then the second, then the third.
6209_34600_000007_000002 At intervals he knocked at the doors.
6209_34600_000007_000003 No one answered. Nothing makes the heart so like a stone as being warm between sheets. The noise and the shaking had at length awakened the infant.
6209_34600_000007_000004 He knew this because he felt her suck his cheek.
6209_34600_000007_000005 She did not cry, believing him her mother.
6209_34600_000008_000000 He was about to turn and wander long, perhaps, in the intersections of the Scrambridge lanes, where there were then more cultivated plots than dwellings, more thorn hedges than houses; but fortunately he struck into a passage which exists to this day near Trinity schools.
6209_34600_000008_000001 This passage led him to a water brink, where there was a roughly built quay with a parapet, and to the right he made out a bridge.
6209_34600_000009_000000 Weymouth, a hamlet, was then the suburb of Melcombe Regis, a city and port.
6209_34600_000009_000001 Now Melcombe Regis is a parish of Weymouth.
6209_34600_000009_000002 The village has absorbed the city.
6209_34600_000009_000003 It was the bridge which did the work.
6209_34600_000009_000004 Bridges are strange vehicles of suction, which inhale the population, and sometimes swell one river bank at the expense of its opposite neighbour.
6209_34600_000010_000000 The boy went to the bridge, which at that period was a covered timber structure.
6209_34600_000010_000003 His bare feet had a moment's comfort as they crossed them. Having passed over the bridge, he was in Melcombe Regis.
6209_34600_000011_000000 The bridge opened on a rather fine street called saint Thomas's Street.
6209_34600_000011_000001 He entered it.
6209_34600_000011_000002 Here and there were high carved gables and shop fronts.
6209_34600_000011_000003 He set to knocking at the doors again: he had no strength left to call or shout.
6209_34600_000012_000000 At Melcombe Regis, as at Weymouth, no one was stirring.
6209_34600_000012_000001 The doors were all carefully double locked, The windows were covered by their shutters, as the eyes by their lids.
6209_34600_000012_000002 Every precaution had been taken to avoid being roused by disagreeable surprises.
6209_34600_000012_000005 All its lethargies mingle their nightmares, its slumbers are a crowd, and from its human bodies lying prone there arises a vapour of dreams.
6209_34600_000012_000006 Sleep has gloomy associates beyond this life: the decomposed thoughts of the sleepers float above them in a mist which is both of death and of life, and combine with the possible, which has also, perhaps, the power of thought, as it floats in space.
6209_34600_000012_000007 Hence arise entanglements.
6209_34600_000012_000008 Dreams, those clouds, interpose their folds and their transparencies over that star, the mind.
6209_34600_000012_000010 Mysterious, diffused existences amalgamate themselves with life on that border of death, which sleep is. Those larvae and souls mingle in the air.
6209_34600_000012_000011 Even he who sleeps not feels a medium press upon him full of sinister life.
6209_34600_000012_000012 The surrounding chimera, in which he suspects a reality, impedes him.
6209_34600_000012_000013 The waking man, wending his way amidst the sleep phantoms of others, unconsciously pushes back passing shadows, has, or imagines that he has, a vague fear of adverse contact with the invisible, and feels at every moment the obscure pressure of a hostile encounter which immediately dissolves.
6209_34600_000012_000014 There is something of the effect of a forest in the nocturnal diffusion of dreams.
6209_34600_000013_000000 This is what is called being afraid without reason.
6209_34600_000014_000000 What a man feels a child feels still more.
6209_34600_000015_000000 The uneasiness of nocturnal fear, increased by the spectral houses, increased the weight of the sad burden under which he was struggling.
6209_34600_000017_000001 His blows, on which he was expending his last energies, were jerky and without aim; now ceasing altogether for a time, now renewed as if in irritation.
6209_34600_000018_000000 One voice answered.
6209_34600_000019_000000 That of Time.
6209_34600_000020_000000 Three o'clock tolled slowly behind him from the old belfry of saint Nicholas.
6209_34600_000022_000000 That no inhabitant should have opened a lattice may appear surprising. Nevertheless that silence is in a great measure to be explained.
6209_34600_000022_000002 People would not even open their windows for fear of inhaling the poison.
6209_34600_000023_000000 The child felt the coldness of men more terribly than the coldness of night.
6209_34600_000023_000001 The coldness of men is intentional.
6209_34600_000023_000002 He felt a tightening on his sinking heart which he had not known on the open plains.
6209_34600_000023_000004 This was the summit of misery.
6209_34600_000023_000005 The pitiless desert he had understood; the unrelenting town was too much to bear.
6209_34600_000024_000000 The hour, the strokes of which he had just counted, had been another blow.
6209_34600_000024_000001 Nothing is so freezing in certain situations as the voice of the hour.
6209_34600_000024_000002 It is a declaration of indifference.
6209_34600_000024_000003 It is Eternity saying, "What does it matter to me?"
6209_34600_000025_000001 However, the little infant leaned her head against his shoulder, and fell asleep again.
6209_34600_000026_000000 This blind confidence set him onwards again.
6209_34600_000026_000001 He whom all supports were failing felt that he was himself a basis of support.
6209_34600_000026_000002 Irresistible summons of duty!
6209_34600_000027_000001 It is probable that he did not understand them.
6209_34600_000028_000003 It was a piece of waste land not built upon-probably the spot where Chesterfield Place now stands.
6209_34600_000028_000004 The houses ended there.
6209_34600_000028_000005 He perceived the sea to the right, and scarcely anything more of the town to his left.
6209_34600_000029_000000 What was to become of him?
6209_34600_000029_000001 Here was the country again.
6209_34600_000029_000002 To the east great inclined planes of snow marked out the wide slopes of Radipole.
6209_34600_000029_000003 Should he continue this journey?
6209_34600_000029_000004 Should he advance and re-enter the solitudes? Should he return and re-enter the streets?
6209_34600_000029_000005 What was he to do between those two silences-the mute plain and the deaf city?
6209_34600_000029_000006 Which of the two refusals should he choose?
6209_34600_000030_000000 There is the anchor of mercy.
6209_34600_000031_000000 All at once he heard a menace.
6209_34601_000003_000000 CHAPTER five
6209_34601_000004_000000 MISANTHROPY PLAYS ITS PRANKS.
6209_34601_000006_000000 It was enough to drive one back: he advanced.
6209_34601_000006_000001 To those to whom silence has become dreadful a howl is comforting.
6209_34601_000007_000000 That fierce growl reassured him; that threat was a promise.
6209_34601_000007_000001 There was there a being alive and awake, though it might be a wild beast.
6209_34601_000008_000000 He turned the corner of a wall, and, behind in the vast sepulchral light made by the reflection of snow and sea, he saw a thing placed as if for shelter.
6209_34601_000008_000001 It was a cart, unless it was a hovel.
6209_34601_000008_000003 It had a roof-it was a dwelling.
6209_34601_000008_000004 From the roof arose a funnel, and out of the funnel smoke.
6209_34601_000008_000005 This smoke was red, and seemed to imply a good fire in the interior.
6209_34601_000008_000006 Behind, projecting hinges indicated a door, and in the centre of this door a square opening showed a light inside the caravan.
6209_34601_000008_000007 He approached.
6209_34601_000009_000000 Whatever had growled perceived his approach, and became furious.
6209_34601_000009_000002 He heard a sharp sound, as of a chain violently pulled to its full length, and suddenly, under the door, between the hind wheels, two rows of sharp white teeth appeared.
6209_34601_000011_000000 The mouth was silent.
6209_34601_000012_000000 The head began again,--
6209_34601_000013_000000 "Is any one there?"
6209_34601_000014_000000 The child answered,--
6209_34601_000015_000000 "Yes."
6209_34601_000016_000000 "Who?"
6209_34601_000018_000000 "You?
6209_34601_000018_000001 Who are you? whence do you come?"
6209_34601_000019_000000 "I am weary," said the child.
6209_34601_000020_000000 "What o'clock is it?"
6209_34601_000021_000000 "I am cold."
6209_34601_000023_000000 "I am hungry."
6209_34601_000024_000000 The head replied,--
6209_34601_000025_000000 "Every one cannot be as happy as a lord.
6209_34601_000025_000001 Go away."
6209_34601_000026_000000 The head was withdrawn and the window closed.
6209_34601_000027_000000 The child bowed his forehead, drew the sleeping infant closer in his arms, and collected his strength to resume his journey.
6209_34601_000027_000001 He had taken a few steps, and was hurrying away.
6209_34601_000028_000000 However, at the same time that the window closed the door had opened; a step had been let down; the voice which had spoken to the child cried out angrily from the inside of the van,--
6209_34601_000029_000000 "Well! why do you not enter?"
6209_34601_000030_000000 The child turned back.
6209_34601_000031_000000 "Come in," resumed the voice.
6209_34601_000032_000000 The child, at once repulsed and invited, remained motionless.
6209_34601_000033_000000 The voice continued,--
6209_34601_000034_000000 "You are told to come in, you young rascal."
6209_34601_000035_000000 He made up his mind, and placed one foot on the lowest step.
6209_34601_000036_000001 He drew back.
6209_34601_000036_000002 The gaping jaws appeared.
6209_34601_000038_000000 The jaws retreated, the growling ceased.
6209_34601_000039_000000 "Come up!" continued the man.
6209_34601_000040_000000 The child with difficulty climbed up the three steps.
6209_34601_000040_000001 He was impeded by the infant, so benumbed, rolled up and enveloped in the jacket that nothing could be distinguished of her, and she was but a little shapeless mass.
6209_34601_000041_000000 He passed over the three steps; and having reached the threshold, stopped.
6209_34601_000042_000000 No candle was burning in the caravan, probably from the economy of want. The hut was lighted only by a red tinge, arising from the opening at the top of the stove, in which sparkled a peat fire.
6209_34601_000042_000001 On the stove were smoking a porringer and a saucepan, containing to all appearance something to eat.
6209_34601_000042_000002 The savoury odour was perceptible.
6209_34601_000042_000003 The hut was furnished with a chest, a stool, and an unlighted lantern which hung from the ceiling.
6209_34601_000042_000004 Besides, to the partition were attached some boards on brackets and some hooks, from which hung a variety of things.
6209_34601_000042_000005 On the boards and nails were rows of glasses, coppers, an alembic, a vessel rather like those used for graining wax, which are called granulators, and a confusion of strange objects of which the child understood nothing, and which were utensils for cooking and chemistry.
6209_34601_000042_000009 Everything in the caravan was indistinct and misty.
6209_34601_000043_000000 URSUS, PHILOSOPHER.
6209_34601_000044_000000 The child, in fact, was entering the house of Homo and Ursus.
6209_34601_000044_000001 The one he had just heard growling, the other speaking.
6209_34601_000045_000000 The child having reached the threshold, perceived near the stove a man, tall, smooth, thin and old, dressed in gray, whose head, as he stood, reached the roof.
6209_34601_000045_000001 The man could not have raised himself on tiptoe.
6209_34601_000049_000000 The child placed his burden carefully on the top of the chest, for fear of awakening and terrifying it.
6209_34601_000050_000000 The man continued,--
6209_34601_000051_000003 Worthless vagabond! in the streets at this hour!
6209_34601_000051_000004 Who are you? Answer!
6209_34601_000051_000005 But no I forbid you to answer.
6209_34601_000051_000006 There!
6209_34601_000051_000007 You are cold.
6209_34601_000051_000008 Warm yourself as quick as you can," and he shoved him by the shoulders in front of the fire.
6209_34601_000052_000000 "How wet you are!
6209_34601_000052_000001 You're frozen through!
6209_34601_000052_000002 A nice state to come into a house!
6209_34601_000052_000003 Come, take off those rags, you villain!" and as with one hand, and with feverish haste, he dragged off the boy's rags which tore into shreds, with the other he took down from a nail a man's shirt, and one of those knitted jackets which are up to this day called kiss me quicks.
6209_34601_000053_000000 "Here are clothes."
6209_34601_000054_000001 The limbs having been rubbed, he next wiped the boy's feet.
6209_34601_000055_000000 "Come, you limb; you have nothing frost bitten!
6209_34601_000055_000003 Dress yourself!"
6209_34601_000056_000000 The child put on the shirt, and the man slipped the knitted jacket over it.
6209_34601_000058_000000 The man kicked the stool forward and made the little boy sit down, again shoving him by the shoulders; then he pointed with his finger to the porringer which was smoking upon the stove.
6209_34601_000059_000000 "You are hungry; eat!"
6209_34601_000060_000000 The man took from the shelf a crust of hard bread and an iron fork, and handed them to the child.
6209_34601_000061_000000 The boy hesitated.
6209_34601_000062_000000 "Perhaps you expect me to lay the cloth," said the man, and he placed the porringer on the child's lap.
6209_34601_000063_000000 "Gobble that up."
6209_34601_000064_000000 Hunger overcame astonishment.
6209_34601_000064_000001 The child began to eat.
6209_34601_000064_000002 The poor boy devoured rather than ate.
6209_34601_000064_000004 The man grumbled,--
6209_34601_000065_000000 "Not so quick, you horrid glutton!
6209_34601_000065_000001 Isn't he a greedy scoundrel?
6209_34601_000065_000003 You should see a lord sup.
6209_34601_000065_000004 In my time I have seen dukes eat.
6209_34601_000065_000005 They don't eat; that's noble.
6209_34601_000065_000006 They drink, however.
6209_34601_000065_000007 Come, you pig, stuff yourself!"
6209_34601_000066_000000 The absence of ears, which is the concomitant of a hungry stomach, caused the child to take little heed of these violent epithets, tempered as they were by charity of action involving a contradiction resulting in his benefit.
6209_34601_000066_000001 For the moment he was absorbed by two exigencies and by two ecstasies-food and warmth.
6209_34601_000067_000000 Ursus continued his imprecations, muttering to himself,--
6209_34601_000068_000001 His Majesty touched nothing.
6209_34601_000068_000002 This beggar here browses: browses, a word derived from brute.
6209_34601_000068_000005 I have played the flute to the hurricane.
6209_34601_000068_000006 I have not pocketed a farthing; and now, to night, beggars drop in.
6209_34601_000068_000007 Horrid place!
6209_34601_000068_000008 There is battle, struggle, competition between the fools in the street and myself.
6209_34601_000068_000009 They try to give me nothing but farthings.
6209_34601_000068_000011 Well, to day I've made nothing.
6209_34601_000068_000013 Eat away, hell born boy!
6209_34601_000068_000014 Tear and crunch!
6209_34601_000068_000015 We have fallen on times when nothing can equal the cynicism of spongers.
6209_34601_000068_000016 Fatten at my expense, parasite!
6209_34601_000068_000018 It is not appetite, it is ferocity.
6209_34601_000068_000020 Perhaps he has the plague.
6209_34601_000068_000021 Have you the plague, you thief?
6209_34601_000068_000024 Let the populace die, but not my wolf.
6209_34601_000068_000027 I have worked far into the night.
6209_34601_000068_000029 I was to night, by hunger.
6209_34601_000068_000030 I was alone.
6209_34601_000068_000031 I made a fire.
6209_34601_000068_000032 I had but one potato, one crust of bread, a mouthful of bacon, and a drop of milk, and I put it to warm.
6209_34601_000068_000033 I said to myself, 'Good.' I think I am going to eat, and bang!
6209_34601_000068_000034 this crocodile falls upon me at the very moment. He installs himself clean between my food and myself.
6209_34601_000068_000037 You shark! how many teeth have you in your jaws?
6209_34601_000068_000038 Guzzle, wolf cub; no, I withdraw that word.
6209_34601_000068_000039 I respect wolves.
6209_34601_000068_000040 Swallow up my food, boa.
6209_34601_000068_000042 'tis all one, though!
6209_34601_000069_000000 Just then a wail, touching and prolonged, arose in the hut.
6209_34601_000069_000001 The man listened.
6209_34601_000070_000000 "You cry, sycophant!
6209_34601_000070_000001 Why do you cry?"
6209_34601_000071_000000 The boy turned towards him.
6209_34601_000071_000001 It was evident that it was not he who cried. He had his mouth full.
6209_34601_000072_000000 The cry continued.
6209_34601_000073_000000 The man went to the chest.
6209_34601_000074_000000 "So it is your bundle that wails!
6209_34601_000075_000000 He unrolled the jacket.
6209_34601_000075_000001 An infant's head appeared, the mouth open and crying.
6209_34601_000076_000003 Who is there?
6209_34601_000076_000005 Corporal, call out the guard! Another bang!
6209_34601_000076_000007 Don't you see it is thirsty?
6209_34601_000076_000008 Come! the little one must have a drink.
6209_34601_000076_000009 So now I shall not have even the milk!"
6209_34601_000077_000000 He took down from the things lying in disorder on the shelf a bandage of linen, a sponge and a phial, muttering savagely, "What an infernal place!"
6209_34601_000078_000000 Then he looked at the little infant.
6209_34601_000078_000002 This rough and sudden dressing made the infant angry.
6209_34601_000079_000000 "She mews relentlessly," said he.
6209_34601_000080_000001 "Come! take your supper, creature!
6209_34601_000080_000002 Let me suckle you," and he put the neck of the bottle to its mouth.
6209_34601_000081_000000 The little infant drank greedily.
6209_34601_000084_000000 "You are going to choke!" growled Ursus.
6209_34601_000084_000001 "A fine gobbler this one, too!"
6209_34601_000085_000000 He drew away the sponge which she was sucking, allowed the cough to subside, and then replaced the phial to her lips, saying, "Suck, you little wretch!"
6209_34601_000086_000000 In the meantime the boy had laid down his fork.
6209_34601_000086_000001 Seeing the infant drink had made him forget to eat.
6209_34601_000086_000002 The moment before, while he ate, the expression in his face was satisfaction; now it was gratitude.
6209_34601_000086_000003 He watched the infant's renewal of life; the completion of the resurrection begun by himself filled his eyes with an ineffable brilliancy.
6209_34601_000086_000004 Ursus went on muttering angry words between his teeth.
6209_34601_000086_000005 The little boy now and then lifted towards Ursus his eyes moist with the unspeakable emotion which the poor little being felt, but was unable to express.
6209_34601_000086_000006 Ursus addressed him furiously.
6209_34601_000087_000000 "Well, will you eat?"
6209_34601_000088_000000 "And you?" said the child, trembling all over, and with tears in his eyes.
6209_34601_000088_000001 "You will have nothing!"
6209_34601_000089_000000 "Will you be kind enough to eat it all up, you cub?
6209_34601_000091_000001 "What has it got to do with me?
6209_34601_000091_000002 Who speaks of me? Wretched little barefooted clerk of Penniless Parish, I tell you, eat it all up!
6209_34601_000091_000003 You are here to eat, drink, and sleep-eat, or I will kick you out, both of you."
6209_34601_000092_000000 The boy, under this menace, began to eat again.
6209_34601_000092_000001 He had not much trouble in finishing what was left in the porringer.
6209_34601_000092_000002 Ursus muttered, "This building is badly joined.
6209_34601_000092_000003 The cold comes in by the window pane." A pane had indeed been broken in front, either by a jolt of the caravan or by a stone thrown by some mischievous boy.
6209_34601_000092_000005 The blast entered there.
6209_34601_000093_000000 He was half seated on the chest.
6209_34601_000093_000001 The infant in his arms, and at the same time on his lap, was sucking rapturously at the bottle, in the happy somnolency of cherubim before their Creator, and infants at their mothers' breast.
6209_34601_000094_000000 "She is drunk," said Ursus; and he continued, "After this, preach sermons on temperance!"
6209_34601_000096_000001 What useful trouble Bishop Tillotson gives himself, thundering against excessive drinking.
6209_34601_000096_000006 One cannot see clearly.
6209_34601_000096_000007 That being over there abuses my hospitality.
6209_34601_000096_000009 Comfort is wanting here.
6209_34601_000096_000010 By Jove!
6209_34601_000096_000015 Nothing sold all day.
6209_34601_000096_000017 You are losing your time, old friend.
6209_34601_000096_000018 Pack up your physic.
6209_34601_000096_000019 Every one is well down here. It's a cursed town, where every one is well!
6209_34601_000096_000022 Ice is night.
6209_34601_000096_000023 What a hurricane!
