6385_220959_000001_000000 sixteen: OUTWARD FORMS AND SYMBOLS MUST BE USED TO CONVEY INTELLECTUAL CONCEPTIONS
6385_220959_000002_000001 One is the knowledge of things perceptible to the senses-that is to say, things which the eye, or ear, or smell, or taste, or touch can perceive, which are called objective or sensible.
6385_220959_000002_000002 So the sun, because it can be seen, is said to be objective; and in the same way sounds are sensible because the ear hears them; perfumes are sensible because they can be inhaled and the sense of smell perceives them; foods are sensible because the palate perceives their sweetness, sourness or saltness; heat and cold are sensible because the feelings perceive them. These are said to be sensible realities.
6385_220959_000003_000001 For example, the power of intellect is not sensible; none of the inner qualities of man is a sensible thing; on the contrary, they are intellectual realities.
6385_220959_000003_000002 So love is a mental reality and not sensible; for this reality the ear does not hear, the eye does not see, the smell does not perceive, the taste does not discern, the touch does not feel.
6385_220959_000003_000003 Even ethereal matter, the forces of which are said in physics to be heat, light, electricity and magnetism, is an intellectual reality, and is not sensible.
6385_220959_000003_000004 In the same way, nature, also, in its essence is an intellectual reality and is not sensible; the human spirit is an intellectual, not sensible reality.
6385_220959_000003_000005 In explaining these intellectual realities, one is obliged to express them by sensible figures because in exterior existence there is nothing that is not material.
6385_220959_000003_000006 Therefore, to explain the reality of the spirit-its condition, its station-one is obliged to give explanations under the forms of sensible things because in the external world all that exists is sensible.
6385_220959_000003_000008 This is an intellectual or spiritual state, to explain which you are obliged to have recourse to sensible figures.
6385_220959_000003_000010 This exaltation and this progress are spiritual states and intellectual realities, but to explain them you are obliged to have recourse to sensible figures because in the exterior world there is nothing that is not sensible.
6385_220959_000004_000000 So the symbol of knowledge is light, and of ignorance, darkness; but reflect, is knowledge sensible light, or ignorance sensible darkness?
6385_220959_000004_000001 No, they are merely symbols.
6385_220959_000004_000002 These are only intellectual states, but when you desire to express them outwardly, you call knowledge light, and ignorance darkness.
6385_220959_000005_000001 Thus in the Old Testament it is said that God appeared as a pillar of fire: this does not signify the material form; it is an intellectual reality which is expressed by a sensible image.
6385_220959_000006_000000 Christ says, "The Father is in the Son, and the Son is in the Father." Was Christ within God, or God within Christ?
6385_220959_000006_000001 No, in the name of God!
6385_220959_000006_000002 On the contrary, this is an intellectual state which is expressed in a sensible figure.
6385_220959_000007_000000 We come to the explanation of the words of Baha'u'llah when He says: "O king!
6385_220959_000007_000003 Sleeping and waking is passing from one state to another.
6385_220959_000007_000004 Sleeping is the condition of repose, and wakefulness is the condition of movement.
6385_220959_000007_000005 Sleeping is the state of silence; wakefulness is the state of speech.
6385_220959_000007_000006 Sleeping is the state of mystery; wakefulness is the state of manifestation.
6385_220959_000008_000000 For example, it is a Persian and Arabic expression to say that the earth was asleep, and the spring came, and it awoke; or the earth was dead, and the spring came, and it revived.
6385_220959_000008_000001 These expressions are metaphors, allegories, mystic explanations in the world of signification.
6385_220959_000009_000000 Briefly, the Holy Manifestations have ever been, and ever will be, Luminous Realities; no change or variation takes place in Their essence. Before declaring Their manifestation, They are silent and quiet like a sleeper, and after Their manifestation, They speak and are illuminated, like one who is awake.
6385_220959_000010_000000 seventeen: THE BIRTH OF CHRIST
6385_220959_000011_000000 Question.--How was Christ born of the Holy Spirit?
6385_220959_000012_000000 Answer.--In regard to this question, theologians and materialists disagree. The theologians believe that Christ was born of the Holy Spirit, but the materialists think this is impossible and inadmissible, and that without doubt He had a human father.
6385_220959_000014_000000 The materialists believe that there must be marriage, and say that a living body cannot be created from a lifeless body, and without male and female there cannot be fecundation.
6385_220959_000014_000001 And they think that not only with man, but also with animals and plants, it is impossible.
6385_220959_000014_000002 For this union of the male and female exists in all living beings and plants.
6385_220959_000015_000000 Briefly, they say a man without a human father cannot be imagined.
6385_220959_000015_000002 For example, in former times the telegraph, which causes the East and the West to communicate, was unknown but not impossible; photography and phonography were unknown but not impossible."
6385_220959_000016_000000 The materialists insist upon this belief, and the theologians reply: "Is this globe eternal or phenomenal?" The materialists answer that, according to science and important discoveries, it is established that it is phenomenal; in the beginning it was a flaming globe, and gradually it became temperate; a crust was formed around it, and upon this crust plants came into existence, then animals, and finally man.
6385_220959_000017_000000 The theologians say: "Then from your statement it has become evident and clear that mankind is phenomenal upon the globe, and not eternal.
6385_220959_000017_000001 Then surely the first man had neither father nor mother, for the existence of man is phenomenal.
6385_220959_000017_000003 As you admit that the first man came into existence without father or mother-whether it be gradually or at once-there can remain no doubt that a man without a human father is also possible and admissible; you cannot consider this impossible; otherwise, you are illogical.
6385_220959_000018_000000 eighteen: THE GREATNESS OF CHRIST IS DUE TO HIS PERFECTIONS
6385_220959_000019_000001 If being without a father is a virtue, Adam is greater and more excellent than all the Prophets and Messengers, for He had neither father nor mother.
6385_220959_000019_000002 That which causes honor and greatness is the splendor and bounty of the divine perfections.
6385_220959_000019_000004 The substance of Adam's physical life was earth, but the substance of Abraham was pure sperm; it is certain that the pure and chaste sperm is superior to earth.
6385_220959_000020_000000 Furthermore, in the first chapter of the Gospel of john, verses twelve and thirteen, it is said: "But as many as received Him, to them gave He power to become the sons of God, even to them that believed on His name:
6385_220959_000022_000000 From these verses it is obvious that the being of a disciple also is not created by physical power, but by the spiritual reality.
6385_220959_000022_000001 The honor and greatness of Christ is not due to the fact that He did not have a human father, but to His perfections, bounties and divine glory.
6385_220959_000022_000002 If the greatness of Christ is His being fatherless, then Adam is greater than Christ, for He had neither father nor mother.
6385_220959_000022_000004 Moreover, the expression which john uses in regard to the disciples proves that they also are from the Heavenly Father.
6385_220959_000022_000005 Hence it is evident that the holy reality, meaning the real existence of every great man, comes from God and owes its being to the breath of the Holy Spirit.
6385_220959_000023_000001 Is it better for a man to be created from a living substance or from earth?
6385_220959_000023_000002 Certainly it is better if he be created from a living substance.
6385_220959_000023_000003 But Christ was born and came into existence from the Holy Spirit.
6385_34655_000006_000000 CHAPTER two.
6385_34655_000007_000000 THE RESEMBLANCE OF A PALACE TO A WOOD.
6385_34655_000008_000000 In palaces after the Italian fashion, and Corleone Lodge was one, there were very few doors, but abundance of tapestry screens and curtained doorways.
6385_34655_000008_000001 In every palace of that date there was a wonderful labyrinth of chambers and corridors, where luxury ran riot; gilding, marble, carved wainscoting, Eastern silks; nooks and corners, some secret and dark as night, others light and pleasant as the day.
6385_34655_000008_000002 There were attics, richly and brightly furnished; burnished recesses shining with Dutch tiles and Portuguese azulejos.
6385_34655_000008_000003 The tops of the high windows were converted into small rooms and glass attics, forming pretty habitable lanterns.
6385_34655_000008_000004 The thickness of the walls was such that there were rooms within them.
6385_34655_000008_000005 Here and there were closets, nominally wardrobes.
6385_34655_000008_000006 They were called "The Little Rooms."
6385_34655_000008_000007 It was within them that evil deeds were hatched.
6385_34655_000009_000002 In those elegant caverns princes and lords stored their plunder.
6385_34655_000009_000005 They were gilded oubliettes, savouring both of the cloister and the harem.
6385_34655_000009_000006 Their staircases twisted, turned, ascended, and descended.
6385_34655_000009_000007 A zigzag of rooms, one running into another, led back to the starting point.
6385_34655_000009_000009 A confessional was grafted on to an alcove.
6385_34655_000009_000010 Perhaps the architects of "the little rooms," building for royalty and aristocracy, took as models the ramifications of coral beds, and the openings in a sponge.
6385_34655_000009_000011 The branches became a labyrinth.
6385_34655_000009_000012 Pictures turning on false panels were exits and entrances.
6385_34655_000009_000014 The floors of these hives reached from the cellars to the attics.
6385_34655_000009_000016 Passages, niches, alcoves, and secret recesses.
