6836_61803_000001_000000 CHAPTER NINETY NINE.
6836_61803_000002_000000 ATTEMPTED MURDER AND SUICIDE.
6836_61803_000003_000000 After its second involuntary recess-less prolonged than the first-the Court has once more resumed its functions under the great evergreen oak.
6836_61803_000005_000000 From the golden brightness, displayed by them at noon, they have changed to a lurid red-as if there was anger in the sky!
6836_61803_000006_000000 It is but an accident of the atmosphere-the portent of an approaching storm.
6836_61803_000007_000000 For all this, it is remarked as singular, that a storm should be coming at the time: since it symbolises the sentiment of the spectators, who look on with sullenness in their hearts, and gloom in their glances.
6836_61803_000008_000000 It would seem as if Heaven's wrath was acting in concert with the passions of Earth!
6836_61803_000010_000000 In the place late occupied by him another stands.
6836_61803_000010_000001 Cassius Calhoun is now the prisoner at the bar!
6836_61803_000012_000000 The judge is the same, the jury the same, and the spectators as before; though with very different feelings in regard to the criminality of the accused.
6836_61803_000014_000001 The evidence is already before them; and though entirely circumstantial-as in most cases of murder-the circumstances form a chain irresistibly conclusive and complete.
6836_61803_000016_000000 The motive both for the murder and the mutilation: for the testimony of Gerald has been confirmed by a subsequent examination of the dead body. The surgeon of the cantonment has pronounced the two distinct, and that Henry Poindexter's death must have ensued, almost instantaneously after his receiving the shot.
6836_61803_000017_000000 Why should Cassius Calhoun have killed his own cousin?
6836_61803_000018_000000 No one can answer these questions, save the murderer himself.
6836_61803_000018_000001 No one expects him to do so-save to his Maker.
6836_61803_000022_000000 He starts at the invitation-falling, as it does, like a death knell upon his ear.
6836_61803_000023_000001 Despairingly: when on the faces that encircle him he sees not one wearing an expression of sympathy.
6836_61803_000024_000000 There is not even pity.
6836_61803_000024_000001 All appear to frown upon him.
6836_61803_000027_000000 His demeanour is completely changed.
6836_61803_000028_000000 And not strange that he should.
6836_61803_000029_000000 He feels that there is no chance of escape; that he is standing by the side of his coffin-on the edge of an Eternity too terrible to contemplate.
6836_61803_000030_000000 To a conscience like his, it cannot be otherwise than appalling.
6836_61803_000031_000000 All at once a light is seen to flask into his eyes-sunken as they are in the midst of two livid circles.
6836_61803_000033_000000 The spectators, guessing his intention, stand breathlessly observing him.
6836_61803_000034_000000 There is silence even among the cicadas.
6836_61803_000035_000000 It is broken by the formalised interrogatory of the judge?
6836_61803_000037_000000 "No!" he replies, "I have not.
6836_61803_000037_000002 I acknowledge that I have forfeited my life, and deserve to lose it."
6836_61803_000040_000000 The declaration is answered by a cry from the crowd.
6836_61803_000043_000000 "I know that I've got to die," proceeds the prisoner, with an air of seeming recklessness.
6836_61803_000044_000000 "After what I've confessed, it would be folly in me to expect pardon; and I don't.
6836_61803_000044_000003 I did take his life, as I've told you. You are all asking why, and conjecturing about the motive.
6836_61803_000044_000004 There was none."
6836_61803_000046_000000 No one speaks, or in any way attempts interruption.
6836_61803_000047_000000 "You wonder at that.
6836_61803_000049_000000 "Yes, by mistake; and God knows I was sorry enough, on discovering that I had made it.
6836_61803_000049_000001 I didn't know myself till long after."
