6836_61804_000000_000000 CHAPTER ONE HUNDRED.
6836_61804_000001_000000 JOY.
6836_61804_000004_000000 Though saddened by the series of tragedies so quickly transpiring, she was but human; and, being woman, who can blame her for giving way to the subdued happiness that succeeded?
6836_61804_000004_000001 Not i Not you, if you speak truly.
6836_61804_000005_000000 The passion that controlled her may not be popular under a strictly Puritan standard.
6836_61804_000006_000000 Do not reproach the young Creole, because this passion was paramount in her soul.
6836_61804_000006_000001 Do not blame her for feeling pleasure amidst moments that should otherwise have been devoted to sadness.
6836_61804_000006_000002 Nor, that her happiness was heightened, on learning from the astonished spectators, how her lover's life had been preserved-as it might seem miraculously.
6836_61804_000007_000000 The aim of the assassin had been true enough.
6836_61804_000008_000000 Not harmlessly, however: since it struck one of the spectators standing too close to the spot.
6836_61804_000010_000000 The stunning shock-with the mental and corporeal excitement-long sustained-did not fail to produce its effect; and the mind of Maurice Gerald once more returned to its delirious dreaming.
6836_61804_000012_000000 When again restored to consciousness, it was to discover that the fair vision of his dreams was no vision at all, but a lovely woman-the loveliest on the Leona, or in all Texas if you like-by name Louise Poindexter.
6836_61804_000013_000001 The spirit of the aristocratic planter-steeped in sorrow, and humiliated by misfortune-had become purged of its false pride; though it needed not this to make him willingly acquiesce in an alliance, which, instead of a "nobody," gave him a nobleman for his son.
6836_61804_000013_000002 Such, in reality, was Sir Maurice Gerald-erst known as Maurice the mustanger!
6836_61804_000014_000000 In Texas the title would have counted for little; nor did its owner care to carry it.
6836_61804_000014_000001 But, by a bit of good fortune-not always attendant on an Irish baronetcy-it carried along with it an endowment-ample enough to clear Casa del Corvo of the mortgage held by the late Cassius Calhoun, and claimed by his nearest of kin.
6836_61804_000015_000000 This was not Woodley Poindexter: for after Calhoun's death, it was discovered that the ex captain had once been a Benedict; and there was a young scion of his stock-living in New Orleans-who had the legal right to say he was his son!
6836_61804_000017_000000 After a visit to his native land-including the European tour-which was also that of his honeymoon-Sir Maurice, swayed by his inclinations, once more returned to Texas, and made Casa del Corvo his permanent home.
