7067_76047_000059_000000 A pause fell between the two gentlemen.
7067_76047_000059_000001 They had smoothed over the extreme harshness of their separation and there was very little more to be said.
7067_76048_000009_000000 CHAPTER THE SEVENTH
7067_76048_000010_000000 COMPANIONSHIP
7067_76048_000012_000000 "Well," said dr Martineau, extending his hand to Sir Richmond on the Salisbury station platform, "I leave you to it."
7067_76048_000013_000000 His round face betrayed little or no vestiges of his overnight irritation.
7067_76048_000014_000000 "Ought you to leave me to it?" smiled Sir Richmond.
7067_76048_000015_000000 "I shall be interested to learn what happens."
7067_76048_000016_000000 "But if you won't stay to see!"
7067_76048_000017_000000 "Now Sir, please," said the guard respectfully but firmly, and dr Martineau got in.
7067_76048_000018_000000 Sir Richmond walked thoughtfully down the platform towards the exit.
7067_76048_000019_000000 "What else could I do?" he asked aloud to nobody in particular.
7067_76048_000020_000000 For a little while he thought confusedly of the collapse of his expedition into the secret places of his own heart with dr Martineau, and then his prepossession with Miss Grammont resumed possession of his mind.
7067_76048_000020_000001 dr Martineau was forgotten.
7067_76048_000021_000000 Section two
7067_76048_000022_000000 For the better part of forty hours, Sir Richmond had either been talking to Miss Grammont, or carrying on imaginary conversations with her in her absence, or sleeping and dreaming dreams in which she never failed to play a part, even if at times it was an altogether amazing and incongruous part.
7067_76048_000022_000001 And as they were both very frank and expressive people, they already knew a very great deal about each other.
7067_76048_000023_000000 For an American Miss Grammont was by no means autobiographical.
7067_76048_000023_000001 She gave no sketches of her idiosyncrasies, and she repeated no remembered comments and prophets of her contemporaries about herself.
7067_76048_000023_000002 She either concealed or she had lost any great interest in her own personality.
7067_76048_000023_000003 But she was interested in and curious about the people she had met in life, and her talk of them reflected a considerable amount of light upon her own upbringing and experiences.
7067_76048_000023_000004 And her liking for Sir Richmond was pleasingly manifest.
7067_76048_000023_000005 She liked his turn of thought, she watched him with a faint smile on her lips as he spoke, and she spread her opinions before him carefully in that soft voice of hers like a shy child showing its treasures to some suddenly trusted and favoured visitor.
7067_76048_000024_000000 Their ways of thought harmonized.
7067_76048_000024_000001 They talked at first chiefly about the history of the world and the extraordinary situation of aimlessness in a phase of ruin to which the Great War had brought all Europe, if not all mankind.
7067_76048_000024_000002 The world excited them both in the same way; as a crisis in which they were called upon to do something-they did not yet clearly know what.
7067_76048_000024_000003 Into this topic they peered as into some deep pool, side by side, and in it they saw each other reflected.
7067_76048_000025_000000 The visit to Avebury had been a great success.
7067_76048_000025_000002 Its delight was particularly manifest in the cream and salad it produced for lunch.
7067_76048_000025_000003 Both Miss Grammont and Miss Seyffert displayed an intelligent interest in their food.
7067_76048_000025_000004 After lunch they had all gone out to the stones and the wall.
7067_76048_000026_000000 Sir Richmond and Miss Grammont had walked round the old circumvallation together, but Belinda Seyffert had strayed away from them, professing an interest in flowers.
7067_76048_000026_000001 It was not so much that she felt they had to be left together that made her do this as her own consciousness of being possessed by a devil who interrupted conversations.
7067_76048_000027_000000 When Miss Grammont was keenly interested in a conversation, then Belinda had learnt from experience that it was wiser to go off with her devil out of the range of any temptation to interrupt.
7067_76048_000028_000000 "You really think," said Miss Grammont, "that it would be possible to take this confused old world and reshape it, set it marching towards that new world of yours-of two hundred and fifty million fully developed, beautiful and happy people?"
7067_76048_000029_000000 "Why not?
7067_76048_000029_000001 Nobody is doing anything with the world except muddle about. Why not give it a direction?"
7067_76048_000031_000000 "Obdurate clay with a sort of recalcitrant, unintelligent life of its own."
7067_76048_000032_000001 "I believe what you say is possible.
7067_76048_000032_000002 If people dare."
7067_76048_000033_000000 "I am tired of following little motives that are like flames that go out when you get to them.
7067_76048_000033_000001 I am tired of seeing all the world doing the same.
7067_76048_000033_000002 I am tired of a world in which there is nothing great but great disasters.
7067_76048_000033_000003 Here is something mankind can attempt, that we can attempt."
7067_76048_000034_000000 "And will?"
7067_76048_000035_000000 "I believe that as Mankind grows up this is the business Man has to settle down to and will settle down to."
7067_76048_000036_000000 She considered that.
7067_76048_000037_000000 "I've been getting to believe something like this.
7067_76048_000037_000001 But-... it frightens me.
7067_76048_000038_000000 "So we just live like pigs.
7067_76048_000038_000001 Sensible little piggywiggys.
7067_76048_000038_000002 I've got a Committee full of that sort of thing.
7067_76048_000038_000003 We live like little modest pigs. And let the world go hang.
7067_76048_000039_000000 "Not quite that!"
7067_76048_000040_000000 "Well!
7067_76048_000040_000001 How do you put it?"
7067_76048_000041_000002 We want bright little lives of our own."
7067_76048_000043_000000 "We have a right to life-and happiness.
7067_76048_000044_000000 "First," said Sir Richmond, "as much right as a pig has to food.
7067_76048_000044_000001 But whether we get life and happiness or fail to get them we human beings who have imaginations want something more nowadays....
7067_76048_000044_000002 Of course we want bright lives, of course we want happiness.
7067_76048_000044_000003 Just as we want food, just as we want sleep.
7067_76048_000044_000004 But when we have eaten, when we have slept, when we have jolly things about us-it is nothing.
