8324_286681_000000_000000 TWO LITTLE CRAYFISHES QUARREL
8324_286681_000001_000000 The day after the Eels left, the pond people talked of nothing else.
8324_286681_000001_000001 It was not that they were so much missed, for the Eels, you know, do not swim around in the daytime.
8324_286681_000001_000002 They lie quietly in the mud and sleep or talk.
8324_286681_000001_000003 It is only at night that they are really lively.
8324_286681_000001_000004 Still, as the Mother Mud Turtle said, "They had known that they were there, and the mud seemed empty without them."
8324_286681_000002_000000 The larger people had been sorry to have them go, and some of them felt that without the Eels awake and stirring, the pond was hardly a safe place at night.
8324_286681_000003_000000 "I think it is a good deal safer," remarked a Minnow, who usually said what she thought.
8324_286681_000004_000000 "Why didn't you ask them?" said a Stickleback.
8324_286681_000005_000000 "Why?" replied the Minnow.
8324_286681_000006_000000 "I have heard some queer things about the Eels myself," said the Stickleback, "but I have never felt much afraid of them.
8324_286681_000006_000001 I suppose I am braver because I wear so many of my bones on the outside."
8324_286681_000007_000000 Just then a Wise Old Crayfish came along walking sidewise.
8324_286681_000008_000000 The Crayfish stuck his tail into the mud.
8324_286681_000008_000001 He often did this when he was surprised.
8324_286681_000008_000002 It seemed to help him think.
8324_286681_000008_000003 When he had thought for a while, he waved his big pinching claws and said, "It would be better for me not to tell what I think.
8324_286681_000008_000004 I used to live near them."
8324_286681_000009_000000 This showed that the Wise Old Crayfish had been well brought up, and knew he should not say unpleasant things about people if he could help it.
8324_286681_000009_000002 That was when he was teaching some young Crayfishes, his pupils.
8324_286681_000009_000003 Their mother had brought up a large family, and was not strong.
8324_286681_000009_000004 She had just cast the shell which she had worn for a year, and now she was weak and helpless until the new one should harden on her.
8324_286681_000010_000000 While their mother was so weak, the Wise Old Crayfish amused the children, and taught them things which all Crayfishes should know.
8324_286681_000010_000002 It made no difference to them which way they came.
8324_286681_000010_000003 They were restless pupils, and their teacher could not keep them from looking behind them.
8324_286681_000010_000004 Each one had so many eyes that he could look at the teacher with a few, and at the other little Crayfishes with a few more, and still have a good many eyes left with which to watch the Tadpoles.
8324_286681_000010_000006 They had good ears, and there were also fine smelling bristles growing from their heads.
8324_286681_000010_000007 The Wise Old Crayfish sometimes said that each of his pupils should sit in a circle of six teachers, so that he might be taught on all sides at once.
8324_286681_000011_000000 "That is the way in which children should learn," he said, "all around at once.
8324_286681_000011_000001 But I do the best I can, and I at least teach one side of each."
8324_286681_000012_000000 This evening the Wise Old Crayfish was very sleepy.
8324_286681_000012_000002 When he tried to walk, his eight legs stumbled over each other, and the weak way in which he waved his pinching claw legs showed how tired he was.
8324_286681_000013_000000 After he had told his pupils the best way to hold their food with their pinching claws, and had explained to them how it was chewed by the teeth in their stomachs, one mischievous little fellow called out, "I want to know about the Eels.
8324_286681_000013_000001 My mother would never let me go near them, and now they've moved away, and I won't ever see them, and I think it's just horrid."
8324_286681_000014_000000 "Eels, my children," said their teacher, "are long, slender, sharp nosed, slippery people, with a fringe of fins along their backs, and another fringe along their bellies.
8324_286681_000014_000001 They breathe through very small gill openings in the backs of their heads.
8324_286681_000014_000002 They have large mouths, and teeth in their mouths, and they are always sticking out their lower jaws."
8324_286681_000015_000000 "And how do-" began the Biggest Little Crayfish.
8324_286681_000018_000001 The Biggest Little Crayfish had beaten.
8324_286681_000019_000000 "I'd like to see them running on the land," said the saucy one.
8324_286681_000020_000001 "That's all you know!
8324_286681_000020_000002 They don't run on land."
8324_286681_000021_000000 "Well, I guess they do," replied the saucy one.
8324_286681_000021_000001 "I know as much about it as you do!"
8324_286681_000022_000000 "Eels swim.
8324_286681_000022_000001 They don't run," said the biggest one.
8324_286681_000022_000002 "Guess I know!"
