8419_286667_000000_000000 THE DANCE OF THE SAND HILL CRANES
8419_286667_000001_000000 One fine day in spring, a great flock of Sand hill Cranes came from the south.
8419_286667_000001_000001 They were flying high and quietly because the weather was bright. If it had been stormy, or if they had been flying by night, as they usually did, they would have stayed nearer the ground, and their leader would have trumpeted loudly to let his followers know which way he was going.
8419_286667_000001_000002 They would also have trumpeted, but more softly, to tell him that they were coming after.
8419_286667_000002_000000 They were a fine company to look upon, orderly, strong, and dignified. Their long necks were stretched out straight ahead, their long legs straight behind, and they beat the air with slow, regular strokes of the strong wings.
8419_286667_000002_000001 As they came near the pond, they flew lower and lower, until all swept down to the earth and alighted, tall and stately, by the edge of the water.
8419_286667_000003_000000 They had eaten nothing for several days, and were soon hunting for food, some on land, and some in the water, for they had stopped to feed and rest.
8419_286667_000003_000001 Those who hunted in the water, did so very quietly.
8419_286667_000003_000002 A Crane would stand on one leg, with his head against his breast, so quietly that one might think him asleep: but as soon as anything eatable came near, he would bend his body, stretch out his neck, open his long, slender bill, and swallow it at one gulp.
8419_286667_000003_000003 Then he would seem to fall asleep again.
8419_286667_000004_000001 They were those who thought of staying there for the summer.
8419_286667_000005_000000 When the flock arose to fly on again, eight Cranes stayed behind.
8419_286667_000005_000001 They watched their friends fly away, and stood on the ground with their necks and bills uplifted and mouths open, while they trumpeted or called out, "Good bye!
8419_286667_000005_000002 Stop for us in the fall!"
8419_286667_000005_000003 The flying Cranes trumpeted back, "We will!
8419_286667_000005_000004 Don't forget us!"
8419_286667_000006_000000 That night they slept near together, as they had done when with the large flock, and one Crane kept awake to watch for danger while the others tucked their heads under their wings.
8419_286667_000006_000001 They were fine looking, even when they slept, and some people never look well unless they are awake.
8419_286667_000006_000002 They were brownish gray, with no bright markings at all, and their long legs gave them a very genteel look.
8419_286667_000006_000003 The tops of their heads were covered with warty red skin, from which grew short black feathers that looked more like hairs.
8419_286667_000007_000000 One morning, when the Cranes awakened, a fine young fellow began to strut up and down before the rest, bowing low, and leaping high into the air, and every now and then whooping as loudly as he could.
8419_286667_000007_000001 The Gulls, who had spent the winter by the pond, screamed to each other, "The Crane dance has begun!" Even the Frogs, who are afraid of Cranes, crept quietly near to look on.
8419_286667_000008_000000 It was not long before another young Crane began to skip and hop and circle around, drooping his wings and whooping as he went.
8419_286667_000008_000001 Every Crane danced, brothers, and sisters, and all, and as they did so, they looked lovingly at each other, and admired the fine steps and enjoyed the whooping.
8419_286667_000008_000002 This went on until they were so tired they could hardly stand, and had to stop to eat and rest.
8419_286667_000009_000000 When they were eating, the young fellow who had begun the dance, stalked up to the sister of one of his friends, as she stood in the edge of the pond, gracefully balanced on one leg.
8419_286667_000009_000001 She did not turn her head towards him, although, having such a long and slender neck, she could have done so with very little trouble.
8419_286667_000009_000002 She stood with her head on her breast and looked at the water.
8419_286667_000009_000003 After a while, he trumpeted softly, as though he were just trying his voice.
8419_286667_000009_000004 Then she gave a pretty little start, and said, "Oh, are you here?
8419_286667_000009_000005 How you did frighten me!"
8419_286667_000010_000000 "I am sorry," he said.
8419_286667_000010_000001 "I did not want to frighten you." And he looked at her admiringly.
8419_286667_000011_000001 "Of course I am not frightened now that I know who it is."
8419_286667_000012_000000 Then they stood and fished for a long time without saying anything.
8419_286667_000012_000001 When she flew away, she said, "That is a very pleasant fishing place." He stood on the other leg for a while, and thought how sweet her voice sounded as she said it.
8419_286667_000012_000002 Then he thought that, if she liked the place so well, she might come there again the next day.
8419_286667_000012_000003 He wondered why he could not come too, although everybody knows that a Crane catches more if he fishes alone.
8419_286667_000013_000002 As she stalked off toward the pond, she passed him, and she said over her shoulder, "I should think you would be hungry.
8419_286667_000013_000003 I am almost starved." After she had gone, he wondered why she had said that.
8419_286667_000013_000004 If he had been an older Crane, and understood the ways of the world a little better, he would have known that she meant, "Aren't you coming to that fishing place?
8419_286667_000013_000005 I am going now." Still, although he was such a young Crane and had never danced until this year, he began to think that she liked him and enjoyed having him near.
8419_286667_000013_000006 So he flew off to the fishing place where he had seen her the day before, and he stalked along to where she was, and stood close to her while she fished.
8419_286667_000015_000000 That pleased him, of course, because Cranes think that big mouthfuls are the best kind, so he tipped his head to one side, and watched his neck as the mouthful slid down to his stomach.
8419_286667_000015_000001 He could see it from the outside, a big bunch slowly moving downward.
8419_286667_000015_000002 He often did this while he was eating.
8419_286667_000015_000004 He pitied short necked people.
8419_286667_000015_000006 I can take bigger mouthfuls than that.
8419_286667_000015_000007 You ought to see what big mouthfuls I can take."
8419_286667_000016_000000 She changed, and stood on her other leg.
8419_286667_000016_000001 "I saw you dancing this morning," she said.
8419_286667_000016_000002 Now it was not at all queer that she should have seen him dancing, for all the eight Cranes had danced together, but he thought it very wonderful.
8419_286667_000017_000000 "Did you notice to whom I bowed?" he asked.
8419_286667_000017_000001 He was so excited that his knees shook, and he had to stand on both legs at once to keep from falling.
8419_286667_000018_000000 "To my sister?" she asked carelessly, as she drew one of her long tail feathers through her beak.
8419_286667_000019_000000 "No," said he.
8419_286667_000019_000001 "I bowed to her sister." He thought that was a very clever thing to say.
8419_286667_000019_000002 But she suddenly raised her head, and said, "There! I have forgotten something," and flew off, as she had done the day before.
8419_286667_000019_000003 He wondered what it was.
8419_286667_000019_000004 Long afterward he asked her what she had forgotten and she said she couldn't remember-that she never could remember what she had forgotten.
8419_286667_000020_000000 It made him feel very badly to have her leave him so.
8419_286667_000020_000001 He wanted a chance to tell her something, yet, whenever he tried to, it seemed to stick in his bill.
8419_286667_000020_000002 He began to fear that she didn't like him; and the next time the Cranes danced he didn't bow to her so much, but he strutted and leaped and whooped even more.
8419_286667_000020_000003 And she strutted and leaped and whooped almost as loudly as he.
8419_286667_000020_000004 When they were all tired out and had stopped dancing, she said to him, "I am so tired!
8419_286667_000020_000005 Let us go off into the woods and rest."
8419_286667_000021_000000 You may be very sure he was glad to go, and as he stalked off with her, he led the way to a charming nesting place.
8419_286667_000021_000001 He didn't know just how to tell what he wanted to, but he had seen another Crane bowing to her, and was afraid she might marry him if he was not quick.
8419_286667_000021_000002 Now he pointed with one wing to this nesting place, and said, "How would you like to build a nest there?"
8419_286667_000022_000000 She looked where he had pointed, "I?" she said.
8419_286667_000023_000000 "Let me help you," he said.
8419_286667_000023_000001 "I want to marry and have a home."
8419_286667_000025_000001 They were very, very happy, and after a while-but that is another story.
8419_286676_000001_000000 THE CLEVER WATER ADDER
8419_286676_000002_000001 The Snapping Turtle was left to himself a great deal until the day when he and Belostoma drove away the boys.
8419_286676_000002_000002 After that his neighbors began to understand him better and he was less grumpy, so that those who wore shells were soon quite fond of him.
8419_286676_000003_000000 Belostoma did not have many friends among the smaller people, and only a few among the larger ones.
8419_286676_000003_000001 They said that he was cruel, and that he had a bad habit of using his stout sucking tube to sting with.
8419_286676_000003_000002 Still, Belostoma did not care; he said, "A Giant Water Bug does not always live in the water.
8419_286676_000003_000004 After that, I shall fly away on my wedding trip.
8419_286676_000003_000005 mrs Belostoma may go with me, if she feels like doing so after laying her eggs here.
8419_286676_000003_000006 I shall go anyway.
8419_286676_000003_000007 And I shall flutter and sprawl around the light, and sting people who bother me, and have a happy time." That was Belostoma's way.
8419_286676_000003_000009 And perhaps that was so.
8419_286676_000004_000000 With the Water Adders it was different.
8419_286676_000004_000001 They were good-natured enough, yet the Mud Turtles and Snapping Turtle were the only ones who ever called upon them and found them at home.
8419_286676_000004_000002 The small people without shells were afraid of them, and the Clams and Pond Snails never called upon any one.
8419_286676_000004_000003 The Minnows said they could not bear the looks of the Adders-they had such ugly mouths and such quick motions.
8419_286676_000004_000004 The larger fishes kept away on account of their children, who were small and tender.
8419_286676_000005_000000 One might think that the Sand Hill Cranes, the Fish Hawks, and the other shore families would have been good friends for them, but when they called, the Adders were always away.
8419_286676_000005_000001 People said that the Adders were afraid of them.
8419_286676_000006_000000 The Yellow Brown Frog wished that the Adders could be scared, badly scared, some time: so scared that a chilly feeling would run down their backs from their heads clear to the tips of their tails.
8419_286676_000006_000001 "I wish," said he, "that the chilly feeling would be big enough to go way through to their bellies.
8419_286676_000006_000002 Their bellies are only the front side of their backs, anyway," he added, "because they are so thin." Of course this was a dreadful wish to make, but people said that one of the Adders had frightened the Yellow Brown Frog so that he never got over it, and this was the reason he felt so.
8419_286676_000007_000001 She could swim very fast, could creep, glide, catch hold of things with her tail, hang herself from the branch of a tree, lift her head far into the air, leap, dart, bound, and dive. All her family could do these things, but she could do them a little the best.
8419_286676_000008_000000 One day she was hanging over the pond in a very graceful position, with her tail twisted carelessly around a willow branch.
8419_286676_000008_000001 The Snapping Turtle and a Mud Turtle Father were in the shallow water below her.
8419_286676_000008_000002 Her slender forked tongue was darting in and out of her open mouth.
8419_286676_000008_000003 She was using her tongue in this way most of the time.
8419_286676_000008_000004 "It is useful in feeling of things," she said, "and then, I have always thought it quite becoming." She could see herself reflected in the still water below her, and she noticed how prettily the dark brown of her back shaded into the white of her belly.
8419_286676_000009_000000 The Snapping Turtle felt cross to day, and had come to see if a talk with her would not make him feel better.
8419_286676_000009_000001 The Mud Turtle was tired of having the children sprawl around him, and of mrs Mud Turtle telling about the trouble she had to get the right kind of food.
8419_286676_000010_000000 The Clever Water Adder spoke first of the weather.
8419_286676_000010_000001 "It must be dreadfully hot for the shore people," she said.
8419_286676_000011_000001 "How they must wish for shells!"
8419_286676_000012_000001 "What for?
8419_286676_000012_000002 To fly with?
8419_286676_000012_000003 Let them come in swimming with their children, if they are warm and tired."
8419_286676_000013_000000 The Water Adder laughed in her snaky way, and showed her sharp teeth.
8419_286676_000013_000001 "I have heard," she said, "that when the Wild Ducks bring their children here to swim, they do not always take so many home as they brought."
8419_286676_000014_000001 The Mud Turtle smiled. "I have heard," she went on, "that when young Ducks dive head first, they are quite sure to come up again, but that when they dive feet first, they never come up."
8419_286676_000016_000000 "Oh, nothing," replied the Water Adder, swinging her head back and forth and looking at the scales on her body.
8419_286676_000017_000000 "I know what you mean," said the Snapping Turtle, "and you know what you mean, but I have to eat something, and if I am swimming under the water and a Duckling paddles along just above me and sticks his foot into my mouth, I am likely to swallow him before I think."
8419_286676_000018_000000 The Water Adder saw that he was provoked by what she had said, so she talked about something else.
8419_286676_000018_000001 "I think the Ducks spoil their children," said she.
8419_286676_000018_000002 "They make such a fuss over them, and they are not nearly so bright as my children.
8419_286676_000018_000003 Why, mine hatch as soon as the eggs are laid, and go hunting at once.
8419_286676_000018_000004 They are no trouble at all."
8419_286676_000019_000000 "I never worry about mine," said the Mud Turtle, "although their mother thinks it is not safe for them all to sleep at once, as they do on a log in the sunshine."
8419_286676_000020_000000 "It isn't," said the Adder decidedly.
8419_286676_000020_000001 "I never close my eyes.
8419_286676_000020_000002 None of us Adders do.
8419_286676_000020_000003 Nobody can ever say that we close our eyes to danger." They couldn't shut their eyes if they wanted to, because they had no eyelids, but she did not speak of that.
8419_286676_000020_000004 "How stupid people are," she said.
8419_286676_000021_000000 "Most of them," remarked the Turtles.
8419_286676_000022_000000 "All of them," she said, "except us Adders and the Turtles.
8419_286676_000022_000001 I even think that some of the Turtles are a little queer, don't you?"
8419_286676_000023_000000 "We have thought so," said the Mud Turtle.
8419_286676_000024_000000 "They certainly are," agreed the Snapping Turtle, who was beginning to feel much better natured.
8419_286676_000025_000000 "What did you say?" asked the Adder who, like all her family, was a little deaf.
8419_286676_000026_000000 "Ouch!" exclaimed the Snapping Turtle.
8419_286676_000026_000001 "Ouch!
8419_286676_000026_000002 Ouch!"
8419_286676_000027_000000 "What is the matter?" asked the Mud Turtle.
8419_286676_000028_000001 Then they swam away, pushing themselves quickly through the water with swift strokes of their hairy oar legs.
8419_286676_000031_000000 "Reach your tail with your head?" asked the Water Adder in her sweetest voice.
8419_286676_000031_000001 "Nothing is easier." And she wound herself around the willow branch in another graceful position, and took the tip of her tail daintily between her teeth.
8419_286676_000034_000000 "What a rude person she is!" they said.
8419_286676_000034_000001 "Always trying to show how much more clever she is than other people.
8419_286676_000034_000002 We would rather be stupid and polite."
8419_286676_000035_000000 After a while the Snapping Turtle said, "But then, you know, we are not stupid."
8419_293469_000003_000000 In all the meadow there was nobody who could tell such interesting stories as the old Tree Frog.
8419_293469_000003_000001 Even the Garter Snake, who had been there the longest, and the old Cricket, who had lived in the farm yard, could tell no such exciting tales as the Tree Frog.
8419_293469_000003_000002 All the wonderful things of which he told had happened before he came to the meadow, and while he was still a young Frog.
8419_293469_000003_000003 None of his friends had known him then, but he was an honest fellow, and they were sure that everything he told was true: besides, they must be true, for how could a body ever think out such remarkable tales from his own head?
8419_293469_000004_000000 When he first came to his home by the elm tree he was very thin, and looked as though he had been sick.
8419_293469_000004_000001 The Katydids who stayed near said that he croaked in his sleep, and that, you know, is not what well and happy Frogs should do.
8419_293469_000005_000000 One day when many of the meadow people were gathered around him, he told them his story.
8419_293469_000005_000001 "When I was a little fellow," he said, "I was strong and well, and could leap farther than any other Frog of my size.
8419_293469_000005_000002 I was hatched in the pond beyond the farm house, and ate my way from the egg to the water outside like any other Frog.
8419_293469_000005_000003 Perhaps I ought to say, 'like any other Tadpole,' for, of course, I began life as a Tadpole.
8419_293469_000005_000005 We were all in a hurry to be Frogs, and often talked of what we would do and how far we would travel when we were grown.
8419_293469_000006_000000 "Oh, how happy we were then!
8419_293469_000006_000001 I remember the day when my hind legs began to grow, and how the other Tadpoles crowded around me in the water and swam close to me to feel the two little bunches that were to be legs.
8419_293469_000008_000000 "I did have when I was a Tadpole," said the Tree Frog.
8419_293469_000008_000001 "I had a beautiful, wiggly little tail with which to swim through the waters of the pond; but as my legs grew larger and stronger, my tail grew littler and weaker, until there wasn't any tail left.
8419_293469_000008_000004 Some of the other Frogs started with me, but they stopped along the way, and at last I was alone.
8419_293469_000009_000000 "I was a bold young fellow, and when I saw a great white thing among the trees up yonder, I made up my mind to see what it was.
8419_293469_000009_000001 There was a great red thing in the yard beside it, but I liked the white one better.
8419_293469_000009_000002 I hopped along as fast as I could, for I did not then know enough to be afraid.
8419_293469_000009_000003 I got close up to them both, and saw strange, big creatures going in and out of the red thing-the barn, as I afterward found it was called.
8419_293469_000009_000004 The largest creatures had four legs, and some of them had horns. The smaller creatures had only two legs on which to walk, and two other limbs of some sort with which they lifted and carried things.
8419_293469_000009_000005 The queerest thing about it was, that the smaller creatures seemed to make the larger ones do whatever they wanted them to.
8419_293469_000009_000006 They even made some of them help do their work.
8419_293469_000009_000007 You may not believe me, but what I tell you is true.
8419_293469_000009_000008 I saw two of the larger ones tied to a great load of dried grass and pulling it into the barn.
8419_293469_000010_000000 "As you may guess, I stayed there a long time, watching these strange creatures work.
8419_293469_000010_000003 There I rested until sunset, and then began my evening song. While I was singing, one of the people from the house came out and found me.
8419_293469_000010_000004 She picked me up and carried me inside.
8419_293469_000010_000005 Oh, how frightened I was!
8419_293469_000010_000006 My heart thumped as though it would burst, and I tried my best to get away from her.
8419_293469_000010_000007 She didn't hurt me at all, but she would not let me go.
8419_293469_000011_000000 "She put me in a very queer prison.
8419_293469_000011_000001 At first, when she put me down on a stone in some water, I did not know that I was in prison.
8419_293469_000011_000002 I tried to hop away, and-bump! went my head against something.
8419_293469_000011_000003 Yet when I drew back, I could see no wall there.
8419_293469_000011_000004 I tried it again and again, and every time I hurt my head.
8419_293469_000011_000005 I tell you the truth, my friends, those walls were made of something which one could see through."
8419_293469_000012_000000 "Wonderful!" exclaimed all the meadow people; "wonderful, indeed!"
8419_293469_000013_000000 "And at the top," continued the Tree Frog, "was something white over the doorway into my prison.
8419_293469_000013_000001 In the bottom were water and a stone, and from the bottom to the top was a ladder.
8419_293469_000013_000002 There I had to live for most of the summer.
8419_293469_000013_000003 I had enough to eat; but anybody who has been free cannot be happy shut in.
8419_293469_000013_000004 I watched my chance, and three times I got out when the little door was not quite closed.
8419_293469_000013_000005 Twice I was caught and put back.
8419_293469_000013_000006 In the pleasant weather, of course, I went to the top of the ladder, and when it was going to rain I would go down again.
8419_293469_000013_000007 Every time that I went up or down, those dreadful creatures would put their faces up close to my prison, and I could hear a roaring sound which meant they were talking and laughing.
8419_293469_000014_000001 After they stopped hunting, the wind blew the door open, and I hopped out."
8419_293469_000015_000000 "You don't say!" exclaimed a Grasshopper.
8419_293469_000016_000002 It seemed to me that just stretching my legs was enough to make me wild with joy.
8419_293469_000016_000003 Well, I came right here, and you were all kind to me, but for a long time I could not sleep without dreaming that I was back in prison, and I would croak in my sleep at the thought of it."
8419_293469_000017_000000 "I heard you," cried the Katydid, "and I wondered what was the matter."
8419_293469_000018_000000 "Matter enough," said the Tree Frog.
8419_293469_000018_000001 "It makes my skin dry to think of it now.
8419_293469_000018_000002 And, friends, the best way I can ever repay your kindness to me, is to tell you to never, never, never, never go near the farm house."
8419_293469_000019_000000 And they all answered, "We never will."
8419_293473_000002_000000 THE DIGNIFIED WALKING STICKS.
8419_293473_000003_000000 Three Walking Sticks from the forest had come to live in the big maple tree near the middle of the meadow.
8419_293473_000003_000001 Nobody knew exactly why they had left the forest, where all their sisters and cousins and aunts lived. Perhaps they were not happy with their relatives.
8419_293473_000003_000002 But then, if one is a Walking Stick, you know, one does not care so very much about one's family.
8419_293473_000004_000000 These Walking Sticks had grown up the best way they could, with no father or mother to care for them.
8419_293473_000004_000001 They had never been taught to do anything useful, or to think much about other people.
8419_293473_000004_000002 When they were hungry they ate some leaves, and never thought what they should eat the next time that they happened to be hungry.
8419_293473_000004_000003 When they were tired they went to sleep, and when they had slept enough they awakened.
8419_293473_000004_000004 They had nothing to do but to eat and sleep, and they did not often take the trouble to think.
8419_293473_000004_000005 They felt that they were a little better than those meadow people who rushed and scrambled and worked from morning until night, and they showed very plainly how they felt.
8419_293473_000004_000006 They said it was not genteel to hurry, no matter what happened.
8419_293473_000005_000000 One day the Tree Frog was under the tree when the large Brown Walking Stick decided to lay some eggs.
8419_293473_000006_000000 "A place?" said the Brown Walking Stick, waving her long and slender feelers to and fro.
8419_293473_000006_000001 "A place?
8419_293473_000006_000002 Oh, no! I think they will hatch where they are.
8419_293473_000006_000003 It is too much trouble to find a place."
8419_293473_000007_000001 "Some mothers do not think it too much trouble to be careful where they lay eggs."
8419_293473_000008_000000 "That may be," said the Brown Walking Stick, "but they do not belong to our family." She spoke as if those who did not belong to her family might be good but could never be genteel.
8419_293473_000008_000002 She thought the meadow people very common.
8419_293473_000009_000000 The Five Legged Walking Stick looked much like his sister.
8419_293473_000009_000001 He had the same long, slender body, the same long feelers, and the same sort of long, slender legs.
8419_293473_000009_000002 If you had passed them in a hay field, you would surely have thought each a stem of hay, unless you happened to see them move.
8419_293473_000009_000003 The other Walking Stick, their friend, was younger and green.
8419_293473_000009_000004 You would have thought her a blade of grass.
8419_293473_000010_000000 It is true that the brother had the same kind of legs as his sister, but he did not have the same number.
8419_293473_000010_000001 When he was young and green he had six, then came a dreadful day when a hungry Nuthatch saw him, flew down, caught him, and carried him up a tree.
8419_293473_000010_000002 He knew just what to expect, so when the Nuthatch set him down on the bark to look at him, he unhooked his feet from the bark and tumbled to the ground.
8419_293473_000010_000003 The Nuthatch tried to catch him and broke off one of his legs, but she never found him again, although she looked and looked and looked and looked.
8419_293473_000010_000004 That was because he crawled into a clump of ferns and kept very still.
8419_293473_000011_000000 His sister came and looked at him and said, "Now if you were only a Spider it would not be long before you would have six legs again."
8419_293473_000012_000002 His relatives all waved their feelers, one at a time, and said, "Ah, he has the true Walking Stick spirit!" Then they paid no more attention to him, and after a while he and his sister and their green little friend left the forest for the meadow.
8419_293473_000013_000000 On the day when the grass was cut, they had sat quietly in their trees and looked genteel.
8419_293473_000013_000001 Their feelers were held quite close together, and they did not move their feet at all, only swayed their bodies gracefully from side to side.
8419_293473_000013_000002 Now they were on the ground, hunting through the flat piles of cut grass for some fresh and juicy bits to eat.
8419_293473_000013_000003 The Tree Frog was also out, sitting in a cool, damp corner of the grass rows.
8419_293473_000013_000004 The young Grasshoppers were kicking up their feet, the Ants were scrambling around as busy as ever, and life went on quite as though neither men nor Horses had ever entered the meadow.
8419_293473_000015_000002 Then there was a great scrambling and the Crickets frolicked with them.
8419_293473_000015_000004 She did not quite wish it, you understand, and would never have thought of it if she had turned brown.
8419_293473_000016_000000 "Ah," said the Five Legged Walking Stick, "what scrambling!
8419_293473_000016_000001 How very common!"
8419_293473_000017_000000 "Yes, indeed!" said his sister.
8419_293473_000017_000001 "Why can't they learn to move slowly and gracefully?
8419_293473_000017_000002 Perhaps they can't help being fat, but they might at least act genteel."
8419_293473_000018_000000 "What is it to be genteel?" asked a Grasshopper suddenly.
8419_293473_000019_000000 "Why," said the Five Legged Walking Stick, "it is just to be genteel.
8419_293473_000019_000001 To act as you see us act, and to----"
8419_293473_000021_000000 The Walking Sticks looked very uncomfortable, and the brother and sister could not think of anything to say.
8419_293473_000021_000001 It was the young green one who spoke at last.
8425_246962_000007_000000 HELEN AND THE CURATE.
8425_287387_000004_000000 CHAPTER eight
8425_291444_000001_000000 TO THE PUBLIC.
8425_292520_000006_000000 Dark, with crumbling railing and planks, The bridge leads into the sunset. Across it many lonely figures, Their eyes a flare with the sunset, Their faces glowing with its colors, Tramp past me through the evening.
8425_292520_000012_000000 The crowd thins, the players are alone; In their faith's raucous monotone, Loud with gaudy angels, tinsel cherubim, A drum pounds out the hymn.
8425_292520_000013_000000 INCARNATION
8425_292520_000022_000000 Monotonously the solemn reeds Waved to our passing; Ahead the canal shimmered, blotched green by the water weeds. With a grinding swing And see saw of sound, The steamer slunk down the canal.
8425_292520_000024_000000 That night from a dingy hotel room, I saw the moon, like a golden gong, Redly loom Across the lake; like a golden gong In a temple, which a priest ere long Will strike into throbbing song, To wake some silent twinkling city to prayer. The lake waves were flakes of red gold, Burnished to copper, Gold, red as the tangled gleam Of sunlight in your hair.
8425_292520_000033_000000 NIGHT PIECE
8425_292520_000034_000000 A silver web has the moon spun, A silver web upon all the sky, Where the frail stars quiver, every one Like tangled gnats that hum and die.
8425_292520_000038_000000 And that other night, When the river rippled with faint spears Of street lights vaguely reflected.
8425_292520_000038_000001 Grey The evening, like an opal; low, A grey moon shrouded in sea fog: Air pregnant with spring; rasp of my steps Beside the lapping water; within The dark.
8465_246940_000003_000000 ADVICE IN THE DARK.
8465_246940_000004_000000 It was some moments before either of them spoke, and it did not help Wingfold that she sat clouded by a dark coloured veil.
8465_246940_000005_000000 "You must not fear to trust me because I doubt my ability to help you. I can at least assure you of my sympathy.
