8609_262281_000002_000000 CHAPTER sixteen.
8609_262281_000003_000000 MUCH TO ALTER.
8609_262281_000004_000000 At the same moment Constance Channing was traversing the Boundaries, on her way to Lady Augusta Yorke's, where she had, some days since, commenced her duties.
8609_262281_000004_000001 It took her scarcely two minutes to get there, for the houses were almost within view of each other.
8609_262281_000004_000002 Constance would willingly have commenced the daily routine at an earlier hour.
8609_262281_000004_000003 Lady Augusta freely confessed that to come earlier would be useless, for she could not get her daughters up.
8609_262281_000004_000004 Strictly speaking, Lady Augusta did not personally try to get them up, for she generally lay in bed herself.
8609_262281_000005_000000 "That is one of the habits I must alter in the children," thought Constance.
8609_262281_000006_000000 She entered, took off her things in the room appropriated to her, and passed into the schoolroom.
8609_262281_000006_000001 It was empty, though the children ought to have been there, preparing their lessons.
8609_262281_000006_000002 Fanny came running in, her hair in curl papers, some bread and butter in her hand.
8609_262281_000007_000000 "Carry has not finished her breakfast, Miss Channing," quoth she.
8609_262281_000007_000001 "She was lazy this morning!"
8609_262281_000008_000001 "Why did you come down half dressed, my dear?"
8609_262281_000009_000000 "I am quite dressed," responded Fanny.
8609_262281_000009_000001 "My frock's on, and so is my pinafore."
8609_262281_000010_000000 "And these?" said Constance, touching the curl papers.
8609_262281_000011_000000 "Oh, Martha got up late, and said she had no time to take them out.
8609_262281_000011_000001 It will keep in curl all the better, Miss Channing; and perhaps I am going to the missionary meeting with mamma."
8609_262281_000012_000000 Constance rang the bell.
8609_262281_000012_000002 Lady Augusta was wont to say that she had too much expense with her boys to keep many servants; and the argument was a true one.
8609_262281_000013_000000 "Be so kind as to take the papers out of Miss Fanny's hair.
8609_262281_000013_000001 And let it be done in future, Martha, before she comes to me."
8609_262281_000014_000000 Gently as the words were spoken, there was no mistaking that the tone was one of authority, and not to be trifled with.
8609_262281_000014_000001 Martha withdrew with the child.
8609_262281_000014_000002 And, just then, Caroline came in, full of eagerness.
