8797_294123_000023_000000 The Chinese has been called the type of permanence, and well he has merited it, dozing as he has through the ages.
8797_294123_000024_000001 We are in the midst of our own.
8797_294123_000024_000002 The Slav is just girding himself up to begin.
8797_294123_000025_000001 It is not the nature of life to believe itself weak.
8797_294123_000025_000002 There is such a thing as race egotism as well as creature egotism, and a very good thing it is.
8797_294123_000025_000003 In the first place, the Western world will not permit the rise of the yellow peril.
8797_294123_000025_000005 The Western world is warned, if not armed, against the possibility of it.
8797_294123_000026_000001 From the West he has borrowed all our material achievement and passed our ethical achievement by.
8797_294123_000026_000004 A marvellous imitator truly, but imitating us only in things material.
8797_294123_000026_000005 Things spiritual cannot be imitated; they must be felt and lived, woven into the very fabric of life, and here the Japanese fails.
8797_294123_000027_000000 It required no revolution of his nature to learn to calculate the range and fire a field gun or to march the goose step.
8797_294123_000027_000001 It was a mere matter of training.
8797_294123_000027_000002 Our material achievement is the product of our intellect.
8797_294123_000027_000003 It is knowledge, and knowledge, like coin, is interchangeable.
8797_294123_000027_000004 It is not wrapped up in the heredity of the new born child, but is something to be acquired afterward.
8797_294123_000027_000006 Our soul stuff is not a coin to be pocketed by the first chance comer.
8797_294123_000027_000008 The leopard cannot change its spots, nor can the Japanese, nor can we.
8797_294123_000027_000009 We are thumbed by the ages into what we are, and by no conscious inward effort can we in a day rethumb ourselves.
8797_294123_000028_000001 Though we have strayed often and far from righteousness, the voices of the seers have always been raised, and we have harked back to the bidding of conscience.
8797_294123_000028_000002 The colossal fact of our history is that we have made the religion of Jesus Christ our religion.
8797_294123_000028_000003 No matter how dark in error and deed, ours has been a history of spiritual struggle and endeavour.
8797_294123_000029_000001 "It seems to me that they have no soul," was her answer.
8797_294123_000030_000000 This must not be taken to mean that the Japanese is without soul.
8797_294123_000030_000002 There was no feel, no speech, no recognition.
8797_294123_000030_000003 This Western soul did not dream that the Eastern soul existed, it was so different, so totally different.
8797_294123_000032_000000 Measured by what religion means to us, the Japanese is a race without religion.
8797_294123_000032_000002 As one Japanese has written:
8797_294123_000033_000000 "Our reflection brought into prominence not so much the moral as the national consciousness of the individual. . . .
8797_294123_000033_000001 To us the country is more than land and soil from which to mine gold or reap grain-it is the sacred abode of the gods, the spirit of our forefathers; to us the Emperor is more than the Arch Constable of a Reichsstaat, or even the Patron of a Kulturstaat; he is the bodily representative of heaven on earth, blending in his person its power and its mercy."
8797_294123_000034_000000 The religion of Japan is practically a worship of the State itself. Patriotism is the expression of this worship.
8797_294123_000034_000001 The Japanese mind does not split hairs as to whether the Emperor is Heaven incarnate or the State incarnate.
8797_294123_000034_000002 So far as the Japanese are concerned, the Emperor lives, is himself deity.
8797_294123_000034_000003 The Emperor is the object to live for and to die for. The Japanese is not an individualist.
8797_294123_000034_000004 He has developed national consciousness instead of moral consciousness.
8797_294123_000034_000006 Only exists the honour of the State, which is his honour.
8797_294123_000034_000007 He does not look upon himself as a free agent, working out his own personal salvation.
8797_294123_000034_000009 He has a "sense of calm trust in fate, a quiet submission to the inevitable, a stoic composure in sight of danger or calamity, a disdain of life and friendliness with death." He relates himself to the State as, amongst bees, the worker is related to the hive; himself nothing, the State everything; his reasons for existence the exaltation and glorification of the State.
8797_294123_000035_000000 The most admired quality to day of the Japanese is his patriotism.
8797_294123_000035_000002 "For God, my country, and the Czar!" cries the Russian patriot; but in the Japanese mind there is no differentiation between the three.
8797_294123_000035_000004 The patriotism of the Japanese is blind and unswerving loyalty to what is practically an absolutism.
8797_294123_000035_000005 The Emperor can do no wrong, nor can the five ambitious great men who have his ear and control the destiny of Japan.
8797_294123_000036_000000 No great race adventure can go far nor endure long which has no deeper foundation than material success, no higher prompting than conquest for conquest's sake and mere race glorification.
8797_294123_000036_000001 To go far and to endure, it must have behind it an ethical impulse, a sincerely conceived righteousness.
8797_294123_000036_000002 But it must be taken into consideration that the above postulate is itself a product of Western race egotism, urged by our belief in our own righteousness and fostered by a faith in ourselves which may be as erroneous as are most fond race fancies.
8797_294123_000036_000003 So be it.
8797_294123_000036_000004 The world is whirling faster to day than ever before.
8797_294123_000036_000005 It has gained impetus. Affairs rush to conclusion.
8797_294123_000036_000006 The Far East is the point of contact of the adventuring Western people as well as of the Asiatic.
8797_294123_000036_000007 We shall not have to wait for our children's time nor our children's children.
87_121553_000007_000000 Song that as greatly doth transcend our Muses, Our Sirens, in those dulcet clarions, As primal splendour that which is reflected.
